question:
I can’t shake off this sharp pain that’s been gripping my right groin for the past two weeks. It’s relentless, and I find some relief only when I stand up, which is a small comfort. I went to the doctor, but honestly, I’m still worried. My blood pressure was measured at 140/92, and my heart rate was 88, which seemed a bit high for me. They listened to my heart and checked my abdomen, lungs, and other areas, but everything seemed unremarkable; no hernias, nothing alarming.

Still, something feels wrong. The doctor did some tests and found tenderness in my lower back, specifically at L4 and L5. The right side of my sacrum looks off too, and the seated flexion test confirmed something was amiss. They took some images of my hip and lower back, and thankfully, there were no obvious issues. But I can’t help but worry about what could be causing this pain. 

I’m left wondering which structure is responsible for this discomfort. Is it a ligament or a muscle? I feel like I’m just in the dark, and the uncertainty is making me anxious. I really hope I can find answers soon because living with this pain is exhausting.
options: A. Sacrotuberous ligament B. Quadratus lumborum muscle C. Piriformis muscle D. Posterior sacroiliac ligament E. Iliolumbar ligament F. Anterior sacroiliac ligament G. Psoas major muscle H. Sacrospinous ligament I. Gluteus medius muscle J. Iliacus muscle

question:
I can hardly shake off the anxiety that has settled in since my baby was born. Just moments after the cesarean delivery at 38 weeks, the nurses noticed that my newborn was breathing rapidly—tachypnea, they called it—with a respiratory rate of 90 breaths per minute. They mentioned something about retractions, which sounded alarming. I kept staring at my little one, who seemed so active and alert, yet my heart raced with worry. Thankfully, there was no cyanosis, but I felt so helpless watching my baby being whisked away for observation in intensive care.

The doctors reassured me that there were no signs of fever or rash, and the blood gas analysis showed no CO2 retention. Still, I couldn’t shake the fear that something might be seriously wrong. I kept asking myself what exactly was happening. Was this just a benign condition, or was it something more serious? I heard them discussing different management approaches—everything from antibiotics to surfactant therapy—and I couldn’t help but feel overwhelmed. 

I just want to know, is this normal? Will my baby be okay? I keep praying for the doctors to figure it out soon, but the uncertainty is weighing heavily on me.
options: A. Respiratory support with mechanical ventilation is the first-line management B. The condition is benign and self-limiting, requiring no specific treatment C. This is hard to distinguish from pneumonia and sepsis so empirical antibiotics are given for 48 hours after birth until sepsis is ruled out D. Surfactant deficiency is the underlying cause, so surfactant therapy is required E. This is most likely transient tachypnea of the newborn and requires no antibiotics F. Tachypnea in this case is likely due to a congenital heart defect, so echocardiography is indicated G. ABG is needed to monitor  and it is normal to have CO2 retention H. A chest X-ray must be done immediately to confirm the diagnosis of neonatal pneumonia I. Empirical antifungal therapy should be initiated until fungal sepsis is ruled out J. Oxygen therapy is the mainstay of therapy with  monitoring with SpO2

question:
Over the past year, I've been on an emotional rollercoaster as my child and several other kids were evaluated by a pediatric cardiac surgeon for similar congenital heart defects. I remember the day so clearly when I first heard the loud holosystolic murmur over my child's chest. It was terrifying to think that something could be so wrong. The doctors assured us that their vital signs were stable and that they were on appropriate medications, but I couldn’t shake the worry.

They performed echocardiograms on each child, and I held my breath as we waited for the results. I felt a wave of anxiety wash over me when I learned that one of the children would need surgical closure of the defect. The thought of surgery sent me into a spiral of fear. I kept wondering which child it would be and what that meant for their future.

I couldn't help but compare my child to the other patients. Would they need surgery too? There was a 5-year-old boy with a 3-mm muscular defect, an 18-month-old with a 6-mm defect, and so many others with varying degrees of severity. It felt overwhelming. 

I keep replaying the details in my mind, hoping for answers while grappling with my fears about what this all means for my child and their health. I just want them to be okay.
options: A. A 5-year-old boy with a 3-mm muscular defect and mild left-to-right shunt B. An 18-month-old boy with a 6-mm defect and moderate pulmonary hypertension responsive to vasodilators C. A 7-year-old boy with an 11-mm muscular defect and severe pulmonary vascular disease that is unresponsive to pulmonary vasodilators D. A 6-year-old boy with a 7-mm defect and bidirectional shunting E. A 3-year-old girl with a 2-mm perimembranous defect and normal pulmonary pressures F. A 15-month-old girl with a 4.5-mm defect showing decreasing size on follow-up imaging G. A 5-year-old girl with a 2-mm membranous defect and a left-to-right shunt without associated left ventricular dilation H. An 8-month-old girl with a 3-mm defect and normal pulmonary artery pressures I. A 4-year-old girl with multiple small muscular defects (<3mm each) and normal right ventricular pressure J. A 9-month-old boy with a 4-mm muscular defect with pulmonary hypertension

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. It all started five days ago when I came down with a fever and chills that just wouldn’t quit. My head was pounding, and I felt this terrible pain in my back that made it hard to even move. I knew something wasn’t right, so I went to the hospital. 

When I got there, the doctor took my temperature, and it was a bit over 100 degrees. My blood pressure was low, and I remember feeling so thin and sweaty. They noticed my pupils were tiny, and I felt embarrassed about my teeth and the track marks on my arms and legs. I just couldn’t help but worry about what all this could mean.

They admitted me and started me on antibiotics right away. But then, a few hours later, I heard them say something about my blood cultures coming back positive for Staphylococcus aureus. That word “Staphylococcus” kept echoing in my mind, and I felt my heart race. What was next? I could hardly breathe thinking about it. I just want to know if there’s something more going on, something worse. I’m terrified of what might happen if they don’t act quickly. I keep wondering if they’ll need to repeat the blood cultures or do some tests to figure this out. I feel so lost and scared right now.
options: A. Repeat blood cultures only if the patient develops new symptoms B. Repeat blood cultures 24 hours after initial cultures were drawn C. Initiate antifungal therapy and defer repeat blood cultures D. Do not repeat blood cultures E. Perform transthoracic echocardiography before repeating blood cultures F. Repeat blood cultures 48 hours after initial antibiotics are started G. Perform transesophageal echocardiography immediately H. Repeat blood cultures now I. Order a CT scan of the chest to assess for septic emboli J. Wait for sensitivity results before repeating blood cultures

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry as I sit in the waiting room for my routine prenatal visit. I’m 27 weeks pregnant with my first child, and while most of my pregnancy has gone well, I’ve started experiencing this overwhelming fatigue and some mild swelling in my legs. It’s unsettling, especially since my sister had preeclampsia during her pregnancy.

As I finally enter the exam room, I can’t help but feel anxious. I’ve been managing my epilepsy with lamotrigine, and I have no history of tobacco or alcohol use, but I just can’t shake off this nagging concern. The nurse takes my temperature, pulse, and blood pressure, and everything seems normal, but those tiny signs of swelling in my ankles make me uneasy.

I know I should be feeling joyful about this pregnancy, but instead, I keep thinking about what might happen next. What if something is wrong? I’ve heard about the risks associated with preeclampsia, and my mind races with possibilities. I just want reassurance. The doctor comes in, and I can see the concern in their eyes too. They start discussing the next steps, and I can’t help but feel a sense of dread. What if I need further monitoring or worse? I just hope everything will be okay for me and my baby.
options: A. Admit the patient for observation and preeclampsia workup B. Reassure the patient and schedule a follow-up appointment C. Initiate corticosteroid therapy for fetal lung maturity D. Order coagulation studies and liver chemistries E. Order urine dipstick and ambulatory blood pressure monitoring F. Initiate low-dose aspirin therapy G. Repeat platelet count and peripheral smear in 2 weeks H. Perform a biophysical profile to assess fetal status I. Perform a non-stress test to assess fetal well-being J. Measure serum protein and albumin levels

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread since my baby boy was born at just 34 weeks. Everything seemed fine during my pregnancy, but there were signs—like the polyhydramnios. When he arrived, I was filled with joy, but it quickly turned to worry as I learned that he was struggling to breathe in the NICU. His Apgar scores were 6 and 8, which I know isn’t terrible, but seeing him with those excessive secretions and moments where his oxygen levels dipped made my heart race. 

He’s only a newborn, and it’s terrifying to witness him in respiratory distress, with those intercostal retractions and unusual sounds when the doctors listened to his lungs. They mentioned his temperature was a bit high and that his belly looked distended, which only added to my fears. 

I can’t help but feel overwhelmed when they talk about the possibility of serious conditions like esophageal atresia or other issues that could be affecting him. I’ve been trying to keep it together, but the thought of what he might be facing keeps me up at night. I just want him to be okay and to come home with me. The uncertainty is so hard to bear. My heart aches for him, and I’m praying for answers soon.
options: A. Pyloric stenosis B. Esophageal atresia with tracheoesophageal fistula C. Congenital diaphragmatic hernia D. Laryngeal web E. Ventricular septal defect F. Bronchogenic cyst G. Hirschsprung disease H. Choanal atresia I. Meconium ileus J. Duodenal atresia

question:
I can't shake the worry that has settled in my chest. Just last night, my 5-year-old son started complaining about a sore throat. At first, I thought it was nothing serious, but it quickly escalated. By the time morning came, he was struggling to breathe, and I could see he was in distress. His temperature shot up to 103°F, and he was drooling, which made my heart race even faster. 

When we got to the emergency department, he seemed so ill, leaning forward to breathe as if that would somehow help. He wouldn’t even talk to me or let the doctors examine his mouth. I felt so helpless watching him like that. He’s usually such a vibrant, healthy kid, always up to date on his vaccinations and taking his multivitamins. 

I could see the concern in the doctors’ eyes as they rushed around him. His pulse was racing at 155 beats per minute, and his breathing was rapid too. I couldn't help but think, what could be causing this? I was terrified, wondering if it was something serious. I just want to know what's wrong and make it better for him. Every moment felt like an eternity, and all I could do was hope that he would be okay.
options: A. Haemophilus influenzae B. Streptococcus pneumoniae C. Parainfluenza virus D. Staphylococcus aureus E. Group A Streptococcus F. Adenovirus G. Mycoplasma pneumoniae H. Epstein-Barr virus I. Corynebacterium diphtheriae J. Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV)

question:
I can hardly shake this feeling of anxiety since my last appointment. It’s been two months since I had that surgery to remove the craniopharyngioma, and while I’ve been trying to stay positive, something just doesn’t feel right. I thought I was doing okay, but I keep getting these intermittent fevers that spike up to 39°C. It’s unnerving, to say the least. 

I also noticed that my appetite has increased, which is strange. I’ve been taking my medications—Levothyroxine, hydrocortisone, desmopressin, and my testosterone injections—so I thought everything was under control. But when I went for my follow-up, my temperature was still high at 38.8°C. My heart raced a bit, and I can’t help but worry about what this could mean.

The doctors did a thorough check and said my craniotomy scar looks fine, but I can’t shake this fear of something being wrong. They ran a bunch of tests—blood cultures, a urinalysis, even an MRI of my head. Everything seemed unremarkable, but I still can’t help but feel anxious about the possibility of an infection or something else lurking. I just want to know what’s causing these fevers. It’s hard to focus on anything else when I feel like there’s still so much uncertainty.
options: A. Medication-induced fever B. Residual tumor progression C. Drug reaction D. Hypothalamic dysfunction E. Occult postoperative infection F. Autonomic dysregulation G. Autoimmune hypophysitis H. Overrepletion of thyroid hormone I. Inadequate glucocorticoid replacement J. Meningeal irritation

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping in over the last four months. It all started with a low-grade fever and this constant sense of malaise that just won’t go away. I’ve lost about 20 pounds, which is alarming, and I’m so fatigued that even simple tasks feel monumental. 

I remember feeling a bit off when I had my mitral valve replacement five years ago, but this is different. I went to see the doctor, and they checked my temperature—it was 38.1°C (100.6°F). My heart rate was elevated, and I could barely catch my breath. During the exam, the doctor mentioned hearing a new murmur in my heart, which really shook me. 

I can’t help but wonder if something serious is happening. Why am I feeling this way? Is there an infection lurking inside me? With my history, I’m terrified of what could be causing these symptoms. I know there are so many potential culprits, but the uncertainty is eating away at me. I just hope I can figure this out soon, because the thought of something more serious is really weighing heavily on my mind.
options: A. *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* B. *Bartonella henselae* C. HACEK group organisms D. *Candida albicans* E. Beta-hemolytic streptococci F. *Staphylococcus aureus* G. Coagulase-negative *Staphylococcus spp.* H. *Pseudomonas* aeruginosa I. *Streptococcus bovis* J. *Enterococcus*

question:
I can hardly believe what happened to me. It all started about a week ago when I began feeling weak and unwell, almost like I was running a fever. I’ve had my fair share of health issues, including hepatitis C and cirrhosis, but this felt different. When I went to the emergency room, my temperature was 102°F, and I was terrified. My blood pressure was high, and my pulse was racing. I remember lying there, feeling utterly drained and noticing the jaundice spreading over my skin.

The doctors examined me and mentioned something about fluid in my abdomen and tenderness, which only made me more anxious. They admitted me and started me on antibiotics. I thought maybe this was it, maybe I was finally getting better. But four days later, I was still feeling the effects of the jaundice, and I noticed strange bruises all over my arms and legs. The nurses were concerned too; they had to apply pressure to two IV sites because I was bleeding. 

What’s happening? I can’t shake the worry that something is seriously wrong with my body. I just want to understand what’s going on and why I’m feeling this way. I’m scared, and I don’t know what the future holds.
options: A. Fibrinolysis activation due to liver failure B. Vitamin K deficiency due to liver dysfunction C. Diffuse activation of the coagulation cascade D. Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) E. Platelet dysfunction secondary to sepsis F. Decreased production of coagulation factors G. Immune-mediated platelet destruction H. Hypersplenism causing thrombocytopenia I. Decreased metabolism of an anticoagulant J. Bacterial destruction

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread. At 59, I thought I was in pretty good health, but lately, everything feels off. I’ve been so tired, like I can't get enough rest, and it’s worrying me. I've also lost weight without trying, and there’s this awful abdominal pain that just won’t go away. I can’t remember the last time I felt normal.

My medical history isn’t too bad, but I do deal with anxiety and diabetes. I had a foot fracture recently, which was a painful reminder of my age, and I caught a cold that knocked me out for a week. Now, on top of everything else, my blood pressure is high, and I found out I have a mild heart murmur. I try not to think about it, but it’s hard.

I’ve been taking my medications like metformin and insulin, but nothing seems to help. I went to my doctor, and they ran tests—my white blood cell count was alarmingly high. I just can’t help but worry about what this all means. I keep thinking about the different possible diagnoses my doctor mentioned. What if it’s something serious? I really don’t want to face that. The uncertainty is eating away at me, and I’m just hoping for some answers soon.
options: A. Myelodysplastic syndrome B. Polycythemia vera C. Chronic lymphocytic leukemia D. Primary myelofibrosis E. Leukemoid reaction F. Essential thrombocythemia G. Chronic myeloid leukemia H. Acute myeloid leukemia I. Chronic myelogenous leukemia J. Paraneoplastic leukocytosis

question:
I can’t shake off this overwhelming worry since my baby was born just a day ago. He’s a sweet little boy, but he’s been struggling to feed, which I thought was just normal newborn fussiness. Then, I noticed his breathing seemed really fast, and his skin has this alarming bluish-grey tint. It’s like something is really wrong, and I can’t help but feel terrified.

He was born at 37 weeks, and while I thought everything was fine, I didn’t have the best prenatal care. I’ve never used drugs during my pregnancy, so this is just so confusing and frightening. The nurses took his temperature, and it was a normal 98.2, but his blood pressure was low, and his heart was racing at 170 beats per minute. The worst part is when they said he looked lethargic and had this dangerous cyanosis. They mentioned something about jugular venous distention, and all I could think was, “What does this mean for my baby?”

They listened to his chest and said he was breathing too fast, and I could hear this murmur. They even took him for a chest X-ray and an electrocardiogram. I can’t help but fear they might find something seriously wrong. I’m just praying that whatever it is can be treated. My heart aches for him. I feel so helpless and scared.
options: A. Total anomalous pulmonary venous return B. Complete transposition of the great arteries C. Isolated opening in membranous interventricular septum D. Persistent truncus arteriosus E. Enclosed muscular floor within the right atrium F. Pulmonary venous drainage into the right atrium G. Proximal atrialization of the right ventricle H. Severe tricuspid valve regurgitation I. Right ventricular hypertrophy with pulmonary stenosis J. Hypoplastic left heart syndrome

question:
I've been feeling really uneasy lately about some changes in my body. I've noticed that certain bones, particularly in my legs, seem to be getting larger, and it’s been weighing heavily on my mind. I keep wondering what could be causing this bone enlargement. I've tried to do some research, but there are so many conditions to consider. 

I came across a list of possible causes, and it made me feel even more anxious. There’s Lytic Paget disease, which sounds serious, and then there’s Osteochondroma, an abnormal bone growth. I read about Osteoid osteoma and Fibrous dysplasia too, and they all seem alarming in their own ways. 

What really troubles me is that I could also be dealing with Melorheostosis or even something like Hyperparathyroidism, which affects calcium levels. The thought of Giant cell tumors or Aneurysmal bone cysts adds to my worry. 

I know I need to see a doctor to get to the bottom of this, but the uncertainty is really getting to me. I just want to understand what’s happening with my body and whether I should be scared. I can’t shake the feeling that this is something serious, and I can’t help but feel overwhelmed.
options: A. Lytic Paget disease B. Osteochondroma C. Osteoid osteoma D. Fibrous dysplasia E. Melorheostosis F. Type II neurofibromatosis G. Hyperparathyroidism H. Giant cell tumor I. Osteopetrosis J. Aneurysmal bone cyst

question:
For the past two days, I've been battling an intense headache that just won’t go away. It’s been so bad that even the slightest exertion leaves me gasping for breath. I’ve also had two episodes of vomiting, which is really unsettling, and I haven’t been able to urinate at all during this time. 

Over the last couple of years, I've noticed my fingers becoming increasingly painful and stiff, but I kept telling myself it was just getting older. I don’t have any history of serious illness, I don’t take any medications, and I’ve never smoked or drank alcohol, so this all feels so sudden and alarming.

When I went to see the doctor, I could tell something was wrong. I felt moderately distressed, and my heart was racing. They found my blood pressure was really high, and my oxygen levels were low. I noticed the doctor looking concerned when they examined me—my skin was pale, and I had swelling in my legs, which I hadn’t even realized was a problem. There were strange spots on my skin, and my joints felt stiff. 

The doctor listened to my chest and heard crackles, which made me even more anxious. I can’t shake the feeling that something serious might be going on, and the uncertainty is really weighing on me. What could this all mean?
options: A. Elevated anti-RNA polymerase III antibodies B. Decreased serum complement concentration C. Increased anti-CCP antibody titers D. Increased anticentromere antibody titers E. Decreased serum haptoglobin concentration F. Increased serum aldosterone levels G. Elevated anti-Scl-70 antibodies H. Elevated anti-PM/Scl antibodies I. Increased serum erythropoietin levels J. Increased serum ferritin concentration

question:
I took my 2-month-old son to his routine health check-up, and I was feeling a mix of relief and anxiety, just like any parent would. The doctor said his growth and development were on track, which was a relief, but then she mentioned something that really shook me. His head circumference had jumped from the 50th percentile to the 90th percentile since his newborn visit. I couldn’t help but feel a knot in my stomach.

As I looked at my little boy, I noticed how his head appeared elongated and narrow, with a prominent occiput and broad forehead. No one wants to think there might be something wrong, but I couldn’t shake the worry. The doctor did say there were no facial dysmorphic features and that the rest of the exam was unremarkable, but still, my mind raced with questions. 

What if there’s something serious going on? I kept thinking about all the possibilities. I wanted to ensure he was okay, so I asked about what we should do next. The doctor mentioned some options but I just felt overwhelmed. Should we monitor it, or do we need further tests? I left the appointment feeling anxious, hoping we could figure out what this all meant for my son’s health.
options: A. Increased time in the prone position while awake and monitored B. Measurement of parental head circumferences to assess for familial macrocephaly C. Referral to a physical therapist to address positional head shape deformities D. Cranial ultrasound to assess for hydrocephalus E. MRI of the brain to evaluate intracranial structures F. Observation with no further intervention unless symptoms worsen G. Reevaluation of head circumference in one month H. Referral to a pediatric endocrinologist for evaluation of growth abnormalities I. Referral to craniofacial specialists J. Referral for genetic testing

question:
I can’t shake the worry that has settled in since that skateboarding competition. After I took a pretty bad fall, I started feeling this strange sensation in my head—it's hard to describe, just a really funny feeling that won’t go away. At first, I thought it was just a bump, but when I went to the doctor, they ran some tests and everything came back fine. I was relieved but still uneasy because the feeling lingered. 

Weeks later, I went back for another check-up, hoping for answers, but again, nothing abnormal showed up. I remember the doctor examining me closely, checking my reflexes and the nerves in my head, and they said everything looked normal, but I just don’t feel right. They even did some structural tests and mentioned something about the greater wings of my sphenoid being out of place. 

I can’t help but feel anxious about what this all means. It’s frustrating not knowing why I feel this way and if it could lead to something worse. I keep wondering if I should be more worried about what’s going on inside my head, and the uncertainty is really weighing on me. What if it’s something serious that they just haven’t caught yet?
options: A. Suboccipital strain B. Cranial base dysfunction C. Compression D. Superior vertical strain E. Lateral strain F. Sidebending rotation G. Inferior vertical strain H. Posterior cranial base strain I. Torsion J. Sphenobasilar synchondrosis compression

question:
I've been feeling really off for the past eight months, and it's been tough. I used to walk two miles every day without breaking a sweat, but now I struggle to make it half a mile before I'm completely wiped out. Climbing just one flight of stairs leaves me breathless, and it's scary to think about how quickly my stamina has dropped. 

I’m 70, and while I’ve dealt with high blood pressure and arthritis for a while, this fatigue is different. I take lisinopril and aspirin daily, and occasionally Tylenol for pain. I haven’t noticed any weight loss or any blood in my stool or urine, but I can’t shake this feeling something isn’t right. 

When I went to the doctor, they did a physical exam. I saw the concern in their eyes when they noted my pale skin and dry hands. They took my vitals, and I felt a knot in my stomach when they mentioned my heart rate was elevated. 

I haven't had a colonoscopy in eight years, but they said my last one showed benign polyps, so I thought I was in the clear. Now, I’m left wondering what’s causing this fatigue. I just want to feel like myself again, and the uncertainty is really weighing on me. What’s next? I’m anxious about what they might find.
options: A. CT scan abdomen B. Capsule endoscopy C. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy (EGD) D. Reticulocyte count analysis E. Packed red blood cell transfusion F. Colonoscopy G. Bone marrow biopsy H. Oral iron supplementation I. Peripheral blood smear J. IV iron supplementation

question:
I can’t shake this nagging worry that something might be seriously wrong with me. Just recently, I started experiencing mild shortness of breath and this annoying cough that just won’t go away. It’s been chronic and dry, which has me feeling more anxious than ever. I thought I was in good health for a 65-year-old woman, never smoked a day in my life, and I’ve kept up with all my cancer screenings. 

When I went to see the doctor, my vital signs were normal, and my oxygen levels were decent. But then they did a chest X-ray, and I learned I have a moderate left pleural effusion. That phrase keeps echoing in my mind—what does it mean? The thought of fluid around my lungs is terrifying. 

They did a thoracentesis, and I can’t help but feel uneasy about the results. The fluid they took out was light-green, and I read the analysis: the pH was low, and there were abnormal cell findings. The waiting for more tests is unbearable. 

I keep worrying about what could be causing all this. I’m just desperate for answers and praying it’s not something dire. What if I end up with a chronic condition? My mind races with all the possibilities. I can’t shake this feeling of dread.
options: A. Sclerodactyly with skin tightening B. Joint hypermobility with skin hyperextensibility C. Gottron's papules over the knuckles D. Raynaud's phenomenon with digital ulcers E. Scattered, seborrheic keratoses over the chest and back F. Clubbing of the digits G. Synovitis of the metacarpophalangeal joints and subcutaneous nodules H. Erythema nodosum on the shins I. Morning stiffness in the proximal interphalangeal joints J. Butterfly rash across the nasal bridge

question:
I’ve been feeling increasingly short of breath over the past two months, and honestly, it’s been terrifying. At 75, living with hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and coronary artery disease already keeps me on edge, but this is something else. My breathing seems to be getting worse, and I can’t shake the feeling that something is seriously wrong.

I went to see the doctor, and during the examination, I could feel my heart racing and my breathing was so labored. I overheard them say my oxygen levels were only at 88%, which made me panic a bit. They listened to my lungs and noted that there was something strange going on in the lower part of my left lung. The doctor mentioned a chest CT scan, which revealed a significant pleural effusion on the left side. 

Then came the thoracentesis—1400 mL of bloody fluid was taken out. That was alarming. The doctor said the fluid tests didn’t show any signs of infection or cancer, but I can’t help but worry about what might be causing this. I feel uneasy and scared, and I keep wondering what the next steps will be. What if they can’t figure out what’s wrong? I just want to breathe normally again and not feel this weight pressing down on me.
options: A. Pleural fluid amylase measurement B. Positron emission tomography (PET) scan C. Closed pleural biopsy D. Serum protein electrophoresis E. Bronchoscopy F. Interferon-gamma release assay of blood G. Repeat thoracentesis with cytopathologic study H. Pleural fluid flow cytometry I. Video-assisted thoracoscopic surgery (VATS) J. Echocardiography

question:
I still can't shake the worry from today. My 9-year-old daughter started experiencing shortness of breath out of nowhere, and then I noticed her lips had turned a worrying shade of blue. It was terrifying. She has a complicated heart history, including dextrocardia and a double inlet left ventricle, so I knew we had to get her help right away.

When we arrived at the hospital, her oxygen saturation was only 81%. I could feel my heart racing as they rushed her in for a physical exam. The doctors mentioned her rapid breathing and the tachycardia they observed. They did an ECG, which thankfully showed sinus rhythm, and an echocardiogram that revealed her left ventricular function was normal. But still, why was she turning blue? 

I couldn’t help but feel overwhelmed by the uncertainty. They discussed additional tests to figure out the cause of her cyanosis, and I felt a sinking feeling in my stomach. Each option they mentioned—like a CT angiogram or cardiac catheterization—made me more anxious about the risks involved. I just want to understand what’s happening to her and hope we can find a solution soon. The thought of her condition worsening is almost too much to bear.
options: A. A BNP level of 150 pg/mL B. A subcostal echocardiographic image demonstrating a mean gradient of 3 mmHg through the Fontan conduit C. A D-dimer level of 250 ng/mL D. A chest X-ray showing normal pulmonary vasculature E. A CT angiogram showing patent Fontan pathway F. An albumin of 1.8 G. An activated protein C resistance ratio of 0.3 H. A protein S level of 85% I. An antithrombin III activity of 95% J. A cardiac catheterization showing mean pulmonary artery pressure of 15 mmHg

question:
For the past three months, I’ve been suffering from these terrible migraine headaches. I can’t shake the feeling that something is really wrong. I came to this osteopathic clinic hoping for some help, but honestly, I was feeling pretty desperate. The migraines have been relentless, and while I’ve tried several medications, they only provide temporary relief. It’s so frustrating.

During my visit, the doctor examined me and found a strain at the sphenobasilar synchondrosis. I didn’t even know that was a thing! My sacral base is apparently tilted anteriorly. I can’t help but worry about what this all means. I’m anxious that this could lead to more serious issues. The doctor mentioned something about osteopathic manipulative treatment, and now I’m wondering if that’s really going to help or if I’m just grasping at straws.

I keep thinking about what else might be going on. What if there’s something more severe causing my headaches? I can’t help but feel overwhelmed by the uncertainty. I just want to understand what’s happening to my body and find a way to stop these migraines once and for all.
options: A. Decreased anteroposterior diameter of the head B. External rotation of the parietal and temporal bones C. Compression of the fourth ventricle D. Internal rotation of the parietal and temporal bones E. Widening of the transverse diameter of the cranium F. Increased cranial rhythmic impulse amplitude G. Sacral base posteriorly tilted H. Flattened occiput with posterior displacement I. Increased anteroposterior diameter of the head J. Cephalad deviation of the sphenobasilar synchondrosis

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry since our 4-month-old son’s last checkup. During the routine visit, the doctor seemed concerned about how he’s been so distressed at night. We’ve been trying to wean him off nighttime feedings, but every time 3-4 hours pass without him eating, he becomes inconsolable. It’s heartbreaking to see him so upset. 

The growth assessment was troubling too; he’s slipped from the 25th to the 5th percentile in length, while his weight has stayed at the 25th percentile. I can’t help but notice how different he looks. His face has this fullness that I can’t quite describe, and his abdomen is so distended. His limbs seem so thin, it makes me anxious. 

What really shook me was when the doctor felt his liver—it extends down to his iliac crest, but thank goodness his spleen seems normal. I just feel like something is wrong, especially after they drew blood. The results showed this milky white layer on top, and I can’t stop worrying about what it means for him. All these possible diagnoses are swirling in my mind, and I just want to make sure he’s okay. I can’t help but feel scared about what might be going on with my little boy.
options: A. Prader-Willi syndrome B. Congenital hyperinsulinism C. Carnitine palmitoyltransferase II deficiency D. Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase deficiency E. Gaucher disease F. Lipoprotein lipase deficiency G. Glycogen storage disease type 1 H. Tay-Sachs disease I. Familial hypercholesterolemia J. Niemann-Pick disease type A

question:
I can't shake this feeling of anxiety lately. I’m a 15-year-old girl, and I’ve been living with phenylketonuria (PKU) since I was born. I remember the moment I found out; my confirmatory test showed my phenylalanine level was way higher than it should have been. Ever since then, I’ve been careful about what I eat, keeping my levels mostly in check during my childhood.

But now, at school, it’s becoming really tough. The phenylalanine-free formula I have to drink smells so strong, and there’s no way to keep it cold. I’ve been thinking about switching to cafeteria meals, and I’m even considering a vegetarian diet. I just want to fit in and not feel so different from everyone else.

However, I can’t help but worry about what this unrestricted vegetarian diet could mean for me. What if I start to experience health issues? I’ve heard that it could lead to some serious problems like cognitive decline or even irreversible damage. The thought of mood swings or growth delays terrifies me. I’m constantly battling these thoughts in my head, wondering if I’m making the right choice or if I’m putting myself at risk. I just want to make sure I’m doing the best for my health, but it feels overwhelming.
options: A. Hyperammonemia and acute mental status changes B. Mild cognitive impairment with preserved executive function C. Progressive vision loss and retinal degeneration D. Reversible neurological symptoms without long-term consequences E. None — a diet free of animal protein is sufficient to provide metabolic control F. Mood dysregulation, inattentiveness, and hyperactivity G. Growth delay and osteoporosis H. Anxiety and depression without cognitive changes I. Cognitive decline and irreversible demyelination J. Gastrointestinal symptoms and malabsorption

question:
I can hardly believe what just happened. Just two hours ago, I was feeling fine, but then everything changed so quickly. I suddenly had trouble speaking, and it felt like my right side just went numb. I couldn't even lift my right arm or leg properly! It was terrifying. I remember sitting there, trying to make sense of it all, but my words wouldn’t come out right.

When the ambulance arrived, I was scared. I thought maybe it was just my diabetes acting up, but deep down, I knew something was really wrong. I’ve been managing type 2 diabetes and hypertension for years, but this felt different. They brought me to the emergency department, and I could tell they were concerned too. I was alert, but when they asked me the month and my age, I just couldn’t answer. My mind was racing, and I felt so helpless as they noticed my right facial droop and weakness.

Every moment felt like an eternity. I kept thinking about everything I’ve been through with my health—smoking for so long, dealing with high blood pressure and cholesterol. I just wanted to know what was happening to me. As they started asking questions and checking my vitals, I could feel the weight of worry pressing down on me. What was the next step? I really hope they figure this out soon.
options: A. Carotid duplex ultrasound B. Computerized tomography (CT) of the head C. Intravenous (IV) tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) D. Aspirin E. Fingerstick glucose level F. Electrocardiogram (ECG) G. Neurological consultation H. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brain I. Echocardiogram J. Complete blood count with coagulation profile

question:
I can hardly believe what happened to me. I’m 34, and this is the third time this month I’ve felt this awful sensation in my chest. It feels like something is stuck there, and it’s terrifying. This time, it was triggered by the news about my dad's heart attack. I was at the emergency department, and the discomfort lasted a full 15 minutes. 

I’ve had these episodes before, usually at the gym when I’m drinking sports drinks, but they would go away after a little rest. Now, I’ve been struggling with swallowing for months, and it’s becoming more concerning. I don’t feel like I have palpitations or trouble breathing, but the thought that something might be seriously wrong weighs heavily on me.

My medical history isn’t great either; I’m dealing with obesity and chronic GERD, which I manage with omeprazole. My mom has scleroderma, so there’s a lot of worry that runs in the family. I try to take care of myself, drinking socially but avoiding tobacco and drugs. 

While I was being examined, my vital signs showed some high blood pressure, but they said I wasn’t in acute distress. Still, I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety about what’s really going on inside me. What if this is something serious? I just want answers and to feel normal again.
options: A. Nuclear stress test B. Esophageal manometry C. 24-hour pH monitoring D. Esophageal scintigraphy E. High-resolution esophageal ultrasound F. Barium swallow G. Electrocardiogram H. Endoscopy I. Impedance testing J. Chest CT with contrast

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of dread since my visit to the doctor. Two weeks ago, I started noticing swelling in my legs. At first, I thought it was just fatigue or something minor, but it hasn’t gone away. I mentioned it to my doctor, along with some other troubling symptoms—joint pain, headaches, frothy urine, and this weird tingling in my fingers and toes. I tried to convince myself that they weren’t connected to the swelling, but deep down, I’m not so sure. 

I have a history of rheumatoid arthritis, diabetes, and hypertension, so I guess I should have expected that something might be off. During the exam, the doctor noted the swelling in my legs was quite pronounced, and they seemed genuinely concerned. The mention of cardiac enlargement in the chest radiograph left me feeling uneasy. And then there’s the urinalysis; the results showed protein in my urine and some concerning casts. 

I keep wondering what all this could mean. The doctor didn’t dive into specifics, but I can’t help but think about what could be causing this edema. The uncertainty is overwhelming. I’m worried about my health and what might be happening with my body. Am I facing something serious? What’s next?
options: A. Elevated levels of IL-6 B. Elevated levels of hemoglobin A1c C. Antibodies to phospholipase A2 receptor D. Increased serum TNF-alpha levels E. Abnormally shaped red blood cells F. Elevated serum complement levels G. Decreased serum albumin with normal globulins H. Anti-nuclear antibodies with homogeneous pattern I. Altered kappa to lambda ratio J. Elevated rheumatoid factor titers

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread as I think back to yesterday. My 5-year-old daughter started complaining about her stomach hurting, and it just kept getting worse. By the next day, her pain was so intense that I knew something was seriously wrong. She hadn't had a bowel movement in 72 hours, and honestly, I’ve seen her struggle with constipation before, but this felt different. 

To make things worse, she started vomiting three times throughout the night and refused to eat anything. I remember watching her, so small and fragile, and felt completely helpless. When we got to the doctor’s office, they examined her stomach, and I could see that they were concerned too. Her upper abdomen was swollen, and they mentioned something about tympany, but thankfully, there were no signs of an abdominal mass or other alarming symptoms. 

Still, I’m left in a state of worry, thinking about what could be causing all this. I can’t stop wondering if it’s something serious, like Hirschsprung disease or even something more complicated. The uncertainty is eating away at me, and I just want to know that my little girl will be okay.
options: A. Hirschsprung disease B. Intestinal lymphoma C. Superior mesenteric artery syndrome D. Chronic intestinal pseudo-obstruction E. Volvulus F. Malrotation of the gut G. Pyloric stenosis H. Intussusception I. Meckel diverticulum J. Duodenal web

question:
I took my 4-year-old son to the clinic for what I thought would be just a routine well-child checkup. I was feeling a bit anxious anyway because he started walking so late at 20 months. He can drink from a cup, but he still can’t use silverware, and his speech is limited to just 2-word phrases. He can stack four blocks and scribble, but he can’t even draw a circle. 

As I sat there, I noticed that his height was way above the 99th percentile, while his weight was only at the 15th percentile. That didn't sit well with me. The doctor examined him and found some concerning things. He mentioned bilateral inferior lens dislocation, long slender fingers, a high-arched palate, and hyperelastic skin. My heart sank when I saw how his thumb and fifth finger overlapped when he wrapped one hand around the other wrist. 

I felt a wave of worry wash over me. What could all of this mean? I wanted to understand why my son was experiencing these issues. The doctor talked about various conditions, but I couldn’t help but feel overwhelmed, fearing the worst. I just want to know how to help him and what the future holds.
options: A. Fibrillin 1 deficiency B. Procollagen peptidase deficiency C. Type I collagen mutation D. Deficiency of pyridoxine-dependent enzymes E. Alpha-1,4-glucosidase deficiency F. Mutation in the FGFR3 gene G. Type V collagen deficiency H. Lysyl hydroxylase deficiency I. Homogentisic acid oxidase deficiency J. Cystathionine synthase deficiency

question:
I can't shake this feeling of worry after my recent visit to the clinic for my annual checkup. It’s been a tough few days since I had that tooth extraction due to an infection. I’m on amoxicillin-clavulanate now, and they prescribed me hydrocodone-acetaminophen for the pain, which I’ve been taking twice daily for the last couple of days. 

I thought I was managing okay—after all, I have my diabetes and mild reflux to deal with, but I’ve been feeling relatively well overall. However, there’s one thing that’s really concerning me: I haven’t had a bowel movement in six days. That’s not normal for me at all! I keep thinking about my medications. Could it be the hydrocodone? I know constipation can be a side effect, and with my iron supplements and everything else, I just feel a bit overwhelmed. 

I don’t want to ignore this, but I'm really worried about what this could mean for my health. Should I call my doctor again? I just hope this isn’t something serious. It feels like so much is weighing on me right now.
options: A. Ferrous sulfate B. Phenformin C. Levofloxacin D. Cefdinir E. Metformin F. Amoxicillin-clavulanate G. Magnesium hydroxide H. Magnesium citrate I. Hydrocodone-acetaminophen J. Oxycodone

question:
I recently went in for a routine check-up, just a regular visit to my primary care doctor. But during the urinalysis, I was shocked to learn that they found 3+ protein and a couple of red blood cells in my urine. I had no symptoms and felt fine, but now I can’t shake this feeling of worry. I don’t have any family history of kidney issues, and I don’t smoke or drink, so why is this happening?

My vital signs seemed okay—my temperature was normal, blood pressure was fine, and my pulse was steady. The physical exam didn’t show anything unusual either, which only adds to my anxiety. It’s like I’m caught in this limbo of feeling perfectly fine but knowing there’s something potentially wrong inside me.

Now, I can’t help but wonder what the next step should be. Should I just wait it out, or do I need more tests? What if it’s something serious? The thought of needing to see a nephrologist or undergoing more invasive procedures like a biopsy haunts me. I’m trying to stay calm, but the uncertainty is overwhelming. All I want is to understand what’s going on with my health.
options: A. Repeating the urine dipstick test B. 24-hour urine collection C. Referring to a nephrologist immediately D. Ordering a renal biopsy E. Performing a kidney ultrasound F. Prescribing a low-protein diet G. Testing for urinary Bence Jones proteins H. Starting captopril I. Measuring serum albumin and creatinine J. Initiating corticosteroid therapy

question:
I can hardly believe what happened. Just yesterday, I was at the construction site, working like I always do. But then, everything went dark. I woke up in the emergency department, completely confused and unable to communicate. It felt surreal. 

I remember feeling so hot, like my body was on fire, and I was drenched in sweat. I overheard the doctors talking about my vital signs—my temperature was a staggering 105°F. My heart was racing at 150 beats per minute, which just adds to my anxiety. I’ve had a history of seizures and schizophrenia, and I worry that my medication might have contributed to this chaos. I’ve been on haloperidol for a while, and now I'm scared it could be something more serious. 

I can’t shake the feeling that something went terribly wrong. It’s terrifying to think I was found unconscious by my coworkers. They must have been worried sick. What if I hadn't woken up? I just hope the doctors figure out what’s happening to me. Why can’t I move my arms and legs purposefully? I feel so helpless, and I just want to understand what’s going on.
options: A. Anticholinergic toxicity B. Exertional heat stroke C. Malignant hyperthermia D. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome E. Central nervous system infection F. Drug-induced hyperthermia G. Septic shock H. Nonexertional heat stroke I. Thyroid storm J. Status epilepticus

question:
I can’t shake the terrible feeling that something is deeply wrong. It all started when I was brought into the emergency department, completely unconscious. I was in a haze, but I remember the chaos—doctors rushing around me, the bright lights, and the coldness in my extremities. I learned later that I was bleeding significantly from my rectum, and my vital signs were alarming: my pulse racing at 110, blood pressure dangerously low at 90/60, and my breathing rapid at 26 breaths per minute. 

I had no known medical history, which only added to the confusion and fear. Once I was stabilized with IV fluids and a blood transfusion, I was still terrified. They inserted a nasogastric tube, which thankfully didn’t show any blood, but I could feel the worry around me intensifying when the rectal examination revealed active bleeding. The doctors estimated it was bleeding at a rate of 2-3 mL per minute, but they couldn’t find any obvious cause like hemorrhoids or fissures. 

Now, I’m left wondering what’s going to happen next. What’s causing this bleeding? Should they do a colonoscopy or something more invasive? I can’t help but feel a sense of dread about what’s coming. I just want to know that I’ll be okay.
options: A. Repeat nasogastric lavage B. Exploratory laparotomy with segmental bowel resection C. Colonoscopy D. Push enteroscopy E. Capsule endoscopy F. Magnetic resonance angiography (MRA) G. CT angiography of the abdomen and pelvis H. Mesenteric angiography I. Upper endoscopy J. Tagged red blood cell scintigraphy

question:
I can't shake off this growing worry about my left knee. It’s been hurting for over a year now, and I've tried icing it and resting, but the pain just lingers. Recently, I bumped my knee, and I was afraid it would make things worse, but at least it didn’t change the pain when I walk. I work as a butcher, so I’m always on my feet, and I can’t afford to let this pain take control of my life.

I live with my wife, who’s been supportive, but I feel like I’m letting her down. On top of all this, I’m managing my diabetes with insulin and metformin and juggling high blood pressure meds, which makes everything feel more complicated. I’ve been trying to attend Alcoholics Anonymous, but I haven't seen much progress there either.

At my doctor’s appointment, they noted some mild redness and bruising on my knee, but thankfully, it didn’t hurt when they moved it around. Still, I noticed I’ve been walking a bit differently to avoid the pain. I can’t help but wonder what’s next. What if I need a more serious treatment? I just want to be able to walk without worrying about this constant ache. I’m anxious about what my doctor might suggest as the first step to manage this situation.
options: A. MRI B. Intra-articular corticosteroid injection C. Knee replacement evaluation D. Glucosamine supplementation E. Physical therapy referral F. Colchicine G. Joint immobilization H. Arthroscopic debridement I. Weight loss J. Aspirin

question:
I can’t shake this nagging worry that something is seriously wrong with my back. It all started about two weeks ago when I found myself glued to my computer for hours on end, racing to meet a major project deadline. I thought it was just fatigue at first, but the pain in my back has only gotten worse. 

I finally decided to seek medical attention because the discomfort was becoming unbearable. The doctor examined me and noted that my paraspinal muscles felt hypertonic and tender. That really got me anxious. I never had any significant health issues before, and I can’t recall any trauma that could have caused this. 

What really concerned me was when the doctor checked around my scapula. There was this sharp tenderness I felt during the motion testing, and I could see the worry in the doctor’s eyes too. When I leaned forward, it seemed like my left side was moving oddly, which just added to my anxiety. 

I keep thinking about what could be happening with my spine. I don’t want this to turn into something more serious, and I’m left feeling completely unsettled as I wait for answers. What if this is just the beginning of a long, painful journey?
options: A. T4 NRRSR B. T5 NSLSL C. T2–T6 NSLRR D. T5 ERRSL E. T6 FRLSR F. T5 NRRSL G. T6 ERLSL H. T4 FRLSL I. T5 FRRSR J. T6 FRRSL

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety as I sit in the doctor’s office for my sports clearance evaluation. I’m 19 and a dedicated athlete, but I can’t ignore my past—I've had multiple spontaneous pneumothoraces, which still haunt me. Right now, I feel fine, but the thought of what could go wrong is always at the back of my mind.

During the physical exam, the doctor pointed out some things I didn’t even realize were concerning. Apparently, I have joint hypermobility, and then there’s this chest wall deformity called pectus excavatum. It’s so unsettling to think that my body isn't quite as it should be. The doctor even mentioned my upper-to-lower body segment ratio is off, which just adds to my worry.

Now, I'm sitting here, wondering what else they might find during the examination. It feels like there could be hidden issues lurking beneath the surface. What if they discover something serious? I’ve heard about conditions like mitral valve prolapse and scoliosis, and the thought of having any of those makes my heart race. I just want to be cleared for sports so I can focus on my training, but I can’t help but feel anxious about what could be revealed. What if there’s more to this than I know?
options: A. Pes planus (flat feet) B. Mitral valve prolapse C. Arachnodactyly (long, slender fingers) D. Kyphosis E. A midsystolic ejection murmur heard best over the right second intercostal space F. Increased arm span-to-height ratio G. Thoracolumbar scoliosis H. Hyperopia I. Aortic root dilation J. Lens dislocation (ectopia lentis)

question:
I recently went in for a follow-up appointment, and I have to admit, I was feeling pretty anxious. It’s been three months since I started taking estradiol and micronized progesterone to help with my menopausal hot flashes. While I’ve noticed some improvement in my symptoms and my mood has been better, I can’t shake this feeling of worry. 

I’ve been dealing with dry skin, occasional constipation, and this constant, mild fatigue that just doesn’t seem to go away. Thankfully, I haven’t experienced any falls or fractures, but with my history of hypertension, dyslipidemia, osteoporosis, and Hashimoto’s, I can’t help but feel overwhelmed. 

During the appointment, my doctor reviewed my medications—lisinopril, atorvastatin, alendronate, cholecalciferol, and levothyroxine. I know I’m on a lot, and I keep wondering if they’re interacting in ways I don’t understand. I’m particularly concerned about my thyroid function tests. I saw that my TSH levels have changed significantly since my last test, and I can’t help but think it could be the estradiol, or maybe the calcium I’m taking for osteoporosis? 

All these thoughts keep racing through my mind, and I just want to make sure I’m doing everything I can to manage my health. It’s so hard not to feel anxious when you know your body is going through so many changes.
options: A. Initiation of estradiol B. Impact of changes in body weight C. Interference from concurrent progesterone therapy D. Seasonal variation in thyroid function E. Drug interaction with atorvastatin F. Interaction between alendronate and levothyroxine G. Inadequate levothyroxine dose adjustment H. Interference of levothyroxine absorption by calcium supplementation I. Progression of underlying Hashimoto's thyroiditis J. Drug interaction with omeprazole

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that has been hanging over me since my diagnosis. I had been feeling unwell for a while, and after some blood work, they told me I had pancytopenia. I thought that would lead to answers, but I waited six long months without any follow-up. During that time, my condition only got worse, and I felt completely lost and scared about what was happening to my body. 

When they finally diagnosed me with hairy-cell leukemia, I was overwhelmed. How could this happen? I learned that there had been a root cause analysis conducted to figure out what went wrong, which made me feel a bit better. But then I started to wonder—what should be done next? It seems like there are so many options on the table, and I worry that if they don’t choose the right path, someone else could end up in the same situation I did. 

Should they focus on the physician who missed the follow-up? Or create a flowchart to clarify the events? I just want to make sure this doesn’t happen again. The thought of others experiencing this kind of delay terrifies me. I feel anxious about the potential risks in the system and hope they take the right steps to prevent similar errors in the future.
options: A. Focus on individual accountability of the physician who missed follow-up B. Create a flowchart to illustrate the sequence of key events in this case C. Create an action plan to assign responsibilities to prevent similar errors in the future D. Evaluate the current information technology for laboratory management E. Conduct a failure mode and effects analysis to evaluate potential risks in the system F. Perform a time-motion study to identify inefficiencies in result reporting workflows G. Convene a multidisciplinary team to review the laboratory reporting process H. Perform a retrospective chart review of other cases with similar errors I. Identify and address gaps in the electronic medical record system J. Implement a system for automatic alerts for abnormal lab results

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread after what happened to me. I’m 27 and have a history of asthma, which already makes me anxious, but things took a turn for the worse after I was in a car accident. I remember feeling dazed when I got to the emergency department. My heart was racing, and I couldn’t believe my blood pressure was so low—70 over 35! They said my temperature was slightly elevated, and I felt like I was in a fog, struggling to breathe.

The doctors were quick to act, giving me IV fluids and some medications, which thankfully made my blood pressure stabilize a bit. But then, suddenly, I started having serious trouble breathing. I could hear wheezing and felt like I was gasping for air. My heart was pounding even harder, hitting 160 beats per minute. The fear was overwhelming. I remember the panic as they decided to intubate me. I couldn’t help but think about my asthma and how this could all spiral out of control.

I was finally stabilized and transferred to intensive care, but I can’t shake the worry about what’s next. What if my asthma flares up again, or something worse happens? I just want to feel safe and healthy again, but right now, everything feels so uncertain.
options: A. Previous episodes of angioedema B. Anti-A, B, and O antibodies in the serum C. History of beta-lactam allergy D. Irregularly irregular heart rhythm E. Chronic bronchitis and emphysema F. Multiple drug allergies G. Hemolytic anemia and ataxia H. Previous anaphylactic reactions I. History of multiple blood transfusions J. Recurrent pulmonary embolism

question:
I can hardly believe what happened to me. Just a few hours ago, I was found slumped next to my computer, completely out of it. My family discovered me and rushed me to the emergency department. I felt so foggy and disoriented, almost like I was in a dream. They told me they found an empty pill bottle nearby, but I didn’t even remember what I took. I didn’t want to worry them, but inside, I was terrified.

I’ve struggled with anxiety for a long time, and I know I haven’t been taking care of myself—skipping my exercises and ignoring my health. The doctors said my vital signs were mostly normal, but I still felt so vulnerable and scared. When I finally started to talk, I admitted to taking “a few” acetaminophen pills, but my parents thought the bottle was full. I kept asking myself if I did something really bad, and what that meant for my future.

I can’t shake this feeling of dread. I know I need help, but I don’t know what’s going to happen next. I just want to be okay and not feel this overwhelming fear anymore. What if I really hurt myself? The doctors were discussing what to do next, and I just hoped they would act quickly.
options: A. Liver function tests only B. Blood acetaminophen levels C. Empiric flumazenil administration D. N-acetylcysteine E. Lactated ringer bolus F. Charcoal G. Psychiatric consultation H. Comprehensive toxicology screen I. Gastric lavage and observation J. Serial neurological examinations

question:
I can't shake the worry that's been building over the past couple of weeks. My son, just 6 years old, has been running a fever and limping around, holding his right thigh in pain. At first, I thought maybe he just hurt himself during soccer practice, but it’s been two weeks, and he still seems uncomfortable. 

I took him to the doctor, and it was nerve-wracking. He has no rash or joint pain, but with his older sister having lupus, I couldn't help but feel anxious. The doctor said he looked well overall, but when they examined his thigh, I could see the concern in their eyes—swelling, tenderness, warmth, and even some redness. The way he walked, with that limp, broke my heart.

The doctor ran some tests and mentioned his blood work showed some elevated levels, but the X-rays looked fine. Then they did an MRI, and that’s when the real fear set in. I overheard words like "periosteal elevation" and "osteolytic areas." I just felt this sinking feeling in my stomach. 

Now, I’m sitting here waiting to hear what the next steps are—what they will recommend. I can’t help but think about all the possibilities, and I just want my little boy to be okay. What could this mean for him? I feel so helpless.
options: A. MRI with contrast B. Empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics C. CT-guided needle aspiration D. Bone scan E. Surgical debridement F. Bone biopsy of the right femur G. Anti-inflammatory therapy H. Nafcillin therapy I. Arthrocentesis J. Blood culture and observation

question:
I can't shake this terrible feeling that something is really wrong with me. It all started two days ago when I woke up with a sore throat. At first, I thought it was just a cold, but then the coughing kicked in, and my nose became so stuffy. I even had a low-grade fever and those awful body aches. I just felt miserable.

Today, I noticed my cough was getting worse. I started bringing up this thick yellow phlegm, and I could barely catch my breath. My heart raced, and I felt this tightness in my chest that made me panic a little. My mom was really worried, too; she said she heard this weird sound when I breathed. I didn’t want to worry her, but I couldn’t help but feel anxious. I barely ate anything and hardly drank any fluids.

When we went to the doctor, I felt so exhausted and scared. They checked my temperature, and it was 39°C. My heart rate was fast, and my breathing was shallow. I saw the concern in the doctor's eyes when I struggled to breathe. They mentioned something about stridor and retractions, which sounded serious. I just want to feel better and understand what’s happening. Why is this happening to me?
options: A. Group A Streptococcus B. Parainfluenza virus type 1 C. Haemophilus influenzae type b D. Mycoplasma pneumoniae E. Staphylococcus aureus F. Adenovirus G. Influenza A virus H. Respiratory syncytial virus I. Epstein-Barr virus J. Corynebacterium diphtheriae

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread since I had my first seizure. I’m 26 and have been living with HIV for eight years now, managing it with combination antiretroviral therapy. My viral load has been undetectable, and my CD4 count was stable, so I thought I was doing okay. But then, out of nowhere, I experienced this tonic-clonic seizure that lasted two whole minutes. 

When it was over, I felt so confused and disoriented. I could barely follow simple commands. I was really scared to learn that I had a fever, and my neck felt stiff. To make things worse, I noticed weakness on my left side, and they said my reflexes were all messed up, especially that Babinski sign. 

I couldn’t help but wonder what was happening to me. My heart raced as they examined me, and I kept thinking about all the possible complications. I know my condition makes me more vulnerable, and I was terrified that something serious could be going on. I just want to be okay again. I can’t stop worrying about what the doctors will decide as the next step. It feels like everything is spinning out of control, and I need answers fast.
options: A. Start empiric tuberculosis treatment B. Initiate broad-spectrum antifungal coverage C. Administer lorazepam and load with levetiracetam D. Start high-dose trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole E. Order CT of the head F. Obtain blood cultures, and initiate treatment with vancomycin, ceftriaxone, ampicillin, acyclovir, and dexamethasone G. Perform lumbar puncture immediately H. Begin empiric fluconazole therapy I. Begin high-dose ganciclovir therapy J. Perform lumbar puncture

question:
I can hardly believe I’m sitting here, trying to process everything after my first prenatal appointment. At 33 years old, I’m pregnant for the second time, but this wasn’t planned—yet, I really want this baby. I’m only eight weeks along, and already, I’m feeling overwhelmed. 

I’ve struggled with type 2 diabetes for a while now, and my blood sugar levels have been hard to control. My doctor mentioned my pre-pregnancy HbA1c was at 10.1%, which is way above the target. I’m just taking metformin three times a day—what if that’s not enough? 

During the check-up, I learned that my BMI is 35, and my blood pressure is okay, but I can’t shake this anxiety. They did a quick ultrasound and confirmed the heartbeat, which was a relief, but I can’t stop worrying about what could go wrong. The urinalysis showed glucosuria, and I can't help but think about the potential complications that could arise. 

I read somewhere that conditions like placental issues or fetal macrosomia could lead to serious problems. What if something goes wrong with the baby? I’m so scared of the risks involved, especially with my diabetes. I just want to do everything I can to keep this little one safe. I can’t help but feel like I’m walking on a tightrope, and it’s terrifying.
options: A. Placental insufficiency B. Polyhydramnios-related complications C. Neonatal hypoglycemia D. Fetal macrosomia E. Preterm birth F. Major congenital anomaly G. Intrauterine growth restriction H. Uncontrolled maternal hyperglycemia during labor I. Amniotic fluid embolism J. Shoulder dystocia during delivery

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of worry ever since I got tackled during football practice two days ago. I thought I just had a bump and bruise, but now I’m feeling this mild shortness of breath that’s really starting to scare me. It’s like I can’t take a full breath without feeling this sharp pain in my neck and left shoulder. At rest, it’s about a 4 out of 10, but the moment I move my left arm or try to breathe deeply, it gets so much worse. 

I’ve been trying to manage it with ice and taking it easy, which helps a bit, but I’m still uneasy. I noticed that my left collarbone looks a bit elevated compared to the right, which makes me wonder if something’s really wrong. When I touch the area above my collarbone, it’s incredibly tender, and I can’t help but feel anxious about what it means. 

I’m worried that this could be something serious, and I really need to know what's going on. I just want to be able to breathe normally and not feel this constant ache. I’m hoping the doctor can figure this out quickly because I can’t keep feeling like this.
options: A. Acromioclavicular joint separation B. Pectoralis minor syndrome C. Thoracic outlet syndrome D. Clavicular posterior rotation somatic dysfunction E. First rib somatic dysfunction F. Costoclavicular syndrome G. Anterior sternoclavicular joint dislocation H. Subclavian vein thrombosis I. Cervical radiculopathy (C5-C6) J. Posterior and inferior sternoclavicular somatic dysfunction

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming worry after what happened yesterday. I started feeling this intense back pain that shot straight into my abdomen. It was so bad, I rated it a 10 out of 10 during those awful episodes. I’ve always dealt with asthma and anxiety, but this pain felt different—much worse. 

I finally decided I couldn’t wait any longer and rushed to the emergency department. I was terrified. I kept thinking about my past health issues, including having been treated for chlamydia. What if this was something serious? 

The doctors asked about my medical history and what I was feeling. I’m on fluoxetine for anxiety, and I wondered if that was somehow related. They took some blood and did a urinalysis, but it was all a blur—I just wanted answers. 

When they mentioned that I was pregnant, my heart dropped. I had so many questions racing through my mind. What does this mean for me? I was so worried about the implications of everything, especially given my medical background. I just want to know what’s going on and if I’m going to be okay. What’s the right test to figure this out? I’m scared, and I just need clarity.
options: A. Urinalysis with microscopy B. Serum lipase and amylase C. Pelvic examination with cervical cultures D. Renal ultrasound E. CT scan with contrast F. Complete blood count with differential G. Abdominal ultrasound H. Transvaginal ultrasound I. MRI of the abdomen and pelvis J. Urine culture

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread as I think back to the day I brought my two-week-old son to the doctor. He had been so sleepy, barely feeding, and I noticed this awful grunting sound every time he tried to breathe. It all seemed to spiral so quickly; he was born at home, and although everything seemed fine at first, he just wasn’t the same anymore.

I remember the doctor looking at him closely, measuring his temperature, which was normal, but everything else felt alarming. His heart was racing, and his breathing was so fast. I could see his little nostrils flaring, and it broke my heart to notice his skin around his mouth turning a shade of blue. I felt helpless as they checked his belly and found his liver was enlarged. How could this happen?

I couldn’t understand all the medical terms, but the doctor mentioned things like “bounding pulses” and “enlarged cardiac silhouette.” I just kept thinking about how my sweet boy was not thriving. They talked about potential heart conditions, and I was terrified of what that could mean for him. What was wrong with my baby? I’m left with so many questions and a heavy heart, just praying that he gets the care he needs.
options: A. Tetralogy of Fallot B. Patent ductus arteriosus C. Double outlet right ventricle D. Hypoplastic left heart syndrome E. Ebstein anomaly F. Total anomalous pulmonary venous connection G. Tricuspid atresia H. Transposition of the great arteries I. Atrioventricular septal defect J. Truncus arteriosus

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that washed over me when I was brought to the hospital. I remember feeling so confused and out of it, like I was lost in a fog. I couldn’t provide any of my medical history, which only made everything more concerning. 

My mind was racing, but I couldn’t articulate anything. I sensed something serious was happening to my body. I overheard the doctors talking about my vital signs, and they seemed alarmed. I was scared when I heard them mention my sodium and potassium levels—whatever that meant. It felt like I was sinking deeper into a pit of worry.

I caught snippets about my blood gas results, and the numbers they mentioned made my stomach drop. A pH of 7.12? That sounded really bad. I was struggling to breathe, and the fact that my oxygen levels were low added to my panic. I could see the concern in the faces of the medical staff, and it terrified me. 

I just wanted to understand what was happening, but all I could do was sit there, lost and overwhelmed. I couldn’t help but feel that I was in a life-or-death situation, and I desperately wanted to pull through this confusion and fear.
options: A. Primary respiratory alkalosis with metabolic compensation B. Primary respiratory acidosis with metabolic compensation C. Primary metabolic acidosis with an anion gap D. Mixed metabolic acidosis and metabolic alkalosis E. Primary metabolic acidosis without concomitant process F. Non-anion gap metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation G. Primary metabolic acidosis with concomitant respiratory acidosis H. Mixed respiratory acidosis and metabolic alkalosis I. Compensated metabolic acidosis with normal respiratory function J. Primary metabolic acidosis with respiratory alkalosis

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread. Just a few days ago, during a basketball game, I felt something tear in my knee. I brushed it off at first, thinking it was just a minor injury. But now, I can barely walk without my right foot slapping against the floor. It’s so frustrating! My foot doesn’t lift properly, and I’m scared I might have done something serious. 

I've been trying to stay positive, but the bruising on my leg is alarming. It started off as a little discoloration, but it’s been getting worse. I went to see a neurologist, hoping for some reassurance, but it only made me feel more anxious. When the doctor examined me, they rated the strength of my right foot’s dorsiflexion at just 2 out of 5. That’s when panic really set in. What if this is something that affects my ability to walk normally? 

I keep worrying about what I might have done to myself. I’ve heard about potential complications from knee injuries, and I can’t help but think about what that could mean for my future. What if this is something serious? The thought just gnaws at me. I hope it’s nothing worse than a simple injury, but I can’t shake this overwhelming concern.
options:
A. It causes numbness of the lateral foot. B. It affects the lateral compartment muscles primarily. C. It causes numbness between the first and second toes. D. It results in loss of ankle plantar flexion. E. It causes weakness of great toe extension only.

### Input

**Original Question:**
A 25-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a 2-day history of fever, chills, and severe headache. She has no significant past medical history and takes no medications. Her temperature is 39.5°C (103.1°F), blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse is 100/min, and respiratory rate is 18/min. Physical examination reveals nuchal rigidity and photophobia. Lumbar puncture reveals an opening pressure of 250 mm H2O, glucose of 45 mg/dL (serum glucose 90 mg/dL), protein of 55 mg/dL, and WBC count of 100/μL with 95% lymphocytes. Which of the following is the most likely causative organism? F. It primarily affects gastrocnemius function. G. It causes weakness of toe flexion. H. It causes weakness of ankle inversion. I. It causes numbness of the anterolateral lower leg. J. It is likely functional because the patient can evert his foot.

question:
I can hardly shake off this nagging feeling of worry after my recent check-up. I’m 32 years old and currently 26 weeks along with my third pregnancy, which already has me on edge. The doctors have been monitoring my anti-D titers, and I just learned that my latest lab results are above the critical threshold. Just hearing that sent a chill down my spine. 

I can’t help but think about how this could impact my baby. They mentioned something about the titers being sensitized, and I feel completely overwhelmed. I keep asking myself what the next step will be. Should I be preparing for an early delivery at 32 weeks? Or is it better to wait and check the titers again in a week? 

I’ve read up on some options like plasmapheresis and corticosteroids, but the thought of needing any of those treatments makes me anxious. I just want to ensure that my baby is safe and healthy. I can’t stop wondering if I’m doing enough or if I should be more proactive about all of this. It feels like I’m just waiting for the next piece of information, but the uncertainty is so unsettling. I just hope everything turns out alright.
options: A. Recommend delivery at 32 weeks gestation B. Repeat anti-D titers in 1 week C. Initiate maternal plasmapheresis D. Recommend corticosteroids for fetal lung maturity, then immediate delivery E. Administer corticosteroids to the mother F. Order peak systolic velocity of the fetal middle cerebral artery G. Monitor fetal heart rate variability with continuous cardiotocography H. Recommend repeat titer in 4 weeks I. Perform a cordocentesis to assess fetal hemoglobin J. Schedule an immediate amniocentesis

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry after what happened to my grandfather. He’s 87 and has been living in a subacute nursing facility due to his Parkinson’s and history of stroke. Lately, I've noticed he seems more confused than usual, and he’s been withdrawing from conversations. It’s heartbreaking to see him like this.

I visited him recently, and he was wearing his hearing aids, which looked clean and seemed to be working fine. He mentioned he wasn’t experiencing any ringing in his ears, but I couldn’t help but feel something was off. When I looked closer, I saw dark, paste-like debris in both of his ears, especially in the right one. It looked concerning, and I couldn’t understand how it got there.

The staff did some tests, and even after taking out his hearing aids, they found that sound was more pronounced in his right ear. It just added to my anxiety. I can't help but worry about what this means for him. Is it just earwax buildup, or could it be something more serious? The thought of him struggling with his hearing on top of everything else is really weighing on me. I just want to make sure he gets the care he needs.
options: A. Bilateral cerumen impaction with greater severity on the right B. Presbycusis that is greater on the right C. Conductive hearing loss that is greater on the right D. Left-sided otosclerosis E. Sensorineural hearing loss on the left F. Age-related cochlear degeneration G. Central auditory processing disorder H. Noise-induced hearing loss affecting the left ear I. Meniere disease with right-sided predominance J. Eustachian tube dysfunction affecting the right ear

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that settled over me while I was in the hospital. I’m 41 and have cerebral palsy, so being bedbound has always been a part of my life, but I never expected to face something like this. I was admitted for a urinary tract infection related to my catheter, and by the third day, everything took a turn for the worse.
