I started having trouble breathing, and it felt like the walls were closing in around me. My oxygen levels plummeted to 87%, and I was terrified. They put me on oxygen through a nasal cannula, and it helped bring my levels back up to 98%, but I couldn’t shake the panic.

The doctors examined me, and I could see their concern as they noted my trachea was deviated to the right and heard diminished breath sounds on my right side. They did some tests and imaging, and I could tell from their expressions that things weren’t good. My right lung was completely opaque, and I was left wondering what would happen next. I felt so vulnerable, and all I could think about was what they would do to help me. I wish I could communicate my fears and ask them to make it all go away. I just want to breathe easily again.
options: A. Chest tube placement B. Administer IV furosemide C. High-flow nasal cannula oxygen therapy D. Chest physiotherapy E. Incentive spirometry F. Needle decompression thoracostomy G. Endotracheal intubation H. Bronchoscopy with lavage I. Postural drainage and percussion J. Empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread that settled in the pit of my stomach last week when I noticed my 2-year-old son was constantly getting sick. For the past week, he’s been vomiting and having diarrhea, and it’s just heartbreaking to see him like this. He throws up everything he eats or drinks, and I feel so helpless. I rushed him to the emergency department because I was terrified he was getting worse.

He usually seems so lively, but now he’s crying and just doesn’t have the energy he used to. I feel like I’m failing him somehow. I’ve been trying to piece it all together—he goes to daycare, but I have no idea if he was exposed to someone who was sick. Thankfully, he’s otherwise healthy and up to date with his vaccinations, but seeing him like this is a nightmare.

His temperature was slightly elevated, and his heart was racing. He was crying but could be comforted, which gives me a tiny bit of hope, but then I noticed he wasn’t even making tears anymore. I can’t help but worry about what might be happening inside his little body. I know he needs help, and I just hope they can figure out what’s wrong with him before it gets worse.
options: A. Hyponatremia B. Hyperchloremia C. Hypocalcemia D. Hypokalemia E. Hypophosphatemia F. Metabolic acidosis with normal sodium levels G. Hyperkalemia H. Hypernatremia I. Pseudohyponatremia J. Hypermagnesemia

question:
I can't shake the feeling of worry that's been creeping in over the past few months. I’m 16, and I just went to the pediatrician because I haven’t had my period at all. It’s been really unsettling. On top of that, I’ve been feeling incredibly fatigued and cold, and I’ve had issues with constipation that just won’t go away. 

To make matters worse, my migraines, which I've dealt with for years, have been happening more often, especially with the aura. It’s been affecting my performance on the track team, and I feel like I’m letting everyone down. I can’t help but notice that my mom and sister both started their periods at 15, so the fact that I’m still waiting is really concerning.

At the doctor’s office, I was weighed and measured—I’m 5 feet 4 inches and weigh only 100 pounds, which I can’t help but think is too low. They said my vital signs were normal, but I felt so pale and noticed my hair is thinning. It’s terrifying to think something might be seriously wrong with me. 

I just want answers. The doctor mentioned tests to figure out what’s going on, and I’m left feeling anxious about what could be causing all of this. What’s wrong with me?
options: A. MRI of the pituitary gland B. Bone age radiograph C. TSH level D. Pelvic exam E. FSH and estrogen levels F. LH and testosterone levels G. Anti-thyroid peroxidase (anti-TPO) antibodies H. Serum ferritin level I. Serum cortisol level J. Complete blood count with differential

question:
I can’t shake off this overwhelming feeling of worry. It all started a few months ago when I began experiencing this persistent aching pain in my wrists and fingers. It’s been so bad that some days I can hardly get through my daily tasks. The pain doesn’t just stop during the day; it keeps me up at night, and I’ve even been having these night sweats that leave me drenched. I’ve noticed my appetite has also taken a nosedive, which isn’t like me at all.

When I finally went to see a doctor, I was anxious about what they might find. The examination revealed that my wrists and fingers were swollen, but thankfully, there was no tenderness. Still, I can’t help but feel uneasy about it all. My vital signs showed a slightly elevated temperature and my blood pressure was concerning. I heard the doctor mention something about my blood work showing protein in my urine and some other abnormalities, but I couldn’t focus on the details. 

It’s terrifying to think about what could be causing all this. I keep reading about possible complications and I’m left wondering how serious this could be. What if it leads to something more severe? I can’t shake the feeling that I need answers, and fast.
options: A. Coronary artery disease B. Thrombotic complications C. Cardiac tamponade D. Cerebrovascular disease E. Renal cell carcinoma F. Community acquired pneumonia G. Pulmonary hypertension H. Systemic vasculitis I. End-stage renal disease J. Pulmonary fibrosis

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of panic after what happened to me recently. It all started out of nowhere when I suddenly felt this sharp, stabbing pain in my chest that made it hard to breathe. The pain was so intense, especially when I took a deep breath. I rushed to the emergency department because I knew something was really wrong. 

To make things worse, my left leg had been swollen and painful for the past few days. I thought it was just a minor issue, but now I can’t help but worry. I’m only 25 and generally healthy, other than taking my birth control. 

When I got to the hospital, they checked my vitals. My heart rate was racing at 115 beats per minute, and my oxygen levels were a bit low at 93%. I felt so anxious seeing the doctors look concerned as they examined me. They found that my left leg was swollen, and I could see the worry on their faces too. 

I’ve had all my Covid vaccines, and thankfully, that test came back negative. But now I’m left wondering what could be causing all of this. I just want answers. What if it’s something serious? I need to know what tests they’re going to run next. I can’t shake this feeling of dread.
options: A. Troponin measurement B. D-dimer testing C. Arterial blood gas analysis D. High-sensitivity CRP measurement E. Transthoracic echocardiogram F. Exercise stress test G. CT pulmonary angiography H. Chest X-ray I. Ventilation-perfusion scan J. Serum D-dimer testing

question:
I've been dealing with this nagging pain and swelling in my right ankle for weeks now, and I can't shake the worry that something is seriously wrong. I didn’t hurt it—there was no trauma at all—but the discomfort is just getting worse. I’ve been taking NSAIDs, hoping they'd help, but they haven’t made any difference. 

When I went to the doctor, my temperature was normal, but my heart was racing a little, and my breathing felt off. The examination was concerning; my ankle was tender to the touch, and I could barely move it. They mentioned something about chondrocalcinosis and joint effusion in the right talotibial joint after the imaging. It sounds alarming, and I can’t help but wonder what it all means for me. 

I keep thinking about what might be causing this. The thought of having a serious condition is weighing heavily on my mind. I need answers and a treatment plan soon because the pain is affecting my daily life, and I’m worried about what this could mean for my health in the long run. I just want to feel normal again.
options: A. Hyperparathyroidism B. Hemochromatosis C. Wilson disease D. Hyperuricemia E. Hyperphosphatemia F. Hypocalcemia G. Pseudohypoparathyroidism H. Vitamin D deficiency I. Hypomagnesemia J. Hypoparathyroidism

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety since we took my son to the doctor. He’s only 6 years old, but over the past year, I’ve noticed some really concerning changes. He suddenly started developing body odor, which I thought was strange for his age. Then there’s the acne that seemed to pop up out of nowhere, and to top it all off, I found pubic hair when I was helping him get dressed.

What worries me the most is that he’s had a significant growth spurt recently. We had to buy him new clothes, and I just can't understand why this is happening so early. During the examination, the doctor said he’s at Tanner stage 2 for pubic hair and that his testicular volume was about 5 mL, which I guess is concerning.

They also did some tests, and it turns out his bone age is already at 9 years. I can’t help but worry about what this means for him. I’ve spent nights wondering if it’s something serious like a hormonal issue or something else entirely. The doctor mentioned various possibilities, and my mind keeps racing through all the potential diagnoses. I just want to understand what’s going on with my little boy.
options: A. Primary hypothyroidism with secondary precocious puberty B. Benign premature adrenarche C. Gonadotropin-independent precocious puberty D. Central precocious puberty related to a central nervous system lesion E. Familial male-limited precocious puberty F. Idiopathic central precocious puberty G. Late-onset congenital adrenal hyperplasia H. McCune-Albright syndrome I. Precocious puberty related to a peripheral androgen-secreting tumor J. Adrenal carcinoma causing androgen excess

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety after my last prenatal visit. I’m 34 weeks along, and while everything seemed routine, I can’t help but worry. I’ve always been a bit shorter than average, and so is my partner, but now I’m feeling the weight of that. During the visit, the doctor measured my fundal height—it was only 30 cm, which just didn’t feel right to me.

Then, I had an ultrasound. I thought everything would be fine, but they mentioned the fetal weight is below the 10th percentile for my gestational age. I can’t stop thinking about what that means for my baby. The ultrasound showed normal anatomy and fluid levels, but my mind is racing with concern. 

I feel so lost and helpless, trying to understand what’s happening. The doctor mentioned several options for next steps, but I’m just overwhelmed. Should I be preparing for something serious? I want to do everything I can to ensure my baby is healthy, but I’m scared. I keep imagining all the “what ifs.” I just wish I could feel more assured about everything. I don’t know what the right choice is, and this uncertainty is weighing heavily on me.
options: A. Biophysical profile testing B. Maternal serum screening for PAPP-A C. Genetic amniocentesis D. Nonstress testing E. Middle cerebral artery Doppler assessment F. Umbilical artery Doppler flow velocimetry G. Repeat ultrasound in 2 weeks H. Daily fetal movement counts I. Immediate delivery by cesarean section J. Serial fundal height measurements only

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping up on me lately. It started a few months ago when I noticed I was constantly thirsty—like, really thirsty. I’m talking about drinking up to 4 liters of water every day! It’s been exhausting. I find myself rushing to the bathroom every couple of hours during the day, and even waking up once or twice at night to urinate. It feels like my body is completely out of control.

My medical history isn’t exactly simple. I had a pituitary macroadenoma removed about ten years ago, and I also deal with type 2 diabetes, which is usually well-managed. I’ve been on amitriptyline for my fibromyalgia and depression for about six months now, and I'm starting to wonder if it’s affecting me in ways I didn’t anticipate.

I went to see my doctor, and thankfully, my vital signs were stable, and my mucous membranes looked fine. But still, I can’t help but feel anxious about what could be happening inside me. I did a urinalysis, and the results showed I’ve been producing an alarming amount of urine—almost 4 liters in just one day! I can’t help but think about what all of this means. Is it something serious? I just want to understand what’s going on, and I’m feeling really worried about my health.
options: A. Partial central diabetes insipidus B. Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion C. Hyperosmolar nonketotic state D. Chronic kidney disease with impaired concentrating ability E. Central diabetes insipidus F. Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus G. Psychogenic polydipsia H. Primary polydipsia I. Medication-induced polyuria J. Hypothalamic dysfunction leading to impaired thirst regulation

question:
Lately, I've been feeling really anxious about my memory and cognitive abilities. It's like every day brings a new worry. Just the other night, I struggled to remember a recent conversation with my friend. I could see the look on their face; they were clearly concerned too. I’ve also noticed that I’m having more trouble finding the right words when I’m talking, which is so frustrating. Sometimes, I even misplace items around the house, like my keys or glasses, and I can’t help but feel a sinking dread each time I can’t find them. 

Even more concerning, I’ve been feeling less inclined to go out and socialize. I used to enjoy being around people, but now I find myself wanting to stay home more and more. I can’t shake this feeling that something isn’t right, and I worry that these changes might be signs of something serious. I’ve read a bit about Alzheimer’s, and I can’t help but wonder if I’m at risk. I just wish I could get some clarity on what’s happening and whether I should be more concerned about these symptoms. It’s all so overwhelming.
options: A. Changes in sleep patterns B. Difficulty remembering recent conversations C. Word-finding difficulty D. Decreased interest in social activities E. Difficulty with complex mathematical calculations F. Difficulty maintaining personal hygiene G. Misplacing items frequently H. Getting lost navigating familiar areas I. Problems with abstract reasoning J. Problems with word-finding during conversations

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that has settled over me lately. It all started about nine months ago when I began hearing things—voices, whispers, even messages that I thought were from my deceased sister. I remember sitting in our living room, staring at the vase that seemed to hold her spirit. At first, my husband thought I was just joking, but things escalated quickly. 

Last night at dinner with his parents, I don’t even know what came over me. I felt a rush of anger and suddenly I found myself threatening them with a knife. I didn’t mean to, but it felt like I was losing control. My husband had to call the police, and I could see the fear in his eyes. 

Now I’m sitting here, unable to speak, while he explains everything to the psychiatrist. I can’t look anyone in the eye. I’ve been so depressed for the past year, and I can’t sleep at all. I’ve lost weight—twelve pounds in six months—and I feel like I’m a shadow of my former self. I don’t use drugs or alcohol, and the thought of harming myself or anyone else terrifies me. I just want to understand what’s happening to me, but I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of panic. What’s wrong with me?
options: A. Bipolar I disorder with psychotic features B. Major depressive disorder with psychotic features C. Substance/medication-induced psychotic disorder D. Delusional disorder E. Schizophreniform disorder F. Borderline personality disorder G. Psychotic disorder due to another medical condition H. Schizophrenia I. Schizoaffective disorder J. Persistent depressive disorder (dysthymia)

question:
I can't shake the worry that has settled over me since I was admitted to the intensive care unit just a day ago. At 82 years old, I’ve always tried to stay strong, but the past few days have been terrifying. I’ve been feeling lightheaded and weak, and there were moments when I thought I might pass out. Then came the alarming reality of melena—I noticed dark, tarry stools, which sent my anxiety into overdrive.

I have a history of moderate aortic stenosis and coronary artery disease, and I’ve been on several medications: aspirin, clopidogrel, simvastatin, metoprolol, and lisinopril. After my symptoms worsened, I was given intravenous fluids and blood products, which helped stabilize me. I’m grateful I didn’t bleed any further, but the thought of what might be going on inside my body is haunting me. I had upper and lower endoscopies—thankfully, they didn’t show anything alarming, but what if there’s something else lurking?

Now, the doctors are discussing the next steps in my evaluation. I can’t help but feel anxious about what tests they might suggest. I just want to know what’s wrong and if I’ll be okay. The uncertainty is overwhelming. I wish I could just wake up and have this all behind me.
options: A. CT angiography B. Video-capsule endoscopy C. Push enteroscopy D. Nuclear medicine bleeding scan E. Mesenteric angiography F. Small bowel follow-through G. Repeat upper endoscopy with side-viewing scope H. Magnetic resonance enterography I. Double-balloon enteroscopy J. Abdominal ultrasound with Doppler

question:
I can't shake the feeling of anxiety since I went to the student health clinic last week. For about a week now, I've been dealing with this mild to moderate pelvic pain that just won’t go away. It gets worse during intercourse, and then I noticed some vaginal spotting afterward, which really freaked me out. On top of that, I’ve had some weird intermenstrual bleeding. 

I've been sexually active recently, with three partners in the last month, which makes me even more nervous about what might be going on. At the clinic, they checked my vital signs, and everything seemed normal, but the abdominal examination showed some mild tenderness, which didn’t help ease my worries. 

During the pelvic exam, they found mucopurulent cervical discharge and I felt pain when they moved my cervix, which was really alarming. They did a urine test for pregnancy, and thankfully, it came back negative, but I still feel like something is seriously wrong. 

Now, I’m just waiting to find out what kind of tests I need to confirm what’s happening. I can’t help but feel anxious about it all, and I really hope it’s nothing too serious. The uncertainty is weighing heavily on me.
options: A. Transvaginal ultrasound B. Vaginal pH testing C. Cervical culture for Chlamydia and Gonorrhea D. Complete blood count with differential E. Pelvic ultrasound F. Laparoscopy G. No additional tests are required to make the diagnosis H. Endometrial biopsy I. Nucleic acid amplification J. Contrast-enhanced computed tomography (CT)

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of dread as I sit in the clinic, waiting to hear what’s wrong with me. For the past year, I’ve been struggling more and more to catch my breath, especially when I exert myself even a little. And this dry cough—it's relentless. I’ve worked as an aerospace engineer, but I've also spent years in coal mining and sandblasting. I can’t help but worry that my exposure to all those particles is catching up with me.

When the nurse took my vital signs, I tried to stay calm, but I felt my heart racing. They said my oxygen levels were a bit low at 94%, and I couldn’t help but feel a knot tighten in my stomach. The doctor listened to my lungs and mentioned hearing some fine crackles. No wheezing was good, but still, it all felt off. 

I overheard the word "pneumoconiosis," and my heart sank. What if that’s what I have? I know it’s linked to my past jobs, and I’m terrified of what that means for my health. Now, the doctor is talking about different tests they might need to run to figure this out. I just want to know what’s going on, but my mind races with worst-case scenarios. What if it’s something serious? I can’t help but feel so worried about what the future holds.
options: A. V/Q scan B. High-resolution CT (HRCT) with inspiratory and expiratory views C. Bronchoalveolar lavage D. Computed tomography (CT) imaging of the chest E. Pulmonary function testing with spirometry F. Serum ACE level measurement G. Diffusing capacity of the lungs for carbon monoxide (DLCO) measurement H. Lung biopsy with histopathological examination I. Sputum cytology for asbestos or silica particles J. FEV1/FVC ratio measurement

question:
I can’t shake the fear of what happened after the head-on collision I was in. I was wearing my seatbelt, so I thought I’d be okay, but the pain hit me hard. I didn’t lose consciousness, which I guess is a good sign, but something felt really off. 

When I got to the emergency department, they started checking me out. I was shocked to find out that I had weakness in both my legs, like they just didn't want to cooperate with me. The doctors mentioned I had some kind of sensory loss in my groin, which sounded alarming. To make matters worse, they told me my Achilles reflex was absent, but I still had some reflexes in my knees. That didn’t really comfort me. 

And then they did a bladder scan. I couldn’t believe it when they said I had 900 mL of retained urine and was experiencing urinary retention. I felt so helpless. They’re scheduling me for an urgent MRI now, but all I can think about are the possibilities—what if it’s something serious? The thought of not being able to walk or the implications of whatever they might find is weighing heavily on me. I just want answers and to know I’ll be okay.
options: A. Central cord syndrome B. Transverse myelitis C. Lumbar spinal stenosis D. Spinal epidural hematoma E. Anterior cord syndrome F. Brown-Séquard syndrome G. Cauda equina syndrome H. Conus medullaris syndrome I. Spinal cord infarction J. Sacral plexopathy

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. It all started when I noticed these huge bruises on my body—one on my right chest and armpit, another massive one on my right side, and yet another on my left lower back. They look so alarming, like they could take up half my torso. I had surgery for my prostate cancer just a few months ago, and I thought I was recovering well, but now I’m not so sure. 

I don't feel any pain, but the sight of those bruises is terrifying. I’m also worried about my knees; they’re swollen and tender, and I can barely move them without discomfort. My temperature is normal, and my heart rate seems okay, but I can’t help but feel something is off. 

The doctors are running tests, but the anxiety is eating at me. What if this is something serious? I’ve read about complications that can arise after surgery, and I can’t help but feel overwhelmed. I’m trying to stay calm, but with all these symptoms and my cancer history, I can't shake the fear that something is really wrong. What if I’m facing another battle? I just want answers and hope that this isn’t as bad as it looks.
options: A. Vitamin K deficiency B. Factor XIII deficiency C. Liver disease coagulopathy D. Classic von Willebrand disease E. Secondary hyperfibrinolysis F. Hemophilia A G. Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) H. Acquired factor VIII inhibitor I. Antiphospholipid syndrome J. Primary hyperfibrinolysis

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry about my little girl. She just turned 30 months, but I can’t help but compare her development to the other kids at daycare. It’s been weighing on my mind. She can fetch familiar objects when I ask her, and she does use about ten single words, which gives me some hope. She even brings me things to show me, which is sweet. 

But then I start to think about the things she struggles with. She can’t kick a ball, and it’s so concerning that she can’t stack more than two blocks. I’ve noticed she also has a hard time following two-step commands. And when I ask her to identify pictures in a book, she just stares blankly instead of pointing them out. 

I’ve been reading up on developmental milestones, and I’m really worried that her skills might be closer to those of an 18-month-old. What if there’s something wrong? I just want to see her thrive and catch up with her friends. I keep wondering if I should talk to someone about it. Am I overreacting, or is this something I really need to address?
options: A. 18 months B. 16 months C. 17 months D. 15 months E. 21 months F. 20 months G. 22 months H. 14 months I. 12 months J. 24 months

question:
I still can’t shake off the panic that gripped me when I found my 2-year-old son had ingested some unknown clear liquid from a plastic water bottle in the garage. It all happened so fast—just 30 minutes before we rushed to the emergency department. The liquid had a strong odor, something I can’t quite place, but it didn’t smell like bleach. I worried it might be something related to the automotive work we sometimes do.

When I first realized what happened, he started crying and then vomited. He’s been coughing ever since, and now he refuses to drink anything, even though he’s somewhat calmed down. I can’t help but feel terrified as he’s never had any health issues before this. 

The doctors took his vital signs, and I could see the worry in their eyes too. He was alert but crying, with a runny nose and red eyes. They listened to his lungs, and I could hear those strange sounds they mentioned—rhonchi and crackles. My heart sank when they mentioned the faint opacities in his chest X-ray.

I just keep thinking about what could happen next. I feel so helpless, praying they can help him and that this won’t turn into something worse. What’s the right step now? I’m just so scared for my little boy.
options: A. Start high-flow oxygen therapy B. Administer activated charcoal C. Administer empiric antibiotics D. Start rapid sequence intubation E. Perform emergency endoscopy F. Obtain an electrocardiogram G. Administer nebulized bronchodilators H. Order serum electrolytes and blood gas I. Perform bronchoscopy J. Initiate gastric lavage

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of anxiety as I sit in the waiting room for my routine prenatal check-up. I’m 34 weeks pregnant with twins, and I’ve been trying to stay calm, but everything feels so overwhelming. I was diagnosed with gestational diabetes at 28 weeks, and I’m worried about what that means for my babies. 

I remember how relieved I was when my first-trimester ultrasound confirmed my pregnancy, but now I’m filled with doubt. My medical history isn’t exactly comforting either—there’s the factor V Leiden mutation I have, and I had a nasty flu early on that thankfully resolved. I’m doing everything I can, taking my prenatal vitamins, enoxaparin, and metformin, but I can’t help but feel that something might go wrong.

During the examination, my doctor checks my vital signs, and they seem stable, which is a small relief. But then I see the growth scan results for my twins. Twin A’s growth has been concerning; they’ve dropped from the 19th percentile at 26 weeks to just 8th percentile now. What does this mean? I can’t stop thinking about the possibilities—could it be the gestational diabetes, or something else? I need answers, and I’m scared about what the future holds for my babies.
options: A. Gestational diabetes B. Maternal hypertensive disorder C. Twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome D. First-trimester infection E. Aneuploidy F. Factor V Leiden mutation G. Multiple gestation H. Unequal placental cord insertion I. Placental insufficiency J. Selective intrauterine growth restriction

question:
I can’t shake off this overwhelming sense of worry. It all started when I noticed my little boy, just three months old, wasn’t feeding well. For the past two days, he’s been so lethargic, barely waking up, and I just felt a sinking feeling in my stomach. He was born healthy at term, but now I can't help but think about the three times he’s had ear infections since he was born. 

I remember when his umbilical cord finally fell off at eight weeks; it felt like such a milestone. But now, as I hold him, I can’t help but notice how thin he’s getting — he’s in the 30th percentile for height and the 20th for weight. When I took his temperature, it was alarmingly high at 39.0°C (102.2°F), and his blood pressure was worryingly low. 

The doctor examined him and found these white patches in his mouth and some strange, scaly rashes in his groin. My heart raced as they mentioned blood cultures and other tests. I just kept thinking, “What could be causing this?” I feel so helpless and scared, wondering if there’s something seriously wrong with my baby. I can’t help but worry about what the underlying issue might be, and I just want to see him healthy and happy again.
options: A. Impaired neutrophil chemotaxis B. Defective beta-2 integrin C. Defective NADPH oxidase D. Abnormal toll-like receptor function E. Defective IL-12 receptor signaling F. Defective CD40 ligand G. Abnormal neutrophil granule formation H. Impaired myeloperoxidase function I. Defective neutrophil adhesion molecule expression J. Defective interferon-gamma production

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread ever since I took my 3-month-old daughter to the doctor. For the past two weeks, she has been so different—poor feeding, constant irritability, and vomiting. It’s been absolutely heartbreaking to watch her struggle. She was born prematurely at 36 weeks, but her birth was smooth, so I never expected anything like this.

When we arrived at the physician’s office, I felt my anxiety spike. The doctor noted her growth parameters; she’s in the 5th percentile for length and just the 3rd for weight. It hit me hard to hear that. Her vital signs seemed normal, but I couldn't help but worry when they checked her temperature, pulse, and respiratory rate. Everything seemed unremarkable physically, but my gut told me something was off.

I keep replaying every moment in my mind—what could be causing this? The doctor mentioned some lab findings, but I was too overwhelmed to fully grasp what they meant. I just want to know why my baby is suffering like this. It feels like we’re in this fog of uncertainty, and all I want is to see her healthy and happy again. I can’t help but worry about what might be the underlying cause of all these troubling symptoms. I just hope we find answers soon.
options: A. Impaired NH3 production in proximal tubules B. Dysfunction of the H+-ATPase pump in α-intercalated cells C. Enhanced K+ secretion in principal cells D. Inability of the proximal tubule to reabsorb HCO3- E. Inability of the distal tubule to secrete H+ F. Impaired CFTR gene function G. Defective Cl-/HCO3- exchanger in α-intercalated cells H. Impaired carbonic anhydrase activity in proximal tubules I. Defective Na+/H+ exchanger in proximal tubules J. Increased aldosterone resistance in collecting ducts

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of dread after my recent visit to the clinic. At just 16, I’ve been feeling an unshakeable fatigue that has left me exhausted all the time. I also had this low-grade fever that wouldn't go away, and I noticed some swelling in my neck that really worried me. When the doctor finally told me I had been diagnosed with a rare type of lymphoma, my heart sank. How could this happen to me?

What’s even scarier is hearing about the connection between this type of lymphoma and the community near the power plant. It’s been rumored that the drinking water there might be contaminated, and now I can’t help but wonder if that’s what caused my illness. I’ve heard that public health officials are investigating this, trying to figure out if the water exposure really increases the risk for kids like me.

I keep thinking about the control group they’re planning for their study. It feels like all of this is happening to me, yet so many others could be affected too. I just can’t help but feel anxious about what this means for my health and for others in the community. It’s terrifying to think that so many young people might be facing the same struggles as I am now.
options: A. Individuals from an unaffected community with no exposure to the contaminated water B. Individuals with no history of cancer from a neighboring community C. Individuals without lymphoma that were not exposed to the contaminated water D. Individuals without lymphoma but with other chronic diseases E. Individuals without lymphoma from the local outpatient clinic F. Individuals with lymphoma from a region unaffected by the water contamination G. Individuals without lymphoma who have lived in the community for less than one year H. Individuals without lymphoma that were exposed to the contaminated water I. Individuals without lymphoma matched by age and gender to the cases J. Individuals with lymphoma without exposure to the contaminated water

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread after what happened to me. Just a few days ago, I took amoxicillin for a simple infection, and before I knew it, I was in the emergency room having a severe anaphylactic reaction. It was terrifying. They managed to stabilize me, but now I’m facing a new problem. I’ve noticed my urine output has dropped dramatically, and I can’t help but worry about what that means.

Despite receiving regular fluid infusions, things aren’t improving. In fact, I overheard the doctors mention that my creatinine levels are rising, which sounds really serious. I feel so helpless. They did a urinalysis and thankfully, there was no blood or protein, but that doesn’t ease my mind. I can’t stop thinking about what’s happening to my kidneys. 

I keep wondering if this is going to lead to something worse, like acute tubular necrosis. It’s hard to focus on anything else when I’m scared about my health. I just want to be back to normal, but the uncertainty is weighing on me. What if this keeps getting worse? I really hope they find a way to fix this soon.
options: A. Pre-renal azotemia always progresses to ATN if left untreated for more than 48 hours B. Contrast-induced nephropathy and sepsis share similar pathophysiological mechanisms in causing ATN C. The S3 segment of the proximal tubule is relatively resistant to ischemic injury compared to other nephron segments D. In ATN the final change microscopically is changes of the apical brush of the tubular cells and loosening of the junctions with the membrane E. Prognosis of acute tubular necrosis is unrelated to the prognosis of the cause of it and it’s treatment and outcome F. Damage by toxic agents is different to those from ischemia G. The medullary thick ascending limb is most susceptible to hypoxic injury due to its high metabolic demands H. Recovery from ATN is dependent on the regenerative capacity of tubular epithelial cells regardless of the initial insult I. The least effected places are the proximal staining tubule and thick ascending limb of loop of Henle- the part in the medulla J. Rhabdomyolisis, crystals and multiple myeloma are also risk factors

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of anxiety that’s been weighing on me since my last visit to the pediatrician. My dad took me in because he was really concerned about my delayed puberty. It’s hard to watch all my friends develop while I seem to be stuck in place. I’m 17 now, and it feels like everyone else is moving forward, and I’m just... not.

During the appointment, I tried to put on a brave face, but inside, I was really worried. I felt fine physically, but when the doctor examined me, I could see the concern in his eyes too. My breasts are still undeveloped, and everything else seemed normal, but I’m only at Tanner stage I. They checked my vital signs, and my blood pressure was higher than I expected, which made my heart race even more.

I kept thinking about what this all means for me. The doctor said something about additional findings that might help figure out what’s going on, but I couldn’t help but fear the worst. What if it’s something serious? I just want to feel normal and not so out of place among my peers. I left the office feeling even more anxious, wondering what the next steps would be and what they might discover.
options: A. Low serum cortisol B. XY karyotype C. Growth hormone deficiency D. Elevated FSH levels E. Low serum aldosterone F. Hypokalemia G. Primary hypothyroidism H. Hyperandrogenism I. Turner syndrome karyotype J. Aromatase enzyme deficiency

question:
I can’t shake the worry that settled over me when the pain hit. Just three hours ago, I was walking home after playing football with friends, and out of nowhere, I felt this sharp, severe pain in my lower abdomen and right groin. It was so intense that I couldn’t help but double over. I started feeling nauseous and even vomited a couple of times. 

When I finally got to the emergency department, I was a bundle of nerves. I’ve never had anything like this before, and the doctors seemed concerned too. They checked my vitals, which were stable, but I could tell something wasn’t right. 

The exam revealed some troubling signs, especially the swelling on the right side. When the doctor elevated my testicle, the pain was unbearable, and they mentioned something about a missing reflex on that side. I could hardly focus on what they were saying, but I could sense the urgency in their voices. 

I keep replaying those moments in my head, worrying about what could be the cause. They’re going to do further tests, and I’m just praying that it’s nothing serious. The thought of something being wrong down there is terrifying. What if it’s something major? I just want this pain to go away and to know that I’ll be okay.
options: A. decreased arterial blood flow to the right testicle B. increased muscle tension in the paravertebral tissue at T10-T11 C. warm, rubbery tissue at the level of T11-L2 D. tenderness localized to the pubic symphysis E. inflammation and erythema of the epididymis F. gangliform nodule between the transverse and spinous processes of L1 G. referred pain to the lower extremity due to sciatic nerve compression H. impaired lymphatic drainage of the inguinal region I. hypertonicity of the pelvic floor muscles J. diminished cremasteric reflex bilaterally

question:
I’m really starting to worry about this pain in my mid-back. It all began just four days ago, and it hasn’t gotten any better. As a 24-year-old parkour athlete, I’m used to pushing my body, but this feels different. I can’t shake the feeling that something might be seriously wrong.

I went to see a doctor, and they did a neurological exam, which thankfully came back normal. But during the structural examination, they found that one of my vertebrae has a right transverse process that’s more posterior than the left. What does that even mean? They said the asymmetry resolves when I bend forward, but how can I be sure that it’s nothing serious?

I’m anxious because they mentioned the alignment of the spinous process with the T10 transverse process level. I can't help but feel like I need to know what’s going on. Is it something simple, or is there a deeper issue at play? I just want to get back to training without this nagging pain, but the uncertainty is really getting to me. What if it’s something worse than I think? I wish I could just have a clear answer.
options: A. T9 extended, rotated left, sidebent right B. T10 extended, rotated right, sidebent right C. T9 neutral, rotated right, sidebent right D. T9 extended, rotated right, sidebent right E. T8 flexed, rotated right, sidebent right F. T11 flexed, rotated left, sidebent left G. T10 flexed, rotated right, sidebent left H. T10 flexed, rotated left, sidebent right I. T9 flexed, rotated left, sidebent left J. T9 flexed, rotated right, sidebent right

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming worry after what happened this morning. I woke up and noticed bright red blood in my stool, and I’m not talking about just a little bit—I saw it again yesterday too. It’s terrifying! I had been celebrating my birthday last night, and I guess I drank way too much. I ended up vomiting heavily, which was awful, but at least I’m not feeling nauseous right now.

I rushed to the emergency department because I couldn’t ignore the blood any longer. I felt fine otherwise, but this whole situation has me on edge. They checked my vitals, which seemed okay, but I can't help but worry about what’s going on inside me. My abdomen was examined, and thankfully it wasn’t tender, but they found grossly bloody stool during the rectal exam. 

I’ve never had anything like this happen to me before. I don’t take any medications, and my medical history is clear, so I can’t wrap my head around why this is happening. I just keep thinking about all the possible causes. Is it something serious? I’m terrified of what this could mean for my health. I just want answers and hope that everything will be alright.
options: A. Mallory-Weiss tear B. Inflammation and infection of colonic outpouching C. Ischemic colitis D. Colonic angiodysplasia E. Submucosal esophageal tear F. Rectal fissure G. Vascular malformation H. Erosion into a gastric vessel I. Hemorrhoidal bleeding J. Peptic ulcer disease

question:
I've been feeling really anxious lately. About three days ago, I started experiencing this sharp pain when I urinate. It’s been getting worse, and now I find myself rushing to the bathroom more than ever. I can't shake this nagging worry, even though I haven’t noticed any blood in my urine. I’m trying to stay calm, but it’s hard when I’m constantly on edge. 

I went to see my primary care doctor because I thought it might help. I was hoping for some clarity, but now I’m just more confused. I don’t have any fevers or chills, and there’s no unusual vaginal discharge, thank goodness. I’ve never had any major health issues before and I’m not on any medications, so I really didn’t expect this. 

I’ve been in a steady relationship for four years, and I use a copper IUD, so I thought I was safe from complications. But during the exam, my doctor found some tenderness in my lower abdomen. It’s just a lot to process. What if it’s something serious? I feel like I’m stuck in limbo, waiting to see what the next steps are. I just want this pain to go away and to know that I’m going to be okay.
options: A. Fosfomycin B. Ciprofloxacin C. Cephalexin D. Levofloxacin E. Doxycycline F. Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole G. Azithromycin H. Observation with follow-up in 2 weeks I. Amoxicillin-clavulanate J. Ampicillin

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that washed over me after my delivery. I’m 22 and had been so excited to welcome my second child. The labor was induced for over 30 hours with continuous oxytocin, and everything seemed normal until the moment I delivered. The placenta came out intact, but then the bleeding started. It was alarming—more than 1050 mL of blood loss, and no matter what they did, my uterus just wouldn’t firm up. 

They tried everything: uterine massage and more oxytocin, but I could feel the panic in the room. The nurses were checking for lacerations and clots, but they found nothing. I was so scared; I could see the concern on their faces, and I felt utterly helpless. My heart raced as I thought about what could happen next. 

I knew they were considering their options, and I just kept wondering what would be the right thing to do. I felt like I was in a nightmare, and I couldn’t help but worry—was I going to be okay? What if this bleeding didn’t stop? It’s terrifying to feel so vulnerable, especially after everything I had gone through to bring my baby into the world.
options: A. Perform manual exploration of uterus B. Administer methylergonovine intramuscularly C. Initiate crystalloid fluid resuscitation D. Initiate tranexamic acid infusion E. Provide an additional dose of oxytocin intravenously F. Begin misoprostol administration G. Administer carboprost intramuscularly H. Perform immediate hysterectomy I. Insert Bakri balloon J. Begin fresh frozen plasma transfusion

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been creeping in ever since my last doctor’s appointment. At 44, I’ve been battling hepatitis C for what feels like forever. I tried treatment with peginterferon, ribavirin, and telaprevir, but nothing seemed to work. It’s been a tough road, especially since I also have a history of alcohol use disorder. Thankfully, I’ve managed to stay sober for the past three years, but the worry never really goes away.

During my latest check-up, the doctor noticed some strange spider-like marks on my chest. That was alarming enough, but then they felt my abdomen and said my spleen was slightly enlarged. I could barely breathe as they mentioned my liver enzymes were high, and my platelets were low. The numbers they shared with me didn’t sound good. I’ve been trying to stay healthy, but I’m scared about what it all means.

Now I’m left wondering what the next steps should be. The doctor mentioned different screening tests, but I’m feeling overwhelmed. What if this means more bad news? I need to figure out what’s going on with my liver and what this all means for my future. It’s hard to not feel anxious about it all.
options: A. CT scan of the abdomen and serum alpha-fetoprotein B. Liver biopsy and serum alpha-fetoprotein C. MRI of the liver and serum alpha-fetoprotein D. Abdominal ultrasound and liver function tests E. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy and measurement of serum alpha-fetoprotein F. CT scan of the abdomen and esophagogastroduodenoscopy G. Measurement of serum alpha-fetoprotein H. Abdominal ultrasound and liver elastography I. MRI of the liver and liver biopsy J. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy and abdominal ultrasound

question:
I can’t shake this nagging worry that something is seriously wrong with me. Just the other day, I went to see my primary care provider because I’ve been experiencing this intense burning sensation right behind my breastbone and painful swallowing. I mean, it felt like fire inside my chest! 

At 23, I never thought I’d be dealing with these kinds of issues. I have some health problems, like hypothyroidism and endometriosis, and I’m always exhausted from chronic fatigue syndrome. I take my medications—levothyroxine, doxycycline, and naproxen—every night since I often forget them in the morning. But now, I can’t help but wonder if they’re even helping.

During my appointment, I was nervous about what the doctor would find. My temperature was normal, and my blood pressure was fine, but I just felt off. They decided to schedule an upper endoscopy to look more closely inside. What if they find something serious? I’ve been trying to stay calm, but I can’t stop thinking about what could be lurking down there. 

I just want answers and relief from this pain. I’m worried about what they might discover during the endoscopy, and I can’t help but feel overwhelmed by it all.
options: A. Salmon-colored mucosa under white light in distal esophagus B. Mirror-image ulcers surrounded by normal mucosa in mid-esophagus C. Scattered punched-out ulcers throughout the entire esophagus D. Diffuse erythema with punctate hemorrhages in distal esophagus E. Circumferential erosions with adherent white exudates F. Whitish plaques with underlying erythematous mucosa G. Longitudinal streaks with friable mucosa and contact bleeding H. Cobblestone appearance with multiple superficial erosions I. Linear furrows with stacked circular rings and white papules J. Serpiginous ulcers with raised borders in proximal esophagus

question:
I can’t shake this nagging worry that something is really wrong with my left knee. It all started about two months after I sprained my ankle while playing basketball. I thought the ankle would heal, but then this intense pain crept into my knee. It hurts especially when I try to fully extend it, and no matter how much ibuprofen I take or how many times I ice it, the pain just won’t go away. 

I’ve had my fair share of ankle sprains before, but I’ve never felt anything like this in my knee. When I went to see a doctor, they examined my knee and found tenderness on the outside, and they mentioned something about the fibular head not moving properly. Strangely, my ankle doesn’t hurt at all, which makes me even more anxious. They did some X-rays of my leg, and thankfully, there were no fractures, but I can’t help but feel that something else is going on. 

I’m left wondering what this could mean for me. I keep thinking about what else could be wrong. I just want to be able to play basketball again without worrying about my knee. What if this pain is a sign of something serious? I really hope to get some answers soon.
options: A. Plantarflexion of the foot B. Pain with resisted eversion of the foot C. Increased external rotation of the tibia D. Restricted anterior glide of the talus E. Tenderness over the medial collateral ligament F. Dorsiflexion of the foot G. External rotation of the talus H. Increased valgus stress of the knee I. Hyperextension of the knee J. Decreased internal rotation of the tibia

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been creeping in since I was diagnosed with stage IV non-small-cell lung cancer. At 65, I never imagined I’d be facing something so daunting, especially with my heavy smoking history. I enrolled in a clinical trial, hoping that the PD-1 inhibitor would give me a fighting chance against this relentless disease.

After several weeks of treatment, I was anxious to see if there had been any improvement. At the eight-week mark, I felt a glimmer of hope when my right lung lesion shrank a bit, and the liver spots looked smaller too. But then, by week 16, I was hit with a wave of anxiety. My right lung lesion had started to grow again, and even though my liver lesion had fluctuated, it wasn’t looking good. The left lung lesion also seemed to be getting worse. 

I keep replaying the numbers in my head, trying to decipher what they mean for my future. Am I experiencing a delayed progression? Or could this be a mixed response? The uncertainty is unbearable. Every appointment fills me with anxiety, and I can’t help but worry about what comes next. Will I have more time? Or is this just the beginning of a rapid decline? I’m terrified of what these changes mean for me.
options: A. Delayed progression B. Disease flare C. Initial response followed by progression D. Pseudoprogression E. Complete response F. Mixed response G. Partial response H. Progressive disease I. Stable disease J. Treatment failure

question:
For the past two months, I’ve been dealing with this persistent cough that just won’t go away. It feels like it’s getting worse, and I’ve started to experience sharp chest pain that feels like it’s ripping through me, especially when I take a deep breath. I’ve also noticed that I’ve lost about 5 kilograms recently, which is worrying me. My face and arms swell up intermittently, and it seems to get worse when I lie down. 

To top it all off, I’ve been having these strange visual disturbances that I can’t seem to shake. I used to smoke for 50 years but quit last year, and I drink alcohol only occasionally, so I can’t help but wonder what’s going on with my body. 

When I went to see the doctor, they examined me and pointed out that my right eyelid was drooping and my pupils were different sizes. I could see the concern in their eyes when they noticed the distended veins in my neck and arms. They said they needed to do a CT scan, and I couldn’t shake the feeling that something really serious might be wrong. All of this is just weighing heavily on my mind. What if it’s something terrible? I can’t help but feel that this is just the beginning of a long, difficult journey.
options: A. Brain stem metastasis B. Cervical lymph nodes C. Anterior mediastinum D. Right upper lobe E. Right lower lobe F. Left lower lobe G. Pleural cavity H. Posterior mediastinum I. Central hilar region J. Left upper lobe

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety. It’s been two months since I stopped taking my birth control pills, and I still haven’t gotten my period. I’ve always had regular cycles, every 28 to 30 days, ever since I started menstruating at 13. I thought stopping the pills would be the first step toward conceiving, but now I’m just left waiting and worrying.

I’ve taken multiple home pregnancy tests, all of which came back negative. It feels so disheartening. I don’t have any unusual symptoms—no bleeding or spotting, and I’ve never had any STIs. But I can’t help but notice I’ve been struggling with some acne lately. My BMI is in the normal range, but I still feel uneasy. 

When I visited the doctor, they did a physical examination, and everything seemed unremarkable. They even ran a urine pregnancy test, which also came back negative. I just feel like I’m in this limbo, not knowing what’s going on with my body. 

The doctor mentioned some options for next steps, but the uncertainty is overwhelming. I keep thinking, what if something is seriously wrong? I just want to understand why this is happening so I can move forward with my plans to start a family.
options: A. Begin clomiphene citrate therapy B. Measure her serum human chorionic gonadotropin level C. Measure serum testosterone and DHEA-S levels D. Perform transvaginal ultrasound to evaluate ovarian structure E. Perform endometrial biopsy F. Order pelvic MRI to evaluate hypothalamic-pituitary anatomy G. Order thyroid function tests and prolactin level H. Measure her follicle-stimulating hormone and estradiol levels I. Continue to monitor her for one more month J. Start progesterone challenge test

question:
I've been feeling really off lately, and it’s starting to worry me. I’m 28 and just got accepted into a master’s program, which should be amazing, right? But instead of being excited, I’ve been battling this overwhelming low energy and irritability for weeks now. I thought it was just stress from starting school, but it’s more than that. Some days, I feel on top of the world—super productive and even a bit euphoric. But then, out of nowhere, I crash. I’ve had spells where I just feel worthless, guilty, and utterly drained. 

I don’t take any medications and only drink a couple of glasses of wine on the weekends, but I can't shake this feeling that something’s seriously wrong. My friends have noticed too; they say I seem tired and distracted, and I've had to ask people to repeat things because I can’t focus. I went to see my doctor, hoping to figure it out, but I left feeling even more anxious. I can't help but worry about what this could mean for my future. What if this is just the beginning of something I can't manage? I really need to get to the bottom of this.
options: A. Premenstrual dysphoric disorder B. Persistent depressive disorder C. Cyclothymic disorder D. Generalized anxiety disorder E. Bipolar II disorder F. Borderline personality disorder G. Adjustment disorder with depressed mood H. Bipolar I disorder I. Substance-induced mood disorder J. Major depressive disorder

question:
I can’t shake off this dreadful feeling that something is seriously wrong. For the past four months, I’ve been dealing with this relentless lower back pain that just won't go away. No matter what I do, it doesn’t seem to get better, and I can’t pinpoint anything that triggers it. I’ve tried over-the-counter medications, but they haven't helped at all. The pain is so bad that it even disrupts my sleep at night, leaving me feeling utterly exhausted.

To make matters worse, I’ve noticed I’ve been feeling increasingly fatigued lately, and I’ve lost weight without even trying. I’ve been managing my hypertension with medication, but this new set of symptoms is frightening me. When I went to see my primary care doctor, he examined me and said I looked pale. He pressed on my lower back, and it was tender, which only added to my worries.

I’m just feeling so overwhelmed and anxious about what could be going on inside my body. The doctor mentioned some tests, but I can’t help but fear what they might reveal. I know I need answers, but the uncertainty is really weighing on me. I just hope it’s nothing too serious.
options: A. Bone marrow biopsy B. MRI of the lumbar spine C. Alkaline phosphatase measurement D. Peripheral blood smear E. Serum protein electrophoresis F. PET scan of the whole body G. CT scan of the axial skeleton H. Serum free light chain assay I. Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry (DEXA) scan J. 24-hour urinary protein measurement

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of anxiety ever since I sought fertility consultation with my husband. It’s been a long journey for us, especially since we met during humanitarian work in Nepal a decade ago. But now, the struggle to conceive has become overwhelming. 

Lately, I’ve been experiencing this persistent lower abdominal discomfort that feels vague yet unsettling. My menstrual cycle has turned erratic, with spotting and even blood clots appearing more frequently. It’s baffling and alarming, especially since I haven’t had any pain during intercourse or any unusual discharge. Still, the thought of something being wrong weighs heavily on me.

During the examination, the doctor noticed mild bleeding and some tenderness, which only heightened my worries. They performed a hysterosalpingogram, and the results showed sinus tract formation and peritubal adhesions. I can’t help but feel that these findings are serious. 

Now, a sample has been sent for microbiological analysis, and I’m left wondering what could be causing all of this. Each possible pathogen rattles around in my mind, and I can’t help but feel concerned. Could this really affect our chances of starting a family? The uncertainty is overwhelming, and I just hope for answers soon.
options: A. *Mycoplasma genitalium* B. *Klebsiella granulomatis* C. *Treponema pallidum* D. *Chlamydia trachomatis* E. *Escherichia coli* F. *Ureaplasma urealyticum* G. *Actinomyces israelii* H. *Trichomonas vaginalis* I. *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* J. *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread after what happened last night. I’m only 25, and I thought I’d be recovering smoothly from the hemorrhoidectomy I had to get rid of those stubborn internal and external hemorrhoids. But instead, I woke up with this awful suprapubic pain and couldn’t urinate at all. It was terrifying. I kept thinking, “What’s wrong with me?” 

The surgery seemed straightforward, but now I’m wondering if it was something they did during the operation or maybe something that went wrong afterward. I’ve read that local inflammation might affect the urethra, or could it be that I just didn’t get enough fluids afterward? I couldn’t help but worry about the pain I was in. Did it cause some kind of spasm? 

I felt so helpless lying there, waiting for someone to figure out what was going on. I just wanted to get back to normal, but instead, I was battling this painful complication. I hope this isn’t something serious, but I can’t shake the anxiety that something went wrong during or after the surgery. What if this is a long-term issue? It’s hard to stay calm when I don’t even know what’s happening to my body.
options: A. Local inflammation affecting urethral compliance B. Limiting intravenous fluids in the postoperative recovery unit C. Injury to pelvic nerves D. Excessive post-operative pain causing urethral spasm E. Residual effects of spinal anesthesia F. Post-operative edema compressing the urethra G. Inadequate post-operative pain management H. Inadequate perioperative fluid management I. Performing 3 quadrant hemorrhoidectomy instead of 2 J. Reactive bladder sphincter dysfunction

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread ever since I took my 7-month-old daughter to the emergency department. It all started about 12 hours ago when she became lethargic and refused to eat. As a mother, it’s terrifying to see your baby so unresponsive. We live in a small rural town in the Appalachian mountains, and I thought maybe it was just teething—she’s been using a teething ring, but this seemed different.

She’s usually such a happy baby, but now she just lay there, and her skin, lips, and tongue had a strange bluish tint. I had to act fast, so I rushed her to the hospital. Thankfully, she’s been healthy so far with no major medical issues and is up to date on her immunizations. I felt a little relief when the doctors checked her vital signs, but the oxygen saturation was only 86%. That’s when my heart really sank. 

They listened to her chest and everything seemed normal, but I couldn’t help but worry. I thought about how she’s been breastfed and just starting on formula and baby food. All I wanted was for her to be okay. I kept asking myself what could be causing this sudden change. The doctors mentioned a few possibilities, but nothing made me feel any better. I just wanted to hold her and hear her laugh again.
options: A. Abnormal hemoglobin polymerization under physiologic oxygen levels B. Low partial pressure of oxygen in ambient air C. Decreased activity of a reducing enzyme in erythrocytes D. Increased levels of methemoglobin in the blood E. Inhalation of an odorless gas with high hemoglobin affinity F. Impaired oxygen diffusion across alveolar membranes G. Ingestion of a toxin that inhibits mitochondrial respiration H. Cyanotic congenital heart defect I. Increased production of fetal hemoglobin J. Defective oxygen unloading due to abnormal hemoglobin structure

question:
I can hardly believe what happened this weekend. My 7-year-old niece, who seemed perfectly fine until yesterday, suddenly woke up crying and gasping for breath. I was just sitting there, enjoying our time together when her voice changed and she started struggling to breathe. It was terrifying. 

The day before, she had a little cough and some congestion, but nothing serious. Now, she was in such distress, and I felt completely helpless. I remember her temperature was high—38.5°C, and her breathing was rapid. I tried to stay calm, but seeing her in that state was heart-wrenching. The way she was coughing, it sounded like a barking seal, and I could hear a stridor. 

I rushed her to the emergency department, praying that they could help her. The doctors checked her over and said her oxygen levels were okay, but the retractions in her chest were alarming. They couldn’t find anything wrong with her lungs, but I couldn’t shake off the worry. What if it got worse? What was causing this? They mentioned that her COVID test was negative, but it didn't ease my fears. 

I kept thinking about what could happen next. I just wanted her to be okay. What’s the right step to take in a situation like this? The thought of her needing intensive care made my stomach turn. I just hope they know what to do to help her.
options: A. Administer nebulized albuterol and prednisolone B. Transfer to pediatric intensive care unit C. Order chest CT scan D. Administer dexamethasone E. Perform nasopharyngeal endoscopy F. Obtain anteroposterior and lateral neck radiographs G. Begin empiric antibiotic therapy H. Initiate nebulized epinephrine treatment I. Order immediate blood cultures J. Administer supplemental oxygen

question:
I've been feeling increasingly anxious about my health lately. It all started about six months ago when I began experiencing these intermittent fevers. At first, I thought it was just a passing bug, but then the shortness of breath kicked in, and it really terrified me. I can’t even lie down comfortably anymore without feeling like I’m gasping for air. I’m constantly fatigued, and the chest pain has made it even harder to focus on anything else.

When I finally decided to see a doctor, they examined me and mentioned something about my jugular venous pressure being normal, which I guess is a good sign? But then they listened to my heart and noted this strange early diastolic sound, along with a soft murmur at the apex. That was alarming. The doctor didn’t find any issues with my skin or eyes, but I can’t shake off this feeling of dread. 

I keep worrying about what could be causing these symptoms. Could it be something serious like restrictive cardiomyopathy or maybe even infective endocarditis? I feel trapped in this cycle of fear and uncertainty, and I just want to know what’s wrong and how to fix it.
options: A. Restrictive cardiomyopathy B. Nonbacterial thrombotic endocarditis C. Subacute bacterial endocarditis D. Mitral valve infective endocarditis E. Constrictive pericarditis F. Mitral valve prolapse G. Cardiac myxoma H. Atrial septal defect I. Acute viral myocarditis J. Rheumatic mitral stenosis

question:
I can’t shake the worry that’s been consuming me lately. At just 15 years old, I’ve been struggling with my weight for as long as I can remember, and it feels like everything is piling up. I’ve noticed excessive hair growth on my face, abdomen, and lower back, and it’s really affecting my self-esteem. I started my period at 12, but my cycles have been all over the place this past year, which has added to my anxiety.

When I went to the doctor, they examined me and mentioned something called hirsutism, which seems to fit what I’m experiencing. They also pointed out some thickened, darkened skin on the back of my neck, which they said can be linked to hormonal issues. I had some blood tests done, and while I found out my testosterone was slightly elevated, other hormone levels were normal. 

Now, I’m left feeling more confused and anxious than ever. The doctor mentioned we might need to do more tests, but I’m worried about what this could mean for my health. I just want to understand what’s happening to my body and find a way to feel like myself again. It’s all so overwhelming, and I can't help but feel scared about what the future holds.
options: A. Glucagon stimulation test B. Hemoglobin A1C measurement C. C-peptide measurement D. Measurement of fasting plasma glucose E. Insulin tolerance test F. Post-prandial glucose measurement G. Random blood glucose test H. 2-hour oral glucose tolerance test I. Measurement of C peptide with random plasma glucose J. Fasting insulin level

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread as I sit here in the hospital. For the past 28 hours, I’ve been battling this persistent, sharp pain in my abdomen. It’s been so intense that I’ve thrown up multiple times. I’ve always managed my type II diabetes and high cholesterol with medications, but this feels different—much worse.

When I arrived, they took my temperature, and it was 101.5°F. I’ve never felt so feverish before. My heart was racing, and I could feel the nurse checking my blood pressure, which was somehow still normal. I just kept thinking, "What’s wrong with me?" They pressed on my right upper quadrant, and the tenderness made me wince in pain. I noticed they were concerned about my dry mouth and how my capillaries weren’t responding as they should.

I feel completely overwhelmed as they run all these tests. I just want to know what’s going on. The fear of the unknown is weighing heavily on me. What if it’s something serious? I can’t help but worry about what the doctors might find. I just want relief and answers.
options: A. *Enterococcus faecalis* B. *Echinococcus granulosus* C. *Staphylococcus aureus* D. *Clonorchis sinensis* E. *Ascaris lumbricoides* F. *Opisthorchis viverrini* G. *Escherichia coli* H. Hepatitis C virus I. *Klebsiella pneumoniae* J. *Salmonella typhi*

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that has been consuming me since my heart attack about a month ago. I went to my primary care doctor because I’ve been having real trouble achieving an erection. It’s so frustrating because I find my wife incredibly attractive and I really want to be intimate with her, but my body just won’t cooperate. 

I feel this overwhelming guilt about it, like I'm letting her down. It’s hard to explain, but I’ve also found myself feeling down and lacking energy for things I used to love—like working on my motorcycles. Everything just feels off. 

When I visited the doctor, he checked my vitals, and I suppose they were okay, but I’m worried about my blood pressure being high. I’ve been taking medication since the heart attack, and now I can’t help but wonder if these meds might be causing more problems than they’re solving. 

I just feel so overwhelmed—this isn’t just about my physical health; it’s affecting my mood and my relationship. What’s happening to me? I keep questioning if it’s something more serious or if it’s just me being anxious and depressed. I just want to feel like myself again.
options: A. Cardiovascular deconditioning B. Aortoiliac occlusion C. Depression D. Medication side effect E. Performance anxiety disorder F. Anxiety G. Peripheral vascular disease H. Psychogenic erectile dysfunction I. Testosterone deficiency J. Post-MI autonomic dysfunction

question:
I recently went in for what I thought was just a routine check-up, feeling pretty good about myself since I had finally quit smoking. I didn’t have any complaints, and my vital signs seemed stable, so I thought everything was fine. But during the physical exam, something unexpected happened. The doctor performed an osteopathic evaluation and noticed a decreased cranial rhythmic impulse. I couldn’t help but feel a knot in my stomach when I heard that. 

It turns out that there was a cranial strain pattern that indicated some unusual movement in the sphenobasilar synchondrosis. I tried to focus as the doctor explained that this was consistent with findings from previous visits. But honestly, I felt overwhelmed—what did that even mean for me? The doctor went through a list of possible diagnoses, and I just sat there, worrying about what could be going on. I kept thinking: could this lead to something serious? Am I missing something important? I left the office with so many questions and a heavy sense of concern weighing on me. I just hope it’s nothing I need to lose sleep over.
options: A. Temporal bone external rotation B. Vertical strain dysfunction C. Persistent sacral nutation D. Occipitomastoid compression E. Sphenobasilar torsion F. Cranial flexion G. Sphenobasilar extension H. Cranial compression I. Atlanto-occipital joint dysfunction J. Lateral strain pattern

question:
I’ve been feeling really off lately, and honestly, it’s starting to worry me. For about a week now, I've had this persistent abdominal pain that I can only describe as a mild "tummy ache." But the thing is, it feels like it’s more than just that. For the past month, I’ve struggled to get through the simplest daily activities. Most days, I feel an overwhelming sadness that just hangs over me. I can barely find the motivation to do anything, and concentrating at work has become almost impossible.

Some days, I feel so heavy and drained that getting out of bed feels like an enormous task. I’ve been sleeping for 10 to 12 hours, but I still wake up feeling exhausted. I can't shake this heavy sensation in my legs, and it’s like I’m stuck in this fog. On top of everything, I’ve noticed I’m eating more than usual, which is strange for me. I can’t help but worry about what all this means. Is there something really wrong with me? I just want to feel like myself again, but it’s hard not to feel scared about what’s happening to me.
options: A. Feelings of grandiosity and decreased need for sleep B. An increased frequency of symptoms during winter C. Avoiding social activities due to fear of rejection D. Persistent thoughts about maintaining cleanliness E. Intrusive thoughts about past traumatic events F. Periods of intense anger followed by remorse G. Excessive worry about multiple life circumstances H. Guilt related to the way she treats others I. Difficulty maintaining relationships due to unstable self-image J. Recurrent episodes of panic with autonomic symptoms

question:
I recently went to the doctor for a check-up, and I can't shake this feeling of worry. I'm 14 and just enrolled in a new practice, so I thought it would be routine. My parents mentioned that there’s a family history of intestinal polyps on my dad's side, which really got me thinking. I’ve never noticed any blood in my stool, but I can't help but feel uneasy about what that could mean.

During the exam, my vital signs seemed okay, but I still felt anxious. They checked my heart rate, blood pressure, and even my breathing, all of which were normal. I thought that would ease my mind, but it didn’t. They noticed I have some freckles around my mouth, and while my abdomen was soft and non-tender, I couldn’t shake the feeling that something might be wrong.

The doctor didn’t find any obvious issues like fissures or hemorrhoids during the rectal exam, but knowing about the family history of polyps makes me nervous. I keep thinking, what if I develop something serious by the time I turn 18? The thought of colon cancer looms in my mind. I just wish I could feel more reassured, but the uncertainty is really weighing on me.
options: A. Malignant melanoma B. Intussusception C. Small bowel obstruction D. Gastrointestinal bleeding E. Bowel infarction F. Mesenteric ischemia G. Intestinal perforation H. Longitudinal melanonychia I. Colonic volvulus J. Colon cancer

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been creeping in over the past week. It started with these awful headaches that just won’t go away. I thought maybe it was just stress from work, but then I developed this persistent cough that doesn’t seem to get any better—it's completely nonproductive, which makes it even more frustrating. 

To make matters worse, my eyes have been red and irritated, almost like they’re suffusing. I can’t help but feel something is seriously wrong. Just eight days ago, I got bitten by a rat while I was out on a job. I remember thinking it was just a minor incident, but now I can’t stop worrying about what could happen next. 

I’ve been reading about potential infections, and the thought of something serious terrifies me. I keep running through the list of possible bacterial infections in my head. What if it’s something dangerous? I just want to know what’s going on and if I need to take action before it gets worse. I’ve been trying to stay calm, but it’s hard when I feel like my health is slipping away from me. I really hope I can figure this out soon.
options: A. Francisella tularensis B. Bartonella henselae C. Rickettsia typhi D. Spirillum minus E. Leptospirosis F. Borrelia recurrentis G. Streptobacillus moniliformis H. Capnocytophaga canimorsus I. Pasteurella multocida J. Yersinia pestis

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. For the past five months, I've been dealing with watery diarrhea that just won’t let up. It’s accompanied by these crampy pains in my abdomen that come and go, making it hard to focus on anything else. I’ve lost about 1.8 kilograms over the last six months, despite feeling hungry and eating normally. My wife has even noticed that my face and neck flush after meals or when I’m stressed, which makes me feel even more anxious.

On top of all this, I was diagnosed with asthma last year, and I’m on medication for hypertension, but I can’t help but worry that something else is going on. My doctor said my vital signs looked okay, but I’m still so concerned. I’ve been trying to stay calm, but the mild tenderness in my abdomen and the murmur they detected during the exam just adds to my anxiety. 

I can’t stop thinking about what all of this means for my health. If this is something serious, like a malabsorption syndrome or worse, I just don’t know what I’m going to do. I feel so helpless right now, and the thought of it being something like T-cell lymphoma or carcinoid heart disease is terrifying. I really hope I can get some answers soon.
options: A. Malabsorption syndrome B. T-cell lymphoma C. Achlorhydria D. Metastatic liver disease E. Right-sided heart failure F. Dementia G. Carcinoid heart disease H. Bronchial carcinoid I. Megaloblastic anemia J. Cushing syndrome

question:
I can hardly believe what’s happening to me. Just the other day, I found myself in the emergency room, feeling this unbearable facial pain and weakness. I was so fatigued, and on top of that, my head was pounding like never before. I’ve had my struggles with diabetes and HIV, but this felt different—much worse. 

I’ve been trying to keep up with my medications—zidovudine, lamivudine, lopinavir, ritonavir, and metformin—but to be honest, I haven’t been very compliant lately. I know I should be better about it, but life has been overwhelming. When the doctor examined me, I couldn’t believe the tenderness over my right maxillary sinus. And then I saw it—a black eschar over my nares and palate. It was terrifying.

I can’t shake the worry that something serious is going on. My CD4 count is low, and I’ve been reading about the complications that can arise with my condition. I’m terrified to think about what could happen next. What if I start experiencing more severe symptoms? I keep thinking about the things I read—like impaired eye movements or altered mental status. I just want to feel better and not have to face these fears.
options: A. Impaired extraocular eye movements B. Unilateral ptosis C. Retro-orbital pain D. Proptosis with chemosis E. Reduced ability to detect odors F. Blood-tinged nasal discharge G. Diplopia with lateral gaze H. Decreased corneal reflex I. Altered mental status J. Facial numbness in V2 distribution

question:
I can’t shake off this overwhelming sense of fatigue that’s been creeping in over the past couple of days. I’m 80 years old and usually manage just fine on my own, but lately, I’ve felt like I need to take more naps, even though I sleep well at night. Just yesterday, I tried to carry my usual two bags of groceries from the car, something I’ve always done easily, but I struggled to lift even one. It was exhausting, and I had to rest after each trip. 

I’m really worried because I’ve been feeling this way and I can’t pinpoint why. I don’t have any chest pain, or shortness of breath, and I haven’t been running a fever or coughing—nothing like that. But I did have my grandson over last week, and he had a runny nose and cough. I wonder if I caught something from him. 

When I went to urgent care, the doctors seemed concerned too. I looked tired, but they said everything appeared normal with my tests. I’m relieved that my vaccinations are up to date, but I still feel uneasy. What if there’s something they missed? What if this fatigue is a sign of something worse? I just want to feel like myself again. What do I do next?
options: A. Refer to physical therapy B. Initiate a trial of corticosteroids for possible inflammatory condition C. Refer for a sleep study to evaluate for obstructive sleep apnea D. Order a thyroid-stimulating hormone level E. Prescribe empiric antibiotics for possible bacterial infection F. Check serum ferritin and iron studies for possible anemia G. Order a brain MRI to rule out a central nervous system etiology H. Order a chest CT to rule out occult pulmonary pathology I. Order a viral respiratory panel including SARS-CoV-2 J. Perform an echocardiogram to evaluate for heart failure

question:
I can’t shake this nagging worry that something is really wrong. For the past eight months, I’ve been dealing with this intense pain in my legs that just won’t go away. It starts after I walk just a block or two, and then it feels like a terrible cramping and tingling radiates down from my buttocks. It’s especially bad when I’m walking downhill; I can barely manage it. The only relief I get is when I sit down or lean forward, but that’s not a long-term solution.
