I’m 73, and my medical history isn’t exactly comforting. I’ve been living with hypertension, high cholesterol, and type 2 diabetes for years. I had a heart attack when I was 55 and had surgery for an abdominal aortic aneurysm at 60. I’ve been a smoker for 30 years—one pack a day—but I don’t drink or do drugs. I take a bunch of medications for my conditions, but this leg pain has me more concerned than usual.

When I went to the doctor, they checked my vitals, and my blood pressure was a bit high. They also did a physical exam, which showed that my muscle strength is okay, but my feet and toes have reduced sensation. They took X-rays of my spine and found some degenerative changes. Now, I’m left wondering what the next step should be, and I can’t help but feel anxious about what it all means.
options: A. CT angiography of lower extremities B. Bone scan C. Nerve conduction studies D. EMG of lower extremities E. Measurement of the ankle brachial index F. CT scan of the spine G. Measurement of HLA-B27 antigen H. Doppler ultrasound of lower extremities I. MRI scan of the spine J. Plain radiographs of the lumbar spine with flexion and extension views

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread after what happened to me. Just the other day, I was in a low-speed car accident. My vehicle was stationary when another car hit me from behind at 11 miles per hour. At first, I thought I was okay, but then the intense back pain hit me. It’s unlike anything I’ve felt before. I didn’t have any other symptoms, but this pain is just overwhelming.

I’ve been dealing with back issues for a while now—I’ve been going to physical therapy, and the pain is usually worst in the mornings. It gets a bit better when I’m active, but when I’m inactive, it flares up again. And now, with finals coming up, I’m really worried about my academic performance. I can barely focus with this pain, and I’m scared it’s going to affect my grades.

When I got to the emergency department, I was a bundle of nerves. They checked my vitals, and I know I was tense, but what really got me was the physical exam. They found spinal tenderness and limited motion, which made my anxiety spike. I feel like I need documentation to excuse me from my finals and work, but I’m terrified of what this might mean for me long-term. I just want to know what’s wrong and how I can get better.
options: A. Herniated nucleus pulposus B. Psychogenic pain disorder C. Acute disc herniation D. Musculoskeletal strain E. Spondylolisthesis F. Factitious disorder G. Conversion disorder H. Malingering I. Spinal cord contusion J. Vertebral fracture

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been growing for the past three months. I’ve noticed my eyes turning yellow, and it’s becoming more pronounced every day. The itching is relentless, driving me to scratch my skin until it’s raw. I’ve never had any significant health issues before, and I’m not on any medications, so this sudden change is terrifying. 

When I finally went to see the doctor, my vital signs were normal, but the examination revealed the icteric sclerae and those awful scratch marks all over my trunk and arms. I thought maybe it was just a temporary issue, but then they ran some tests, and I felt a wave of dread wash over me. 

The results showed elevated alkaline phosphatase levels, and the thought of my liver being involved is haunting me. I can’t stop thinking about what might be going on inside my body. They mentioned something about a procedure called MRCP, which revealed beading in my bile ducts. Now, I’m just sitting here, waiting to hear what the next steps are. 

I can’t help but feel overwhelmed. The uncertainty is frightening. What if this is something serious? I worry about what the next diagnostic test will reveal. Will it confirm my fears? I just want answers, and the waiting is unbearable.
options: A. Colonoscopy B. Nuclear medicine hepatobiliary scan C. Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiography (PTC) D. Upper endoscopy (EGD) E. Liver biopsy F. No further testing is indicated G. Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) H. Antimitochondrial antibody testing I. Serum IgG4 level testing J. CT scan of the abdomen with contrast

question:
I went to the clinic recently, accompanied by my daughter for what was supposed to be a routine follow-up. Honestly, I felt fine at the time, but my daughter seemed worried. She mentioned that I’ve been feeling more fatigued lately, especially when I exert myself. I’ve also found myself sleeping a lot more than usual, which has me concerned.

Just last week, I finished a 10-day course of ciprofloxacin for a prostate infection, and my urinary symptoms thankfully cleared up. But with my history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and paroxysmal atrial fibrillation, I can’t help but worry. I’m also dealing with moderate vascular dementia, which makes it hard to keep track of everything.

During the examination, they noted my heart rate was unusually low at 45 beats per minute, and I could see the concern on the doctor's face. They found some mild swelling in my legs too, which really freaked me out. I mean, what’s happening to my body? 

Now, I’m left wondering what the next steps will be. What if my heart isn’t functioning properly? I just want to feel normal again. I can’t shake this feeling of dread that something more serious might be going on. I’m anxious about what they might find next.
options: A. Reduce the sotalol dose by 50% B. Obtain an electrocardiogram C. Check serum digoxin level D. Initiate temporary pacing E. Order an echocardiogram F. Schedule Holter monitoring G. Obtain cardiac biomarkers H. Check serum electrolytes I. Stop the verapamil with close follow-up J. Obtain thyroid function tests

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping in over the past year. I’m 47, and lately, I’ve been feeling unusually fatigued. It’s not just physical tiredness; my interest in sex has taken a nosedive, and I hardly ever wake up with morning erections anymore. When I do try to engage in intimacy, it’s just not the same. I even find myself having occasional headaches in the mornings, which only adds to my anxiety.

I’ve ruled out some things—I haven’t lost any hair in unusual places, and there’s no history of trauma or mumps that I know of. I went through puberty just fine, and I’m divorced now with two healthy kids, but I can’t help but feel alarmed about what’s happening to me. 

I learned during my examination that my testicles are smaller than they should be, which is unsettling. My weight is a concern too; my BMI is 38, and I can’t help but wonder if that plays a role. With all these symptoms piling up, I’m left anxious and confused. What could be causing all of this? I’m contemplating what tests might finally give me some answers, but the uncertainty is weighing heavily on my mind. I just want to feel like myself again.
options: A. Karyotype analysis B. Sleep study C. Semen analysis D. Abdominal ultrasound E. Serum cortisol measurement F. MRI of the pituitary G. Bone density scan H. Genetic testing for Klinefelter syndrome I. Dynamic pituitary hormone testing J. Testicular ultrasound

question:
I went to the clinic recently because I needed an evaluation for my dyslipidemia. Just a week ago, I had a fasting lipid panel done, and it showed that my triglycerides were elevated. Honestly, I felt fine, but I couldn’t shake off the worry. My medical history isn't simple; I’ve had an aortic valve replacement and I’m managing type II diabetes. I take several medications like aspirin, warfarin, regular insulin, and atorvastatin, which makes me anxious about potential interactions.

During my visit, my vital signs seemed okay—temperature at 37.0°C, pulse 90, and blood pressure 125/80—but it’s hard not to panic when dealing with all these numbers. Thankfully, the physical exam didn’t reveal anything alarming, but then my healthcare provider mentioned starting fenofibrate for my triglyceride levels. That’s when I started to feel a bit overwhelmed. 

I’ve always heard about the importance of monitoring before starting new medications, and I can’t help but wonder what’s necessary for me. Should I get more tests done? What if something is wrong that we haven’t caught yet? The uncertainty is really unsettling. I just want to make sure I’m doing everything right to manage my health.
options: A. Obtain baseline thyroid function tests B. Obtain gallbladder ultrasound C. Monitor blood glucose levels more frequently D. Obtain liver function test E. Increase aspirin dosage F. Decrease the warfarin dose G. Measure serum creatinine phosphokinase level H. Discontinue atorvastatin I. Check fasting lipid profile again J. Obtain renal function panel

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming worry about my baby boy. Just a month old, he seemed perfectly healthy at first, but for the past ten days, he’s been struggling to feed. Every time he tries to eat, I notice he gets really sweaty and starts having trouble breathing. It’s terrifying to see him like this!

He was born vaginally at 38 weeks, and I thought everything went well—no prenatal care, but he was discharged at just two days old with good Apgar scores. I remember feeling so relieved. But now, I can’t help but feel that something is very wrong. He’s not gaining weight like he should; the pediatrician said he’s only in the 10th percentile for his weight and the 20th for his length.

When I took him to the doctor, they found a heart murmur and said his breathing was labored. They mentioned something about his heart being enlarged and that there’s an intracardiac shunt. I’m just so scared. How could this happen? What does it mean for his future? I keep thinking about all the things that might have changed in his little body and how it could affect him. I just want to help him and make sure he’s okay.
options: A. Closure of the ductus arteriosus B. Increase in systemic vascular resistance C. Left ventricular outflow tract obstruction D. Development of pulmonary venous congestion E. Increased left-to-right shunting due to septal defect enlargement F. Decreased systemic cardiac output G. Failure of physiologic cardiac remodeling H. Decrease in pulmonary vascular resistance I. Progressive right ventricular hypertrophy J. Persistent pulmonary hypertension

question:
I can’t shake this nagging concern about the pain in my lower back. It started just a few days ago, and I can’t pinpoint exactly when or how it happened. I think it might have begun after I woke up one morning, but I really can’t be sure. The pain is right-sided and feels so localized; it doesn’t radiate anywhere else, which is a small relief, I guess.

I’ve had two pregnancies, and I delivered my second child about a year ago, but I didn’t expect to be dealing with this kind of discomfort now. When I think about it, I’m worried there might be something more serious going on. I haven’t noticed any other symptoms, but the pain is really bothering me, especially when I try to move or bend.

I remember during the examination, the doctor mentioned something about the right sacral sulcus being shallow and that there was tenderness in my lower back muscles. I didn’t understand all the medical terms, but it sounded serious. The seated flexion test was positive on my left side, and that just added to my anxiety. I keep wondering what this could mean for me—what if it’s something that could affect my daily life? I just want to find some answers and, honestly, some relief.
options: A. Bilateral sacral flexion about the middle transverse axis B. Left-on-left sacral torsion C. Right unilateral sacral flexion about the middle transverse axis D. Left unilateral sacral flexion about the superior transverse axis E. Right unilateral sacral extension about the superior transverse axis F. Left sacral rotation on a right oblique axis G. Right unilateral sacral flexion about the superior transverse axis H. Left unilateral sacral extension about the middle transverse axis I. Right-on-left sacral torsion J. Left unilateral sacral flexion about the middle transverse axis

question:
I can’t shake off this overwhelming worry about what’s been happening to me lately. I’m only 27, and until now, I thought I was pretty healthy. But for the past few weeks, I’ve been dealing with this relentless upper back pain that just won’t let up. It’s especially bad when I’m studying for long periods, which has been a real issue. The pain feels achy and constant, like a dull knife digging into my back, and I’d rate it a solid 7 out of 10.

I finally decided to visit the clinic, hoping to get some answers. The doctor examined me and said my upper body strength was normal, which was a small relief, but then they found a tender spot on the left side of my back, right near my shoulder blade. It’s so sensitive that I can barely touch it without wincing. 

I’m just feeling so anxious about what this could mean. I’ve read about various possible diagnoses, and honestly, I’m scared that it might be something serious. I keep thinking about how I need to study but can’t because of this pain, and I just want to be normal again. What if it doesn’t go away? I can’t help but feel really concerned about what’s happening to my body.
options: A. Serratus posterior superior strain B. Rhomboid major muscle spasm C. T7 posterior tender point D. Latissimus dorsi muscle strain E. Scapulothoracic bursitis F. T6 posterior tender point G. T12 posterior tender point H. T8 posterior tender point I. Myofascial pain syndrome involving the trapezius J. T9 posterior tender point

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been creeping in over the past two weeks. It all started with my legs swelling up—at first, I thought it was just a side effect of my methadone treatment, but it’s gotten worse. I’ve been so tired, and to make matters worse, I noticed blood in my urine. I’ve tried to brush it off, telling myself it’s probably nothing, but I can’t ignore it any longer.

I’m in a stable relationship, and I want to be there for my partner, but I feel like I’m falling apart. When I went to the doctor, they examined me and I could see the concern in their eyes. They mentioned my pallor and jaundice, and I felt my heart drop when they talked about my liver being enlarged. The doctor even checked my blood pressure, and it was high—152 over 98. 

Now, I’m left with so many questions swirling in my mind. What’s happening to me? Why am I experiencing all of this? I just can’t help but worry about what the next steps will be. The thought that something could be seriously wrong with my kidneys is weighing heavily on me. I keep asking myself, what if this is worse than I think? I just hope I can get some answers soon.
options: A. Membranoproliferative pattern with double contours B. Diffuse mesangial cell proliferation with capillary wall thickening C. Crescentic glomerulonephritis with fibrinoid necrosis D. Granular subepithelial immune deposits ("spike and dome" appearance) E. Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis with podocyte effacement F. Nodular mesangial expansion with Kimmelstiel-Wilson lesions G. Linear IgG deposits along glomerular basement membrane H. Glomerular basement membrane thinning and splitting I. Apple-green birefringence on Congo red stain J. Wire loop lesions with hyaline thrombi

question:
I can’t shake off the worry that gripped me when my 4-month-old son started having trouble breathing. He had been perfectly healthy and born right on time, but it all changed so suddenly. It started with a runny nose, a mild fever, and a cough that lasted for three days. I thought it was just a common cold, but overnight, his breathing became rapid and labored, and it just got worse in a matter of hours.

This morning, I heard these awful sounds when he breathed, and my heart dropped. I immediately called for an ambulance. The paramedics arrived quickly, and they put him on high-flow oxygen through a nasal cannula. While they were with us, they checked his blood sugar, which thankfully was normal, but I couldn’t help but feel the weight of every second.

At the hospital, they checked him again, and I noticed he was so agitated and struggling to breathe. His little chest was moving so fast—70 breaths a minute! I could see his nostrils flaring, and he was making these grunting noises. It felt like an eternity as they examined his lungs and listened for those coarse sounds. I’m terrified of what might happen next. Is he going to be okay? What if this leads to something worse? I just want him to breathe normally again.
options: A. pH, 7.45; partial pressure of carbon dioxide, 35 mm Hg; bicarbonate, 25 mEq/liter B. pH, 7.6; partial pressure of carbon dioxide, 25 mm Hg; bicarbonate, 24 mEq/liter C. pH, 7.3; partial pressure of carbon dioxide, 55 mm Hg; bicarbonate, 28 mEq/liter D. pH, 7.35; partial pressure of carbon dioxide, 50 mm Hg; bicarbonate, 27 mEq/liter E. pH, 7.38; partial pressure of carbon dioxide, 48 mm Hg; bicarbonate, 26 mEq/liter F. pH, 7.2; partial pressure of carbon dioxide, 40 mm Hg; bicarbonate, 15 mEq/liter G. pH, 7.4; partial pressure of carbon dioxide, 45 mm Hg; bicarbonate, 26 mEq/liter H. pH, 7.5; partial pressure of carbon dioxide, 30 mm Hg; bicarbonate, 22 mEq/liter I. pH, 7.1; partial pressure of carbon dioxide, 65 mm Hg; bicarbonate, 20 mEq/liter J. pH, 7.25; partial pressure of carbon dioxide, 60 mm Hg; bicarbonate, 24 mEq/liter

question:
I can’t shake the worry that’s been creeping in over the last few months. My little girl, just four years old, has been experiencing this awful pain and swelling in both her knees, and also her right ankle and wrist. It started about three months ago, and it just seems to get worse. We’ve been using acetaminophen and ice packs, which help a bit, but it’s terrifying to see her struggle. 

Every morning, she wakes up and her joints feel “stuck,” making it hard for her to move. After a few minutes, she can finally get them moving again, but it breaks my heart to see her in discomfort. On top of that, she occasionally complains of mild eye pain, which thankfully goes away on its own. 

Five months ago, she had an upper respiratory infection that didn’t need treatment, but now I’m worried this is something more serious. When I took her to the doctor, they found her joints were swollen and tender, and her eyes showed signs of inflammation. I feel so helpless. Could this be juvenile idiopathic arthritis or something worse? The uncertainty is overwhelming. I just want my little girl to feel like herself again, without this constant pain and swelling. It’s all so frightening.
options: A. Oligoarticular juvenile idiopathic arthritis B. Reactive arthritis C. Seronegative polyarticular juvenile idiopathic arthritis D. Lyme disease E. Psoriatic arthritis F. Rheumatic fever G. Mixed connective tissue disease H. Septic arthritis I. Post-viral arthritis J. Systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread as I sit here in the emergency department. It all started three days ago when I began experiencing this awful abdominal and pelvic pain. At first, I thought it was just something minor, but it has only gotten worse. The pain is everywhere—my abdomen, pelvis, and even my vagina. On top of that, I’ve been dealing with this terrible vaginal itching and discharge that just won’t go away.

I work at an ice cream parlor, and I guess I’ve been pretty carefree, being sexually active with multiple partners. But now, I can’t help but think if I’ve put myself in a dangerous situation. I’ve felt so uncomfortable during the exam, scratching at the itching, and the doctor mentioned something about the discharge being foul-smelling. I’m really scared. What if something is seriously wrong? 

They checked my vital signs, and while the numbers seemed okay, that doesn’t ease my mind. I just want answers. What’s the first step they’re going to take? I feel like I’m in over my head, and I can’t help but worry about what’s happening to my body.
options: A. KOH prep B. Urinalysis C. Nucleic acid amplification test D. Urine hCG E. Vaginal pH testing F. Pelvic ultrasound G. Cervical swab and culture H. Complete blood count I. Serum β-hCG J. Wet mount

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of panic as I sit in the emergency room, clutching my belly. I’m 29 years old and 23 weeks pregnant, and everything seemed fine until this awful pain started. It’s this sharp, stabbing pain in my left flank that just won’t let up, and it radiates down to my groin. To make matters worse, I’ve been feeling nauseous and have thrown up a couple of times. I can’t believe I’m having to deal with this right now.

I keep running to the bathroom, feeling like I have to go all the time, but there’s no relief. Thank goodness there’s no vaginal discharge, but when they checked me, I could see blood. That was terrifying. My pregnancy has been so normal up until now—I’ve been going to all my prenatal appointments and taking my vitamins. I don’t smoke or drink, and I thought I was doing everything right.

The doctors are checking my vitals, and I’m trying to stay calm, but the tenderness in my side and the blood I saw are making me really anxious. I can’t help but worry about what this means for my baby. I just want to know what’s happening and what’s the next step. I’m feeling so helpless right now.
options: A. Renal ultrasound B. Observation and repeat urinalysis in 24 hours C. Trial of empiric antibiotics for presumed urinary tract infection D. CT urography with contrast E. Magnetic resonance urography F. Noncontrast CT scan of abdomen and pelvis G. Cystoscopy with retrograde pyelography H. Abdominal X-ray to evaluate for nephrolithiasis I. Intravenous pyelogram J. Renal radiograph

question:
I can’t shake off this overwhelming sense of dread. It all started four days ago when I was admitted to the hospital for diverticulitis. I thought I was on the mend, but then everything took a turn. Out of nowhere, I felt this sharp, stabbing pain in my chest that made it hard to breathe. I remember the panic setting in as I struggled to catch my breath. 

When the doctors examined me, they seemed worried too. My heart was racing—115 beats per minute—and my oxygen levels were alarmingly low at just 85%. I could see the concern on their faces, even though I was alert and aware of what was happening around me. They listened to my lungs and noted that they sounded clear, which was a small relief, but they also mentioned my left leg was swollen and tender.

I’ve been fully vaccinated against Covid-19, thankfully, and they ruled that out with a negative test. But still, the uncertainty was crushing. They did a chest X-ray that didn’t show anything wrong with my heart or lungs, yet I could feel something was off. I could see the doctors discussing what to do next, and I couldn’t help but worry about what might be happening inside me. What if it was something serious? I just wanted answers, but all I felt was fear.
options: A. Administer supplemental oxygen and observe B. Obtain a CT angiogram of the chest C. Initiate oral anticoagulation therapy immediately D. Perform an echocardiogram to assess for right heart strain E. Perform a lower extremity Doppler ultrasound F. Obtain a ventilation-perfusion scan of the lungs G. Order a D-dimer test to rule out pulmonary embolism H. Administer thrombolytic therapy immediately without further testing I. Obtain an arterial blood gas analysis J. Administer intravenous heparin

question:
This morning started off like any other day, but then everything changed. I woke up and, to my horror, discovered that I had completely lost vision in my right eye. There was no pain, which made it all the more alarming. I felt a rush of panic as I tried to figure out what was happening. After what felt like an eternity—about an hour—I slowly began to regain my vision, but the fear lingered. 

I’ve been managing hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and stage 4 chronic kidney disease for some time now, and I often worry about how these conditions might affect me. When I went to see the doctor, my blood pressure was surprisingly high at 160/90. Thankfully, my heart rate was steady, but I couldn’t shake the anxiety. They did a thorough examination and everything seemed okay; my vision tests came back normal, and the neurologic exam showed no issues either. Still, the sudden loss of vision felt like a ticking time bomb in my mind. 

I just can’t help but think about what could have caused it. The doctors mentioned some tests to further investigate, and now I’m left with this nagging worry about what all of this could mean for my future. I just want to understand what happened to me.
options: A. Serum homocysteine level measurement B. Retinal fluorescein angiography C. CT angiogram of the brain D. Visual evoked potential testing E. Transcranial Doppler ultrasound F. Magnetic resonance angiogram of the brain with gadolinium G. Electroretinography H. Dilated ophthalmoscopy I. Echocardiography with bubble study J. Carotid Doppler ultrasound

question:
I can hardly believe what’s happening with my newborn son. Just two days old, and he’s already in distress. I delivered him at term without any issues, but now I’m filled with dread. I’m 40 and have my own health struggles—epilepsy, diabetes, and hypertension—so I know my medications like metformin, phenytoin, and labetalol can’t be great for him. I can’t shake the guilt of being a smoker and having a drink now and then, especially since I didn’t manage to get any prenatal care. 

When the doctors examined him, they found several concerning features: microcephaly, hypertelorism, and a flat nasal bridge. I can’t stop thinking about how he has a cleft palate and thin upper lip. It feels surreal that they noted his tiny fingers and nails are underdeveloped, too. And then there was the murmur in his heart, along with weak pulses in his legs. 

I can hardly breathe as the doctors talk, and I keep wondering what’s going on. What could have caused all of this? I’m terrified that it might be linked to my health issues or my lifestyle choices. I just want to know if there’s hope for him. What if it’s something serious? I can’t help but feel overwhelmed and heartbroken.
options: A. Chromosomal abnormality such as trisomy 21 B. Fetal alcohol syndrome C. Teratogenicity caused by maternal medication D. Maternal diabetes-related embryopathy E. Congenital rubella syndrome F. Perinatal hypoxia due to placental insufficiency G. Congenital heart defect unrelated to teratogens H. Intrauterine growth restriction due to maternal smoking I. Neonatal abstinence syndrome J. Patent ductus arteriosus

question:
I can hardly believe what just happened. I’m 65, and I was just working in my garage when I suddenly felt this overwhelming dizziness, like the world was spinning around me. I nearly passed out. I knew something wasn't right, so I called for help, and they rushed me to the emergency department.

When I got there, they took my vital signs, and I remember feeling relieved that my temperature was normal, but my pulse was really fast—117 beats per minute. They mentioned my blood pressure was low, and I could feel the anxiety creeping in. I was scared. They decided to give me some blood products and ordered a CT scan, but then things took a turn for the worse. My temperature shot up, and my blood pressure plummeted to 87/48 mmHg. I felt like my heart was racing at 180 beats per minute, and I started struggling to breathe.

I can’t stop worrying about what could be happening to me. I mean, could it be an infection from the transfusion? Or something even worse? I can’t shake the feeling that something is seriously wrong, and I just want answers. What is going on with my body? I’ve never felt so helpless in my life.
options: A. An underlying malignancy causing anemia of chronic disease B. Sudden rupture of a vessel C. Sepsis secondary to bacterial contamination of transfused blood products D. An undiagnosed bleeding disorder such as hemophilia E. Acute hemolysis due to ABO incompatibility F. Hypocalcemia due to citrate toxicity from transfusion G. Autoimmune reaction against red blood cell antigens H. Transfusion-associated circulatory overload (TACO) I. A past medical history of repeat GI and respiratory infections J. A history of chronic kidney disease causing erythropoietin deficiency

question:
I still can't shake the panic from that day. It all started when my wife found me lying unconscious on the kitchen floor. I vaguely remember feeling off, but I didn’t realize how serious it had become until she called for help. I could tell something was wrong; I had been acting strangely since losing my job a month ago, but I didn't think it would lead to this. 

When the paramedics arrived, I felt completely out of it. I couldn't open my eyes, and even when they tried to talk to me, all I could manage were some nonsensical sounds. It was terrifying. I remember my wife mentioning that she found an empty bottle of my prescription medication nearby, which made me feel even worse. 

At the hospital, I was lethargic and struggling to breathe. I was so cold, and I could barely feel anything. My heart was racing, but my pulse was low, and I could see the worried looks on the faces of the doctors and nurses. They said my breathing was shallow, and I could see that my pupils were not responding as they should. They were talking about different treatments, but I couldn’t focus on what they were saying. All I could think was how frightened I was, and how I wished I could just wake up and make everything better.
options: A. Observation and supportive care only B. Intravenous fluids and naloxone C. Activated charcoal and flumazenil D. Assisted respiration and urine alkalinization E. Gastric lavage and sodium bicarbonate F. Endotracheal intubation and N-acetylcysteine G. Endotracheal intubation and intravenous naloxone H. Intravenous lipid emulsion therapy I. Hemodialysis and intravenous thiamine J. Intravenous benzodiazepines and glucose administration

question:
I’ve been dealing with this nagging arm pain that just won’t go away, and it’s really starting to concern me. Lately, I’ve also noticed some strange tingling sensations, which I can’t shake off. I’ve been trying to figure out what’s going on, and the more I think about it, the more worried I get. 

I remember one night when the pain was so intense that I couldn’t sleep. It felt like it was getting worse whenever I moved around, but oddly, it seemed to ease up a bit when I rested. I’ve heard that this could be a sign of something serious like cervical radiculopathy, but then again, I’m not sure. I’ve also tried holding my arm above my head to see if that helps, and sometimes it does ease the pain, but I’m still feeling so anxious.

I can’t help but wonder if I should see a doctor soon. I mean, the thought of it being something like peripheral neuropathy or even worse has been weighing heavily on my mind. I just want to understand what’s happening and find some relief. It’s so hard not knowing what’s going on with my body. I really need to get to the bottom of this.
options: A. Improvement with rest and worsening with activity B. Positive Tinel's sign at the elbow C. Nocturnal exacerbation of symptoms D. Relief of pain when holding the arm above the head E. Weakness in multiple nerve distributions F. Exacerbation with repetitive hand movements G. Reproduction of pain with tilting head to affected side and rotating head to contralateral side H. Bilateral symmetric distribution of symptoms I. Compensatory inter-phalangeal joint flexion of the thumb when attempting to pinch J. Pain localized to a specific dermatome

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that settled over me this past hour. I suddenly found myself in the emergency department, clutching my chest in agony. The pain was intense, radiating to my back, and it only seemed to worsen after I ate. I felt nauseous and, to my horror, I ended up vomiting twice—thankfully, it wasn’t bloody, but it was terrifying nonetheless.

I’ve dealt with hypertension and type 2 diabetes for years now, but this felt different. I’ve been a pack-a-day smoker for three decades and drink a few beers every day, but I never thought it would come to this. When I saw the nurse, my heart was racing at 110 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was alarmingly low. They mentioned something about my temperature being high too, which only added to my anxiety.

During the examination, the doctor pressed on my abdomen, and I winced in pain; it felt so distended. I couldn’t help but worry about what was happening inside me. They said my bowel sounds were decreased, and I could feel the panic rising. I just wanted to understand what was going on. I never expected to be in this situation, and I can’t help but feel that something truly serious is taking place.
options: A. at McBurney's point B. at the 6th intercostal space on the right C. between the spinous and transverse processes of T5 and T7 on the left D. at the 5th intercostal space on the right E. between the spinous and transverse processes of T7 and T8 on the left F. at the costovertebral angle on the right G. at the 8th intercostal space on the left H. between the spinous and transverse processes of T8 and T9 on the right I. at the 7th intercostal space on the right J. at the 9th intercostal space on the right

question:
I can hardly put into words how terrified I felt when my baby was born at just 35 weeks of gestation. He weighed only 5 pounds and 8 ounces, and I could sense something was very wrong right away. The doctors had already told me about the oligohydramnios during my pregnancy, but nothing could prepare me for what I saw. 

As soon as he came into the world, his skin had a bluish tint, and he barely let out a weak cry. I remember the panic rising in my chest as I watched him struggle to breathe, gasping for air. The doctors were examining him closely and pointed out several concerning features: his nose was flat, his ears seemed oddly shaped, and his chin was receding. To make matters worse, they discovered that one of his legs was shorter than the other, and his right toe was displaced. 

The sound of diminished breath sounds filled the room, and my heart sank further. They mentioned something about his kidneys not looking right on an ultrasound, too. I couldn’t help but feel a wave of dread wash over me—what could be causing all of this? The doctors were discussing tests, and I felt completely helpless, just hoping they would find answers soon.
options: A. Serum creatinine and electrolyte levels B. Skeletal survey C. Karyotyping D. Genetic microarray analysis E. Renal biopsy F. X-ray of the chest G. Chest X-ray H. Voiding cystourethrogram I. Echocardiography J. Amniotic fluid analysis

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of unease since my recent visit to the emergency department. It all started during a routine health check when my primary care doctor mentioned my blood pressure reading—a staggering 180/115 mmHg. I felt fine at the time, no symptoms whatsoever, but the doctor referred me to the ER, and I couldn’t help but feel a growing knot in my stomach.

When I arrived at the hospital, they took my blood pressure again, and it was even higher—197/105 mmHg. My heart raced as they examined me. They checked my temperature, pulse, and oxygen levels, and thankfully, those seemed normal. But I couldn’t shake the worry. I’ve had hypertension before, but this felt different. 

The doctors mentioned my lab results from last week were normal, which gave me a slight sense of relief, but I kept thinking about the implications of all this. What if it’s something serious? I kept hearing terms like “hypertensive emergency” and “acute kidney injury” in my mind, and it sent chills down my spine. 

I’m trying to remain calm, but I can’t help but feel anxious about what this all means for my health. What could be causing all this? I just want answers and to understand why my body is reacting this way.
options: A. Essential hypertension with acute kidney injury B. Pheochromocytoma crisis C. Hypertensive urgency D. Primary hyperaldosteronism E. Hypertensive emergency F. Malignant hypertension G. Acute hypertensive nephrosclerosis H. Secondary hypertension due to renal artery stenosis I. Chronic kidney disease with hypertensive urgency J. Hypertension

question:
I can hardly shake off the anxiety after my recent follow-up visit. A year ago, I was diagnosed with stage IV breast cancer, and since then, it's been a whirlwind of treatments and uncertainty. I've been on letrozole and zoledronic acid since my initial therapy with paclitaxel, but just when I thought I was managing, my ulcerative colitis flared up after being stable for years. 

I remember those months of fatigue, joint pain, and, worst of all, the bloody diarrhea. It was terrifying. After trying mesalamine and glucocorticoids without relief, I was put on prednisone. The relief was almost immediate, but as I tried to taper my dose down to 2.5 mg, I was met with overwhelming fatigue and nausea. It’s like every time I take a step forward, I’m pushed two steps back. 

Now, I’m on 5 mg daily, which keeps things somewhat stable, but I can’t help but worry about my back pain and the fact that I have bone metastases. The recent CT scan showed stable lesions, but it also revealed a fracture in my vertebrae. It’s hard to focus on anything else. 

I just want to know what the next steps are. The uncertainty feels suffocating, and I can’t help but feel a sense of dread about what’s next.
options: A. Obtain 24-hour urinary free cortisol measurement B. Reassure the patient, and recommend a slower prednisone taper with an initial dose of 4 mg C. Increase prednisone dose to 7.5 mg daily and monitor symptoms D. Obtain cortisol levels 30 and 60 minutes after injection of cosyntropin E. Start hydrocortisone replacement at physiologic doses F. Obtain early morning ACTH and cortisol measurements for three consecutive days G. Schedule an endocrinology consultation for steroid-sparing therapy H. Perform CRH stimulation test I. Perform bilateral adrenal CT with contrast J. Obtain a contrast-enhanced MRI of the head (with pituitary protocol)

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping over me for the last five days. It all started when I noticed some strange vaginal symptoms—itching, redness, and a thick white discharge that just wouldn’t go away. I’ve never had anything like this before, and it’s really unsettling. I went to see the doctor, hoping for some answers.

I’m 62 and I already deal with heart failure, chronic kidney disease, and type 2 diabetes, which makes everything feel so much scarier. My medications include metformin, metoprolol, and a few others, but I wasn’t sure if any of that could be causing this. The doctor examined me and found the same symptoms I was worried about—vulvar redness and that thick discharge. They even did a test that revealed pseudohyphae, which I later learned is often linked to yeast infections.

Now, after receiving treatment for what they think is a genitourinary issue, I can't stop wondering what the next step should be. They mentioned my diabetes medication, empagliflozin, but I don’t know if I should stop it or change something. I feel like each decision could have huge implications for my health, and it’s weighing heavily on my mind. I just want to feel normal again.
options: A. Stop empagliflozin, and start canagliflozin B. Discontinue empagliflozin and increase metformin dose C. Add sitagliptin and discontinue empagliflozin D. Switch empagliflozin to dapagliflozin E. Continue the current medication regimen F. Reduce empagliflozin dose to 5 mg daily G. Discontinue both empagliflozin and metformin H. Stop empagliflozin and initiate insulin therapy I. Stop empagliflozin, and start dulaglutide J. Switch to a combination of metformin and sulfonylurea

question:
I can’t shake off this nagging worry that’s been growing over the past few weeks. It started with a vague discomfort in my abdomen, something I couldn’t quite put my finger on. At first, I thought it was nothing serious, but as the days passed, the discomfort lingered, and I began to feel more anxious. I’ve tried to convince myself it’s just a passing issue, but the unease only deepened.

I went to the clinic today, hoping for some reassurance. I explained to the doctor that I hadn’t experienced any burning when urinating, no flank pain, and thankfully, no bleeding. But during the examination, I could feel my heart racing a bit when the doctor noted tenderness in my abdomen and the fluid wave. The bimanual pelvic exam revealed something concerning—right adnexal fullness. What does that even mean?

My medical history isn’t really alarming; I manage my hypertension with lisinopril, and I’ve had two cesarean sections, but this all feels so different. As I lay there, I couldn’t help but think about what could be wrong. The doctor mentioned something about histopathologic findings, but I couldn’t focus on the details. I just felt this overwhelming sense of dread, wondering what the next steps would be and what it all meant for my health.
options: A. Irregularly narrowed tubules with papillary branching B. Granulosa cells arranged in a Call-Exner body pattern C. Uniformly small, round cells with scant cytoplasm D. Mucin-filled glandular structures E. Spindle-shaped fibroblast bundle F. Sheets of large, pleomorphic cells with necrosis G. Signet-ring cells within glandular tissue H. Thecal cell hyperplasia I. Psammoma bodies surrounded by serous epithelium J. Lipid-laden stromal cells

question:
I can’t shake this worry that something’s really wrong with me. It’s been a month since I gave birth, and I’ve been dealing with this nagging low back pain that just won’t go away. It started out as a dull ache, but now it feels sharper, especially when I bend forward. I’ve tried taking over-the-counter pain relievers, but they hardly make a dent. 

When I went to the clinic, I felt so anxious. The doctor examined my back and mentioned that my sacral bases felt deep and that the angles were off on both sides. That was unsettling to hear. I can barely move without feeling pain, and it’s terrifying to think about what might be causing it. The rest of the exam seemed fine, but I can’t help but feel that something is seriously wrong. 

I keep wondering about the next steps. What if there are more issues hiding behind this pain? I just want to feel normal again, especially after having my baby. I’m left thinking about what additional tests or findings might come next. I can’t shake this feeling of dread, and it’s really starting to take a toll on me.
options: A. Positive spring test with sacral sulcus asymmetry on the left B. Positive spring test and negative seated flexion test C. Negative spring test and equivocal seated flexion test D. Positive spring test and equivocal seated flexion test E. Positive spring test and positive seated flexion test on the right F. Positive spring test with bilateral sacral sulcus asymmetry G. Positive spring test and positive seated flexion test on the left H. Negative spring test and positive seated flexion test on the left I. Bilaterally positive seated flexion test with a negative spring test J. Positive spring test and positive sphinx test

question:
I've been weightlifting for years, but recently, something's gone wrong. About a week ago, I started feeling this nagging back pain that just won’t go away. It’s an aching discomfort, and I’d rate it a solid 6 out of 10. What worries me the most is that it gets worse when I lift heavy weights at the gym. I’ve tried to push through it, but the pain really makes it hard to enjoy my workouts like I used to. 

When I visited the clinic, I hoped for some answers. The doctor did an examination and mentioned something about restrictions in my spine, specifically around T5 to T10. I could barely touch my toes or bend backward without feeling sharp pain. I felt so helpless when they pointed out that my T7 was positioned oddly. 

It’s terrifying to think about what this could mean for my health and my ability to lift weights. I just want to get back to my routine without this constant worry hanging over me. What if this is something serious? I can’t help but feel anxious about what might be next.
options: A. ERRSL B. FSLRR C. FSRRL D. ESRRL E. NSRRL F. ESLRR G. FRRSL H. NRRSL I. NSLRR J. FSLLR

question:
I can't shake off this feeling of dread as I think back to my baby's one-year checkup. It was supposed to be a routine visit, but my heart felt heavy with concern. Since he was six months old, he has been plagued by infections. I remember the terrifying day when he was hospitalized for pneumonia at just eight months. It’s hard to forget the worry etched on the doctors’ faces. And then there were the three episodes of ear infections, each one making me feel more helpless than the last.

His birth was unremarkable; everything went smoothly, and I had hoped that would mean good health for him. But then I learned about our family history—cousins with similar issues and the heartbreaking loss of one at just two years old from pneumonia. My mind races with fear that my son could face the same fate.

At the checkup, the doctor said he looked well and wasn’t in distress, which eased my anxiety slightly. But I can't help but wonder about what lies ahead. I find myself questioning whether there’s something more serious going on with his immune system, especially with all those infections. The uncertainty is overwhelming, and I just want to protect my child from any more suffering. What if this is just the beginning?
options: A. The condition shows complete penetrance in female carriers B. This disease is characterized by B cell maturation problem resulting in B cell adherence C. Symptoms rarely start before 2 years of age D. The condition shows sporadic mutations in 80% of cases E. This diagnosis account for the most common primary immune-deficiencies, almost 50% of them F. This disease primarily affects the innate immune system G. T-cell dysfunction is the primary immunological defect H. This is an autosomal dominant disease I. Neutrophil dysfunction is the main pathological finding J. The condition primarily affects the complement system

question:
I can hardly believe what’s happening to me. Just a week ago, I was fine—completely oriented and able to recognize my husband. But now, I’ve been confused for several days, unable to even recognize him. It’s terrifying. I’m 82 years old, and while I have well-managed type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and hyperlipidemia, this sudden change in my mental state has me deeply worried.

My husband took me to the clinic, where they examined me. I could only remember my name; everything else felt like a fog. They mentioned something about diffuse wheezing and that my chest looked a bit odd. I’ve had a long history of smoking—over 60 years—and I managed a steel mill, where I might have been exposed to asbestos. I always thought I was safe, but now I’m not so sure.

The doctors did some imaging, and I can’t shake the feeling of dread. They found a mass in my right lung, and while they didn’t find any tumors in my brain, I can’t help but think about what this means. I’m scared. What if this is something serious, like cancer? I’m just trying to hold it together, but the uncertainty is overwhelming. What will happen next?
options: A. Small-cell lung cancer B. Squamous-cell carcinoma of the lung C. Adenosquamous carcinoma D. Mesothelioma E. Mucoepidermoid carcinoma F. Non-small cell lung cancer, NOS G. Large-cell lung cancer H. Pleomorphic carcinoma I. Adenocarcinoma of the lung J. Bronchial carcinoid tumor

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety that’s been building up inside me lately. At 62, I never thought I’d be dealing with something like this. For the past year, I’ve been struggling with this overwhelming urge to urinate, especially during the night. I wake up four to five times, and it’s exhausting. It’s not just annoying; it’s downright worrying. 

To make matters worse, I’ve had several bouts of acute cystitis that needed treatment with antibiotics like ciprofloxacin, but it feels like things are only getting worse, not better. When I went to the doctor, they performed a digital rectal examination. I thought maybe it would bring some relief, but instead, I learned that my prostate is firm and symmetrically enlarged. 

I can't help but think about the potential complications ahead. What if I end up with chronic infections or even something more serious? The thought of developing issues like bladder wall hypertrophy or irreversible kidney problems is terrifying. I just want to feel normal again. I can’t help but worry about what this all means for my future and if I will ever find relief from this constant discomfort.
options: A. Recurrent urinary tract infections with gram-negative organisms B. Impaired intracavernosal blood flow C. Urethral stricture formation D. Bladder wall hypertrophy and trabeculation E. Irreversible decrease in renal function F. Progressive detrusor muscle weakness G. Development of prostatic calculi H. Inflammation of the renal interstitium I. Vesicoureteral reflux J. Chronic bacterial prostatitis

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that settled in when I was hospitalized recently. I'm 59, a lifelong smoker with a heavy history, and I went in for some troubling respiratory symptoms. Breathing had become a struggle, and I was wheezing constantly. They decided to perform a bronchoscopy, which felt pretty routine, but then things took a turn I never expected. 

After the procedure, I was back in my room, but I started feeling mildly short of breath. They gave me an albuterol nebulizer, and I thought I’d be okay. But just two hours later, everything spiraled out of control. I suddenly couldn’t breathe, my heart felt like it was racing, and I felt so weak I could hardly respond. I was terrified when they had to perform a needle decompression for a pneumothorax. 

It all happened so fast, and I can’t help but wonder if there was something they could have done to catch the problem earlier. I keep thinking about how crucial it is for medical teams to monitor closely after such procedures. I wish there had been better protocols in place, or maybe even more regular checks on my vital signs. It’s haunting to think about what could have happened if things hadn’t turned around in that moment.
options: A. Mandatory documentation of all procedural steps in the electronic health record B. Implementation of routine post-bronchoscopy monitoring with continuous pulse oximetry C. Introduction of a process improvement measure to ensure routine post-bronchoscopy chest radiography D. Implementation of a real-time procedure tracking system E. Development of standardized post-procedure nursing protocols F. Implementation of a post-procedure safety checklist G. Regular assessment of vital signs every 15 minutes for 2 hours post-procedure H. Use of a structured template for the handover after bronchoscopy I. Establishment of clear escalation protocols for post-procedure complications J. Requirement for direct communication between bronchoscopist and primary team

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry after my recent visit to the clinic. I’m 42 and love playing tennis, but lately, my right elbow has been feeling strangely tight. It’s not painful during my regular activities, but the moment I try to hit a tennis ball, that soreness hits me hard. 

When I went to see the doctor, they examined my elbow and found tenderness on the lateral side. They also noticed that I couldn't fully supinate my right hand. It’s such a strange feeling—one minute, I’m enjoying the game, and the next, I’m left wondering what’s really going on with my arm. 

I keep thinking about all the possible diagnoses they mentioned. I can’t help but worry if it’s something serious like a ligament sprain or maybe even lateral epicondylitis. What if this limits my ability to play tennis for good? I just want to get back to the court without this nagging tightness. The thought of not being able to play is really stressing me out. I keep asking myself, how did this happen? I hope I find out soon what’s wrong so I can figure out how to fix it.
options: A. Ulnar collateral ligament sprain B. Olecranon bursitis C. Supinator muscle strain D. Lateral epicondylitis E. Posterior radial head F. Radial nerve entrapment G. Medial epicondylitis H. Proximal radioulnar joint dysfunction I. Anterior radial head J. Radial collateral ligament tear

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been creeping in over the past week. It started with a nagging cough that just wouldn’t go away, and now I’m struggling to catch my breath. It feels like I’m dragging my body around, completely exhausted. My cough has turned productive, and I’ve noticed the sputum is this unsettling shade of green. 

Thinking back, I realize I’ve had this happen before. I was hospitalized twice in the past nine months for pneumonia in my left lung. I can't help but feel anxious about it all. I’ve been a smoker for 36 years, and I know that can’t be helping. 

When I finally made it to the doctor, my fever was high, and my heart was racing. The nurse told me my oxygen levels were alarmingly low. I could hear wheezing in my lungs, and the doctor listened closely, noting the crackles in my left lung. 

Now, I’m just sitting here, waiting for answers. What’s happening to me? Why does it feel like I can’t breathe properly? The doctor mentioned needing to take further steps, but I can’t help but feel worried about what that might mean. I just want to feel normal again, to breathe easily without fear of what might be lurking in my lungs.
options: A. Pulmonary function tests B. Echocardiography C. V/Q scan of the lungs D. Empiric antibiotic therapy without further imaging E. CT scan of the chest F. Chest ultrasound G. Sputum culture and sensitivity testing H. Bronchoscopy I. Pulmonary function testing J. Blood cultures

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of worry since my parents took me to the doctor. I’ve been feeling so uncomfortable in my own skin lately, constantly checking my weight multiple times a day. It’s like my mind is fixated on the number, and no matter what, I always feel like I'm overweight. I can see the concern in my parents' eyes—they brought me to the physician because they think my behavior is alarming.

At the appointment, everything felt surreal. My height is 166 cm, and I weigh 50 kg, which seems fine on paper, but I see myself differently. I can’t help but feel ashamed and embarrassed about my body. The doctor did a physical exam, and I could tell things weren’t right when they noticed my thin appearance, damaged molars, and those calluses forming on my knuckles. They even mentioned mild swelling in my parotid glands, which made my heart sink.

I’m scared that I’m not just going through a phase, and the thought of being diagnosed with something like anorexia or bulimia terrifies me. I just want to feel normal again, but how do I get there when I feel so trapped in this cycle of shame and anxiety? I really hope that I can figure this out before it gets worse.
options: A. Atypical anorexia nervosa B. Bulimia nervosa C. Picky eating disorder D. Normal adolescent behavior E. Major depressive disorder F. Binge eating disorder G. Anorexia nervosa H. Avoidant/restrictive food intake disorder I. Other specified feeding or eating disorder J. Body dysmorphic disorder

question:
I’m really worried about what’s been happening to me lately. I’m 15, and up until now, I’ve had no health issues, but ever since I joined the gymnastics team at school, my upper back pain has been getting worse. It started off as just a little tightness, but now it feels like a constant ache, and my muscles are so tight that it’s hard to move sometimes.

I finally decided to see a doctor because it was getting unbearable. During the examination, the doctor mentioned something about my left midthoracic paraspinal muscles being hypertonic. I didn’t really understand what that meant, but it sounds serious. They also found that the transverse processes from T2 to T8 were more forward on the left side, and that didn’t change when I moved my back.

I can’t shake the feeling that something is really wrong. It’s scary not knowing what’s going on, especially since I’ve always been active and healthy. I just want to be able to enjoy gymnastics without this pain. I’ve been thinking about all the diagnosis options the doctor mentioned, but I’m just hoping for some clarity soon. What if it’s something that keeps me from doing what I love?
options: A. T2-8 NSRRR B. T2-8 ESRRR C. T2-8 FSRRL D. T2-8 FSLRR E. T2-8 NSRLL F. T2-8 ESRRL G. T2-8 FSRRR H. T2-8 NSLRR I. T2-8 NSRRL J. T2-8 ESLRR

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread after what happened to me recently. It all started about 48 hours ago when I noticed I was feeling unusually lethargic. I mean, I’ve always had some memory issues, but I was usually able to interact with the staff and manage my day-to-day routine. Suddenly, I found myself struggling to respond to their questions, and I was completely out of it.

When the nurse came in, I remember feeling so confused; I didn’t even know where I was or what day it was. I was so embarrassed when I realized I needed help with basic things like changing my linens because of incontinence. My temperature shot up to 102.1°F, and my heart was racing at 120 beats per minute. They told me I was combative, but I just felt overwhelmed and frightened.

When I arrived at the emergency department, I couldn’t make sense of anything, and I could see the worry on the faces of the staff. They kept talking about my decision-making capacity and mentioned needing to place a Foley catheter, which terrified me. I just wanted to be myself again and not feel so lost. I keep wondering if I was really capable of making decisions or if my condition had completely taken that away from me. It’s such a scary thought.
options: A. The patient’s capacity is intact but temporarily diminished by infection B. The patient has capacity if reoriented and calm C. The patient does have capacity to make decisions D. Capacity is impaired due to advanced dementia E. The patient does not have capacity to make decisions F. Capacity should be deferred to the nursing home staff’s assessment G. The patient has capacity but requires further evaluation H. Capacity cannot be determined at this time I. The patient’s refusal indicates she retains capacity J. The patient lacks capacity due to delirium caused by infection

question:
I can hardly believe what just happened. I’m a 28-year-old carpenter, and about an hour ago, I was climbing some stairs when I suddenly felt this intense, ripping pain in my chest. It was so severe that I almost froze in place. The pain shot through to my back, and I couldn’t shake off the worry that something was seriously wrong. 

I’ve always had a monitored heart murmur, but I never thought it would lead to something like this. I don’t take any medications, and I’m in a committed relationship, so I thought I was in good health. I don’t use drugs or travel much, which makes this even scarier. When I finally made it to the emergency department, I felt like I was in a fog of anxiety. 

The doctors seemed concerned too, noting that I looked tall and in moderate distress. They took my vital signs, and I could see the worry on their faces as they recorded my blood pressure and pulse. I felt my heart racing as they examined me. I just wanted answers. Why was I experiencing this pain? What was happening to me? I couldn’t help but think about what might be lurking beneath the surface. I’m just hoping for a clear diagnosis soon because this is all so overwhelming.
options: A. Early diastolic murmur at the left upper sternal border B. Late systolic crescendo murmur at the apex with mid-systolic click C. Harsh systolic murmur at the left upper sternal border D. Holosystolic murmur radiating to the axilla E. Systolic ejection murmur at the right second intercostal space F. Continuous machinery murmur at the left infraclavicular region G. Mid-systolic click without a murmur H. Mid-diastolic murmur at the left lower sternal border I. Opening snap with a diastolic rumble at the apex J. Pansystolic murmur at the left lower sternal border

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread since my surgery. It’s been eight days since my hysterectomy for those troublesome uterine fibroids, and I thought I’d be on the mend by now. But then I got the news that my platelet count has plummeted to 9,000. I mean, it was 200,000 before the operation! How could this happen? 

I’ve been in the hospital, and they’ve been keeping a close eye on me because of some complications from wound cellulitis. It’s terrifying to see those little spots—petechiae—on my skin, and I’ve noticed some oozing from my surgical site. I try to stay calm, but I can’t help worrying about what it all means. 

The doctors have me on dalteparin to prevent blood clots, but I’ve never had heparin before. I’m also on vancomycin to fight off a MRSA infection. They say my vital signs are stable, but the thought of this sudden drop in platelets is haunting me. 

I keep hearing them talk about heparin-induced thrombocytopenia, and I can't help but feel overwhelmed. What if this is serious? I wish I could just get through this recovery without more complications. They mentioned possibly needing more tests, but I’m just so anxious thinking about what could be next. Will everything be okay? I just want to feel normal again.
options: A. Anti-PF4/heparin antibody test with optical density measurement B. Anti-platelet antibody screening with cross-matching C. Serotonin release assay D. Serial platelet count monitoring with 4T score calculation E. Platelet factor 4-dependent P-selectin expression assay F. HIT enzyme-linked immunosorbent immunoassay G. Flow cytometry-based platelet activation assay H. No further testing is needed I. Heparin-induced platelet aggregation assay J. Combined functional and immunological HIT testing

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that has settled in since I took my 10-month-old son to the doctor. For the past two days, he's had a fever and has been so irritable, and just last night, he started tugging at his left ear. It’s been so hard to watch him like this. 

He was born premature at 35 weeks, and I thought we had made it past the tough stuff. He breastfed for three months, then switched to formula, and I never imagined we’d face something like this now. He had a cleft lip repair earlier this year, which adds to my worries. I try to keep him safe, and we’ve even been attending parent-child swimming classes for the past two months to have some fun together. 

He’s in daycare with his siblings, and I just hope he’s not picking up something from there. I can’t help but think about his father smoking on the balcony; it worries me that it might affect our little one. 

The doctor said his temperature was 38.5°C, and they found that his left ear was red and bulging. It felt like a punch to the gut hearing that. I’m just anxious about what this all means and if he’ll be okay. I keep wondering if all these factors—his early birth, the cleft lip, or even the swimming classes—could have led to this. I just want him to feel better.
options: A. Premature birth B. Recent introduction of solid foods C. History of cleft lip repair D. Presence of older siblings E. Parental smoking on the balcony F. Incomplete cleft lip G. Tobacco exposure H. Attendance at swimming classes I. Formula feeding J. Frequent contact with water

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety after my visit to the doctor. For the past week, I’ve been dealing with this awful intermittent nausea and vomiting, and it’s really taking a toll on me. I’m a 46-year-old woman with well-controlled diabetes, managed with metformin, so I thought I was doing okay. But now, I’m feeling so weak, and my back and legs ache constantly. 

What worries me the most is that I recently traveled internationally and was given antibiotics for an infection that I can’t even remember. I haven’t been around anyone sick, so why am I feeling this way? During my appointment, the doctor checked my vitals, and I was relieved to see my temperature was normal, but my pulse felt strangely low at 62 beats per minute, and my breathing seemed a bit rapid. 

Then, they did an EKG, and I overheard something about T wave flattening, which just sounds alarming. After some more tests, the doctor prescribed a thiazide medication, but I can’t help but wonder what’s really going on with my health. It feels like I’m in the dark, and the thought of what could be causing all these symptoms is really worrying me.
options: A. Rheumatoid arthritis B. Sjogren syndrome C. Systemic lupus erythematosus D. Wilson disease E. Primary hyperaldosteronism F. Familial hypokalemic periodic paralysis G. Autosomal dominant hypocalcemia H. Pseudohypoaldosteronism type II I. Bartter syndrome J. Gitelman syndrome

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that’s been creeping in over the past few weeks. At 76 years old, I’ve been managing my COPD for a while, but lately, things have taken a turn. It started with a persistent cough that just won’t go away, and now I’m struggling to catch my breath even with the simplest tasks. I’ve lost about 20 pounds too, which has me really worried. 

I’ve smoked for so long—60 years, in fact—and I used to work as a shipbuilder, which I wonder if that’s caught up with me. Just a few weeks ago, I traveled to Ohio, and I can't help but think if that somehow triggered this. 

I went to see the doctor, and they did some chest imaging. The words they used, like “enhanced bronchovascular markings” and “pleural plaques,” sound alarming. They also mentioned something about mild anemia, but I’m trying not to panic. What could be happening to me? I keep wondering what they'll find on the CT scan. The uncertainty is almost unbearable. I just want to know what’s wrong, but the waiting is making me feel even more anxious.
options: A. Nodular mass spreading along pleural surfaces B. Lower lobe cavitary mass C. Tree-in-bud opacities in both lower lobes D. Diffuse centrilobular nodules E. Ground-glass opacities with peripheral distribution F. Mosaic attenuation pattern with air trapping G. Honeycombing H. Bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy I. Upper lobe bronchiectasis with mucoid impaction J. Calcified pleural plaques with subpleural fat

question:
I can hardly shake the worry that’s been creeping in over the past six months. It started with this frustrating difficulty in initiating urination, and honestly, the reduced force of my urinary stream has been incredibly concerning. I’ve found myself waking up multiple times at night just to relieve myself, and I can’t help but think about my father, who faced similar issues in his late sixties. 

My medical history isn’t too alarming; I’ve managed my hypertension and type 2 diabetes pretty well. But this urinary trouble is really weighing on me. I don’t have any burning sensations or blood in my urine, and I’ve never dealt with urinary tract infections, so that’s a small relief. 

When I went for a checkup, the doctor examined me. They said my heart rate was regular, my lungs sounded clear, and my abdomen felt soft without any pain. But then they mentioned my prostate was enlarged, smooth, and firm, which just added to my anxiety. 

I can’t shake the feeling that something is seriously wrong, and I keep worrying about what might come next. I just hope it’s nothing more than a simple issue, but the unknown is definitely making me uneasy. What if it’s something worse? I just want to get to the bottom of this.
options: A. T8-T10 neutral, sidebent left, rotated right B. T12 flexed, rotated right, sidebent right C. L5-S1 facet joint restriction D. Chapman point at the proximal inner thigh E. L2 flexed, rotated left, sidebent left F. S2-S4 somatic dysfunction G. T10-L2 paraspinal muscle hypertonicity H. Coccygeal tenderness and restricted mobility I. Pubic symphysis restriction J. Iliosacral joint dysfunction

question:
I took my 6-year-old daughter to urgent care yesterday, and I can’t shake this feeling of worry. She had developed a rash on her right arm over the past couple of days, and it really caught me off guard. She wasn’t running a fever or showing any other symptoms, but the rash looked concerning—there were these little vesicles on a red base that just didn’t look normal. 

I kept thinking about how she’s always been so healthy, with no daily medications and her vaccinations up to date. But then I remembered that I have lupus, and I couldn’t help but feel nervous about what might be going on with her. The doctors checked her vital signs, and everything seemed okay—her temperature was normal, and her heart and breathing rates were fine. They said she looked well overall, but still, I couldn’t shake this feeling of dread.

They did a physical exam and mentioned that the Nikolsky sign was negative, which I guess was a good sign, but I was still left wondering what this rash meant. They talked about different tests to confirm a diagnosis, but I just felt overwhelmed. I keep replaying the whole visit in my mind, worrying about what’s next and whether my little girl is going to be okay.
options: A. PCR testing of vesicular fluid B. KOH preparation C. Serum IgE levels D. Tzank smear E. Viral serology F. Skin lesion culture G. Direct immunofluorescence testing H. Anti-streptolysin O testing I. Anti-hemidesmosome antibody testing J. Skin biopsy

question:
I can’t shake this nagging worry I’ve had for the past few days. Three days ago, I played intramural soccer at college, and ever since, I’ve been dealing with this sharp pain in my lower back. It started suddenly, and I thought it would just go away, but it’s only gotten worse. I tried taking naproxen, hoping it would help, but it barely made a dent in the discomfort.

Feeling uneasy, I finally decided to visit my family physician. I was nervous during the appointment, especially when they checked my vital signs. They told me everything seemed normal, but I could see that I was still visibly uncomfortable. My legs felt strong, and my reflexes were normal, but I couldn’t shake the feeling that something was really off.

The doctor examined my back and found tenderness at the iliac crest, which made me worry even more. They mentioned that the asymmetry got worse when I extended my back. I couldn’t help but think: what if this is something serious? I just want to know what’s wrong and how to fix it. I hate feeling like this, and I’m desperate for answers.
options: A. L4 FSRRR B. L5 ESLRL C. L5 FSRRL D. L4 ESRRR E. L3 FSRRL F. L4 ESRRL G. L4 NSRRR H. L3 FSRRR I. L3 ESRRR J. L3 NSRRL

question:
I can’t shake this nagging worry that’s been creeping in over the past couple of months. It started with these intermittent abdominal pains, right above my belly button. They come and go throughout the day, lasting around 20 to 30 minutes each time, and they’re really uncomfortable. I haven't had any regurgitation or nighttime cough, but I’ve been feeling nauseous, which is unsettling. 

I've noticed that eating smaller meals helps ease the pain a bit, and ibuprofen taken with food seems to provide some relief too. But I’m anxious; I’ve even gained four pounds since my last doctor’s visit three months ago, and while I haven’t had any diarrhea or changes in my stool, that doesn't calm my nerves. 

I do enjoy a few beers on the weekends, and I’ve smoked for a while, which makes me wonder if that’s catching up with me. I’m still trying to convince myself that it’s nothing serious, but when my doctor examined me and found tenderness above my umbilicus, it sent my heart racing. They did a stool test, and now I'm just waiting for the endoscopy results. The thought of what they might find has me on edge. What if it’s something really bad? I can’t help but feel incredibly anxious about it all.
options: A. Signet ring cells in the gastric mucosa B. Hyperplastic polyps with elongated crypts C. Intestinal metaplasia with goblet cells D. Crypt abscesses in the large intestine E. Urease-producing organism in the small intestine F. Inflammatory infiltrates with eosinophils G. Atrophic gastritis with intestinal metaplasia H. Mucosal defect in the stomach I. Non-caseating granulomas J. Lymphocytic infiltration of the lamina propria

question:
I've been really worried lately. For the past four months, I've been struggling with sexual dysfunction, and it feels like everything just spiraled after we lost a family member. The stress from that has been overwhelming, and it seems to have taken a toll on my marriage too. I still have a normal libido and even manage to get morning erections, but when it comes to ejaculation, I just can't seem to achieve it, which is incredibly frustrating.

I try to keep active with my cycling, which I love, but I can't shake this feeling that something is off. My medical history isn’t the best either—I’ve been dealing with depression and diabetes for a while now, and I'm on citalopram and metformin, but nothing has changed with my meds recently. I thought maybe it was related to my diabetes, but I’m not sure. 

I went to the clinic hoping to get some answers, but they didn't find anything unusual during the physical exam. Now, I’m just left with this nagging worry. Is it psychological stress? Could it be something physical that I’m not aware of? I feel trapped in this cycle of concern, and I just want to figure out what's going on before it affects everything in my life.
options: A. Autonomic neuropathy due to diabetes B. Chronic pelvic floor dysfunction C. Peripheral arterial disease affecting genital blood flow D. Medication side effect E. Psychological stress F. Vascular insufficiency due to prolonged cycling G. Damage to the pudendal nerve H. Testosterone deficiency I. Overuse injury to the perineal region J. Spinal cord compression affecting sacral nerves

question:
I recently went to my gynecologist for a routine check-up, feeling pretty confident since I had no symptoms and a clean medical history. I’ve been using a copper IUD for contraception and there’s no cancer in my family, so I thought everything would be fine. But during the breast examination, my doctor found a 1-cm smooth, nontender mass in the upper outer quadrant of my left breast. I can’t help but feel a pit in my stomach thinking about it.

The skin and nipples looked normal, and there weren’t any swollen lymph nodes, which I hoped was a good sign. Still, the ultrasound showed this oval-shaped lesion with some internal echoes. I thought I could breathe easier when the mammogram came back unremarkable, but I’m still left with so many questions. What does this mean for me? Should I be worried? 

Now, I’m anxious about what comes next. My doctor mentioned some options for management, but I can’t shake the feeling that I need to take action. I just want to make sure it’s nothing serious, but the uncertainty is really weighing on me. What if it’s something more? I just hope I can get clarity soon before my mind runs away with all the “what-ifs.”
options: A. Observation with annual follow-up only B. Fine-needle aspiration with cytology C. Mammogram in six months D. Ultrasound-guided core needle biopsy E. Ultrasound-guided aspiration F. MRI of the breast G. Referral to a breast surgeon for evaluation H. Repeat mammogram and ultrasound in three months I. Excisional biopsy J. Clinical breast exam and breast ultrasound in six months

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping up on me lately. I’m 35, and until recently, my asthma was pretty manageable with my rescue inhaler. But now, I’m experiencing shortness of breath that just doesn’t seem to go away, and I’ve got this nagging lower back pain that started about a month ago. It’s unsettling because I didn’t injure myself—I just woke up one day and felt it, right around the same time my breathing issues got worse.

I went to the family clinic, hoping to get some answers. They took my vital signs, and while I was stable, the doctor noted moderate wheezing in my lungs, which made me feel even more anxious. They discovered a tender nodule below my second rib, and I couldn’t help but worry about what that could mean.

Now, I’m left with so many questions. Why is my asthma suddenly so unmanageable? What does this back pain signify? I keep thinking about what could be going on inside my body. I just want to feel normal again, but instead, I’m caught in this cycle of concern, wondering if something more serious is happening. I really hope I can get some clarity soon.
options: A. Posterior sacral rotation on the superior transverse axis B. Restricted costovertebral joint mobility C. Chapman's points tenderness in the upper thoracic region D. Left sacral rotation on the right oblique axis E. Restricted thoracic inlet mobility F. Anterior sacral rotation on the middle transverse axis G. Elevated first rib on the affected side H. Facilitated segments at T2-T4 I. Anterior rotation of the innominate bones J. Hypertonicity of the thoracolumbar paraspinal muscles

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread after the accident. I was just walking when a car hit me, and everything happened so fast. When the ambulance arrived, they checked me over, and thankfully, I seemed okay at first. My Glasgow Coma Scale was perfect—15, they said—but I could feel something was off. 

During the secondary exam, they discovered blood behind both of my eardrums and noted I was bleeding from my nose. I couldn't even look down with my right eye, which terrified me, even though they reassured me that my pupils were reacting normally. My vital signs were a bit elevated, but they didn’t seem overly concerned.

After they packed my nose to stop the bleeding, things took a strange turn. About three hours in, I noticed this weird salty taste in my throat, and that’s when the worry really set in. I couldn’t help but think about what that might mean. I started to panic, wondering if I could be facing something serious. Could it be a basilar skull fracture? Or maybe something else? The uncertainty is eating away at me, and I just want to know what’s happening to my body.
options: A. Orbital floor fracture B. Hemotympanum C. Ageusia D. Periorbital ecchymosis E. Traumatic optic neuropathy F. Anosmia G. Epistaxis recurrence H. Cerebrospinal fluid rhinorrhea I. Mastoid ecchymosis J. Basilar skull fracture

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been creeping over me since all of this began. Just a few days ago, I started noticing something strange happening. I kept talking about “bunnies, tigers, and emus” appearing in my living room. It felt so real at the time, but now I can’t help but wonder if something is seriously wrong with my mind.

My wife became worried and insisted on bringing me to see my neurologist. I was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis a while back, and just two weeks ago, I went in complaining about weakness in my left arm. I thought I was managing things okay, but now, these bizarre thoughts are consuming me.

During the appointment, I remember trying to focus, but every few moments, I felt compelled to mention those animals again. I could see my neurologist's concern, and it made me feel even worse.
