I wanted to scream, “I’m not crazy! This is really happening!” My vital signs seemed fine, but I couldn’t shake this anxiety about what was going on in my head.

I’m scared that this could be something serious, like a progression of my illness or maybe something even worse. I just want to understand why this is happening and if I’ll ever feel normal again. It’s terrifying to think that my mind might be slipping away from me.
options: A. Delirium due to metabolic derangement B. Infectious encephalitis C. Metabolic abnormality D. Acute psychotic episode E. Paraneoplastic syndrome F. Post-ictal state G. Substance abuse H. Progression of neurologic disease I. Medication side effect J. Autoimmune encephalitis

question:
I can’t shake the worry from my mind as I think back to that day at the mall. It all happened so fast. One moment I was shopping, and the next, I was on the floor, completely out of it. I remember feeling sweaty and shaky, and then confusion washed over me before everything went black. My husband said I was unconscious for about five minutes before the paramedics arrived.

When I came to, I was in the ambulance, feeling drowsy and disoriented. They told me my blood sugar was dangerously low. I hadn’t eaten in five hours, but I had been feeling odd for a while—headaches, a weird milky discharge, and nausea whenever I skipped meals. It’s terrifying to think that something could be seriously wrong, especially since I’ve been a nurse for years and never faced anything like this.

I can’t help but think about my past, too. I was treated for tuberculosis a decade ago, and now I’m facing this frightening situation. My family history is a mystery due to my adoption, which adds to my anxiety. I just want to understand why this happened and what it means for my health moving forward. I feel so lost and worried about what might come next.
options: A. Factitious hypoglycemia due to sulfonylurea use B. Alcohol-induced hypoglycemia C. Reactive hypoglycemia D. Glucagonoma E. Exogenous insulin use F. Non-insulinoma pancreatogenous hypoglycemia syndrome (NIPHS) G. Hypopituitarism H. Noninsulinoma pancreatogenous hypoglycemia syndrome (NIPHS) I. Autoimmune hypoglycemia due to insulin antibodies J. Insulinoma

question:
I can't believe what just happened. I’m 15 years old, and I found myself in the emergency department with this sudden, intense abdominal pain. It started around my belly button and then just shifted to my right side, and I felt so nauseous. I couldn’t stop vomiting, and I had a fever for the last four hours—it was terrifying. My dad was right there with me, and we both agreed to take part in this study for a new diagnostic test that measures something called "serum protein Y" for appendicitis. I know it won’t help me directly, but I thought maybe it could help others in the future.

After some tests, they did a CT scan, and I heard the doctors mention some thickening of my appendix and inflammation. That’s when they decided I needed urgent surgery. I was so scared. A research assistant came in to take a little blood from my finger for that "serum protein Y" test, and I overheard that the result came back really low, suggesting I might not have appendicitis. 

I just wish I could be sure everything would be okay. Who should that research assistant tell about my test result? I mean, what if it changes something important? This whole situation has left me feeling so anxious…
options: A. The emergency department physician and the surgeon B. The surgeon performing the appendectomy C. The patient’s insurance provider D. The research assistant’s supervisor E. The principal investigator of the study, the surgeon, and the patient F. The Institutional Review Board (IRB) overseeing the study G. The patient and his father H. No one else I. The patient’s primary care physician J. The principal investigator of the study

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry ever since I went to the clinic. I’m 25, and for years now, I’ve been dealing with heavy menstrual bleeding and this awful lower abdominal pain that just won’t go away. It usually kicks in about a week before my period, and it’s been so hard to manage. My mother had similar issues at my age, which makes me even more anxious about what could be going on.

During my visit, the doctor examined me and said I seemed stable, but I could tell they noticed my pallor. They pressed on my lower abdomen, and it was tender, but thankfully, there were no masses or anything alarming. I was relieved when the lab tests came back normal, but then they did a transvaginal ultrasound, and that’s when things got a bit unsettling. They found this cystic ovarian lesion with some unusual echoes, and I couldn’t help but feel a wave of fear wash over me. 

Now I’m left wondering what all of this means. I’ve read about possible treatments, but the uncertainty is weighing heavily on my mind. I just want to know what’s happening and how it will affect my life moving forward. What if it’s serious? I can’t help but worry about the possibilities.
options: A. Conservative management is preferred in most cases B. Laparoscopy is the not the definitive method of diagnosis C. Imaging findings alone are sufficient for diagnosis D. The lesions usually appear innocuous E. A chocolate cyst is unlikely in this case F. Surgical management is the mainstay of treatment G. The cystic lesion is most likely malignant H. The condition is unlikely to recur after treatment I. Hormonal therapy is the first-line treatment for all patients J. Pain is unrelated to the menstrual cycle in this condition

question:
I can hardly believe what’s been happening to me lately. I’m 47, and for years I’ve dealt with migraines and that awful chronic pelvic pain, but recently it’s gotten much worse. I found myself in the emergency room again, terrified that I was having a heart attack. I suddenly felt this sharp, nonradiating pain on the right side of my chest, and I just couldn’t shake the fear. 

After countless tests—ECGs and all sorts of blood work—they told me everything looked normal. But this was my fifth visit to the ED in just a month! Each time, I was there for different problems: abdominal pain, joint pain, nausea, diarrhea, back pain... and yet, nothing definitive ever came up. It’s exhausting and so frustrating. 

Now, sitting in front of a new doctor, I voiced my concerns and asked for a referral to a cardiologist. But the doctor suggested we explore other options first, which made me feel anxious all over again. I just want someone to take me seriously. I can’t help but wonder if all these symptoms are connected somehow, or if it’s just me being overly anxious. It’s hard to think straight when you feel so unwell, and I’m left wondering what’s really going on with my body.
options: A. Would you be open to discussing alternative treatment approaches? B. Do you feel your symptoms are being taken seriously? C. Have you considered that your symptoms might be related to anxiety? D. Would you be willing to make regularly scheduled clinic appointments with me? E. What do you think is causing all of these different symptoms? F. I see that you have been to the emergency department five times recently. Does this seem like a lot to you? G. Would you be interested in learning some relaxation techniques? H. Have you had any significant life changes or traumatic experiences recently? I. What are your thoughts about seeing a mental health professional? J. Can I review your test results with you so you can see how well your heart is functioning?

question:
I've been feeling increasingly worried over the past five months as I've noticed a troubling decline in my muscle strength. It started with my shoulders and hips; simple tasks like rising from a chair, climbing stairs, or even combing my hair have become real struggles. The most alarming part is the difficulty I'm having swallowing solid foods—thankfully, liquids are still okay, but it’s terrifying to think about it getting worse.

My medical history isn’t overly complicated; I've been managing hyperlipidemia with fluvastatin for the last five years. But then there's my family history that weighs heavily on my mind. My mother had Hashimoto thyroiditis, and my uncle tragically passed away at just 26 due to Duchenne muscular dystrophy. I can’t help but feel anxious about what’s happening to me.

During my recent visit to the doctor, my vital signs seemed normal, but they noted moderate weakness in my arms and hips. I was hoping for some answers, but all I got were more questions. They mentioned a list of possible diagnostic tests, but I can't shake this feeling of dread. What if it’s something serious? I just want to understand what’s happening to my body before it gets worse.
options: A. Central nuclei with fiber size variation B. Subsarcolemmal accumulations with COX-negative fibers C. Endomysial fibrosis with fatty replacement D. Resolution of symptoms with statin cessation E. Rimmed vacuoles with inclusion bodies F. Intrafascicular infiltration on muscle biopsy G. Necrotic fibers with macrophage infiltration H. Type II fiber atrophy with angulated fibers I. Ring fibers with sarcoplasmic masses J. Perifascicular and perivascular infiltration on muscle biopsy

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping in over the last week. It all started with this awful tightness in my neck. At first, I thought it was just a minor annoyance, but as the days went by, it got worse—much worse. I can’t pinpoint a specific injury, but I’ve been wondering if maybe I need a new pillow. 

When I went to the clinic, I was hoping for some answers. The doctor examined my neck, and it was a bit of a shock to hear that my range of motion is limited in every direction. The worst part was when the doctor pressed on the back of my head; that spot was incredibly tender. I could feel my heart racing as they talked about the findings. They mentioned something about a shallow occipital sulcus on my left side that gets deeper when I flex my neck. 

I can't help but feel anxious about what this all means. What if it’s something serious? I’ve been trying to stay calm, but the thought of being restricted in my movements is really weighing on me. It’s hard not to think about all the things I won’t be able to do if this continues. I just want to feel normal again.
options: A. Extension B. Contralateral rotation with sidebending C. Retraction D. Combined flexion-rotation E. Ipsilateral rotation with sidebending F. Flexion G. Combined extension-rotation H. Rotation I. Sidebending J. Protraction

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of dread that’s settled over me. It all started two weeks ago when I began to feel unwell—fever, chills, and these awful night sweats that soaked my sheets. I just felt so drained, like I couldn't muster the energy for anything. My wife, noticing how bad I looked, insisted on taking me to the emergency room, and I was too exhausted to argue.

When we got there, I was shocked by how unwell they said I appeared. The doctors told me my temperature was over 102 degrees, and after examining me, they found a heart murmur and something concerning in my lungs. I felt a knot tightening in my stomach when they mentioned a vegetation on my aortic valve. They took blood cultures, and I could see the worry in the doctors' faces as they discussed what it might mean.

Now, I’m stuck here, waiting for answers and wondering what could have caused this. I can't help but think about all the things I've done in the past—was it the dental work I had a while back, or perhaps something related to my heart? The uncertainty is terrifying. I just want to know what’s happening to me, and if I’m going to be okay.
options: A. Gastrointestinal instrumentation B. Recent urinary catheterization C. Recent dental procedure D. Colon cancer E. Rheumatic heart disease F. Bicuspid aortic valve G. Chronic kidney disease H. Intravenous drug use I. Periodontal disease J. Valve replacement

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that started when I began experiencing some troubling symptoms. It’s been two weeks now, and I’ve been dealing with constipation, abdominal pain, and this uncomfortable bloating that just won’t go away. I used to have soft bowel movements every other day, but now it’s a struggle to go every three to four days, and when I do, it’s painful, with hard stools that I have to strain to pass. Thankfully, there hasn’t been any blood, but that doesn’t ease my mind.

I take a few medications daily—docusate to help with the constipation, prune juice as needed, a low dose of aspirin, and amitriptyline for my depression, which I just started a month ago. I went to see the doctor, and while my vital signs were okay, the examination revealed some tenderness in my abdomen and a small anal fissure. 

I can’t help but feel anxious about what might be causing all of this. I know I need to manage it, but what’s the best next step? I’m terrified that this could lead to something more serious. I just want to feel normal again and be able to go to the bathroom without all this pain and worry.
options: A. Increase dietary fiber intake, and add polyethylene glycol daily B. Add a stimulant laxative and continue docusate daily C. Stop amitriptyline, and monitor the patient’s depressive symptoms D. Initiate bisacodyl suppositories and increase fluid intake E. Refer for surgical evaluation of chronic constipation F. Perform a colonoscopy to rule out malignancy G. Order CT of the abdomen and pelvis with intravenous and oral contrast H. Switch amitriptyline to a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI) I. Start methylnaltrexone for opioid-induced constipation J. Start lubiprostone, and consider senna if no bowel movement in one week

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping in over the past five days. It all started when I began my new job, which has me walking several miles each day throughout this huge facility. At first, I thought it was just fatigue, but then the low back pain kicked in, and it’s been relentless. The pain is localized to my back, and thankfully, it hasn’t shot down into my legs or anything—still, I can’t help but feel anxious.

I haven't had any falls or injuries that I can think of, which makes this even more puzzling. I’ve only been on oral contraceptives for birth control, so I’m not sure what else could be going on. I decided to get it checked out, and during the examination, the doctor noted that my muscle strength, tone, and reflexes seemed normal, which at least offered a bit of relief. However, they mentioned that my left sacral sulcus is deeper than the right and that there were some other concerning findings.

I can’t help but think about what it could be—there are so many possibilities. I just really hope it’s nothing serious. The pain is affecting my ability to focus on my new job, and I’m genuinely worried about what this means for my health moving forward.
options: A. bilateral sacral extension B. bilateral sacral flexion C. sacral base posterior D. right-on-right sacral torsion E. sacral base anterior F. right-on-left sacral torsion G. unilateral sacral flexion on the right H. left-on-left sacral torsion I. left-on-right sacral torsion J. unilateral sacral extension on the left

question:
I can't shake this feeling of worry as I sit in the doctor's office for my routine prenatal visit. I'm 29 years old and pregnant for the first time, now 33 weeks along. I’ve been managing my systemic lupus erythematosus well, thankfully without any flares during this pregnancy. I take my medications—iron, vitamins, and hydroxychloroquine—very seriously, and I don’t use any substances.

My vital signs were stable, but I felt a knot in my stomach the entire time. The physical exam felt normal, but the ultrasound results left me feeling uneasy. They found only one rhythmic breathing episode that lasted over 30 seconds in a whole hour. There was a little movement, but I can’t help but wonder if it’s enough. The deepest pocket of amniotic fluid measured just 2.5 cm, and while there was one heart rate acceleration, it’s hard not to feel anxious about what it all means. 

What’s the next step? My mind races through the options, each one more daunting than the last. Should I be worried enough to consider inducing labor or something more drastic? I just want to make sure my baby is safe, and the uncertainty is overwhelming. I hope they can reassure me soon and guide me in the right direction.
options: A. Administer corticosteroids and continue close monitoring B. Reassurance with expectant management C. Perform contraction stress test D. Schedule delivery at 37 weeks gestation E. Administer corticosteroids and induce labor F. Schedule cesarean delivery within 24 hours G. Begin twice-weekly umbilical artery Doppler studies H. Start magnesium sulfate for neuroprotection I. Perform amniocentesis for fetal lung maturity J. Initiate daily biophysical profile monitoring

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread that’s been creeping over me. Just a few months ago, I started losing weight without even trying—over 18 pounds in two months! It's terrifying. I’ve been dealing with liver cirrhosis for years, but lately, the pain in my right upper abdomen has gotten worse, and my appetite has dwindled even further. I’ve noticed I’m sometimes short of breath, which is really alarming.

I went to see my doctor, hoping for some answers. They took my vital signs, and everything seemed okay, but then I noticed the worried look on their face during the examination. They mentioned something about scleral icterus and a tender liver, which only made my anxiety spike. 

I’ve had a complicated medical history, including hepatitis E during my first pregnancy and a blood transfusion after a car accident years ago. I drink a couple of pints of beer a week, but I never thought it would lead to something more serious. When they mentioned that an ultrasound showed a liver mass, my heart sank. The biopsy confirmed it was hepatocellular carcinoma.

Now, as I sit here, I can’t help but wonder what led to this. Was it the transfusion? The hepatitis? Or my alcohol consumption? The uncertainty is overwhelming, and I just want to understand what’s happening to me.
options: A. History of blood transfusion B. Genetic predisposition to liver cancer C. History of intermittent right upper quadrant pain D. History of hepatitis E E. Chronic hepatitis B or C infection from transfusion F. Autoimmune hepatitis G. Chronic iron deficiency anemia H. History of mild alcohol consumption I. Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease J. History of alcohol use

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been building over the past few months. It all started about three months ago when I noticed I was more fatigued than usual. At first, I brushed it off, but as time went on, my legs felt heavier and walking became a struggle. I work at a health food store and follow a strict vegan diet, which I thought was healthy. I take various supplements, but nothing seems to help.

Over the past year, my strength has declined significantly. I can hardly walk without feeling weak and unsteady, and now I'm experiencing daily bouts of weakness and even non-bloody diarrhea. I’ve had a history of Crohn's disease since my twenties, along with celiac disease, but it’s been manageable—until now. 

When I visited my doctor, I was shocked by how weak I felt during the examination. My strength was rated only 3 out of 5, and my reflexes were absent. I couldn't believe it when the doctor mentioned the possibility of a deficiency. I never thought I would end up feeling like this—what if it’s something serious? 

It’s all so overwhelming, and I can’t help but worry about what this means for my health. I just want to feel like myself again, but the uncertainty is haunting me.
options: A. Vitamin A B. Copper C. Vitamin B12 D. Vitamin B1 E. Vitamin B6 F. Zinc G. Vitamin D H. Vitamin K I. Vitamin E J. Vitamin B9

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming feeling of worry after the accident. I was driving, completely unrestrained, when everything went wrong. My left arm was hanging out the window, and in an instant, I felt a jolt that I can’t quite describe. The pain shot through my elbow and arm, and I knew something was seriously wrong. 

When I got to the emergency department, I was scared. They examined me and found tenderness in my humerus and elbow. I couldn’t even extend my wrist properly, but thankfully, I could still move my arm without pain. They told me I had a mid-shaft humeral fracture and a small olecranon fracture, but I just wanted to know what this all meant for me. 

Now, two weeks later, I’m feeling even more anxious. I can’t shake this "pins and needles" sensation in my left hand, and my ring and little fingers are numb. It’s terrifying to see my hand starting to atrophy. I keep wondering what could be causing this—could it be something serious like nerve compression or something else? It’s hard to stay calm when I feel like my body is betraying me. I just need answers, but I can’t help but feel like something is really wrong.
options: A. Delayed-onset compartment syndrome B. Cubital tunnel compression from post-traumatic edema C. Compression at Guyon canal D. Nerve root compression E. Post-traumatic neuroma formation F. Compression at the carpal tunnel G. Traumatic humerus injury H. Thoracic outlet syndrome from trauma I. Traumatic elbow injury J. Delayed ulnar nerve subluxation

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry after my recent visit to the clinic. I’m 24, and I went in for what I thought was just a routine Pap smear, since my last one at 21 was completely normal. I’ve had seven partners in my life, and for the past six months, I've been in a committed relationship with one person. I’ve always been careful, using oral contraceptive pills, and I didn’t even think I should be concerned about anything.

So, when the results came back, I was blindsided. They found atypical squamous cells of undetermined significance, and to make matters worse, the HPV test came back positive. I can’t explain how anxious I felt. I mean, what does this mean for my health? Am I at risk for something serious? I don’t have any symptoms like irregular bleeding, but the uncertainty is just overwhelming.

Now, I’m left wondering what the next steps should be. I’ve read about all these options, from getting a biopsy to waiting and seeing, and I’m just so scared. I feel like I’m in a fog, and I don’t know what to do next. Should I just wait and see, or do I need to take immediate action? This is all so unsettling, and I’m just hoping for some clarity soon.
options: A. Perform cervical biopsy immediately B. Repeat cervical cytology alone in 12 months C. Recommend HPV vaccination and repeat cytology in 3 months D. Recommend abstinence and repeat testing in 6 months E. Refer for colposcopy F. Repeat cervical cytology and human papillomavirus testing in 12 months G. Schedule follow-up in 6 months with repeat HPV testing H. Perform endocervical curettage I. Schedule immediate LEEP procedure J. Start antiviral therapy and repeat cytology in 3 months

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of worry that’s been creeping in. Just yesterday, I found myself feeling incredibly fatigued and weak, like I had no energy left in my body. It all started about 24 hours ago, and I couldn't understand why. I recalled a troubling episode from last week—just one instance of blood-tinged diarrhea that seemed to resolve on its own, but now I can’t help but wonder if it's connected.

When I finally went to the emergency department, I was anxious about what they might find. My temperature was slightly elevated, and even though my blood pressure seemed okay, my pulse felt fast. I was struggling to breathe normally, with my respirations at 29 per minute. And then, the examination revealed that I could barely move my legs—my strength was down to 2 out of 5. I felt a chilling fear when they mentioned reduced sensation in my lower extremities and fingertips. 

What could be happening to me? The doctors were discussing the next steps, but I felt completely lost. I just wanted answers and reassurance. I can’t help but feel that something serious might be going on, and the uncertainty is eating away at me.
options: A. Lumbar puncture B. Spirometry C. CT head without contrast D. MRI of the spine E. Serum anti-ganglioside antibodies F. Plasma exchange G. Dexamethasone H. High-dose corticosteroids I. IV immunoglobulin J. EMG/NCV studies

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of anxiety as I recount what’s been happening to me over the past couple of months. I’m 59, and while I’ve been managing my hypertension and high cholesterol with medications like lisinopril and atorvastatin, something feels really off lately. For the last two months, I’ve been dealing with this persistent lower back pain that just won’t go away. 

When I went to the doctor, my blood pressure was okay, but I felt so uncomfortable during the examination. My heart was racing a bit, and I was just trying to stay calm, but the pain was overwhelming. The osteopathic examination revealed something concerning; they found a specific area in my lower back that wasn’t moving right at the aortic bifurcation. It’s troubling to think that something is out of place there. 

I felt a glimmer of hope when they mentioned that the restriction could be resolved with certain movements, but I can’t help but worry about what this means for me moving forward. What if this pain doesn’t go away? Or what if it’s something worse? I just want to feel normal again, but now I’m left wondering about the diagnosis and what’s next.
options: A. L4 FSLLR B. L2 FSRRL C. L2 ESLRL D. L4 ESLRL E. L5 ESLRL F. L4 NSLRR G. L3 ESLRL H. L4 FSRRL I. L2 FSLRL J. L4 ESRRR

question:
I can't shake the worry that's been building over the past few weeks. It all started when I felt this dull, constant pain in my left lower back. At first, I thought it was just a tweak from lifting something too heavy, but then I noticed something troubling: blood in my urine. That was new and incredibly alarming.

Over the last two weeks, I’ve even gained about 3 kilograms, and my shoes are fitting tighter than usual. Nothing like this has ever happened to me before, and I don’t have any chronic medical issues. I haven’t experienced any trauma or illness that I can recall, but now I'm really anxious about what could be going on.

When I went to the emergency department, I felt completely distressed. They checked my vital signs, and I learned my blood pressure was up compared to six months ago. I also noticed swelling in my legs and hands—definitely not normal for me. They found a significant amount of blood and protein in my urine, which makes me worry even more about what's happening inside my body.

I just wish I could understand what’s going on. I need to know what tests they’re going to run to figure this out. The uncertainty is weighing heavily on me, and I can’t help but feel that something is seriously wrong.
options: A. CT with contrast B. Complete blood count (CBC) with peripheral smear C. Renal biopsy D. Positron emission tomography (PET) scan E. 24-hour urine protein collection F. Abdominal ultrasound G. Non-contrast CT H. Doppler ultrasonography of the renal vessels I. Magnetic resonance angiography (MRA) J. Intravenous pyelogram (IVP)

question:
I can’t shake the worry that’s been building inside me since that day in the emergency department. It was terrifying. I’m 66, and I’ve been managing my bipolar disorder with lithium for 15 years, along with my hypertension and asthma. But then, out of nowhere, I experienced this strange episode that lasted about three minutes. My body started jerking uncontrollably, and I lost control of my bladder. I felt completely out of it afterward, confused and unable to remember what had just happened.

It was only ten days after starting a new medication, and I can’t help but wonder if that’s what caused it. When I got to the hospital, my pulse was at 92, and my blood pressure was 135 over 87. They noted my dry mouth and some muscle twitching, along with this awful tremor in my hands. I could barely speak; it felt like my words were trapped inside me. I was disoriented, and the whole experience left me shaken. 

I’ve been trying to piece it all together, worrying about what this might mean for my health. What if this new medication is causing all these problems? I just want to feel like myself again, without these frightening episodes.
options: A. Valproic acid B. Prednisone C. Amlodipine D. Enalapril E. Theophylline F. Sertraline G. Fluoxetine H. Ibuprofen I. Hydrochlorothiazide J. Carbamazepine

question:
I can’t shake off this nagging worry that something might be seriously wrong with me. It all started about six months ago when I began experiencing this intense pelvic pain during intercourse and even while using the bathroom. The pain has only gotten worse, especially during my menstrual periods, and now it’s a daily struggle. I’ve been trying to stay positive, but it’s hard when I’ve been sexually active with my partner for over a year and we haven’t been able to conceive. 

Just three weeks ago, I had my last period, but the pain doesn’t seem to let up. I went to the primary care clinic, hoping for some answers. During the examination, I could feel the tension in the room when they mentioned cervical immobility and tenderness. My heart sank. I kept thinking about what that could mean. 

The doctor told me my hCG test was negative, which was a relief in some ways, but I still feel anxious about what’s next. I can’t help but worry about the possibility of something more serious. I just want to know why I’m in this constant state of discomfort and if I’ll ever get the chance to start a family. What’s the best next step for me? I feel like I’m in a fog and need clarity.
options: A. Serum CA 125 level B. Pelvic ultrasound C. Referral to infertility specialist D. Initiate letrozole E. Exploratory laparoscopy F. Transvaginal ultrasound-guided biopsy G. Endometrial sampling H. Empiric treatment with oral contraceptives I. Diagnostic hysteroscopy J. Pelvic magnetic resonance imaging (MRI)

question:
I can't shake off this gnawing worry that started during my annual evaluation. At 45, I thought I was doing everything right, but when my doctor calculated my 10-year risk of atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease at 15%, it hit me hard. She suggested starting rosuvastatin and low-dose aspirin, and honestly, I felt a wave of anxiety wash over me. 

Then, there’s my husband. He was recently diagnosed with a *Helicobacter pylori* infection, and that really set off alarm bells in my mind. I’ve read about the links between *H. pylori* and gastric ulcers, even cancer, and the thought of that looming over us is terrifying. I couldn’t just sit back and do nothing; I asked my doctor if I should get tested for *H. pylori* too.

I’m just so worried. What if I have it too? What if it’s already causing damage? I thought it was best to be proactive, but I felt so unsure about what the right next steps should be. I keep wondering if I should have pushed harder for testing or if it was wise to just wait and see. The fear of the unknown is weighing heavily on me, and I just want to make sure I’m taking care of myself, especially with everything going on with my husband.
options: A. Order serologic testing for H. pylori antibodies B. Order a stool culture for H. pylori C. Recommend Helicobacter pylori antibody serology testing D. Recommend testing only if gastrointestinal symptoms develop E. Recommend empiric triple therapy without testing F. Defer testing until after initiating aspirin therapy G. Perform a rapid urease test H. Recommend a fecal antigen test for Helicobacter pylori infection I. Schedule a urea breath test in 4 weeks J. Reassure the patient that Helicobacter pylori testing is unnecessary at this time

question:
It all happened so suddenly. I’m 73, and I’ve been managing diabetes and hypertension for years, but lately, I’ve been struggling to keep up with my medications. I thought I was just tired, but then I started feeling really lethargic and confused. I didn’t even know what was happening to me when the ambulance arrived. 

The paramedics were so quick, but I could tell something was seriously wrong. I overheard them talking about my blood pressure; it was higher than usual, and my heart was beating oddly. I remember feeling scared and helpless as they took my vital signs. They told me my temperature was slightly elevated and that my glucose levels were way off. 

I can’t believe I let my diabetes get so out of control. I just didn’t think it was this serious. The confusion was overwhelming, and I felt like I was losing touch with reality. I was worried about what this meant for my health. 

Now, I’m lying here, waiting for answers, feeling the weight of neglecting my health. What if it’s too late? I keep wondering how I can turn this around and if I’ll ever feel like myself again. My mind races with questions about what’s next and how I’m going to manage this moving forward.
options: A. Decreased afferent arteriolar resistance B. Decreased glomerular capillary hydrostatic pressure C. Increased renal plasma flow D. Increased glomerular capillary oncotic pressure E. Decreased mesangial cell contractility F. Increased efferent arteriolar resistance G. Increased Bowman's space oncotic pressure H. Increased Bowman's space hydrostatic pressure I. Decreased filtration fraction J. Enhanced tubuloglomerular feedback

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry since last week when my right foot suddenly started hurting. I’m 28 and have been running for years, but I’ve had some issues with plantar fasciitis in the past. It all began when I started my marathon training. I remember it so clearly—I misstepped during a stride, and that’s when the pain kicked in. 

It’s an achy sensation that I’d rate as a 7 out of 10, and it only seems to get worse when I move my foot. I’ve noticed some swelling around my right ankle, which is alarming. I can’t help but think about what’s happening. Even the slightest movement, like trying to point my toes or move my foot outward, sends sharp pain shooting through me. 

I’m trying to stay calm, but I can’t help but worry about what this could mean for my training and even my running in general. I just want to know what’s going on and how I can fix it. I have to see a doctor soon, but the uncertainty is really weighing on me. What if it’s something serious? I just hope I can get back to running without this pain.
options: A. Pronation ankle sprain B. Posterior fibular head somatic dysfunction C. Anterior talofibular ligament tear D. Syndesmotic ankle sprain E. Anterior fibular head somatic dysfunction F. Tibialis posterior tendinopathy G. Deltoid ligament strain H. Supination ankle sprain I. Peroneal tendon subluxation J. Calcaneal stress fracture

question:
I still can’t shake the memory of that day. I was driving, feeling perfectly fine, when suddenly I was rear-ended by a drunk driver. I remember the impact—it was terrifying. I wasn’t wearing a seatbelt, and the jolt sent my body forward. When the paramedics arrived, I was alert but overwhelmed by this sharp pain in my abdomen. 

They rushed me to the emergency department, and I could sense something was really wrong. My heart was racing, and I felt weak. The doctors were asking me questions, and I tried to answer, but I could feel myself getting more and more tired. As they examined me, I noticed the worry in their eyes. They found bruising on my left side, and I could barely keep my eyes open as they checked my blood pressure—it was really low. 

I remember hearing them say something about multiple rib fractures and the urgency to start IV fluids. The whole situation felt surreal; I was scared. I kept thinking about what was happening inside my body and if I was going to be okay. I felt so vulnerable, and I couldn’t help but worry about my future. Would I recover from this? What would it mean for my life?
options: A. Increased pulmonary capillary wedge pressure B. Increased stroke volume C. Increased cardiac output D. Increased systemic vascular resistance E. Increased oxygen extraction ratio F. Decreased cardiac index G. Decreased pulmonary capillary wedge pressure H. Decreased systemic vascular resistance I. Increased right atrial pressure J. Decreased mixed venous oxygen saturation

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread since that night at the concert. Everything started so innocently, but then I felt this strange numbness around my mouth, and it just wouldn’t go away. I tried to brush it off, thinking maybe it was just the excitement of the crowd, but then I noticed my mouth twitching involuntarily. It was so embarrassing and frightening—I felt like I was losing control.

When I finally got to the emergency department, I was shaken. They took my temperature, which was normal, but my heart was racing, and I felt like I was struggling to breathe properly. It was terrifying to hear that I had a positive Trousseau sign when they inflated the blood pressure cuff. I didn’t understand what was happening to me. 

The doctors were talking about my blood gases, mentioning numbers like pH 7.53 and pCO2 29 mm Hg, but it all went over my head. I just kept thinking, “What’s wrong with me?” I felt so anxious, and I couldn't help but worry that something serious was going on. I just wanted to feel normal again and to understand why my body was acting this way. I hope they can figure it out soon because this feeling is unbearable.
options: A. Decreased serum bicarbonate concentration B. Increased cerebrospinal fluid pH C. Decreased total serum calcium concentration D. Increased renal bicarbonate excretion E. Increased intracellular hydrogen ion concentration F. Decreased cerebral blood flow G. Hyperkalemia H. Increased respiratory drive I. Increased ionized calcium concentration J. Increased neuromuscular excitability

question:
I can't shake the feeling of worry since I went to the clinic a few days ago. I’m 19, and for the past three months, I’ve been dealing with this persistent muscle cramping and an overwhelming sense of weakness. It all started after my last physical examination. I’ve tried to pinpoint what might be making it worse, but nothing seems to help. 

I don’t have any medical history to speak of, and I’ve been lifting weights intensely for about a year now. When I walked into the clinic, I tried to stay calm, but I couldn’t help feeling a little irritable, too. The doctor seemed concerned as well. I mean, I looked fine—my vital signs were normal. But they examined my muscles and noted increased tone and vascularity in my arms since my last visit.

Now, I’m left with this nagging anxiety. What if it’s something serious? They mentioned my magnesium and phosphorus levels were off, but I don’t fully understand what that means for me. I’m just anxious about what comes next. The doctor talked about different options for treatment, and I can't help but feel uneasy about what the right step is. I just want to feel like myself again and not be burdened by this constant worry.
options: A. Intravenous magnesium sulfate administration B. Oral multivitamin prescription C. Serum creatine kinase level D. Reassurance E. Vitamin B12 level F. Thyroid function tests G. Serum calcium level H. Referral to a neurologist for electromyography I. Total testosterone and free testosterone levels J. 12-Lead electrocardiogram (ECG)

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been growing over the past two weeks. It started with this awful shortness of breath that just won’t go away. I’ve noticed my face is swollen, and every morning I wake up with this strange fullness in my head that leaves me feeling disoriented. I’m 67 years old, and I was diagnosed with stage IV non-Hodgkin lymphoma eight months ago, but I didn’t think it would come to this.

When I finally went to the emergency department, I was in such distress. I could barely catch my breath, and my heart was racing. They took my vital signs, and I could see the worry in the nurses’ eyes as they noticed my swelling and the distended veins in my neck. I felt so vulnerable. They listened to my lungs and said they were clear, but I could tell something was seriously wrong. 

Now, I’m left wondering what’s next. They mentioned something about my lymph nodes being enlarged, and I can’t help but feel a knot in my stomach. I wish I could understand what’s happening to me and what they’re planning to do. The uncertainty is weighing heavily on my mind, and I just want to feel better.
options: A. Central line placement and immediate chemotherapy administration B. Immediate thoracentesis to relieve pressure on the lungs C. Emergent tracheostomy and mechanical ventilation D. Anticoagulation therapy for suspected superior vena cava thrombosis E. Bronchoscopy with biopsy to confirm the diagnosis F. Broad-spectrum antibiotics and fluid resuscitation G. IV placement and high-dose glucocorticoid therapy H. Supplemental oxygen and elevation of the head of the bed I. Urethral catheter placement and diuretic therapy J. Endotracheal intubation and initiation of positive pressure ventilation

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. Just the other day, I was in the hospital for pain management after dealing with those awful kidney stones. Everything seemed fine, but then, the day after I got home, I noticed this painful rash on my right forearm. It’s right where the IV line was, and it’s really worrying me. 

The rash is red and warm to the touch, and it hurts—like a constant reminder that something isn’t right. I’ve been feeling feverish too, my temperature hit 100.4°F. My heart feels like it's racing, and even though I’m trying to stay calm, my pulse was at 110 beats per minute when I checked. 

I’m otherwise healthy and don’t take any daily medications, but this rash has me on edge. I can’t help but think about what could be causing it. Is it an infection? What if it’s something serious? I really wish I knew what was going on. The uncertainty is eating at me. I just want to understand why this is happening, especially after everything I’ve been through with the kidney stones. I feel like I need answers, and I hope the doctors can help me figure this out soon.
options: A. *Clostridium perfringens* B. *Group A streptococcus* C. *Streptococcus pneumoniae* D. *Bacillus anthracis* E. *Staphylococcus aureus* F. *Pasteurella multocida* G. *Escherichia coli* H. *Candida albicans* I. *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* J. *Trichophyton rubrum*

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. Just yesterday, I woke up with this awful pain in my joints—my wrists, elbows, and shoulders felt like they were on fire. At first, I thought maybe it was just a bad day, but things got worse quickly. The pain is now symmetrical, and I can barely move without wincing. I also started feeling really tired and even felt like I had a mild fever, with my temperature creeping up to 100°F. 

I’m a schoolteacher, and I usually feel healthy, so this sudden change is really unsettling. I’ve been sexually active with two partners, and while I use condoms sometimes, I can’t help but worry if something is wrong. I went to the emergency department, terrified that it might be something serious. They did some tests, but thankfully, everything seemed normal. They just gave me ibuprofen and sent me home, but I can’t shake the anxiety over what could be causing this pain.

Now, four weeks later, I’m feeling a bit better and no longer need pain medication, but I still can’t help but wonder what the underlying issue might be. I’m just really concerned that something could come back and haunt me. What if this is just the beginning of something worse?
options: A. Parvovirus B19 B. Lyme disease C. Rheumatoid arthritis D. Gonococcal arthritis E. Systemic lupus erythematosus F. Transient synovitis G. Seronegative spondyloarthropathy H. Early-onset osteoarthritis I. Reactive arthritis J. Viral arthritis due to EBV

question:
I can’t shake off this nagging worry that something is seriously wrong with me. It all started with these relentless headaches and weird visual disturbances that I thought would just go away. But then, I noticed some other alarming changes: I’ve been gaining weight, my body hair seems to be growing more than usual, and my periods have become completely irregular. 

Even more concerning, my shoes and rings don’t fit like they used to, and my voice feels deeper. I haven’t experienced anything like this since I was 18! I’ve been trying to stay healthy—I don’t drink, smoke, or take any medications. When I went to see a doctor, they said my vital signs were normal, which gave me a brief sense of relief. But then, during the exam, they pointed out my prominent forehead, the protruding jaw, and my enlarged extremities. 

I can’t help but think about what this all means for my future. What if these changes lead to something more serious? I’m terrified of the complications that could arise from whatever is going on with me. I just want to understand what’s happening and how it could affect my health down the line. The uncertainty is almost unbearable.
options: A. Left ventricular hypertrophy with diastolic dysfunction B. Progressive renal dysfunction C. Accelerated progression of type 2 diabetes mellitus D. Increased risk of cerebrovascular accidents E. Increased risk of osteoporotic fractures F. Reduced cardiac output G. Increased likelihood of obstructive sleep apnea H. Deposition of mucopolysaccharides in the myocardium I. Hyperplasia of the adrenal cortex J. Thickening of the coronary artery walls

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread as I think back to what happened. It all started when I felt a fever coming on—just a low-grade one at first. But then, I became so lethargic; it was like I was dragging myself through molasses. I could barely think straight, and confusion set in. I remember looking in the mirror, and I didn’t recognize the person staring back at me. I looked so frail, almost ghost-like.

My friend rushed me to the emergency department because I just couldn’t communicate or follow any instructions. I was in a state of distress, and it felt terrifying. I overheard my companion telling the doctors about my past—how I’d had multiple sexual partners and had been diagnosed with HIV months ago. I hadn’t kept up with my medical check-ups after that; I don’t know why I let it slip. 

I remember the doctors mentioning my last CD4 count was dangerously low, just 65 cells. I felt a deep pit in my stomach as I realized how serious my situation might be. I just wish I had taken better care of myself. Now, I don’t even know what the next steps are or what’s going to happen to me. I’m scared, and I just want someone to help me figure this out.
options: A. Recheck CD4 and HIV viral load serologies B. Serum cryptococcal antigen testing C. Start antiretroviral therapy immediately D. Brain biopsy to evaluate for malignancy E. Neurological exam with fundoscopy F. Empiric treatment for toxoplasmosis G. Lumbar puncture for cerebrospinal fluid analysis H. Blood cultures and broad-spectrum antibiotics I. CT head without contrast J. Electroencephalogram to assess for seizure activity

question:
I can hardly believe what’s happening to me. At just 34 weeks into my first pregnancy, I started feeling this intense swelling in my legs, and then the headaches kicked in. They were like nothing I’ve ever experienced before. I went to see my doctor, and my blood pressure, which was previously normal at 125/82, had jumped to 147/90. That was alarming on its own, but it got worse.

During the exam, my doctor noted that I had significant pitting edema in my lower legs. I could see it—my feet were ballooning up! And then there was the urinalysis. I was devastated to find out that I had 2+ protein in my urine. I can’t shake off the feeling that something is seriously wrong. 

I’ve been trying to stay calm, but the numbers keep swirling in my mind. My heart rate was steady at 82, and my temperature was normal, but I can’t help but worry about what all of this means for me and my baby. Is this preeclampsia? What if it gets worse? I keep wondering if I’m missing some critical sign that could indicate severe complications. I just want everything to be okay, but I feel like I’m walking on a tightrope, and one misstep could change everything.
options: A. Hematocrit B. Total bilirubin C. Liver transaminases D. Blood pressure E. Reticulocyte count F. Conjugated bilirubin G. ALT/AST ratio H. Creatinine I. Thrombocyte count J. Proteinuria level

question:
I've been feeling really unwell for the past four months, and it's starting to really worry me. It all began with this crampy abdominal pain that just won’t go away. Along with that, I’ve been having these awful episodes of watery diarrhea that leave me feeling drained. I’ve also noticed I’ve lost about 2.5 kg, which is alarming. 

What really concerns me is that after I eat, I experience this strange flushing in my face and neck. It’s like my body is reacting, and sometimes I even feel short of breath, which scares me. My spouse has noticed it too and has been really worried about me. 

When I finally went to see a doctor, they found a murmur in my heart, which I didn’t expect at all. They said it was most prominent at the left lower sternal border. They also pressed on my abdomen, and while there was some tenderness, thankfully, there was no guarding or rebound tenderness. But with all these symptoms piling up, I can’t help but feel that something serious might be happening. I keep thinking about what could go untreated, and the possibilities are haunting me. What if I develop something worse? I just want to understand what’s happening to my body.
options: A. Pigmented dermatitis B. Laryngeal edema C. Achlorhydria D. T-cell lymphoma E. Malabsorptive enteropathy F. Bronchial fibrosis G. Right-sided valvular heart disease H. Carcinoid crisis I. Hepatic metastases J. Megaloblastic anemia

question:
I can't shake this nagging worry that's been creeping up on me lately. At 73, I thought I had my health mostly under control, especially with my history of hypertension and high cholesterol. But recently, I've been having these memory issues that are really alarming. My partner has pointed out that I often need reminders about current events—things I should know—and it feels like I’m withdrawing from social situations because I struggle to keep up with conversations. 

I can still manage my daily routines like showering and dressing, but when it comes to more complex tasks, I find myself relying heavily on my partner. Driving, managing my medications, cooking, and even handling finances have become challenging for me. It’s frustrating and a bit scary. I haven’t had any head injuries, and I don’t feel depressed or have trouble sleeping, but why is this happening?

I went to see a doctor, and they did a bunch of tests. Thankfully, they didn’t find anything alarming, and my vital signs were normal. But when they did a cognitive assessment, I scored lower than I should have, and that really hit me hard. I can’t help but wonder what’s wrong with me. Is this just aging, or is it something more serious? The uncertainty is weighing heavily on my mind.
options: A. Subjective cognitive decline B. Early-stage Alzheimer's disease C. Vascular cognitive impairment D. Pseudodementia E. Major depressive disorder F. Normal pressure hydrocephalus G. Mixed cognitive impairment H. Age-associated memory impairment I. Dementia J. Mild cognitive impairment

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that has settled over me. At 68 years old, I've always tried to take care of myself, especially with my history of atrial fibrillation. But this past week has been terrifying. I felt this overwhelming weakness wash over me, and there were moments when I thought I might actually faint. I had these awful cramping pains in my abdomen, and then there was the diarrhea, which just made everything worse.

When I finally went to the doctor, I was so lightheaded that just sitting up made me feel like I was going to pass out. I remember looking in the mirror and seeing how pale I looked. They checked my vital signs, and I could tell from the concerned expressions on their faces that something wasn't right. I had this large black bowel movement that I couldn’t understand. 

The doctor seemed worried, and I could feel my heart racing. I was scared about the possibility of something really serious happening to me. They mentioned my hemoglobin levels, and although I didn’t fully grasp what it meant, I could sense the urgency in the air. I just kept thinking, what’s going to happen to me? Will I be okay? I felt so vulnerable and frightened, waiting for a plan to help me through this frightening ordeal.
options: A. Ringer lactate bolus B. Transfuse packed red blood cells C. Administer oral ferrous sulfate D. Administer intravenous vitamin K E. Computed tomography (CT) angiography of the abdomen and pelvis F. Endoscopy and pantoprazole G. Administer fresh frozen plasma H. Start a vasopressor infusion I. Perform colonoscopy J. Switch apixaban to warfarin

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that started when I felt a sharp pain in my chest. It was so intense that I knew I had to get help immediately. I rushed to the emergency department, my heart racing with worry. What was happening to me? 

Once there, they did a coronary angiography, and the news wasn’t good. They found significant stenosis in my left anterior descending artery. I can’t help but feel terrified about what that means for my heart. I keep thinking about whether I might have suffered any damage already. 

The doctors mentioned several factors that could predict if there’s been any myocardial necrosis. I feel overwhelmed, thinking about things like the calcium content, presence of cytokines, and those foam cells. I’ve heard about how platelets can affect this too, and I can’t stop worrying about what might be happening in my body right now. 

It’s hard to focus on anything else when I’m scared about the extent of collateral circulation and the condition of my fibrous cap. I just want to know what’s going to happen to me. I keep asking myself how they’ll check for things like troponin T levels and inflammatory markers. This whole experience is just weighing heavily on my mind, and I can’t help but feel anxious about what lies ahead.
options: A. Calcium content B. Presence of cytokines C. Amount of foam cells D. Platelet aggregation index E. Extent of collateral circulation F. Fibrous cap thickness G. Troponin T elevation rate H. Inflammatory marker levels I. Rate of plaque formation J. Degree of endothelial dysfunction

question:
I can't believe what happened tonight. My heart was racing as I rushed my 2-year-old son to the emergency department. Just 15 minutes after he finished his dinner, I saw him swallow a nickel! I panicked, thinking about how dangerous that could be. Thankfully, he seemed fine—he wasn't choking, drooling, or even complaining of any pain. But still, my mind was racing with worry.

Once we got to the hospital, the doctors checked him out. His vital signs were normal, and the physical exam didn't show anything alarming. But then came the part that really made my stomach churn: the X-rays. They revealed a 2-cm round object stuck in his esophagus. I felt a wave of dread wash over me. What if it caused him harm? What if it didn’t come out?

I kept wondering what the next steps would be. The doctors discussed options, and I could feel my anxiety building. Should they try to remove it with a tube? Or would they need to perform an endoscopy? The thought of him needing anesthesia made me feel sick. I just wanted to make sure he would be okay. All I could think about was how helpless I felt in that moment, waiting for answers and hoping for a solution.
options: A. Attempt removal with magnet-tipped nasogastric tube B. Give oral contrast to help pass the coin C. Observe, and repeat the radiograph in several hours D. Perform immediate flexible endoscopy E. Administer glucagon to promote esophageal relaxation F. Arrange for rigid endoscopy and removal of the coin under anesthesia G. Perform emergent CT scan of chest and abdomen H. Discharge home, and schedule repeat radiographs in 2 days I. Administer IV metoclopramide to enhance motility J. Attempt removal with a Foley catheter

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread ever since I brought my baby to the clinic. He’s just two months old, and I can’t believe I let him fall from the bed. It all happened so fast. I just left him for a moment to grab a diaper, and when I came back, I heard him crying on the floor. My heart dropped. I rushed over, terrified of what I might find.

He cried briefly, but thankfully seemed to calm down pretty quickly. He was acting normally afterward, but I couldn’t help but worry—what if something was wrong? The doctor examined him, and I watched every move they made, holding my breath. He smiled occasionally, maintained good eye contact, and followed the doctor's hands, which was somewhat reassuring. Still, I couldn’t ignore that nagging fear.

The doctor said there were no bruises, and he didn’t seem to be in pain when they moved his arms and legs, but I just kept thinking about what could have happened. I felt so guilty for letting him fall like that. I’m terrified of the possibility that I might have caused him harm, even if it didn’t seem like it. I just want to make sure he’s truly okay and learn how to keep him safe from now on. How could I let this happen?
options: A. The child should be referred for skeletal survey to rule out occult fractures B. We should advise the mother to be more careful with the child to prevent similar accidents in the past as the child can move and fall. C. The mother’s account should be accepted, but the family should be referred to social services for home safety education D. The child should be admitted for observation to rule out subtle neurological injury E. A report should be filed with child protective services due to concern for non-accidental trauma F. The child’s symptoms suggest a possible underlying metabolic bone disorder requiring further evaluation G. The mother should be counseled on safe sleep practices to prevent future accidents H. It is very likely the mother is not telling us the real story of how the child has fallen I. The child’s behavior and examination are consistent with a minor fall, and no further investigation is needed J. It is normal for this child age to smile, follow the examiner and even try to catch objects close to him

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. For the past three months, I've been dealing with loose stools, going to the bathroom three to four times a day. It’s embarrassing and exhausting. Alongside that, I've been having this persistent abdominal pain that just won’t go away. Lately, I’ve also been feeling my heart racing, and it’s terrifying. I can’t figure out why I’m so irritable and why my sleep is so poor. I’ve even lost about six pounds without trying, which really worries me.

When I went to the doctor, they took my vital signs, and my heart rate was alarmingly high at 104 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was low. They examined my thyroid, and it was enlarged, which they said was a sign of something serious. I thought I was just stressed, but the doctor mentioned other symptoms like exophthalmos and hyperreflexia. 

It’s overwhelming to think that something could be wrong with my thyroid, and now I’m left wondering what the next steps are. I’ve been prescribed medication to help with my symptoms, but I can’t help but feel anxious about what’s really going on with my body. I just want to feel like myself again and not have to worry about all of this.
options: A. Methimazole B. Hydrocortisone C. Propylthiouracil D. Radioactive iodine therapy E. Observation and close monitoring F. Thyroid suppression therapy G. Lugol's solution H. Plasmapheresis I. Surgical thyroidectomy J. Beta-blocker therapy alone

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety after what happened during my soccer game three days ago. I was slide tackled, and it felt like my leg was hit hard from the outside. I didn’t think much of it at the time, but yesterday, everything changed. My knee started swelling up, and I could barely move it. It felt so unstable, like I couldn’t trust it at all when I tried to put weight on it.

I went to see my doctor, hoping for some reassurance, but as she examined my knee, I could see concern in her eyes. There were bruises all over my leg, and the swelling was worse than I expected. When she moved my knee around, I could hear this weird clicking and catching, which only made me feel more uneasy. I thought I was fine, but now I’m starting to worry about what this could mean for my soccer season.

I’ve always managed my asthma with my inhaler, but now I’m seriously questioning if I can play again. My doctor mentioned something about further tests, and I can’t help but feel scared about what they might find. What if it’s something serious? I just want to be back on the field, but now I’m not so sure that’s going to happen.
options: A. Medial meniscal tear B. Anterior cruciate ligament tear C. Lateral meniscal tear D. Quadriceps tendon rupture E. Tibial plateau fracture F. Patellar subluxation G. Patellar tendinitis H. Lateral collateral ligament tear I. Medial collateral ligament tear J. Posterior cruciate ligament tear

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry as I sit in the emergency department with my 5-week-old baby girl. It all started about a week ago when I noticed her skin was turning yellow. At first, I thought it was just a phase, but over the past four days, things got worse—her urine became darker, and her stools were so pale they almost looked white. I’m terrified that something is seriously wrong.

She’s been exclusively breastfed since birth, and I remember my older son had physiological jaundice, but this feels different. My heart races as I think back to her delivery; it was smooth and uncomplicated at 39 weeks. Here she is now, looking so small and fragile. Thankfully, she doesn’t seem to be in distress; her temperature is normal, and her pulse seems fine, but the jaundice on her skin and eyes is alarming.

The doctors did some examinations, and I can’t help but feel anxious about what they might find. They even mentioned something about her liver being enlarged, which makes my heart sink even further. I just want to know what’s going on. I keep asking myself what diagnostic tests they might need to confirm their suspicions. I can’t stop worrying—what if this is something serious? I feel so helpless.
options: A. Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) B. Cholangiography C. Genetic testing for biliary atresia D. Hepatobiliary scintigraphy E. Abdominal ultrasound F. Sweat chloride test G. Percutaneous liver biopsy H. Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP) I. Serum alpha-1 antitrypsin levels J. Stool elastase measurement

question:
I can't shake the worry that started when my wife rushed me to the emergency department. For the past 12 hours, I had been feeling increasingly confused and lethargic. I could only recognize who I was, but everything else felt like a fog. I remember her looking so anxious, and it made my heart race.

When we got there, the doctors examined me. They took my temperature, which was a bit elevated, and my pulse was racing at 109 beats per minute. I could feel my breathing was slightly off too. They noticed my abdomen was distended, which I hadn’t even realized was a problem, and there were strange, red lacy spots on my chest that worried me even more. I was shocked when they made me move my hands—apparently, I had this flapping tremor that I couldn't control.

I couldn’t help but wonder what was happening to me. I felt like I was losing control, and it scared me. I kept thinking about what might be causing all this. The doctors mentioned various possibilities, but I just wanted to know why I felt this way. It was all so overwhelming, and I hoped they would find answers soon.
options: A. Impaired bilirubin metabolism B. Destruction of gut anaerobes C. Thiamine pyrophosphate deficiency D. Excessive lactate production E. Increased ammonia production in the gut F. Accumulation of hemoglobin in the intestine G. Elevated systemic vascular resistance H. Portal vein thrombosis I. Decreased hepatic urea cycle activity J. Worsening hepatic encephalopathy

question:
I can’t shake off this overwhelming sense of worry that’s been haunting me since my diagnosis. It all started when I noticed a lump in my breast, about 5 cm big. I remember feeling a chill run down my spine when I found out it was a grade 3 tumor. The doctors also mentioned that my axillary lymph nodes were matted, which sounded incredibly serious. 

I underwent neoadjuvant chemotherapy, hoping against hope that it would help. The treatment felt endless, and I was terrified of what it might do to me. But then, after everything, I got the news that I had achieved a pathologic complete response after my modified radical mastectomy. For a moment, I felt relief wash over me. 

Yet, now I can’t help but think about the next steps. The medical team has been talking about TNM staging, and I’m left feeling confused and anxious about what it all means. What if something is still lurking there? I keep questioning if I really understand my own classification and what it means for my future. I just want to be sure that I’m on the right path and that I’m truly cancer-free. The uncertainty is almost too much to bear.
options: A. cT2N2aM0, ypT0N0 B. cT3N2M0, ypT0N0 C. cT3N2aM0, pT0N0M0 D. cT2N1M0, ypT0N0 E. cT3N1M0, ypT0N0 F. cT2N2aM0, ypT1N0 G. cT2N2aM0, ypT0N1 H. cT2N2aM0, ypTisN0 I. cT3N2aM0, ypT0N0Mx J. cT2N2aM0, pT0N0

question:
I can’t shake this nagging worry that something might be seriously wrong with me. At 63, I’ve always been healthy, but during a routine check-up, my doctor mentioned that my alkaline phosphatase levels were elevated—239 U/liter, when the normal range is supposed to be between 30 and 120. I felt a chill run down my spine. 

I didn’t have any symptoms, and everything else in my blood work seemed okay—my calcium, phosphorus, and albumin levels were normal, and even my liver function tests looked fine. But still, the thought of elevated alkaline phosphatase keeps haunting me. 

My doctor said they would need to do more tests to figure out what’s going on. I can’t help but feel overwhelmed. What if it’s something serious? They talked about a few options for next steps, but I can’t focus on anything other than the worry gnawing at me. 

Should I be concerned about my bones? Is there something wrong with my liver that we just can't see? I feel like I’m in limbo, waiting for answers, and I can’t help but think about all the what-ifs. I just want to understand what’s happening to my body and hope it’s nothing to be alarmed about.
options: A. Serum protein electrophoresis B. Dual-energy x-ray absorptiometry of the spine and hip C. Repeat alkaline phosphatase testing in 3 months D. Skeletal survey E. Bone scintigraphy F. Ultrasonography of the right upper quadrant G. Measurement of parathyroid hormone levels H. Liver biopsy I. Abdominal computed tomography J. Magnetic resonance imaging of the spine

question:
This morning, I noticed something alarming while putting on my socks—my left leg felt ice-cold. I’ve had leg pain before, especially at night and when I walk, but this was different. I’ve never felt my leg like this. It was so unusual that I decided to head to the emergency department. 

When I arrived, I was already feeling anxious. The doctors conducted several tests, and I could see the concern on their faces as they examined my leg. They commented on how cool and pale it was, and I felt a sense of dread when they noted that I couldn't move my foot at all. They checked my strength, and I could barely flex my knee. To make matters worse, they said they couldn't find any pulses in my lower leg. 

I’ve been managing diabetes for a while now, and I worried about what this could mean. The thought of my leg being in serious trouble is terrifying. I heard them mention terms like “threatened limb” and talk about imaging tests, and I just felt a wave of panic wash over me. I’m just hoping for the best because the uncertainty is really weighing on me. I can’t shake this feeling that something is very wrong.
options: A. Threatened limb; CT angiography B. Threatened limb; Doppler ultrasound C. Threatened limb; arterial plethysmography D. Threatened limb; MR angiography E. Non-viable limb; MR angiography F. Non-viable limb; Doppler ultrasound G. Non-viable limb; plain radiography H. Threatened limb; carbon dioxide angiogram I. Non-viable limb; duplex ultrasound J. Non-viable limb; CT angiography

question:
I can hardly believe what just happened to me. Just a little over an hour ago, I was sitting at the dinner table with my family, enjoying a meal when everything changed in an instant. Suddenly, I felt this strange weakness creeping in, especially in my right arm. I tried to talk, but my speech started slurring, and I felt like something was terribly wrong.

I remember trying to stand up, but the next thing I knew, I was on the floor, falling to my right side. I didn’t hit my head, and thankfully, I didn’t lose consciousness, but I was terrified. My family rushed to my side, and I could see the concern in their faces. I’ve been managing my hypertension with medication, but I never expected something like this to happen to me.

When I got to the emergency department, they took my temperature and checked my blood pressure, which was elevated. I felt this overwhelming fear when they started examining me and found weakness on my right side, but my left side felt completely fine. I just want to know what’s happening to me and what the doctors are going to do next. I’m so worried about what this all means for my health.
options: A. CT angiogram of the head and neck B. Immediate blood pressure reduction C. MRI of the head D. Aspirin administration E. Antiplatelet therapy F. Aspirin and atorvastatin G. Neurosurgical consultation H. Heparin infusion I. Observation and serial neurological exams J. Alteplase

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread as I sit here, recalling the past six days. It all started with a headache that just wouldn’t go away. At first, I thought it was just stress, but it quickly turned into something much worse. The pain is mostly in the front of my head, and now it radiates down my neck, making it hard to even move without feeling worse. Along with that, I've been feeling feverish, and the light hurts my eyes—photophobia, I think it’s called. 

I’ve had a couple of nights where I felt so hot, I was sweating through my clothes. When I looked in the mirror, I noticed my skin looked pale and sweaty, which was alarming. There’s also this strange rash on my neck and forearms that just appeared out of nowhere. I haven’t traveled recently or been in contact with animals, so I can’t figure out what’s going on. 

After finally deciding to go to the doctor, I was shocked when they mentioned doing a lumbar puncture. They found something in my spinal fluid, and now I'm just filled with anxiety, wondering what this all means. I’ve been sexually active with my partner for three years, so I can’t help but worry what this could lead to. I feel so lost and scared about what could be wrong with me.
options: A. Bacterial meningitis B. Cryptococcal meningitis C. Paraneoplastic meningitis D. Mumps meningitis E. Lymphocytic choriomeningitis virus F. Tuberculous meningitis G. Early-stage fungal meningitis H. Autoimmune meningitis I. Enterovirus meningitis J. Viral encephalitis

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping in for the past month. It started when I was out hiking; I just felt so drained, more than usual. Now, it’s affecting my daily activities, and I can't ignore it anymore. I haven’t seen a doctor in over ten years, and I know I should have been more proactive about my health, especially considering my untreated diabetes. My diet has been pretty poor, and I do have a couple of beers every day, but I don’t smoke, so I thought I was doing okay.

But now, this fatigue is really getting to me. I went to urgent care, hoping for some answers. They checked my vital signs, which seemed fine enough, but I couldn’t help but feel that something was off. I’ve never had a colonoscopy, and now I’m scared about what could be lurking beneath the surface. I can’t help but think about all the possibilities—like what if it’s something serious? I just want to know why I feel this way. It’s hard to focus on anything else when I’m so worried about my health. Will I ever feel normal again?
options: A. Alcohol-induced bone marrow suppression B. Myelodysplastic syndrome causing ineffective erythropoiesis C. Hemoglobinopathy such as alpha-thalassemia trait D. Lead poisoning causing microcytic anemia E. Occult bleeding F. Mineral deficiency G. Erythropoietin deficiency due to chronic kidney disease H. Iron malabsorption due to celiac disease I. Chronic inflammation J. Vitamin deficiency

question:
I recently took my little one for what I thought would be a routine well-child visit, but I can't shake this feeling of worry that crept in during the appointment. Lately, I’ve noticed my child has been having a runny nose and isn’t eating well, which made me anxious right from the start. When the doctor examined them, I felt a mix of relief and concern. My child could sit up straight, crawl around effectively, and had a great pincer grasp, but the fact that they still aren’t walking independently is weighing heavily on my mind. 

The doctor said my child was alert and interactive, even smiling during the exam, which was a bit reassuring. They checked all the vital signs, and everything seemed normal, but I kept thinking about what’s expected at this age. My child’s growth charts show they’re tracking well for height and weight, but I can’t help but worry about the milestones they might be missing. 

I overheard the doctor mention developmental expectations, and I just kept thinking—should they be saying "mama" or "dada" by now? Is it concerning that they haven't reached that point yet? I couldn’t focus on anything else. I just want to make sure I’m doing everything I can for my child’s development and well-being.
options: A. This child should  be saying mama dada and 3 other words B. This child is expected to have stranger anxiety at this age C. This child is likely to have significant delays in development D. It Is expected that this child will play peek a boo E. It is unusual for this child to not be walking yet F. This child is likely 18 months old G. this child is 6 month old H. This child is expected to be able to stand unsupported I. This child is expected to have a poor pincer grasp at this stage J. This child is expected to say "mama" or "dada" nonspecifically

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread from what happened earlier today. I’m 71 years old, and this morning started off like any other, but then everything spiraled out of control. I had what felt like an endless series of bowel movements, and to my horror, I saw bright red blood filling the toilet. I’ve never seen anything like it, and panic set in.

Shortly after that, I felt dizzy—so dizzy that I collapsed right into my daughter’s arms. I remember her voice, shaky and worried, calling for help. When I got to the emergency department, I was terrified. They took my blood pressure, which was 155/94, and checked my pulse. I was so scared, just hoping they would find something that would explain what was happening to me.

They did some examinations and told me I was positive for blood in my stool, even though I wasn't passing anything bloody anymore. I could tell they were concerned. They started two IVs and began giving me fluids, but all I could think was: what’s next? I felt so weak and anxious about what this all could mean for my health. I just want to feel better and not be in this state of worry. What if this is something serious?
options: A. Observation and repeat hemoglobin in 6 hours B. Packed red blood cells C. Angiography D. Coagulation profile evaluation E. Intravenous proton pump inhibitor therapy F. Fresh frozen plasma G. CT abdomen H. Type and screen I. Upper endoscopy J. Colonoscopy

question:
I can hardly shake the worry that’s been weighing on me since my shoulder surgery just two days ago. At 78, I never imagined I’d be facing something like this, especially after the frightening experience of a 4-part proximal humerus fracture on my dominant side. 

During the operation, I overheard the doctors discussing how difficult it was to reduce the lesser tuberosity. They mentioned it ended up too close to the greater tuberosity, and I couldn’t help but feel a knot tighten in my stomach. What does that mean for my recovery? 

I’ve been trying to stay positive, but I can’t shake the fear of complications. What if the malposition leads to issues like biceps tendon dysfunction or even something worse? The thought of struggling with basic movements or not regaining full use of my shoulder is terrifying. 

I keep replaying the moments leading up to the surgery in my head, wondering if there was something I could have done differently to avoid this. I just want to heal properly and regain my independence. It’s hard to focus on anything else when I’m filled with uncertainty about what comes next. Will I be able to lift my arm again? I really hope the recovery goes smoothly, but right now, I can’t help but feel anxious about the future.
options: A. biceps tendon dysfunction B. rotator interval dysfunction C. supraspinatus dysfunction D. external rotation deficit E. internal rotation deficit F. subscapularis impingement G. abduction weakness H. forward flexion limitation I. forward elevation weakness J. glenohumeral instability

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread as I recall the last few days. My 8-year-old son, who has cystic fibrosis, suddenly got really sick. It all started two days ago when he developed a high fever, reaching 39.6°C. At first, I thought it might just be a minor bug, but then his breathing became so rapid, I could hardly believe it—44 breaths a minute! His heart was racing too, at 122 beats per minute. 

He’s had respiratory infections before, but this felt different. The yellow sputum he was coughing up was alarming. I rushed him to the emergency department, and it broke my heart to see him struggling to breathe, with these labored efforts and little retractions under his ribcage. The doctors did a physical exam and mentioned something about decreased breath sounds on his right side, where they noticed dullness when they tapped. 

When the chest X-ray results came back, they revealed consolidation in his right upper lobe. The oxygen saturation was only 91% on room air, which sent me into a panic. I can’t help but worry about what’s lurking inside him. What if it’s a serious infection? I just want to know what’s causing this and if he’s going to be okay.
