options: A. Pseudomonas aeruginosa B. Mycoplasma pneumoniae C. Haemophilus influenzae D. Escherichia coli E. Aspergillus fumigatus F. Klebsiella pneumoniae G. Moraxella catarrhalis H. Streptococcus pneumoniae I. Burkholderia cepacia J. Staphylococcus aureus

question:
I can’t shake off the overwhelming worry that settled in my chest yesterday. My 3-year-old son, who’s usually so full of energy, suddenly had red urine. I noticed it while changing him, and my heart dropped. He wasn’t complaining about any discomfort, and there hadn’t been any burning sensations or frequent trips to the bathroom. No fever, no back pain—he seemed perfectly normal otherwise, just playing and laughing as he always does. 

But then, I took him to the doctor, and that’s when everything changed. The examination went fine at first; he was active and interacted well with the staff. But then they did an abdominal study, and that’s when they found something—a mass in his right flank. The doctor said it didn’t seem tender and felt smooth, but I can’t help but worry about what that means. 

What if it’s something serious? I can’t stop thinking about it. I know he’s been growing and developing well, and he’s up to date on vaccines, but this is terrifying. I’ve heard about tumors in children before, and I can’t help but fear the worst. I just want him to be okay, and I feel so helpless right now.
options: A. This child is having neuroblastoma, a tumor related to supra-renal  glands B. 90% of the patients have a favorable histologic finding in biopsy C. The most common site of metastasis for this tumor is the bone marrow D. This tumor is associated with aniridia and genitourinary abnormalities E. The mass is most likely derived from neural crest cells F. The tumor is often bilateral, especially in familial cases G. The histology of the mass should be rosettes with central  fibrillar material. H. Due to being mostly asymptomatic, most patients have a distant disease at the moment of diagnosis I. The most common presentation of this tumor is hematuria J. This tumor is associated with elevated catecholamines in the urine

question:
I can’t shake off this worry that’s been creeping in since my last doctor’s visit. Two weeks ago, I went in for a follow-up after being treated for my first urinary tract infection, and I was relieved when the doctor said I was asymptomatic now. But then, they checked my blood pressure, and it was 130/80 mm Hg. I remember seeing my previous readings were 136/84 and 130/81, which didn’t seem great either.

I mean, I’m just 16! It feels unsettling to think about my blood pressure being this high. And then there’s my family history weighing on my mind. My dad was just diagnosed with hypertension, and last year, my grandma had a heart attack at only 72. It really makes me anxious to think that I could be heading in the same direction.

I’m not on any medications, and my growth chart shows my weight is in the 95th percentile, but my height is only in the 25th. That disparity has me nervous too. The doctor said my cardiac exam was normal, but I can’t help but feel like something might be wrong.

I know I need to keep monitoring my blood pressure, but it’s hard to not feel overwhelmed. What if this is something serious? I just want to be healthy and not worry about these things.
options: A. Borderline BP requiring continued monitoring B. Isolated systolic hypertension C. Stage 1 hypertension D. Secondary hypertension due to renal causes E. Stage 2 hypertension F. Normal BP for age and height percentile G. Normal BP with white coat syndrome H. Transient BP elevation due to recent UTI I. Stress-induced BP elevation J. Elevated BP (previously described as “prehypertension”)

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of panic that washed over me when my hand slipped while I was placing a central venous catheter in a critically ill patient with HIV/AIDS. I knew the risks, but nothing could prepare me for the moment the exposed needle pricked my skin. My heart raced as I realized I had just sustained a needlestick injury. 

I’ve always been cautious, and thankfully, I haven't had any recent exposures to HIV. Yet, the thought of not being on antiretrovirals really unsettled me. During medical school, I received the hepatitis B vaccination, but I never got tested to confirm if it worked. Now I’m left wondering if I’m protected. 

Born in the U.S. and with no other risk factors for hepatitis B, I thought I was safe, but this incident has turned everything upside down. What if I contracted something? I know I need to act fast, but my mind is racing with questions. I need to undergo some diagnostic tests, but which ones should I get right away? The choices swirl in my head, and I can’t help but feel the weight of uncertainty pressing down on me. I just want to make sure I’m okay.
options: A. HIV antibody/antigen combo test, hepatitis B core antibody, and hepatitis C RNA B. HIV viral load, hepatitis B core antibody, and hepatitis C antibody C. HIV antigen/antibody combo test, complete hepatitis B panel, and hepatitis C viral load D. HIV proviral DNA, hepatitis B DNA, and hepatitis C antibody E. HIV Western blot, hepatitis B e antigen, and hepatitis C genotype F. HIV p24 antigen, hepatitis B surface antibody, and hepatitis C core antibody G. HIV antibody, HIV viral load, and hepatitis B surface antibody H. HIV RNA PCR, hepatitis B surface antigen, and hepatitis C antibody I. HIV antibody, HIV viral load, hepatitis B surface antibody, and hepatitis C antibody J. HIV antibody, hepatitis B surface antibody, and hepatitis C antibody

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that settled over me when my dad suddenly started slurring his speech during dinner. It was just a regular evening, and then, out of nowhere, his face took on a strange droop on one side. I remember feeling my heart race as I rushed to him, desperately trying to assess what was happening. 

He’s 78 and has been managing diabetes and high blood pressure for years, but this sudden change terrified me. I could see the worry in his eyes as he struggled to communicate. I quickly called for help, and the ambulance arrived, whisking him away to the emergency department. 

In the ER, the doctors checked his vital signs. I stood there, anxious, as they noted his blood pressure was high, and he was only aware of who he was but not much else. His left side seemed so weak—how could this be happening? I kept thinking about how fragile he is at his age. 

They asked about the next steps in his care, but I felt lost in the whirlwind of it all. I just wanted to know he would be okay. As I sat there, the uncertainty gnawed at me—what if this was something serious? I couldn’t help but worry about what the doctors would find.
options: A. CT head without contrast B. MRI brain with contrast C. Echocardiography D. Administration of aspirin E. Observation and repeat neurological exam in 1 hour F. Aspirin G. Lumbar puncture H. Carotid Doppler ultrasound I. CT head with contrast J. CT angiogram head and neck

question:
I took my 6-week-old baby to his routine check-up, and honestly, I’ve been feeling so anxious ever since. The doctor said he’s feeding and growing well, which is a relief, but there have been these crying episodes that are really troubling me. Sometimes, it feels like no matter what I do, I just can’t soothe him. During these moments, he curls up his legs and strains, and it breaks my heart to see him like this. 

These crying spells seem to peak in the evenings, starting and stopping without any clear reason. He’s having bowel movements every couple of days and producing enough wet diapers, but I can’t shake this worry. I breastfeed him every 2-3 hours, so I thought I was doing everything right. The doctor said he appears healthy, smiling, and interacting normally, which is comforting, but I can’t help but feel overwhelmed. 

I know his vaccinations are up to date and the examination showed nothing concerning, yet I can’t help but wonder if this could be something serious or if I’m missing something. I’ve read about colic and how it’s common, especially for firstborns, but it just feels so heavy on my heart. I just want to make sure my little one is okay.
options: A. Typically resolves when solid foods are introduced at 4 months B. Behavioral syndrome with continuous crying without most of the times a factor can be identified C. Associated with increased risk of asthma and allergies in later childhood D. Primarily caused by lactose intolerance and requires dietary modification E. More prevalent in formula-fed infants compared to breastfed infants F. More common in firstborn children due to parental inexperience G. Strongly correlated with delayed developmental milestones in early childhood H. Associated with maternal anxiety and depression during pregnancy, requiring psychological intervention I. Colic is generally diagnosed as a diagnosis of exclusion after proper workup with blood tests and imaging examination J. More common in children of mothers that have migraine or children that will develop migraine in later childhood

question:
I can hardly believe what happened to me. It all started when I began feeling extremely nauseous and couldn’t stop vomiting. I thought it was just a bad stomach bug, but then the fever hit. I was burning up, and my temperature soared to 104.9°F. I’ve had my share of health issues—dealing with hepatitis C and having gone through a liver transplant for cancer, but this felt different. 

I remember feeling dizzy and weak, and when I tried to get up, I nearly collapsed. I could hardly respond to anyone around me, and I know I was sweating profusely. Suddenly, I was in an ambulance, and everything became a blur. My heart was racing at 130 beats per minute, and I could hear the medics talking about my blood pressure being dangerously low. I felt so helpless.

When I got to the hospital, they rushed me to intensive care. I overheard the doctors discussing my past admissions for septic shock, and that worried me even more. I couldn't shake the feeling that something terrible was happening inside me. They started me on antibiotics and other medications, but I just kept thinking about how serious my situation was. I desperately wanted to know what they would find out and what this meant for my future.
options: A. Advance directive documentation B. Immunosuppressive medication history C. Recent imaging studies D. Cultures of indwelling devices E. Next of kin contact information F. Baseline cognitive assessment G. Previous discharge summaries of prior hospital admissions H. Code status I. Blood ammonia levels J. Liver function tests

question:
I can't shake the memory of that day at the cross-country race. It was incredibly hot—38.3°C with a suffocating 85% humidity. I remember feeling fine at first, but as I crossed the finish line, everything just went black. The next thing I knew, I was collapsing, and people were rushing to help me. They said I was staggering before I fell, and I could feel the sweat pouring off me as I tried to finish.

When I came to, I was in the emergency department, but I felt so confused and lethargic. My skin felt dry, yet my arms and legs were warm to the touch. I could hear the doctors talking about my fever—my temperature was 40.0°C! I felt so helpless and scared. 

I overheard them discussing what to do next, and my mind raced with worry about what might happen to me. I just wanted them to act quickly to help me cool down. My heart was pounding as they seemed to weigh their options, but I couldn’t shake the fear that something was seriously wrong. All I wanted was to feel better and be okay again.
options: A. Intravenously administer cold normal saline B. Completely immerse the patient to the neck in cold water (10–20°C) C. Administer antipyretics to lower the temperature D. Use ice packs on the groin, axillae, and neck to reduce core temperature E. Perform gastric lavage with cold saline to reduce temperature F. Perform evaporative cooling with fans and misting G. Administer intravenous fluids without active cooling measures H. Place the patient in an air-conditioned room and monitor closely I. Apply a cooling blanket J. Completely immerse the patient to the neck in ice water (2–3°C)

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety since my last clinic visit. I’m 48 years old and was diagnosed with nonischemic cardiomyopathy just three months ago, which was a huge shock. My ejection fraction is only 30%, and I’ve been trying to follow my treatment plan diligently. I’m currently on several medications, including carvedilol and sacubitril-valsartan, but I still worry every day about my condition.

During my recent appointment, I felt somewhat relieved that I was able to walk for an hour without struggling to breathe, and I didn’t have any swelling or trouble lying down. Yet, the doctors mentioned my brain natriuretic peptide levels were elevated, and that really set off alarm bells in my head. I can’t help but think about what that means for me. Is it the weight I’ve put on? My BMI is 36, and I know that’s not good. 

They also found some mild pedal edema, and even though my blood pressure and heart rate were stable, I keep wondering if there’s something more serious going on. What if it’s something like chronic kidney disease or persistent left ventricular dysfunction? I just want to be okay and not have to face more complications. This uncertainty is really weighing on me.
options: A. Subclinical volume overload B. Elevated pulmonary pressures C. Obstructive sleep apnea D. Increased adipose tissue interfering with BNP clearance E. Inadequate dose of diuretic therapy F. Obesity G. Chronic kidney disease H. Prolonged use of beta-blockers I. Persistent left ventricular dysfunction J. Sacubitril-valsartan use

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety that’s been building over the past week. It started with a strange burning sensation on my right arm, which I just brushed off at first. But then, two days later, a rash erupted—these clustered "pimples" that I couldn’t ignore. I really thought applying some over-the-counter zinc ointment would help, but the rash just won’t go away. It’s so frustrating!

I’m a 26-year-old PhD student, and I spend countless hours in the lab. I know that my lifestyle isn’t the most conventional, especially with multiple sexual partners, and that thought keeps nagging at me. I took my temperature this morning, and it was a little high—37.8°C. It’s not like me to feel this way, and I’m worried. 

When I looked at my arm, I saw these crusted lesions stretching from my armpit down to my forearm; it was alarming. I tried to stay calm, but I can’t help but think about what this could mean. I know I need to address this, but what should I do next? Should I get tested for STIs? I just want this rash to go away and to understand what’s happening to me. I can’t help but feel scared about what it might be.
options: A. STI screening panel B. HIV screening C. Acyclovir therapy D. Culture of lesions E. Serologic testing for syphilis F. Topical corticosteroid treatment G. Reassurance and follow-up H. Valacyclovir therapy I. Skin biopsy J. Empiric antibiotic therapy

question:
I can’t shake this nagging feeling of worry. It’s been six months now since I first noticed that burning pain in my legs, and it’s only getting worse, especially in my left leg. I can’t help but feel anxious every time I walk downhill; the pain intensifies, and it’s really hard to manage. On good days, I can ride a stationary bike, and that helps a bit, but it’s not a solution. 

I’m 65, and my medical history is a bit daunting. I have hypertension and diabetes, which I try to keep under control. I even had a heart attack a while back, and I fractured my wrist last year after a fall. It feels like my body is falling apart, and I’m worried about what’s next. 

My doctor referred me to a neurologist because of my leg pain, and honestly, I’m terrified of what might be going on. I’ve had my blood pressure checked; it was higher than I’d like, and I worry if my smoking and drinking habits are catching up to me. I feel like I’m in decent shape, but sometimes I wonder if I’m just fooling myself. 

I just want to know what’s happening to me. I keep thinking about what tests they might run, and I can’t help but feel anxious about the possibilities. What if it’s something serious? I really hope they find answers soon.
options: A. Computed tomography of the lumbar spine B. Ankle-brachial index C. Computerized tomography myelography D. Doppler ultrasonography of the lower extremities E. Electromyography and nerve conduction studies F. Magnetic resonance imaging G. X-ray of the lumbosacral spine H. Serum inflammatory markers (e.g., ESR, CRP) I. Myelography J. Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry (DEXA)

question:
I can’t believe what happened to me yesterday. I woke up feeling fine, but after a long day of typing at work, I suddenly noticed this sharp pain in my left forearm. It just came out of nowhere! I didn’t bump it or anything—there were no injuries that I can recall. I thought it was just fatigue from typing, but by the end of the day, the pain was so intense that I felt I had to go to the emergency department.

When I got there, I was so anxious. The doctor examined me and mentioned that my elbow was showing some unusual signs. I could see the concern in their eyes as they pointed out the medial deviation of my olecranon and how my wrist was oddly positioned. They poked around my forearm, and I winced at the tenderness. Thankfully, there wasn’t any swelling or redness, but I couldn’t shake the feeling that something was seriously wrong. 

The doctor mentioned something about potential dysfunctions in my arm, but honestly, I was too worried to fully grasp what they were saying. I just wanted to understand why this was happening to me. What if it’s something serious? I really need to figure this out soon.
options: A. Abduction of the ulna B. Posterior translation of the ulna C. Anterior translation of the ulna D. Interosseous membrane dysfunction E. Supination of the radius F. Ulnar head subluxation G. Proximal radioulnar joint dysfunction H. Adduction of the ulna I. Distal radioulnar joint dysfunction J. Pronation of the radius

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been creeping over me for the past couple of weeks. It started with these strange visions—clouds morphing into the shapes of dogs, cats, and even monkeys. I mean, it sounds bizarre, but it feels so real. I’ve been managing my simple partial seizures with valproate for years, and the dosage hasn’t changed. I thought I was stable, but now I’m not so sure.

When I visited the behavioral health clinic, I was so anxious. My blood pressure and heart rate were elevated, and I couldn’t help but worry about what this all means. I felt alert and oriented, but my speech came out way too fast and loud. I could see the concern in the doctor’s eyes when I told her about the visions. 

I even took a urine drug test, and I was shocked to find out I tested positive for alcohol and cocaine. I didn’t think I was using anything harmful, but now I’m terrified about what this could mean for my mental health. I’m left wondering if this is some kind of psychotic episode, or if it’s all tied back to my seizures. It feels like I’m losing control, and I just want to understand what’s happening to me.
options: A. Delusion B. Psychotic episode C. Drug-induced psychosis D. Postictal confusion with perceptual distortion E. Hallucination secondary to seizure activity F. Illusion G. Perceptual disturbance due to alcohol use H. Cocaine intoxication I. Visual hallucination J. Misinterpretation of external stimuli

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been building over the past few weeks. It all started about three weeks ago when I began feeling nauseous and my stomach started hurting. At first, I thought it was just something I ate, but then the confusion set in, and it scared me. I’ve been managing my type 2 diabetes with metformin, and I’ve always been careful with my diet, so why was this happening to me?

I went to see my doctor, hoping to figure it out. I was so anxious during the visit. My blood pressure was higher than usual, and my pulse was steady, but I couldn’t help but feel something was very wrong. The doctor examined my abdomen and said it felt soft, which I guess was somewhat reassuring, but it didn’t ease my worries.

I’ve never smoked or had a drink, and I usually just take over-the-counter antacids for my reflux. But now, I’m left with so many questions. What if this is something serious? Why was I feeling so confused? I can’t help but worry about what the doctor might find in my blood tests. What if it’s something I can’t control? I just want to feel normal again.
options: A. 24,25-Dihydroxycholecalciferol B. Fibroblast growth factor 23 (FGF23) C. Calcitonin D. Parathyroid hormone E. Alkaline phosphatase F. 1,25-Dihydroxycholecalciferol G. Calcium H. Phosphate I. Vitamin D-binding protein J. Magnesium

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread since we took our two-week-old son to the doctor. He was born full-term, and everything seemed perfect at first. But then, during the newborn screening, they found only hemoglobin F in his blood. I didn’t even know that could happen, and now I’m just filled with worry. 

The doctor mentioned something about hemoglobinopathies, which sounds serious, and I can’t help but think the worst. I keep replaying the conversation in my head, trying to remember every detail. They suggested that we might need to take a closer look at his blood, maybe through a peripheral blood smear, but I just feel so overwhelmed. 

What if it’s something really serious? They talked about referring us to a pediatric hematologist, and my heart sank at the thought. I want to be strong for my baby, but I can’t help but feel helpless. I keep wondering if I should be doing something more right now. 

I just want to know my son is going to be okay. I can’t stop thinking about what it all means for his future. I need answers, and I need them fast. The waiting is unbearable, and I just hope we can figure this out soon.
options: A. Obtain a peripheral blood smear B. Schedule follow-up in 3 months C. Refer to pediatric hematologist D. Provide reassurance to the parents E. Perform hemoglobin solubility test F. Repeat hemoglobin electrophoresis at 6 months G. Perform family genetic screening H. Order globin gene testing I. Order complete blood count with reticulocytes J. Start prophylactic iron supplementation

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread since I ended up in the emergency department. I'm 68 years old and have been living with diabetes, hypertension, and ischemic heart disease for almost two decades now, but this pain was different. For two long hours, I felt severe abdominal pain that was almost unbearable, and then, to make matters worse, I had a terrifying episode of bloody diarrhea. 

When I got to the hospital, my temperature was a bit elevated, and my blood pressure was concerning, hovering around 145/90. I felt a little dazed but alert enough to grasp what was happening. The doctors examined my abdomen, and while they noted some tenderness, thankfully, there was no guarding or rebound tenderness. They did an X-ray, which thankfully came back normal, but then the CT scan revealed colonic wall thickening and pericolonic fat stranding near the splenic area, which left me feeling even more anxious. 

Now, they’ve started me on bowel rest, IV hydration, and antibiotics, but I can’t shake the worry about what comes next. They mentioned something about needing to evaluate further, and I’m just left wondering what that means. I feel so vulnerable right now, and I really hope they can figure this out quickly.
options: A. Colonoscopy B. Exploratory laparotomy C. Serum lactate measurement D. Sigmoidoscopy E. Angiography F. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the abdomen G. Stool culture and sensitivity H. Inpatient observation I. CT angiography of the abdomen J. Measurement of inflammatory markers (e.g., CRP, ESR)

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry as I sit here reflecting on the past few months. For the last three months, I’ve been struggling to walk, and it’s really starting to scare me. I’ve had a history of twisting my left ankle, but this feels different. I’ve never had this kind of persistent difficulty before, and it’s affecting my daily life.

I’m 55, and while I manage my hypertension with lisinopril, I can’t help but feel overwhelmed. When I recently visited the doctor, my blood pressure was a bit elevated, and I was relieved to hear my heart was okay, but I still felt uneasy. They did some tests, and the doctor listened closely to my heart and checked my lungs, which seemed fine, thankfully.

But then, they examined my left ankle and noticed something unusual with my fibula. It’s hard to explain, but it felt like everything was going wrong. I couldn’t help but worry about what all of this could mean. I just want to understand why I can’t walk properly and what’s happening to my body. The uncertainty is weighing heavily on me, and I feel like I need answers soon. What if it’s something serious?
options: A. Cuboid somatic dysfunction B. Medial tibial torsion C. Talus anterior somatic dysfunction D. Subtalar joint dysfunction E. Distal fibular fracture without displacement F. Posterior fibular head dysfunction G. Navicular somatic dysfunction H. Lateral tibial torsion I. Anterior fibular head dysfunction J. Plantar fascia strain

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread as I think back over the last four months. It all started with this awful, recurrent abdominal pain—sharp and persistent. At first, I thought it was just something I ate, but it didn’t go away. Then, I noticed my stools were foul-smelling and greasy, which was really alarming. I’ve lost about 11 pounds, and I haven’t changed my appetite at all. I’m eating the same, but the weight keeps dropping, and that just makes me more anxious.

When I finally decided to see a doctor, they pressed on my abdomen, and I felt this tenderness on the right side that made me wince. I didn’t know what to think. They ran some tests, and I found out my fasting blood sugar was higher than it should be—186 mg/dL. It’s frightening to think there might be something seriously wrong.

Then came the ultrasound, which revealed these strange round spots in my gallbladder. The doctor explained something about shadowing, but all I could focus on was the mounting fear that something is really wrong with me. I just wish I could understand what’s happening and if there’s a way to fix it.
options: A. Cortisol B. Cholecystokinin C. Amylin D. Glucagon E. Insulin-like growth factor-1 F. Somatostatin G. Gastrin H. Pancreatic polypeptide I. Secretin J. Vasoactive intestinal peptide

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread after what happened to me recently. It all started when I was working a shift as a nurse. Suddenly, I felt this overwhelming weakness wash over me, and my hands began to shake uncontrollably. I was sweating profusely, and I could feel my heart racing in my chest—it was pounding so hard I thought it might burst out. I felt lightheaded and a bit confused, which really scared me. 

My colleague noticed something was off and rushed me to the emergency department. I’ve had similar episodes three times in the past month, but I never thought they would lead me here. I don’t have any ongoing medical issues, and I’m not on any medications. My family history isn’t great either; my relative has Grave’s disease, which has been weighing on my mind. 

In the hospital, they checked my vital signs. I felt anxious, especially when they started ordering tests. Part of me was terrified about what they might find. They seemed concerned too, but I couldn’t help but worry. I just want to understand what’s happening to my body and why these episodes keep coming back. It’s so unsettling to feel this way, and I can’t shake the fear that something serious might be wrong.
options: A. Complete blood count (CBC) B. Electrocardiogram (ECG) C. Urine metanephrine D. Plasma metanephrines E. Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) F. D-dimer test G. Fingerstick blood glucose H. Arterial blood gas (ABG) I. Serum cortisol level J. Serum insulin and C-peptide levels

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been creeping up on me for the past two years. It all started with this shortness of breath that just keeps getting worse. I’m only 40, and I used to smoke half a pack of cigarettes daily for about ten years, but I quit eight years ago. I thought that would help, but now I'm really scared. 

When I went to the doctor, they took my vital signs, and everything seemed okay on the surface—my pulse was 72, blood pressure was 135 over 75, and my respiratory rate was 20. But during the exam, the doctor noticed my chest was oddly shaped and my breath sounds weren’t right. The worst part? They mentioned something about a chest X-ray showing widened spaces between my ribs and a flattened diaphragm. I can't help but think about what that means for me.

The thought of being at high risk for something serious is terrifying. I keep wondering if I could be facing conditions like pulmonary hypertension or even something worse. I just want to breathe normally again and not have this constant anxiety about what might be happening inside my body. What if it’s something really bad? I can’t help but worry about what’s next.
options: A. Secondary spontaneous pneumothorax B. Hepatocellular carcinoma C. Pulmonary hypertension due to interstitial lung disease D. Bronchiolitis obliterans E. Cor pulmonale F. Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension G. Bronchogenic carcinoma H. Pulmonary fibrosis I. Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy J. Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency-related cirrhosis

question:
I can’t shake the fear that washed over me when I found my son, just 6 years old, clutching a hairdryer in the bathtub. The moment I saw him, I felt my heart drop. He’d been exposed to a low-voltage electrical shock, and I couldn’t believe it was happening. After that, everything spiraled. He started vomiting—three times, I counted—each episode making my stomach twist tighter with worry.

When we finally arrived at the emergency department, I could see that he was disoriented, moaning softly with his eyes closed. It was terrifying to watch him struggle to respond, only opening his eyes when someone spoke to him. I held his right hand, which had a nasty blister on the palm, the skin red and angry-looking. I tried to stay calm, but my heart raced as I thought about the pain he might be in.

The doctors examined him, checking his vital signs and his heart. They reassured me that his breathing was stable, but I couldn’t help feeling overwhelmed. I kept wondering what the next step would be. I just want him to be okay. Should we consult a hand surgeon? Or would he need more tests? Every minute felt like an eternity as I waited for answers, my concern only growing with each passing moment.
options: A. Serial troponin measurements B. Administration of IV antibiotics C. Consultation with a hand surgeon D. Tetanus prophylaxis administration E. Noncontrast CT of the brain F. Topical silver sulfadiazine application G. Immediate cardiac monitoring H. Immediate transfer to burn unit I. Emergent fasciotomy J. Pack the right hand in ice

question:
I’ve been running marathons for years, but recently, I started to notice this aching pain in my right groin after I finished a run. At first, I thought it was just fatigue, but then the pain intensified and spread to my pubic region, the front of my hip, and even my lower abdomen. It hurts so much more when I run or change direction, and honestly, it’s starting to scare me.

When I went to the doctor, they examined me and pressed on my pubic symphysis, which was incredibly painful. I could feel the tension when they pushed on my right pubic ramus. Lying on my right side and trying to move my leg was excruciating. I really thought something serious was wrong.

They did a bunch of tests—some of which I thought would help figure this out—but all came back negative. I can’t shake this feeling of worry. I keep wondering what could be causing this pain. I just want to get back to running without fear of hurting myself more. It’s hard to not think the worst. What if it’s something serious? I’m left with a lingering concern about what might be happening inside my body, and I just want answers.
options: A. Trochanteric bursitis B. Athletic pubalgia C. Pelvic floor dysfunction D. Hip labral tear E. Osteitis pubis F. Femoral acetabular impingement G. Pubic ramus stress fracture H. Iliopsoas bursitis I. Sacroiliitis J. Adductor muscle strain

question:
I've been feeling really anxious lately. About ten days ago, I started experiencing these painful spasms in my right thigh, specifically in the back. It’s been tough to cope with, and I’ve been trying to figure out what’s going on. 

I’m 77 years old, and I already deal with some health issues like high cholesterol, high blood pressure, and congestive heart failure. I take medications like atorvastatin and furosemide, but this pain is something different. My vital signs were stable when I went to see the doctor—thank goodness for that—but the discomfort in my thigh is still there.

During the exam, the doctor examined my muscles and found that I had normal strength, which was reassuring. But when they pressed on specific points around my pelvis and thigh, it hurt, and I couldn't help but worry. The standing flexion test on my right side was positive, whatever that means. 

I can’t shake the feeling that there’s something seriously wrong. I just want to know what’s causing these spasms and if it’s something I should be really concerned about. I hope it’s not anything that could lead to more complications, given my age and health history. I just want to get back to feeling normal again.
options: A. Right adductor magnus B. Right piriformis C. Right sartorius D. Right iliopsoas E. Right rectus femoris F. Right tensor fasciae latae G. Right gluteus medius H. Right gracilis I. Right vastus lateralis J. Right hamstring complex

question:
For the past couple of months, I’ve been feeling increasingly uneasy about my health. It all started with this awful swelling in my legs that has just gotten worse. I can’t shake the feeling that something is wrong. Along with that, I’ve been having these mild stomach aches that come and go, but what really worries me is the fatigue. I seem to be tired all the time, and I lost about 3.2 kg without even trying. 

To top it all off, I noticed blood in my urine a few times, which is really alarming. I haven't had any chest pain or trouble breathing, so I keep trying to convince myself that maybe it’s nothing serious. But when I went to the doctor, they found some tenderness in my abdomen, especially on the right side, and they mentioned the swelling in my legs was pretty significant.

They did some tests on my urine. Thankfully, they didn't find protein, but the blood was concerning. I just can’t help but feel anxious about what all this means. I keep wondering if it could be something like kidney problems or worse. I really hope I find out soon what’s going on because this uncertainty is making me feel so uneasy.
options: A. Renal vein thrombosis B. Congestive heart failure C. Acute glomerulonephritis D. Renal-cell carcinoma E. Membranous nephropathy F. Nephrotic syndrome G. Immunoglobulin A nephropathy H. IgA nephropathy I. Polycystic kidney disease J. Renal-vein thrombosis

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that's been creeping up on me lately. It all started when my mom expressed her worries about my eating habits. Over the past four months, I’ve lost about 4 kilograms, and honestly, I just don’t feel like eating anymore. My appetite has completely vanished, and I’ve noticed that I’m not interested in food at all. 

On top of that, my grades have been slipping, and there’s been so much tension with my parents about what my future looks like. I feel like I’m constantly on edge, and I can’t seem to relax. I’ve been more restless than ever, and it’s really starting to take a toll on me. 

To make matters worse, I found out there’s a family history of thyroid issues from my grandmother. I’ve been sexually active with a couple of partners, but I haven’t been consistent with protection, which adds another layer of anxiety. 

During my recent physical exam, the doctor noticed my pulse was a bit fast, and I have these fine tremors in my hands. They’re going to do some testing, but I can't help but worry about what’s really going on with me. I just hope that whatever it is, it can be figured out soon.
options: A. Perform psychiatric evaluation for eating disorders B. Measure TSH, fT3, fT4 C. Order complete blood count and metabolic panel D. Measure cortisol levels E. Measure serum electrolytes F. Obtain toxicology screening G. Order abdominal ultrasound H. Obtain brain MRI I. Perform ECG and cardiac workup J. Screen for autoimmune disorders

question:
I can't shake the anxiety that's been building up over the past week. As a 22-year-old marathon trainee, I was really pushing myself, but then I suddenly developed this intense lumbosacral back pain. It got so bad that I had to stop training altogether, which is incredibly frustrating and worrying for me. The pain is mostly on my right side, and it feels tight in my lower back and buttock. 

Every time I try to transition from sitting to standing, it gets worse. I can't help but think about what might be going on with my body. I’ve read about possible diagnoses, and I can’t help but wonder if it’s something serious. Could it be a nerve issue? I keep replaying the movements in my head, thinking if I had pushed myself too hard or if I did something wrong during my training. 

Now, I'm just trying to figure out what to do next. I know I need to see a doctor soon, but the uncertainty is really weighing on me. Will I be able to get back to training? What if this persists? I just hope it isn’t anything that could keep me from running again for a long time.
options: A. Positive straight leg raise test with radicular symptoms B. Positive FAIR test with sciatic nerve compression symptoms C. Positive piriformis stretch test with contralateral hip rotation D. Positive Thomas test and positive pelvic shift test to the ipsilateral side as the dysfunction E. Positive Patrick's test with ipsilateral sacroiliac joint tenderness F. Negative Thomas test and negative pelvic shift test G. Positive Thomas test and positive pelvic shift test to the contralateral side of the dysfunction H. Positive Ober test with limited hip adduction I. Tender point lateral to ASIS J. Positive FABER test with decreased range of motion bilaterally

question:
I can’t shake the fear I felt when I was found at the shelter, barely responsive. It all happened so fast—I remember being in a daze, unable to piece things together. I’ve struggled with intravenous drug use for a while now, but I never thought it would lead me to such a dire situation. The paramedics arrived, and I could hear them talking about my low blood pressure and rapid heart rate, but I couldn’t respond. 

I felt cold, and the world around me seemed blurred. They pumped fluids into me, but I still felt weak and out of it. I had these painful abscesses on my arms, and someone mentioned a heart murmur, whatever that meant. Suddenly, I understood I was in serious trouble when they started to intubate me. The panic set in as I realized I couldn't breathe on my own. 

Even after they put me under, my blood pressure just kept dropping. I felt like I was spiraling, and I couldn’t help but worry about what would happen next. They finally stabilized me with some steroids, but I can’t shake the feeling of dread. What went wrong that led me here? Will I make it out of this? I’m so scared.
options: A. Fentanyl B. Cisatracurium C. Propofol D. Atracurium E. Etomidate F. Ketamine G. Rocuronium H. Vecuronium I. Midazolam J. Succinylcholine

question:
I can hardly believe what’s been happening to me over the past three months. It started with this persistent constipation that just wouldn’t go away, and then I began feeling incredibly fatigued, almost like I was dragging myself through each day. I also noticed muscle weakness that made simple tasks feel daunting. On top of that, I’ve been drinking water like there’s no tomorrow, and I’m running to the bathroom constantly. 

I’m 30 years old and already managing hypertension with amlodipine and bipolar disorder with lithium, so I’ve been worried about how all these symptoms could be connected. My blood pressure seems stable, but I can’t shake this feeling that something isn’t right. My weight has crept up, and I’m feeling more anxious than ever. 

I remember my calcium levels were normal a few years back, but now I’m scared that they might be causing these issues. I’ve been trying to stay calm, but the fatigue and weakness are really impacting my life. I’m left wondering what the next step should be and if I should be considering changing my medications or undergoing more tests. I just want to feel like myself again, but I feel lost and overwhelmed. What if this is something serious? What do I do next?
options: A. Increase amlodipine dosage B. Order bone mineral density scan C. Order nuclear imaging of the parathyroid glands D. Initiate treatment with cinacalcet E. Begin treatment with bisphosphonates F. Reduce lithium dosage by 50% G. Measure 24-hour urinary calcium excretion H. Replace lithium with an alternative treatment for bipolar disorder I. Perform ultrasound of the parathyroid glands J. Order genetic testing for MEN1 syndrome

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety that’s been hanging over me lately. I’m 27, and it feels like everything is piling up – stress from home and work is really getting to me. I’ve been moody, and I just can’t seem to find a way to cope. On top of that, I have this history with chronic gastritis, and I dealt with *Helicobacter pylori* before—it feels like my stomach is always in knots. 

Then there’s my kidney issue; I’ve been battling chronic pyelonephritis and kidney stones, and I’m in stage 1 chronic kidney disease. That’s really worrying me. I’ve been smoking for eight years now, and I’ve tried to quit with those nicotine patches, but I just end up more anxious and can’t stick with it. My grandfather was a heavy smoker, and he passed away from lung cancer not long ago; it just makes me feel even more scared about my own health.

I went to see my doctor, and they mentioned possibly prescribing a partial nicotine agonist to help me quit, but now I’m left wondering—what kind of tests do I need to have done before starting this treatment? I can’t help but feel overwhelmed by everything that’s happening.
options: A. Electrocardiogram B. Mini-Mental State Examination C. Pulmonary function testing D. Complete blood count E. Serum potassium levels F. 9-item patient health questionnaire G. Echocardiography H. Liver function tests I. Creatinine J. Fagerström Test for Nicotine Dependence

question:
I can’t shake off this sinking feeling after my recent visit to the doctor for my annual health check. I thought everything was fine—I’ve always felt well, and I don’t take any medications. My menstrual cycle has been regular since I was 10, and my husband and I have been careful with a copper IUD for contraception. But then, during the pelvic exam, the doctor found something concerning.

After the ultrasound, I was told there’s a 3.5-cm mass in the wall of my uterus. Four years ago, when they placed the IUD, everything looked normal. Now, I can’t help but worry about what this means. What if it’s something serious? I’m just 29 and have always been healthy. The doctor mentioned various options for next steps, but my mind is racing. Should I remove the IUD? What if I need a biopsy or worse? 

I keep replaying the doctor’s words in my head, trying to understand what happens next. I feel completely overwhelmed by this uncertainty. I just want to be sure I’m taking the right steps to protect my health, but the thought of what this could lead to is terrifying. I wish I had answers.
options: A. Begin oral contraceptive therapy B. Remove IUD and monitor symptoms C. Remove copper IUD and prescribe oral contraceptive therapy D. Initiate GnRH agonist therapy E. Refer for gynecologic oncology consultation F. Recommend uterine artery embolization G. Order serum CA-125 testing H. Repeat ultrasonography in 6 months I. Perform hysteroscopy with endometrial biopsy J. Schedule immediate myomectomy

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread as I sit in the emergency department, trying to process what just happened. I was in a car accident, and now I’m here, clutching my chest in pain. The left side hurts so much, especially when I take a deep breath, and I can barely catch my breath at all. My heart is racing—130 beats per minute! I can feel the panic rising as I struggle to breathe; my oxygen saturation is only 85% on room air.

The doctors checked me over, and while they didn’t find any penetrating injuries, there’s a nasty bruise on my left chest wall. I can see the concern on their faces as they examine me. I overheard them mention something about my trachea being pushed to the right and how my left side isn’t expanding as it should. 

What’s happening to me? I feel so vulnerable and scared, unsure of what’s next. They’ve got so many options for treatment, but I can’t help but worry about what they’ll decide to do. I just want to feel safe again, to breathe normally without this crushing pain. I hope they act quickly because I really don’t know how much longer I can handle this.
options: A. Administer intravenous fluids B. Place a chest tube C. Administer analgesics and observe D. Obtain an arterial blood gas E. Perform emergency thoracotomy F. Obtain a chest x-ray G. Perform pericardiocentesis H. Perform endotracheal intubation I. Perform needle thoracostomy J. Provide supplemental oxygen

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming feeling of worry as I think back on the last few months. It all started about three months ago when I began noticing a strange weakness in my legs. At first, it was just a little numbness, but it gradually got worse, spreading to my upper legs and even my arms. 

Over the past five days, things have taken a turn for the worse. I’ve been getting these awful headaches, and now I struggle to smile or even talk properly. Drinking water feels like a chore. It’s terrifying. I’ve had chronic hepatitis B and Graves disease for so long, but this feels different—much worse. 

I try to focus on the positive, like my vital signs being normal and the fact that I’m still alert and oriented. But the physical exam left me feeling even more anxious. I have this troubling facial paralysis, and I can barely feel anything in my fingertips and toes. My muscle strength is fading, and my reflexes are barely there. 

What’s going on with me? I keep thinking about what might come next and what my doctor will find during further evaluations. I feel so helpless and scared about what this could mean for my future.
options: A. Reduced serum vitamin B12 levels B. Positive GM1 ganglioside autoantibodies C. Elevated anti-acetylcholine receptor antibodies D. Positive ANA with speckled pattern E. Positive Campylobacter stool culture F. Elevated cerebrospinal fluid protein with normal cell count G. Positive anti-acetylcholine receptor antibodies H. Positive anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies I. Positive Lyme disease serology J. Decreased nerve conduction velocities on electromyography

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry as I think back to my son’s recent wellness visit. He’s just six years old, and while the doctor said he looks healthy, I can’t help but feel something isn’t right. Since his last check-up, I’ve noticed he’s been struggling academically. It’s heartbreaking to hear about the weekly disciplinary actions at school because he can’t seem to control his behavior. His teacher mentioned that he has a hard time understanding instructions and his reading skills are far below where they should be.

What really worries me is an incident where he urinated in class. He just couldn’t express that he needed to go, and I can’t imagine how embarrassing that must have been for him. Although he plays with other kids during recess, he often acts in ways that just feel too immature for his age. 

During the physical exam, the doctor noted he made good eye contact and even smiled, but I noticed he was flapping his arms at times, which I found odd. They did a hearing test, and that came back normal, but I’m left wondering what’s really going on with him. I just feel so lost trying to figure out if he might have something like autism or a learning disability. I can’t help but worry about his future and how he’ll cope with all of this.
options: A. Sensory processing disorder B. Fragile X syndrome C. Specific learning disability D. Global developmental delay E. Childhood apraxia of speech F. Autism spectrum disorder G. Rett syndrome H. Social (pragmatic) communication disorder I. Intellectual disability J. Attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD)

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been building since this evening. Out of nowhere, I lost vision in my left eye, and it’s not just a blur—it’s like a dark curtain has fallen over everything. I’ve never experienced anything like this before, and it’s terrifying. I’m not on any medications and don’t usually deal with health issues, but I’ve had these strange episodes of weakness and numbness in the past that would just go away on their own. 

When I got to the emergency department, I was a bundle of nerves. They checked my vital signs, and everything seemed okay, but I can’t help worrying that something is seriously wrong. The doctors examined me and mentioned some decreased sensation in my left foot, which makes my mind race even more. 

The pain in my eye is sharp, and I can’t help but think about what this could mean. What if this is something really serious? I keep wondering what else could be going on inside my body. I just want answers, but the uncertainty is almost unbearable. What additional problems might I face? I can’t stop thinking about it, and it’s making me feel even more anxious.
options: A. Positive Romberg sign B. Ptosis and diplopia worsening throughout the day C. Ipsilateral loss of proprioception and vibration sensation D. Segmental demyelination on nerve conduction studies E. Bilateral spastic paresis of the lower extremities F. Weakness with repeat exertion G. Contralateral loss of pain and temperature sensation H. Electrical pain with neck flexion I. Decreased deep tendon reflexes in the affected limb J. Hyperreflexia in the lower extremities

question:
I can hardly believe what happened to me today. I found myself in the emergency department with this unbearable pain in my abdomen. It started out as just some discomfort after meals over the past few months, and I thought I could manage it with over-the-counter antacids. But then, just an hour ago, everything changed. The pain got so much worse; it felt like it was radiating all the way to my right shoulder. I was nauseous and even started vomiting—something I’ve never experienced before.

I don’t have a history of surgeries and I’ve been managing my hypertension with amlodipine, but this was different. My temperature was up to 101°F, and my heart was racing at 110 beats per minute. The doctors said my abdomen was rigid and that there was tenderness when they pressed on it. I’m terrified that something serious could be wrong. They mentioned a bunch of tests and diagnostic steps, but I just want to know what’s causing this pain. I keep thinking about my job as a carpenter and how I can’t afford to be out of commission. I feel overwhelmed and anxious about what comes next. What if this is more serious than I realize?
options: A. Blood cultures and broad-spectrum antibiotics B. Serum lipase and amylase testing C. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy (EGD) D. Diagnostic peritoneal lavage E. Abdominal computed tomography (CT) scan F. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the abdomen G. Exploratory laparotomy H. Admission and serial abdominal exams I. Abdominal ultrasound J. Chest radiograph

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. Just the other day, I was taken to the emergency department because I started feeling really confused. The staff at the shelter noticed something was off and insisted I get help. I had this awful headache and my muscles were aching, but when they asked me questions, I couldn’t seem to answer them properly. It was terrifying.

When I got to the hospital, they took my temperature, and it was over 102°F. My heart was racing at 115 beats per minute, and I felt like I could hardly breathe. They examined me and said my knees hurt when they tried to extend them. I felt so weak and vulnerable.

Then they did a lumbar puncture, which I had heard about but never thought I’d actually go through. I was so scared, and now I’m left wondering what’s wrong with me. They mentioned elevated lymphocytes and some protein issues, but I just don’t understand what that means for my health. With my HIV status, I can’t help but worry about the worst possible outcomes. I just want answers and to feel better. What could be causing all of this?
options: A. Listeria monocytogenes B. Varicella-zoster virus C. Epstein-Barr virus D. Herpes simplex virus E. Cytomegalovirus F. Neisseria meningitidis G. Cryptococcus H. West Nile virus I. Mycobacterium tuberculosis J. Toxoplasma gondii

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been growing inside me. At just 25 years old, I went to see a doctor because I’ve never had a period—primary amenorrhea, they call it. I’ve never had any serious medical issues before, and I’m not on any medications. To make matters worse, I’m not even sexually active, which feels strange to discuss.

During the examination, I was shocked when the doctor measured my height at 132 cm and my weight at 49 kg. I mean, I’ve always been on the smaller side, but hearing those numbers made everything feel so real. My blood pressure was 125/85, and my heart rate was steady at 80 beats per minute, but then the doctor noticed some concerning features. I have a webbed neck, which I’ve always thought was just part of my look, and my chest is broad with widely spaced nipples. I thought I was developing normally, but it turns out I’m only at Tanner stage 2 for breast and pubic hair development.

What really unsettled me was when the doctor listened to my heart and mentioned an early systolic ejection click. I can’t help but think about what that could mean. Now, I’m left waiting and worrying about what might show up on the echocardiogram. The uncertainty is just overwhelming.
options: A. Bicuspid aortic valve B. Ventricular septal defect C. Tricuspid valve regurgitation D. Atrial septal defect E. Pulmonary valve stenosis F. Hypoplastic left heart syndrome G. Mitral valve prolapse H. Pulmonary stenosis I. Coarctation of the aorta J. Aortic root dilation

question:
I can't shake the feeling of dread as I think back to the last two weeks. It all started with this persistent shortness of breath that just kept getting worse. At first, I brushed it off—maybe it was just age catching up with me—but then the swelling in my legs began. It was alarming to see how noticeably puffy my ankles had become. To top it off, I noticed I had gained about 6.6 pounds, seemingly out of nowhere.

Finally, I couldn’t ignore it any longer and ended up in the emergency department. I felt so vulnerable there, surrounded by the beeping machines and hurried doctors. They listened to my chest and I could hear those crackles they mentioned, which made my heart race. The doctor also found this strange sound near my heart, especially when I was lying on my side. 

I can’t help but feel anxious about all of this. What does it mean? Why is my body reacting this way? I keep thinking about my heart and what could possibly be wrong. The uncertainty is overwhelming, and I just want answers. What is happening to me? I’m so scared.
options: A. Increased left ventricular end-systolic volume B. Left atrial enlargement C. Impaired mitral valve closure D. Decreased cardiac output E. Increased left atrial pressure F. Decreased left-ventricular filling pressure G. Decreased left myocardial compliance H. Increased pulmonary capillary wedge pressure I. Decreased stroke volume J. Impaired diastolic relaxation

question:
I can’t shake the worry that something is seriously wrong with my feet. For the past two weeks, I’ve been dealing with this nagging pain in both of them. It all started the morning after a cross-country competition. I remember thinking I felt fine after the race, but then, suddenly, the pain hit me like a ton of bricks. 

At first, it seemed manageable, especially if I took a break. But as the day wore on, it just got worse, and no amount of rest or ice seemed to help. I’m starting to feel really anxious because I’ve always been active, and now I can barely run without wincing. 

When I went to the clinic, they did a check-up. My vital signs were normal, and I thought that was a good sign. But then they examined my feet and found that they were tender all over the bottom, especially near the metatarsals, but there was no specific spot that hurt the most. They ruled out any severe issues like flat feet or tendon problems, which made me feel a bit relieved, but I couldn’t help but feel uneasy when they took X-rays and everything came back normal. 

Now, I’m just left wondering what’s causing this pain. I really hope it’s nothing serious, but the uncertainty is eating at me.
options: A. Sesamoiditis B. Morton's neuroma C. Lateral longitudinal arch somatic dysfunction D. Plantar fasciitis E. Metatarsal stress fractures F. Tarsal tunnel syndrome G. Peroneal tendinopathy H. Flexor hallucis longus tendinitis I. Medial tibial stress syndrome J. Transverse arch somatic dysfunction

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety after our recent visit to the doctor. My son, who’s just 11, went in for a routine well-child examination before starting preschool and sports. I thought it would be a straightforward check-up, but then I remembered what his previous pediatrician had mentioned about a spinal curve. That thought alone had me on edge, but what I heard during the examination made it even worse.

The doctor found some concerning things during the physical exam. He pointed out that my son has enhanced thoracic kyphosis and noticed that his right scapula was positioned strangely, even when he was standing straight. I felt my heart drop when the doctor mentioned the prominent rib cage hump on the right side when my son bent forward. It’s all so overwhelming.

I keep replaying the doctor's words in my mind, trying to understand what it all means. I mean, could this be something serious? What if it’s a type of scoliosis? The medical jargon about the spinal motion patterns is still swirling in my head, making it hard to focus on anything else. I just want to make sure my son is okay and that we’re not missing anything crucial. The worry is really starting to weigh on me.
options: A. Dextroscoliosis; freedom of motion is sidebent to the right and rotated to the left B. Dextroscoliosis; concavity of the curve is to the left and vertebrae rotated to the right C. Levoscoliosis; concavity of the curve is to the right and vertebrae rotated to the left D. Levoscoliosis; the curve is sidebent to the right and rotated to the left E. Levoscoliosis; freedom of motion is sidebent to the right and rotated to the left F. Levoscoliosis; restricted with extension and convexity of the curve is to the left G. Dextroscoliosis; restricted with flexion and concavity of the curve is to the left H. Levoscoliosis; freedom of motion is sidebent to the left and rotated to the right I. Dextroscoliosis; convexity of the curve is to the left and vertebrae rotated to the left J. Dextroscoliosis; convexity of the curve is to the right and vertebrae rotated to the left

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of anxiety since my visit to the doctor. At 62, I’ve been dealing with some troubling urinary issues—mostly dribbling and needing to go frequently, which is just so embarrassing. My medical history isn’t great either; I’ve been managing hypertension and dyslipidemia for years now. 

During the examination, the doctor found a firm 1-centimeter nodule on my prostate, and I can’t help but worry about what that means. They mentioned the prostate-specific antigen level was elevated, and I learned that it might indicate something serious. I’ve read about the prevalence of prostate cancer in men my age, and the thought of being part of that statistic has me on edge. 

I keep replaying the conversation in my mind, especially the part about how the sensitivity and specificity of the tests can be high, but that doesn’t make it any easier to digest. I feel trapped in this whirlwind of what-ifs, trying to figure out the likelihood of having prostate cancer, and it’s just overwhelming. I know I need to find out more, but the uncertainty is eating at me. I just want to know what’s really going on and what the future holds.

I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety as I sit here reflecting on my recent health issues. I’m 41 years old and have already been through three pregnancies, all resulting in uncomplicated cesarean births. But lately, things have taken a worrying turn. 

My menstrual bleeding has become excessively heavy. I mean, I go through a pad every hour for the first three days of my cycle, and the cramping is unbearable—sometimes reaching a 9 out of 10 on my worst days. It’s hard to believe this is normal. My periods are regular, coming every 25 to 26 days and lasting about eight days, but I dread the onset each time. 

I’ve also been experiencing deep pain during intercourse, which adds to my distress. During my recent visit to the doctor, they performed a pelvic exam that revealed a boggy uterus, and honestly, that description alone sent my heart racing. They mentioned mild anemia and ordered a pelvic ultrasound, but I can’t stop worrying about what they might find. 

I keep replaying the doctor’s words in my mind, thinking of the possible outcomes. I know I need answers, but the uncertainty is overwhelming. What if it’s something serious? I just want to be okay, for myself and my family.
options: A. Multiple hyperechoic foci with posterior shadowing in the myometrium B. A focal hypoechoic lesion with irregular borders in the endometrium C. Endometrial polypoid structures with central vascularity D. Thickened endometrial stripe with irregular vascularity E. Symmetrical, homogeneous endometrial thickening F. Asymmetrical, irregular endometrial thickening G. A large, circular hypoechoic structure within the myometrium with posterior shadowing H. Diffuse myometrial calcifications with acoustic shadowing I. Symmetrical, homogeneous myometrial thickening J. Circular anechoic structures within the myometrium without posterior shadowing

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry after what happened two days ago. I had a fall, and I landed hard on my extended right hand. Ever since, my right forearm has been throbbing with pain. It’s been two days, and no matter how much ibuprofen I take, it barely eases the discomfort. I’ve always kept an active lifestyle, so this sudden pain is really unsettling for me.

I decided it was time to seek medical attention. The doctor examined my arm, and while he noted that my elbow seemed normal, he mentioned that I had limited supination. That made me anxious—what could that mean? I was relieved to hear that the X-rays of my hand and elbow didn’t show any abnormalities, but I still can’t help but feel uneasy about what’s going on.

I just want to know why this is happening and how I can get back to my normal routine. It was terrifying to think something might be seriously wrong, especially since my medical history is unremarkable. I’m trying to stay positive, but I can’t shake the feeling that I need answers soon. What could this pain be? I just wish I could feel like myself again.
options: A. Medial epicondylitis B. Radioulnar synostosis C. Posterior radial head dysfunction D. Olecranon bursitis E. Anterior radial head dysfunction F. Cubital tunnel syndrome G. Annular ligament sprain H. Interosseous membrane dysfunction I. Lateral epicondylitis J. Radial tunnel syndrome

question:
I can hardly believe what I’ve been going through these past five months. It started with this constant urge to urinate, which quickly became overwhelming. I’d find myself needing to rush to the bathroom, only to experience small leaks before I could even get there. It’s been incredibly embarrassing and frustrating. I never thought I’d have to deal with something like this at my age.

I don’t have any major health issues, and I’m not on any medications, so I really didn’t understand what was happening to my body. I finally decided to visit my primary care provider, hoping for some answers. They suggested I try oxybutynin, and thankfully, it seemed to help a bit. But I can’t shake this feeling of worry about what could be causing these symptoms. 

I’ve read about different conditions that could be behind this, like neurogenic bladder or overactive bladder syndrome, and I can't help but feel anxious about what it might mean for my health. I just want to understand what’s happening and hope it’s nothing serious. The uncertainty is really weighing on me. I keep thinking about what ifs, and it’s hard to focus on anything else.
options: A. Neurogenic bladder B. Prostatic hyperplasia C. Detrusor overactivity D. Urethral stricture E. Acute cystitis F. Diabetes mellitus G. Prostatitis H. Overactive bladder syndrome I. Interstitial cystitis J. Bladder outlet obstruction

question:
I can't shake off this overwhelming worry I've been feeling lately. I’m a 27-year-old college student, and for as long as I can remember, I've dealt with bone and muscle aches. But recently, it’s like they’ve intensified overnight. I try to stay active and eat well, but it feels like everything is falling apart, especially with finals looming over me. The stress is unreal, and I’ve even started experiencing some diarrhea, which adds to my anxiety.

I went to see my primary care doctor, hoping for some answers. I’ve been on acyclovir for my HSV, but honestly, it hasn’t helped much. During the exam, the doctor found that I have reduced strength in all my limbs, and they noted some non-specific tenderness. It's tough to think about what this all means. 

I can’t help but feel like there’s something seriously wrong. The doctor mentioned some lab results but didn’t go into detail, and I’m left here wondering what could be the cause of these symptoms. I’ve heard of conditions like vitamin deficiencies and malabsorption, and I can’t help but think, what if it’s something serious? I just want to feel normal again, but the uncertainty is eating away at me.
options: A. Hyperphosphatemia from excessive dietary intake of phosphate B. Vitamin D deficiency due to limited sun exposure C. Malabsorption due to celiac disease D. A genetic mutation affecting calcium-sensing receptors E. Hypoalbuminemia leading to pseudohypocalcemia F. Anaphylaxis when receiving a transfusion G. Sleep deprivation H. Chronic kidney disease with secondary hyperparathyroidism I. Rash over the metacarpophalangeal joints J. A history of anxiety/depression

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry since my son has been dealing with this persistent wet cough for the past six weeks. It’s especially troubling because it seems to get worse every morning, and despite trying treatments like albuterol, prednisone, and even cetirizine, nothing seems to help. 

He hasn’t choked on anything, thank goodness, and there are no signs of fever or weight loss. It’s just this relentless cough that keeps us both on edge. I’ve checked, and no one else in our household is sick, so it’s not contagious at least. His immunizations are all up to date, which is a relief, but there’s still this nagging feeling that something isn’t right.

When we went to the doctor, his temperature was slightly elevated, and his heart rate was a bit fast. The doctor listened to his lungs and heard rhonchi, but everything else seemed normal. Still, I can’t help but feel a sense of dread. What if it’s something serious? 

I’ve been trying to figure out what the next steps should be. Should we do more testing, or try a different medication? I just want to make sure he gets the right diagnosis before it gets worse. It’s tough to see him like this, and I’m worried about what the future holds if we can’t find an answer soon.
options: A. Perform spirometry with bronchodilator testing B. Prescribe a course of oral amoxicillin-clavulanate C. Initiate a trial of inhaled corticosteroids D. Order a mycoplasma IgM antibody test E. Perform a sweat chloride test F. Obtain a nasopharyngeal culture for viral pathogens G. Refer for allergy testing H. Order bronchoscopy I. Prescribe a trial of proton pump inhibitors J. Obtain chest CT

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of worry that’s been creeping in for the past eight months. It all started when my periods became excruciating. I’m 36, a mother of two, and I thought I was managing just fine. But now, I’m using 6 to 8 pads every day during my 5 to 6-day periods, which seem to come like clockwork every 28 days. The heavy flow and intense pelvic cramps start two days before my period, and despite taking naproxen, nothing seems to help. 

To make matters worse, my symptoms have been so debilitating that I’ve lost my job as a janitor. I can’t believe it’s come to this. I had a tubal sterilization a year ago, and I've had two uncomplicated deliveries. I’m in a loving relationship with my spouse, and I try to take care of myself with a daily multivitamin, but I also have a smoking history that haunts me. 

After numerous tests, including ultrasounds and blood work, the doctors said everything looks normal, but I can’t stop worrying. What’s causing this pain and suffering? I feel stuck, and I just want to find a solution. Now, I’m left wondering what the next step should be. I am desperate for relief and anxious about what this all means for my health and my life.
options: A. Hysterectomy B. Progesterone-only pills C. Diagnostic hysteroscopy D. Levonorgestrel-releasing intrauterine device E. Gonadotropin-releasing hormone agonist therapy F. Uterine artery embolization G. Endometrial ablation H. Combined oral contraceptives I. Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) J. Dilation and curettage

question:
I can't shake the fear that gripped me just two hours ago when I suddenly felt an excruciating headache hit me out of nowhere. It was unlike anything I’ve ever experienced, and it left me feeling completely unsteady. I was also alarmed to notice that the left side of my body seemed to be going numb and weak. I tried to move, but it felt like my muscles were failing me. 

After a frantic call to my daughter, I found myself in the emergency department, surrounded by doctors who were clearly concerned. My heart was racing, and my blood pressure felt uncomfortably high. They asked me a lot of questions, and I tried to stay calm, but honestly, my mind was racing with worries about my health. I’ve dealt with hypertension, atrial fibrillation, and diabetes for years, but this felt different—much scarier.

The doctors examined me and mentioned something about my eyes not reacting properly and the weakness on my left side. They seemed particularly worried about my neurological symptoms. I could hear them discussing my condition, and I felt a wave of panic wash over me. What was happening to me? I could only hope they would figure it out quickly, but deep down, I was terrified of what they might find.
options: A. Right corona radiata B. Right basal ganglia C. Right temporal lobe D. Right midbrain E. Right internal capsule F. Right putamen G. Right thalamus H. Right cerebellum I. Right frontal lobe J. Pons

question:
I can hardly shake off the fear that gripped me when I found myself in the emergency department. At 86 years old, I’ve never been one to shy away from a little dizziness now and then, but this was different. It all started about four hours before I arrived at the hospital. I felt this unsettling vertigo, as if the ground beneath me was shifting, and I had a terrifying sensation like I was going to fall at any moment. 

Even though the spinning had calmed down a bit, I still felt this strong pull to the right. I could barely walk straight and was worried about what was happening to me. The doctors took my vital signs, and I remember feeling a slight relief when they told me my blood pressure and oxygen levels were okay, but that didn’t ease my mind entirely.

During the physical exam, they noticed I had trouble moving my right limbs and couldn’t really feel pain or temperature on the right side of my face and the left side of my body. That was alarming. They did a CT scan of my head and thankfully found no bleeding, but I can't help but wonder what else could be going on. I’m scared about what might happen next and what these symptoms could mean for me. What if there’s something really wrong?
options: A. Dysarthria with hoarse voice B. Hemianopia C. Ipsilateral facial numbness D. Horner's syndrome E. Skew deviation of eyes F. Hemiparesis G. Nystagmus with fast phase to the right H. Absent gag reflex I. Contralateral facial droop J. Deviated tongue

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that washed over me when I brought my one-year-old foster son to the emergency department. Since this morning, he’s been acting strangely—l lethargic and distant, which is not like him at all. As soon as we got there, the doctors took one look at him and I could see their concern growing. 

They mentioned the smell of alcohol and cigarettes clinging to him, and I felt my heart drop. The bruises on his shoulders, head, and buttocks were alarming, and I couldn’t understand how they got there. His left leg seemed stiff, and the doctors said something about his eyes showing retinal hemorrhages. 

I could barely focus on everything they were saying with my heart racing. I just wanted to take him home, but then I felt the tension in the room rise when I expressed my impatience. When they suggested that something terrible might be happening—possibly abuse—I felt anger surge within me. I didn’t want to believe it, but I also knew I had to protect him.

The doctors seemed to be debating next steps, and I was left with this overwhelming worry. What if they couldn’t help him? What if I couldn’t protect him? I just wanted to make everything okay again, but I felt so helpless.
options: A. Report the mother to the police B. Perform a skeletal survey to assess for additional injuries C. Perform a lumbar puncture to evaluate for meningitis D. Administer intravenous antibiotics and fluids E. Obtain a court order for emergency medical treatment F. Request an urgent CT scan and call neurosurgery G. Order a toxicology screen to evaluate for ingested substances H. Obtain informed consent for surgery I. Protect the child from the mother J. Contact child protective services

question:
I can’t shake the worry that’s been creeping in since I started feeling this dull pain in my lower back four days ago. It all began after I spent an entire day gardening, which seemed harmless at the time. But now, the nagging ache feels like it’s radiating down my left leg, stopping right at my knee. It’s strange—I can’t pinpoint what made it worse, but it’s been hard to ignore.

I’ve never dealt with back pain like this before, and it’s so unsettling. I went to see a doctor, hoping for some clarity, but the examination left me feeling more anxious. They found tenderness in my lumbar region, but thankfully, the straight leg test came back negative. Still, the diagnosis of sacral somatic dysfunction left me a bit rattled. The doctor mentioned something about my sacrum being rotated, which sounded complicated and concerning.

I can’t help but wonder what other issues might be lurking. Will I need more tests? What if this doesn’t resolve on its own? I’m just trying to stay positive, but the uncertainty is really weighing on me. I keep thinking about what might be next, and it's hard to feel at ease when my body feels so out of whack.
options: A. Compensatory L4 rotation to the left. B. Positive Patrick's test on the right side. C. Restricted sacroiliac joint mobility on the right. D. L5 is rotated to the right and sidebent to the left. E. L5 is rotated to the left and sidebent to the left. F. Increased lumbar lordosis with forward bending. G. A positive standing flexion test on the right. H. A positive seated flexion test on the left. I. L5 is rotated to the right and sidebent to the right. J. Decreased sacral base movement on the right during gait.

question:
I can't shake off this nagging worry that something is seriously wrong. I’m a 42-year-old truck driver, and lately, I’ve been dealing with this persistent low back soreness that seems to get worse the longer I’m on the road. It’s like a dull ache that just won’t go away, and it’s making every long-distance drive feel unbearable.

So, I finally decided to see a doctor, hoping for some answers. During the examination, the doctor performed a few tests, and I could see the concern in their eyes as they noted that my seated flexion test came back positive on the left side. I didn’t fully understand what that meant, but it didn’t sound good. They also mentioned something about a negative spring test and that my sacral sulcus was deep on the left while the other side seemed off too.

I overheard them talking about how my L5 vertebra was tilted to the right, and all this medical jargon made my anxiety spike. I can’t help but feel overwhelmed—what if I have a serious issue with my back? I’m worried that this could affect my job, my life, everything. I just want to know what’s going on and how to fix it before it gets worse.
options: A. Sacral base anterior dysfunction B. Bilateral sacral flexion C. Left-on-left forward sacral torsion D. Unilateral sacral extension on the right E. Left-on-right backward sacral torsion F. Unilateral sacral flexion on the left G. Sacral base posterior dysfunction H. Bilateral sacral extension I. Right-on-left backward sacral torsion J. Right-on-right forward sacral torsion

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry about my health lately. I’m 52, and I’ve been working as a sandblaster for the city for years. Over the past few months, I’ve noticed my breathing getting worse—there's this persistent shortness of breath that just won’t go away. It’s been so frustrating, especially with this nagging, dry cough that doesn’t produce anything. I keep thinking, is this normal?

Aside from this, I haven’t had any other health issues, and I don’t take any medications. I do have a couple of beers after work, which I thought was just a way to unwind. But now, I’m starting to wonder if that’s contributing to how I feel. I went to see a doctor, and while my vital signs were normal, that didn’t ease my mind. The physical exam didn’t show anything significant either, but I can’t help but feel something is off.
