I had a spirometry test, and they mentioned something about an elevated FEV1/FVC ratio, but I’m not sure what that means for me. I keep thinking about what could be wrong, especially when I consider the different possible lung conditions. I just hope it’s nothing serious. The uncertainty is weighing heavily on me. What if it’s something I can’t handle?
options: A. Bilateral hilar adenopathy with egg-shell calcification B. Nodular opacities and hilar lymph node calcification of the upper lobes C. Ground-glass opacities with peripheral distribution in both lungs D. Centrilobular emphysema with bullae formation E. Reticular bilateral opacities of the lower lobes F. Honeycombing pattern of the upper lobes G. Diffuse interstitial infiltrates with pleural thickening H. Small bilateral opacities throughout both lungs sparring the apices and the bases I. Upper lobe fibrosis with traction bronchiectasis J. Small, rounded nodular opacities of the upper lobes

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread ever since I started experiencing this relentless fatigue. It’s not just that; I’ve also noticed intermittent bloody stools, which is terrifying. And on top of everything, I’ve been itching like crazy. I finally decided to go to the doctor, hoping to understand what’s going on.

At 32 years old, I thought I’d be in great health, but now it feels like my body is betraying me. The blood tests revealed that my hemoglobin is low, and my liver enzymes are alarmingly high. It was hard to process the fact that my liver is not functioning well. They did an ultrasound of my abdomen, and thankfully, there was no dilation in my bile ducts, but I can’t help but worry about what’s going on inside me.

With all these symptoms and abnormal results, I’m left feeling anxious and confused. The doctors talked about more tests, but I’m terrified of what they might find. I keep thinking about the implications of liver issues and what might be next. Am I facing something serious? What if it’s something I can’t handle? I just want to feel normal again, and I can’t shake this overwhelming worry.
options: A. Serum ceruloplasmin level B. Liver biopsy C. FibroScan (transient elastography) D. Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy E. Abdominal CT with contrast F. Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography G. Fecal occult blood test H. Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography I. Hepatic venous pressure gradient measurement J. Colonoscopy

question:
I can hardly believe what happened to me. Just 20 minutes ago, I was shot in the abdomen. I remember the chaos, the pain hitting me like a wave, and then I was in the emergency department, feeling so disoriented. I was conscious, but my heart was racing at 102 beats a minute. I could hardly catch my breath, and my mind was spiraling with fear.

When I got there, the doctors were assessing me. I could hear them talking about my wounds—one on the right side of my abdomen, just above my belly button, and another near my back. They looked worried, and I felt my own anxiety spike. I could see the concern in their eyes as they examined me for any signs of severe damage. Thankfully, I could still breathe normally, but myabdomen felt tender, and I was terrified of what that might mean.

As they started IV fluids, I couldn’t shake the worry from my mind. What if things got worse? I thought about the options they had to manage my injury. Would they need to perform surgery? Or could they just monitor me? I kept imagining the worst-case scenarios, and it made my heart race even faster. The doctors were discussing next steps, and I felt so helpless lying there, just wanting to know what would happen next. Every second felt like an eternity, and I couldn't help but wonder if I was going to be okay.
options: A. Observation with serial abdominal exams B. Angiography of the abdominal vessels C. Diagnostic laparoscopy D. Diagnostic peritoneal lavage E. Exploratory thoracotomy F. Administration of broad-spectrum antibiotics prior to imaging G. Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma (FAST) H. Placement of a nasogastric tube followed by abdominal X-ray I. Immediate laparotomy J. CT scan of the abdomen

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. It all started yesterday afternoon when I was lifting a heavy box from the ground. I felt a sharp pain in my lower back, and now it’s morphed into this constant dull ache that just won’t go away. I’ve never had any significant health issues before, so this is really worrying me.

I went to see a doctor because the pain seems to be getting worse. During the examination, the doctor noticed some things that sounded serious. Apparently, my L5 segment shows some abnormal sidebending and rotation. I just kept thinking, “What does this mean for me?” The doctor pointed out a deep left sacral sulcus and a posterior right inferior lateral angle—terms I don’t fully understand but sound alarming.

As I sat there, I couldn’t help but wonder what the right diagnosis could be. I’m feeling anxious about how this might affect my life, my ability to work, and just my general well-being. I just want this pain to go away and to know what’s actually happening to my back. What if it’s something serious? I can’t help but feel a cloud of worry hanging over me.
options: A. Left on left sacral torsion B. Posterior sacral counternutation C. Anterior sacral nutation D. Right unilateral extension E. Bilateral sacral flexion F. Left unilateral flexion G. Right on right sacral torsion H. Right on left sacral torsion I. Bilateral sacral extension J. Left on right sacral torsion

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of panic that washed over me during the game. I play college football, and everything was going fine until that collision. One moment, I was running, and the next, I found myself on the ground—completely out. I briefly lost consciousness, and I can’t even remember what happened right before it. I was wearing my helmet, so I thought I’d be okay, but the worry crept in as I tried to get my bearings.

When I got to the emergency department, I was still feeling a bit dazed. They checked me out about 45 minutes after the hit. My heart rate was steady, and I could breathe just fine, but I couldn’t shake the unease. I mean, how could I forget what happened just before? I was scared that maybe I had done some real damage.

The doctors were thorough, assessing my neurological function, which thankfully came back normal. But now I’m left wondering: Was my initial loss of consciousness enough to warrant imaging? What if something is seriously wrong? I feel fine now, but the fear of lingering issues keeps gnawing at me. I just hope I didn’t make a mistake by not getting a CT or MRI to be sure. What if I miss something crucial?
options: A. Normal neurologic findings during examination B. Inability to remember events that happened 40 minutes before the collision C. A Glasgow Coma Scale score of 14 upon initial evaluation D. Nausea without vomiting following the collision E. Absence of helmet damage after the collision F. Persistent headache for 30 minutes post-collision G. Initial loss of consciousness lasting one minute H. Vomiting once after the collision I. Photophobia J. Dizziness lasting 15 minutes post-collision

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of dread since we got the call about our one-week-old daughter. The state’s newborn screening laboratory suggested there might be something wrong, specifically a possible medium-chain acyl-coenzyme A dehydrogenase (MCAD) deficiency. I remember when she was born, weighing 2900 grams, and now she’s down to 2880 grams. It worries me to think about her weight loss, even if the doctors say it’s normal for newborns.

She seems to be breastfeeding well every 2 to 3 hours, and I’m relieved she’s producing eight to ten wet diapers daily. But I can’t help but feel anxious. We haven’t noticed any signs like poor feeding, vomiting, or lethargy, but what if something’s brewing under the surface? There’s no family history of metabolic disorders, which is a slight comfort, but it doesn’t erase my concerns.

During the examination, the doctor said she appeared normal and didn’t have any detectable issues like hepatomegaly. Still, I keep wondering what we should do next. Should we be doing more tests? Is there something we should change in her feeding? I just want to make sure she’s healthy and safe. It feels overwhelming, and I can’t help but worry about what the future holds for her.
options: A. Order plasma acylcarnitine profile and continue current feeding regimen B. Recommend adjunctive feeding with dextrose dissolved in water twice daily, and arrange confirmatory testing C. Switch to formula feeding exclusively and schedule weekly weight checks D. Start supplementation with medium-chain triglyceride formula and monitor weight gain E. Initiate treatment with cornstarch, and arrange for confirmatory testing F. Instruct the parents to have the child return for evaluation if she develops poor feeding, vomiting, lethargy, or hypotonia. G. Schedule an outpatient follow-up appointment within one week with the primary care physician H. Repeat the newborn screening I. Refer the child to the emergency department for further evaluation with consultation from a metabolic specialist J. Begin carnitine supplementation and arrange for genetic counseling

question:
I can’t believe what just happened. My son, who’s only 12, fell while playing and came home with a swollen, painful knee that was bright red. It looked terrible! I rushed him to the emergency department, my heart racing the whole way. He’s never had anything like this before, and I couldn’t help but worry. 

As we waited, I remembered that he has a history of nosebleeds, which always made me uneasy. But joint swelling? That was new. I started to panic when I thought about the medication mix-up that could have happened. I give anticoagulants to his grandfather daily, mixing them in his milk, and I just kept thinking—what if something went wrong? 

To make matters worse, I recalled that several of my brothers had bleeding disorders, but we never really knew what they were. I felt so helpless. The doctors did some tests, and I overheard them discussing elevated bleeding times and PTT results. I couldn’t understand all the medical jargon, but every word made my stomach churn. 

What if this was something serious? I kept wondering what could be causing this abnormal PTT. I just want to know he’s going to be okay. I can’t shake this feeling of dread as I wait for answers.
options: A. Mutation in factor VIII B. Vitamin K deficiency C. Deficiency of factor IX D. Mutation in carrying protein E. Deficiency of factor XI F. Impaired fibrinogen synthesis G. Acquired hemophilia due to autoantibodies H. Antibodies to factor VIII I. Deficiency of von Willebrand factor J. Liver disease-induced coagulopathy

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming feeling of exhaustion. As a 35-year-old mechanic, I’ve always been able to keep up with my family and job, but lately, it feels impossible. I’ve gained about 10 pounds without any changes in my appetite, and I’ve been struggling with constipation, which is just adding to my stress. 

What worries me most is this persistent fatigue that makes it hard to focus on my work and family. I even find it difficult to bend my neck sometimes, and that’s just not normal for me. I’ve been smoking for about 10 years, and I do drink occasionally, but I thought I was managing it all fairly well. 

I take just a multivitamin and fish oil, hoping that would be enough. When I went to see a doctor, they noted my temperature was normal, but my pulse was surprisingly slow at 58 beats per minute. They found a mobile, nontender mass in my neck, which really freaked me out. Plus, my skin has been unusually dry, and I’m concerned about the delayed reflexes they mentioned during the exam.

I’m just really worried about what all of this could mean for my health and how it’s affecting my ability to care for my loved ones. I feel like I need answers quickly, but I don’t even know what to think right now.
options: A. Iodine deficiency B. Granulomatous inflammation C. Antithyroid peroxidase antibodies D. Autoimmune thyroiditis E. Impaired sensitivity of nuclear receptor F. TSH receptor mutation G. Deiodinase enzyme deficiency H. Impaired thyroglobulin synthesis I. Defective thyroid hormone transport J. Thyroid hormone binding protein abnormality

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. Just ten days after I returned from Mumbai, India, everything took a turn for the worse. It started so suddenly—a fever that hit 38.9°C, a pounding headache, and body aches that made it hard to move. I even started having loose stools, which was the last thing I needed. 

I remember feeling alarmed as my heart raced at 117 beats per minute and my breathing quickened, too. My blood pressure dropped, and I felt this overwhelming fatigue. It was like my body was fighting something I couldn’t see. 

I thought getting my Covid-19 vaccinations would keep me safe, but when I tested negative, I felt this sinking feeling. What was happening to me? I was admitted to the hospital, and they started me on antibiotics for pneumonia, but instead of getting better, my breathing worsened, and I felt even more exhausted. 

I can’t help but worry about what could be going on. They’ve ruled out malaria for now, but I can’t shake the fear that it might be something worse. What if it’s leptospirosis or dengue? I just want answers and a way to start feeling better. The uncertainty is eating away at me, and I’m left anxious about what steps they’ll take next.
options: A. Start empirical treatment for leptospirosis B. Order serological testing for dengue fever C. Perform a computed tomography (CT) scan of the chest to evaluate for pulmonary embolism D. Order a stool culture to evaluate for enteric bacterial pathogens E. Repeat thick and thin smears for malaria F. Order polymerase chain reaction (PCR) testing for chikungunya virus G. Start intravenous corticosteroids for suspected autoimmune disease H. Perform a lumbar puncture to rule out meningitis I. Initiate empiric treatment for typhoid fever J. Order serological testing for yellow fever

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread after what happened just a few hours ago. I was sitting on the couch, relaxing and watching television, when out of nowhere, I felt this sudden vertigo hit me like a ton of bricks. I was so dizzy that I couldn’t even stand up, and then, to make matters worse, I started vomiting. It all unfolded so quickly; I didn't know what was happening.

Just two days ago, I was hiking in New Hampshire, and now I’m in the emergency department, terrified. I’ve been managing my type 2 diabetes for a while, but I’ve never experienced anything like this. I can't help but worry about my history of heart issues, including my previous heart attack and the stents I have.

When the doctors examined me, they pointed out that I had a droop on the left side of my face and that I couldn’t feel anything in my right arm and leg. It’s so frightening to think that something could be seriously wrong. I keep asking myself: What could be causing all of this? Is it something related to my diabetes, or could it be something worse? I just want answers, and I’m feeling so anxious about what might happen next.
options: A. Thrombotic stroke at the anterior inferior cerebellar artery (AICA) B. Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV) C. Cerebellar hemorrhage D. Vestibular neuritis E. Lateral medullary syndrome F. Early disseminated Lyme disease G. Superior cerebellar artery (SCA) occlusion H. Labyrinthine infarction I. Vertebral artery dissection J. Embolic stroke at the posterior inferior cerebellar artery (PICA)

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that washed over me after the car accident. It was just a minor fender bender, but once I got to the emergency department, everything spiraled. They performed a non-contrast CT scan of my abdomen and pelvis, and that’s when they found it—a 2 cm mass in my pancreatic body. I was terrified. They assured me there was no acute trauma, but my mind was racing with all the worst-case scenarios. 

I remember sitting there, waiting for my lab results, and I tried to convince myself that everything would be fine since they said my blood work looked normal. But how can you not worry when something like this comes up? They sent me home with instructions to see my primary care doctor in a week, but that felt like an eternity. 

At my follow-up appointment, I couldn’t focus on anything else. Thankfully, I reported no abdominal pain and the physical exam seemed unremarkable. Yet I still feel this gnawing anxiety about that mass. What’s the next step? I can’t help but wonder what test they will choose to evaluate it further. I just want to know what this all means for my future.
options: A. Fine needle aspiration biopsy B. Positron emission tomography (PET) scan C. Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP) D. Endoscopic ultrasound E. Serum gastrin level F. CEA G. Computed tomography (CT) of the abdomen/pelvis with IV contrast H. CA-125 I. CA 19-9 level J. Serum chromogranin A level

question:
I can’t shake this nagging worry since my follow-up visit two weeks after I had my second baby. I was discharged from the hospital after an uncomplicated delivery, and I thought everything was going smoothly. I’ve been breastfeeding just fine, but I started experiencing this persistent, mild lower back pain right after leaving the hospital. It’s unsettling because I didn’t expect anything like this.

I’m really trying not to panic, but I can’t help it. I don’t have any numbness or tingling, and thankfully no issues with bladder or bowel control, but the pain just won’t go away. When I went to the clinic, the doctor checked me out and said my back has increased lumbar lordosis, which sounds serious. They did some tests, and while I could move my back without much trouble, extending it really made the pain worse. It’s strange—they didn’t find any asymmetry in my sacrum or hips, and some other tests came back negative, which I guess is good, but I still feel uneasy.

I keep wondering what could be causing this discomfort. Is it something serious like a disc issue or just postpartum ligament laxity? I just want to feel normal again and not constantly worry about this pain.
options: A. Pubic symphysis dysfunction B. Pelvic floor muscle weakness C. Left unilateral sacral extension D. Lumbar disc herniation E. Right unilateral sacral flexion F. Bilateral sacral flexion G. Sacroiliac joint hypermobility H. Diastasis recti I. Lumbar facet syndrome J. Postpartum ligamentous laxity

question:
I can’t shake off this overwhelming concern I’ve been feeling since my recent stem-cell transplant. It’s been about 90 days now, and I noticed some strange skin changes that have really freaked me out. I thought everything was going well, but these lesions started appearing, and they don’t seem to fit with what I was prepared for. 

I’ve read that this timing usually points to acute GVHD, but the way my skin looks makes me worry it could be chronic GVHD instead. My mind races with questions about what this could mean for my recovery. I know the doctors are doing their best, but I can’t help but feel anxious about what they might find.

I heard that certain histological findings can help differentiate between acute and chronic GVHD, and I just keep thinking about what they might discover from the biopsy. The idea of hypergranulosis or lymphocytic infiltration keeps popping into my head, and I can’t help but feel a knot in my stomach. What if this is something more serious? I just want to know what’s happening and what I should expect moving forward. The uncertainty is really weighing on me, and I can’t help but feel worried about my health and future.
options: A. Hypergranulosis B. Dyskeratotic keratinocytes C. Diffuse vacuolization in the basal cell layer D. Interface dermatitis E. Epidermal spongiosis F. Satellite cell necrosis G. Apoptotic bodies in the epidermis H. Lymphocytic infiltration of the superficial dermis I. Subepidermal cleft formation J. Perivascular lymphocytic infiltrate

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of dread that’s been hanging over me for the past week. It all started when I noticed this strange milky discharge from my nipples. It only happens when I press on my breasts, but it’s been happening on both sides, and I can’t help but worry. My mom was just diagnosed with breast cancer at 50, and now I’m freaking out that something similar could be happening to me.

I’ve been feeling exhausted lately, too, and some occasional headaches that I thought were just from school stress and lack of sleep. I’ve had no pain or other symptoms, but the thought of breast cancer is constantly in the back of my mind. I’m sexually active and have been on birth control for six months now, so I thought I was managing my health well. 

When I went to see the doctor, they did some tests, and while everything else seemed normal, my prolactin levels came back elevated. I’m just so scared about what this could mean. I don’t know what the next step is, but I can’t help but feel like there’s something seriously wrong. I just want answers, but the uncertainty is eating me up inside. What if it’s something really serious? I can’t stop thinking about it.
options: A. Order CT scan of the head B. Perform breast biopsy C. Repeat prolactin level in macroprolactin-free sample D. Perform mammography and breast ultrasound E. Switch the fluoxetine to sertraline, and then recheck prolactin F. Order magnetic resonance imaging of the pituitary G. Measure serum estradiol levels H. Discontinue oral contraceptive pills and reassess in 4 weeks I. Measure follicle-stimulating hormone and luteinizing hormone levels J. Order genetic testing for BRCA mutations

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of dread as I sit here in the emergency department. It all started just four hours ago with this sharp pain in my left flank. I thought it was just a muscle cramp, but then it spread to my right side, and now it's becoming unbearable. To make matters worse, I noticed blood in my urine and my legs are swelling up. I’ve had membranous nephropathy for the past five months, and I’m on medication for it, but I never expected it to get this bad.

When the doctors checked my vitals, I felt a little relieved that my temperature was normal, but my heart raced at the thought of what could be happening. They examined my abdomen and I could see their concern. The swelling in my legs has me worried sick. I heard them mention something about kidney enlargement during the ultrasound, and I can't help but feel this sinking fear in my stomach.

Just two weeks ago, my kidney function tests were much better, and now it feels like everything is spiraling out of control. I’m terrified of what this could mean for my health. What’s next? I just want answers and hope that whatever is going on can be fixed before it’s too late.
options: A. Intravenous pyelogram B. Renal scintigraphy C. Positron emission tomography (PET) scan D. Renal biopsy E. MR venography F. Kidney function nuclear scan G. CT angiography H. Doppler ultrasonography I. Abdominal CT with contrast J. Retrograde pyelography

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread as I recount the last few days. It all started with an overwhelming fatigue that crept in, leaving me feeling drained. I thought it was just part of my rheumatoid arthritis flare, but then the nausea hit, and I found myself vomiting. This intense abdominal pain in my right upper quadrant made everything worse. I’ve been managing my hypertension and type 2 diabetes with medication, but this felt different—more serious.

I’ve been on rituximab for my arthritis for a month now, hoping it would help after other treatments failed. I take my usual medications, including prednisone and amlodipine, but suddenly I felt like my body was betraying me. I also take acetaminophen for my joint pain and enjoy a couple of glasses of wine on weekends, but did I overdo it? 

When I finally went to the emergency department, the doctors examined me and noted the changes in my joints, but their concerned faces made my heart race. I keep thinking about the lab results from before and now—everything seems off, especially my liver enzymes. What could be causing this? I’m terrified that this new treatment might be harming me instead of helping. I just want to feel normal again, but I can’t help but worry about what they might find.
options: A. Alcoholic hepatitis B. Nonalcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH) C. Ischemic hepatitis D. Acetaminophen toxicity E. Drug-induced liver injury F. Rituximab-induced hepatotoxicity G. Acute viral hepatitis A H. Hepatitis B virus reactivation I. Autoimmune hepatitis J. Reactivation of latent hepatitis C infection

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety. It’s been a week now, and I’ve been feeling so weak all over. It’s like I have no energy at all, and on top of that, there’s this strange tingling around my mouth and fingertips that just won’t go away. It’s really unsettling. My stomach has been cramping, and I’ve been feeling nauseous too. I’ve been sticking to my gluten-free diet, and I’ve been vegan for two years, so I thought I was doing everything right. 

But then, during a physical exam, the doctor tapped my cheek, and I couldn’t believe what happened next. My mouth and the corner of my nose started twitching involuntarily. That was unnerving. I’ve been diagnosed with celiac disease, and I know it can cause all sorts of issues, but this feels different. 

I’m scared that something is seriously wrong. What if it’s related to my diet? I’ve read that malabsorption can happen with celiac disease, but I never expected it would lead to these symptoms. I just hope it’s nothing too serious. I can’t help but worry that I might not be getting the nutrients I need, especially with my dietary restrictions. I just want to feel normal again.
options: A. Impaired activation of cholecalciferol in the liver B. Decreased levels of renal 1α-hydroxylase C. Decreased dietary intake of ergocalciferol D. Autoimmune destruction of parathyroid glands E. Malabsorption of magnesium due to celiac disease F. Decreased intestinal absorption of ergocalciferol G. Vitamin B12 deficiency due to vegan diet H. Increased renal excretion of calcium I. Primary hypoparathyroidism with secondary vitamin D deficiency J. Insufficient calcium intake from a vegan diet

question:
I’m feeling really anxious right now about my little one. Just two days ago, I noticed they had a low-grade fever, a persistent cough, and a runny nose. It all seemed like a typical cold at first, but then today things took a turn. I woke up to find a rash on their face, chest, and arms that was red and blotchy. I can't shake off the worry; it was alarming to see how it was blanching when I pressed on it. 

To make matters worse, I noticed grayish lesions inside their mouth. I have no idea what to make of it, and I’m scared because I can’t even find their vaccination history. I keep thinking about the possible complications that could arise from this. I’ve read about things like bacterial pneumonia and encephalitis, and the thought of those makes my stomach drop. 

I just want to know what’s going on and if my child is going to be okay. I feel so overwhelmed and helpless right now, and I can’t stop worrying about what could happen next. It’s hard not to think the worst when I see them so unwell. I just hope we can get some answers soon.
options: A. Bronchiolitis obliterans B. Guillain-Barré syndrome C. Bacterial pneumonia D. Acute encephalitis E. Myocarditis F. Acute glomerulonephritis G. Post-infectious thrombocytopenia H. Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis I. Otitis media with effusion J. Orchitis

question:
I can hardly believe what I’ve been going through in the past month. It all started about four weeks ago after I played a game of tennis. At first, I just felt a dull ache in my right arm, but it hasn't gone away, and honestly, it’s getting worse. The pain is mostly in my lateral forearm, and it seems to get a bit better when I lift my shoulder, but that numbness in my right thumb is really worrying me. 

When I finally went to see the doctor, they did some tests. My reflexes seemed okay on the left side, but my right biceps was a little sluggish. I never thought I’d be worried about my thumb going numb like this. They tested my strength, and while I could lift my arm and bend my elbow just fine, my wrist extension was weak. That really scared me—I mean, what if I can’t use my arm properly anymore?

Now I’m just left with so many questions. What could be causing this? Is it something serious like a herniated disc or nerve compression? I can’t help but feel anxious about what the future holds for my arm and how this might affect my daily life. I just want to get answers and find some relief.
options: A. A foraminal disc herniation at C6/7 B. Cervical spondylotic myelopathy causing C6 radiculopathy C. Compression of the posterior interosseous nerve by the proximal edge of supinator D. Brachial plexus neuritis involving the upper trunk E. A paracentral cervical disc herniation at C5/6 F. Compression of the C7 nerve root by an osteophyte G. Radial nerve entrapment at the supinator muscle H. A central cervical disc herniation at C4/5 I. Median nerve compression at the carpal tunnel J. Thoracic outlet syndrome with vascular compromise

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming feeling of dread that’s taken over my life lately. Just last week, everything seemed fine, but then my boyfriend broke up with me, and it felt like my whole world crumbled. I’ve been dealing with this nagging muscle pain that makes even the simplest tasks—like showering, cooking, and cleaning—excruciatingly hard. It’s so frustrating because I had just moved back in with my mom, hoping she could help me through this tough time. She’s been trying to keep me organized and assigns me chores, which is somewhat comforting, but the pain just won't go away.

I went to see my doctor, thinking maybe there was something physically wrong, but everything checked out fine. When the doctor suggested I see a psychiatrist, I felt a wave of panic wash over me. I couldn’t help but question whether they were truly trying to help me or if they thought I was just overreacting. My past struggles with anxiety and bulimia haunt me, and it’s so hard to not feel lost and unsure of my next steps. I’m terrified of what this all means for my future. Why can’t I just get back to feeling like myself again?
options: A. Histrionic B. Dependent C. Obsessive-compulsive D. Narcissistic E. Paranoid F. Borderline G. Antisocial H. Schizoid I. Avoidant J. Passive-aggressive

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread that started when I decided to get a cardiovascular risk evaluation. I’m 26, and with my family history of heart issues—my father had a heart attack at 40 and my brother at 33—I felt it was time to be proactive. Honestly, I don't have any significant health problems, and I don't smoke, but I do drink occasionally. 

When I stepped on the scale, I weighed 77 kg, and my BMI was 25.8, which seemed okay to me. But then, during the examination, the doctor noticed these yellowish plaques in my palms, and I could tell he was concerned. My blood pressure was 116/75, and my heart rate was 84, which didn’t seem alarming, but I couldn’t help but feel uneasy.

Then, I learned about my cholesterol levels. My total cholesterol was way too high at 426, and my LDL was off the charts at 315. I mean, how did this happen? I just felt so overwhelmed. With my family history, these numbers were terrifying. What if I’m on the path to having a heart attack like my dad? I can’t help but think about the implications of all this. I’m just really worried about what this all means for my future.
options: A. Type III hyperlipoproteinemia B. Hypoalphalipoproteinemia C. Familial combined hyperlipidemia D. Dysbetalipoproteinemia E. Hypertriglyceridemia secondary to metabolic syndrome F. Familial hypercholesterolemia G. Familial hypertriglyceridemia H. Lipoprotein lipase deficiency I. Polygenic hypercholesterolemia J. Tangier disease

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread. For the past ten days, I've been dealing with this nagging low back pain that just won't go away. I’ve been training intensely for a major ballet performance, spending up to eight hours a day on my feet, and now I’m worried that I might have pushed myself too hard. It’s so frustrating because I’ve tried everything—acetaminophen, ice packs—yet nothing seems to help. 

I remember being diagnosed with mild scoliosis when I was 15, but I never thought it would come back to haunt me like this. I didn’t even have any trauma or accidents; it just started one day out of the blue. When I went to the emergency department, I hoped for some answers, but the doctors did some examinations that left me feeling even more uneasy. They noticed a shallow left sacral sulcus, and the lumbosacral junction didn’t respond well to pressure. 

What if there’s something seriously wrong? I can't afford to be out of commission right now, especially with the performance coming up. I feel like I’m in a race against time, and I’m just praying it’s nothing too serious. I can’t help but worry about what this could mean for my future in ballet.
options: A. right unilateral sacral flexion B. left unilateral sacral flexion C. piriformis syndrome D. sacral counternutation E. bilateral sacral torsion F. L5-S1 facet syndrome G. left sacroiliac joint dysfunction H. left sacral torsion I. left unilateral sacral extension J. sacral shear dysfunction

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread that’s been haunting me since last week. It all started seven days after I was hospitalized for a heart attack. They performed an angioplasty and placed a stent in my artery, and I thought I was on the mend. But then, out of nowhere, I woke up one night with this sharp pain in my left arm. It was so intense that it jolted me from my sleep. I brushed it off at first, but now my fingers are numb, and I can hardly move my arm at all.

I can’t help but worry. My heart has been a constant concern, especially with my history of high blood pressure and cholesterol. I’m on all these medications—atorvastatin, aspirin, lisinopril, metoprolol, clopidogrel—and I thought they would help me feel better, not worse. When I examined my left arm, it felt cold and looked pale. I tried to check my pulse, but I couldn’t find it. It’s terrifying to think that my muscle strength in that arm has dropped to almost nothing. 

I keep replaying everything in my head, wondering what could be wrong. Is it something serious? I feel so helpless and anxious. I just want answers and to know that I’m going to be okay.
options: A. Iatrogenic brachial arterial injury B. Brachial plexus neuropathy C. Acute aortic dissection D. Stress-induced cardiomyopathy E. Subclavian artery stenosis F. Compartment syndrome G. Ventricular pseudoaneurysm H. Left ventricular mural thrombus I. Post-stent thrombosis J. Postmyocardial infarction syndrome

question:
I can’t shake off this nagging worry that something is seriously wrong with me. For the past three months, I've been dealing with this persistent cough that just won’t go away. It’s dry and nonproductive, and I can’t help but feel anxious about it. I went to the doctor a couple of weeks ago, hoping for some relief, and they prescribed diphenhydramine. But honestly, it hasn’t helped at all. 

I don’t smoke, and I only drink a few beers on the weekends, so I thought that would keep me in good health. My weight and height seem fine, and my vital signs were all normal during my last visit. Everything looked okay, even the chest X-ray. But still, I can’t shake this feeling of unease. 

I keep thinking about what could be causing this. It’s just a cough, right? But what if it’s something worse? I’m worried that I might need more tests or treatments. I’ve heard about things like pulmonary function tests or even a high-resolution CT scan, and the thought of it is making me feel more anxious. I just want to know what’s going on and why I can’t seem to get better. What if this cough is a sign of something serious? I feel like I need answers, and fast.
options: A. Sputum culture and cytology B. Methacholine challenge test C. Pulmonary function testing D. Omeprazole therapy E. High-resolution CT scan of the chest F. Empiric antibiotic therapy G. Allergy skin testing H. Referral for psychiatric evaluation I. Trial of inhaled corticosteroids J. CT scan of the chest

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread since my last appointment. At just 16 weeks into my pregnancy, I went in for a routine screening, and the results came back showing elevated alpha-fetoprotein levels. I mean, I was just trying to be excited about the baby, but now I can’t stop worrying about what this could mean. 

After the appointment, I found myself sitting in the waiting room, feeling so anxious about what might be wrong. The doctor mentioned a few possibilities, but honestly, all I could think about were the worst-case scenarios. What if there’s something seriously wrong with the baby? I’ve read about all sorts of issues, like neural tube defects or even fetal abdominal wall defects, and it just makes my heart race. 

I feel so lost right now, especially since I just wanted to be a happy mom-to-be. I even asked for a referral for an abortion because I’m so scared of what this could mean for my baby and me. I know I need to find answers, but the uncertainty is weighing heavily on me. I just hope I can get some clarity soon, because this feeling of worry is consuming me.
options: A. Inaccurate gestational age B. Laboratory processing error C. Fetal abdominal wall defect D. Multiple gestation E. Trisomy 21 F. Threatened abortion G. Oligohydramnios H. Maternal weight error I. Neural tube defect J. Placental abnormalities

question:
This morning, I woke up with an awful pain in my upper abdomen. It felt like a tearing and burning sensation that radiated to my back. I couldn’t shake the feeling that something was really wrong. Just yesterday, I had an upper endoscopy, and they told me I had gastritis and a large hiatal hernia. That’s when my worries started piling up.

I’ve got a history of hypertension and hypercholesterolemia, not to mention the left bundle branch block I was diagnosed with five years ago. My family history doesn’t help either; both my parents had serious heart issues at a young age. I used to smoke a pack a day for 40 years but quit ten years ago, and I drink a few beers daily, which adds to my anxiety about my health.

When I arrived at the emergency department, I could feel the distress creeping in. My temperature was slightly elevated, and my blood pressure readings were a bit off. The doctors examined me and noted that my abdomen was tender, which only heightened my concern. I can’t shake off the thought that this pain could signal something much more serious. What if it’s my heart? What’s the next step? I need answers, and I hope it’s not too late.
options: A. Serial troponin measurements B. Urgent upper endoscopy with biopsy C. Contrast-enhanced CT of the aorta D. CT angiography of coronary arteries E. MRI of the chest and abdomen F. Transthoracic echocardiogram G. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy H. Contrast esophagography with gastrografin I. Abdominal CT with oral and IV contrast J. Nuclear stress test

question:
I can’t shake this growing concern about my right hand. For the past few weeks, I’ve noticed a troubling numbness creeping into my fourth and fifth fingers. It’s not just annoying; it’s making it really hard for me to handle my tools at work as a carpenter. I’ve struggled to grip my hammer tightly, which is quite alarming given how essential it is for my job.

What’s more worrisome is the shooting pain that starts from my right shoulder and travels down my forearm. It’s a sharp, unsettling sensation that’s hard to ignore. I tried to brush it off, but it’s becoming harder to manage. During my check-up, the doctor seemed to be thorough, and while many of my tests came back normal, there was still a mild weakness in my grip and the ability to extend my fingers. 

They did some sensory testing, and it turns out I have reduced feeling in my fifth finger and along the inside of my forearm. That really made me anxious. I mean, what could be causing all this? I feel like I should be able to work without this fear of losing my grip—not just on my tools, but on my livelihood. I just wish I had clarity on what’s happening to my hand.
options: A. Cubital tunnel syndrome B. T1 radiculopathy C. Cervical spondylosis D. Thoracic outlet syndrome E. Brachial plexopathy F. Cervical disc herniation G. Carpal tunnel syndrome H. Median nerve entrapment I. Ulnar neuropathy J. C8 radiculopathy

question:
I recently went for my routine wellness checkup, and honestly, I was feeling pretty good about it. I’ve been thinking about starting volleyball this fall, so I was excited to talk about that. But then, during the exam, things started to feel a bit off. The doctor pointed out that my right shoulder looks lower than my left while I’m standing, and that really made my heart race. 

When I bent forward to touch my toes, I could see a prominent rib hump on my left side. I didn't even know that could happen! The doctor seemed concerned too, mentioning something about my back muscles being tight on one side and that some of my vertebrae were shifting more to the left. 

I can’t shake this feeling of worry. What does it all mean? I’m just a 13-year-old girl who wants to play volleyball, not deal with all this back stuff. I just keep thinking, could this be something serious? I really hope it’s nothing major, but now I can’t help but feel anxious about what’s going on with my body. I really just want everything to be okay.
options: A. Thoracic Rotoscoliosis B. L1-L4 NSRRL C. Adolescent Idiopathic Kyphosis D. Thoracic Scheuermann's Disease E. Congenital Thoracic Scoliosis F. T10-L3 FSRRL G. T4-T7 Type 1 Group H. T4-T7 NSRRL I. T5-T8 NRRSL J. T4-T7 NSLLR

question:
I can’t shake off this nagging worry ever since I was diagnosed with membranous nephropathy three months ago. My doctor started me on Lisinopril, and while I’ve been trying to stay positive, I can’t help but think about the possibility of my condition getting worse. 

I’ve read that certain factors could increase my risk for progressive disease, and it feels overwhelming. For instance, I know that having stable blood pressure readings around 130/80 mmHg is good, but that doesn’t seem to ease my mind. What really keeps me up at night is the proteinuria. At the end of the observation period, I found out I had 6 g/day of protein in my urine, which sounds alarming. 

I keep worrying about the implications of my anti-PLA2R antibody status too. I’m positive for it, and my levels have been stable at 55 RU/mL. Is that a bad sign? I’ve also heard that even a slight increase in serum creatinine could spell trouble, and I’m terrified that any minor changes in my kidney function might lead to significant issues down the road. 

I wish I could feel more at ease about my health, but the uncertainty is really weighing on me. I just want to make sure I’m doing everything right to manage this condition.
options: A. Presence of IgG4 deposits without complement activation B. Stable blood pressure readings averaging 130/80 mmHg C. Proteinuria of 6 g/day at the end of the observation period D. Microscopic hematuria with <5 RBCs/HPF E. A patient who is anti-PLA2R antibody positive, with anti-PLA2R antibody titers stable at 55 RU/mL during the observation period F. Normal C3 and C4 complement levels with stable renal function G. Serum creatinine elevation of 0.3 mg/dL from baseline with eGFR >60 mL/min/1.73m² H. Proteinuria of 3 g/day with a serum albumin of 3.7 g/dL I. Proteinuria reduction of 25% after 3 months of ACE inhibitor therapy J. Anti-PLA2R antibody titers decreasing to 20 RU/mL after treatment

question:
I can't shake this feeling of worry after my son’s recent well-child visit. He’s 13 now, and I thought everything was going fine. He’s excelling in school and plays soccer, so I didn’t expect any issues. The pediatrician checked him over and said his vital signs were normal, and he’s hit all his developmental milestones. That should have reassured me, but then came the forward Adam's bend test. 

When he bent forward, I noticed the doctor’s expression change. She observed a hump on the right side of his back, and my heart sank. I felt this wave of panic sweep over me. I had no idea what it could mean. The doctor didn’t say much, but I could tell something wasn’t right. It’s hard to focus on anything else now. 

I keep replaying the moment in my head, and I’m terrified of what it could indicate. I can’t help but worry about the possibilities—what if it’s something serious? I just want my son to be healthy and happy. I hope we can figure this out soon, but the uncertainty is really weighing on me.
options: A. Vertebrae compressed anteriorly B. Aggressive disease course C. Vertebrae anteriorly displaced D. Vertebrae wedged laterally left E. Vertebrae sidebent left F. Vertebrae posteriorly displaced G. Vertebrae compressed posteriorly H. Vertebrae rotated counterclockwise I. Vertebrae wedged laterally right J. Vertebrae sidebent right

question:
I’ve been really worried lately. It all started about a month ago when I noticed this strange numbness and tingling in my hands and feet that just wouldn’t go away. At first, I thought it was nothing, but it’s gotten worse. I struggle to do simple things like buttoning my clothes, and I feel unsteady on my feet. I’ve had a mild cough for the past six months, ever since I had that upper respiratory infection two months ago, but now this is really concerning me.

I’m 65, have type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and I’ve been dealing with major depression, which I manage with medications. Since I shifted to a vegan diet to help with my blood sugar, I thought I was doing better. I do drink a few beers daily, and I’ve smoked for years, which I know isn’t great, but I never imagined it would lead to this.

When I went to see the doctor, they ran some tests, but I still don't fully understand what’s happening. I felt like I was failing the physical exam when they tested my sensations and balance. The numbness is patchy, affecting my left foot, right hand, and even my left cheek, and I can’t feel my right toes at all. I’m just so anxious about what this could mean for my health. What if it’s something serious? I can’t shake the feeling that I need answers soon.
options: A. Alcoholic neuropathy B. Chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy C. Multiple sclerosis D. Vitamin B12 (cobalamin) deficiency E. Copper deficiency myeloneuropathy F. Paraneoplastic syndrome G. Thiamine deficiency H. Diabetic neuropathy I. Guillain-Barré syndrome J. Sarcoidosis

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of dread after my recent visit to the doctor. They mentioned that my right coronary artery is showing signs of diffuse enlargement, which sounds so serious. I felt a knot tighten in my stomach when they started talking about possible underlying causes. I mean, what could it mean? 

I remember sitting there, my mind racing through all the options they laid out: dissection, arteritis, aneurysm... the list just kept going. Each word felt heavier than the last. I think I might have even stopped breathing for a moment. The thought of something like an aneurysm is terrifying. Or what if it’s something like ectasia or even a congenital malformation? 

I can’t help but worry about what this could mean for my future. Will I have to undergo more tests? What if it’s something serious? I keep replaying the doctor’s words in my head, feeling more anxious with each repetition. It's hard to focus on anything else; the uncertainty is just unbearable. I wish I could just know what’s really going on, but all I have are these nagging questions, and I feel so helpless right now.
options: A. Dissection B. Arteritis C. Aneurysm D. Ectasia E. Congenital malformation F. Stenosis G. Compensatory hypertrophy H. Fistula I. Collateral formation J. Vasospasm

question:
I can’t shake this gnawing feeling in my stomach. Just two weeks ago, my doctor put me on a new medication to help with my depression, fatigue, and insomnia. I was hoping it would help me feel better, but everything seems to have spiraled out of control since then. I’ve been struggling emotionally for months, but lately, it’s gotten so much worse. 

Just three days ago, I got this overwhelming urge to climb Mount Everest. It's ridiculous—I’ve never even climbed before! I’ve spent all my savings on gear, and now I’m sitting in the emergency room after a fall while trying to practice building climbing. My girlfriend is really worried, and honestly, I can’t blame her. 

I’ve been sleepless and feeling so restless. When they examined me, I noticed bruises on my right arm, and I couldn’t focus on anything. I was rambling, and they said I wasn’t even oriented to where I was. It’s terrifying to feel so out of control. I can’t help but wonder if this new medication is responsible for these bizarre changes in my behavior. What if it’s affecting me in ways I don’t understand? I really need to figure this out before things get worse.
options: A. Mirtazapine B. Venlafaxine C. Lamotrigine D. Lithium E. Sertraline F. Escitalopram G. Bupropion H. Aripiprazole I. Duloxetine J. Fluoxetine

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry as I sit here reflecting on what’s been happening with my left knee. I’m 34 and have always loved running, but lately, things have taken a turn for the worse. What started as a slight discomfort during my runs has now morphed into this severe pain that limits my every step. It’s almost embarrassing, but I’ve noticed I’m tripping more often, and it’s terrifying. I can’t pinpoint any specific injury or back pain that could explain it, which only adds to my anxiety.

My past is littered with multiple sprains to my left ankle, but this knee issue feels different. I went to see a doctor, hoping for some clarity. During the exam, they mentioned something about resistance in my ankle joint and weakness in my foot’s movement. That really struck me—what if this is something serious? The doctor checked my reflexes and pulses, which were normal, but I can’t help but worry about what could be causing all of this. 

I just want to understand what’s happening to my body. Is it something simple, or could it lead to more significant problems down the line? The uncertainty is really weighing on me.
options: A. Posterior tibiotalar joint B. Lateral collateral ligament strain C. Lateral meniscus tear D. Tibialis anterior tendinopathy E. Chronic exertional compartment syndrome F. Anterior proximal fibular head G. Superficial peroneal nerve compression H. Posterior fibular head I. Patellofemoral pain syndrome J. Common peroneal nerve entrapment at soleal arch

question:
I can’t shake off the feeling of dread ever since I fell and broke my wrist. It was just a simple trip, but now I’m sitting in the emergency department, and everything feels overwhelming. They told me it’s a fracture in my right distal radius, and I’m in this cumbersome cast. But what’s really worrying me is when they did some tests, they found out my sodium levels are dangerously low—only 128 mEq/liter. 

I’ve been managing a few health issues for a while now, like hypertension and osteoporosis, and I thought I was doing okay with my medications. I take lisinopril, amlodipine, levothyroxine, sertraline, and alendronate regularly. But now, I can’t help but feel anxious about what this low sodium means for me. I’ve heard that it can lead to serious complications, and the doctors have been discussing my treatment options. 

I’m alert and oriented, thank goodness, but I can't help but worry about the next steps. Should I be restricting my fluid intake? Or do I need something more drastic like a saline infusion? All these thoughts are racing through my head. I just want to feel better and not be a burden to anyone. I’m really hoping they can fix this quickly because the uncertainty is making me feel so uneasy.
options: A. Limit intake of free water to 1500 mL daily B. Begin oral salt tablets with loop diuretics C. Administer isotonic saline infusion D. Initiate fluid restriction with urea supplementation E. Perform a water deprivation test F. Administer hypertonic saline infusion G. Discontinue sertraline therapy H. Increase dietary sodium intake I. Limit intake of all fluids to 1000 mL daily J. Administer 1 liter of 0.9% normal saline intravenously

question:
I've been feeling incredibly worried lately. For the past month, I've been struggling with excessive daytime drowsiness and an unshakeable dryness in my mouth. It’s hard to focus on anything when I’m fighting the urge to sleep all the time. My nights are restless, too—I keep waking up to go to the bathroom, and I feel so thirsty all day long. I can’t believe it, but I’ve been drinking up to 20 cups of water daily. It’s not normal, right? 

I went to see the doctor because I just couldn’t ignore these symptoms anymore. They said my skin didn’t have the right turgor and my mouth was really dry. I was so embarrassed when they noticed my tremors, but I’ve been feeling anxious, too. Thankfully, I don’t have any pain or urgency when I urinate, but my medical history is pretty complicated. I’ve had recurrent urinary tract infections and even a head injury from a suicide attempt just three months ago. I have bipolar disorder and hypertension, and I’ve been smoking a pack a day for 25 years. 

I can’t shake this feeling that something is seriously wrong with me. I just want to understand what’s causing these bizarre symptoms, and I’m terrified of what it could be.
options: A. Antipsychotic medication side effect B. Hypothalamic injury C. Primary polydipsia D. Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus E. SIADH syndrome F. Mood stabilizer intake G. Psychogenic polydipsia H. Diabetes insipidus secondary to head trauma I. Chronic hypernatremia J. Chronic urinary tract infection

question:
I can't shake this nagging worry since I went to the clinic last week. At 66, I've always tried to take care of myself, especially with my history of osteoporosis and hypertension. But recently, I've been dealing with this awful upper back pain that just won't go away. It gets so much worse after sitting for long periods, which is hard to avoid. 

I decided to take some acetaminophen, and it helped a little, but not nearly enough. When I saw the doctor, they examined my back and found something concerning. They pointed out a right posterior transverse process near my T2 spinous process that was more pronounced when I extended my spine. I could see the concern in their eyes, and it made my heart race. 

Now, I'm left wondering what this all means. The doctor mentioned a few possible diagnoses, but I couldn't focus on the details because I was so anxious about what might be wrong with me. I keep thinking about how fragile my bones are and how this pain might be a sign of something more serious. I just want to understand what's happening and, more importantly, make sure I can manage this pain before it disrupts my life any further.
options: A. T3 FRRSR B. T2 FRLSL C. T2 ERRSL D. T2 FRRSR E. T2 ERRSR F. T2 ERLSL G. T2 FRLSR H. T2 NRLSR I. T3 ERRSR J. T1 FRRSR

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread ever since my fall. It was a 12-foot drop, and I thought I’d just bruised my leg, but when I got to the hospital, they told me I had a closed tibial shaft fracture. Suddenly, everything spiraled out of control. 

The doctors started talking about compartment syndrome, and I felt my heart race. They mentioned these measurements that could indicate a serious problem. I overheard them discussing things like the anterior compartment pressure and diastolic pressure, but it all sounded so alarming. What if my condition worsened? 

I remember one of the doctors saying something about an intraoperative measurement of 25 with a diastolic pressure of 54 being particularly concerning. I couldn’t help but think, could that be me? I was terrified that I might end up with severe complications. I just wanted to make sure I was going to be okay, but everything felt so uncertain. 

Each number they mentioned felt like a ticking clock, and I kept wondering if I was at risk. I just want to heal and go back to my normal life, but right now, all I feel is this overwhelming worry about what might happen next.
options: A. Intraoperative anterior compartment measurement of 25, with intraoperative diastolic pressure of 54 B. Preoperative anterior compartment measurement of 22, with intraoperative diastolic pressure of 45 C. Preoperative anterior compartment measurement of 25, with preoperative diastolic pressure of 60 D. Intraoperative anterior compartment measurement of 28, with preoperative diastolic pressure of 55 E. Intraoperative anterior compartment measurement of 20, with preoperative diastolic pressure of 40 F. Intraoperative anterior compartment measurement of 24, with preoperative diastolic pressure of 53 G. Preoperative anterior compartment measurement of 32, with intraoperative diastolic pressure of 62 H. Intraoperative anterior compartment measurement of 30, with intraoperative diastolic pressure of 60 I. Intraoperative anterior compartment measurement of 26, with preoperative diastolic pressure of 50 J. Intraoperative anterior compartment measurement of 29, with preoperative diastolic pressure 58

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of anxiety that's been creeping in over the past six months. It all started with these strange headaches and dizzy spells that seem to come out of nowhere. The dizziness often hits first, and it feels like the room is spinning—so disorienting that I have to sit down or brace myself. Each episode lasts anywhere from 30 seconds to a few minutes, but thankfully, I haven’t fallen. 

I’ve tried to pinpoint what triggers this, but I can't identify anything specific. I’ve seen my primary care doctor, a neurologist, and even an ear specialist, but they all said the same thing: nothing seems wrong. I do have high blood pressure, but I'm managing that with medication. I don’t smoke or drink, so I thought I was doing everything right.

When I visited the osteopathic clinic, I felt a bit of hope. They mentioned some issues with the alignment in my neck and head, but I’m left feeling more confused than ever. I can’t help but worry about what could be causing these dizzy spells. It’s terrifying not knowing what’s happening to my body, and I just want to figure this out before it gets worse. What if it’s something serious?
options: A. Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo B. OA ESRRL cervical somatic dysfunction C. Sphenobasilar synchondrosis dysfunction D. Vestibular neuritis with cervical involvement E. Right torsion cranial strain somatic dysfunction F. Left lateral strain cranial somatic dysfunction G. C6–C7 NSRRR cervical somatic dysfunction H. Temporal bone dysfunction with superior semicircular canal dehiscence I. Cervicogenic vertigo with upper cervical dysfunction J. Atlas rotation somatic dysfunction with vascular compromise

question:
I've been feeling really anxious lately, and I can't shake this worry over my health. It all started about a year ago when I noticed my periods becoming less frequent and shorter. At first, I thought it was just a phase, but then things got more complicated. I started experiencing these intense mood swings that I can’t explain, and I even lost about 2.5 kg without trying. 

On top of that, I’ve been waking up at night drenched in sweat, only to be hit with chills and a wave of anxiety afterwards. It’s been exhausting, and I can’t help but feel something might be seriously wrong. I’ve kept up with my Pap smears, which have all come back normal, and I've been active with my husband, who had a vasectomy a decade ago. 

When I went to the doctor, they did a physical exam, and everything seemed fine, but my heart was racing at 103 beats per minute. I can’t help but worry about what could be going on with my body. I just want to know the next step. Should I be getting a pelvic ultrasound or maybe some blood tests? I feel like I’m in the dark here, and it’s really starting to take a toll on my mental health. What if it’s something serious?
options: A. Perform a pelvic ultrasound B. Perform endometrial biopsy C. Prescribe an SSRI for mood swings and anxiety D. Measure serum estradiol concentration E. Measure serum FSH concentration F. Order a 24-hour urine cortisol test G. Offer hormone replacement therapy H. Recommend lifestyle modifications for weight loss I. Measure serum β-hCG concentration J. Measure serum TSH concentration

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping into my mind lately. It’s been a year since I’ve started keeping all these things in my apartment—my mom says they’re just "useless items," but I can’t help but feel like they might be useful someday. The other day, when she suggested I get rid of some old newspapers, I snapped. I didn’t mean to, but I felt so defensive that I stopped talking to her for two weeks. 

I’ve noticed I’m avoiding social situations because I don’t want anyone to see how cluttered my place has become. Even my bed has turned into a storage area, and I’m sleeping on a futon now. Sometimes I feel overwhelmed by the mess, but honestly, I don’t think my behavior is that big of a deal—at least, that’s what I tell myself. 

But deep down, I know something isn’t right. I feel like I’m losing control, and I’m scared about what it all means. What if I can’t change? I don’t want to keep living like this, but I also don’t know where to start. I just wish I could figure out how to handle this and make things better before it gets worse.
options: A. Referral to a professional organizer for home decluttering assistance B. High dose SSRI for hoarding disorder C. Family therapy to address interpersonal conflict D. Psychoeducation about clutter management strategies E. Antipsychotic medication for underlying psychosis F. Exposure and response prevention therapy for obsessive-compulsive disorder G. Motivational interviewing to enhance readiness for change H. Cognitive behavioral therapy for obsessive-compulsive disorder I. Behavioral activation to improve social engagement J. Tricyclic antidepressant for hoarding disorder

question:
I can’t believe I’m sitting here again, feeling so anxious and overwhelmed after experiencing three pregnancy losses in just two years. The first time it happened, I was only six weeks along. I remember the panic when I started bleeding and cramping; it was devastating. Then, at ten weeks, the second loss hit me even harder when the ultrasound showed an embryo without a heartbeat. How could this be happening? Just when I thought I could start to heal, the third loss came at seven weeks, and the ultrasound revealed an anembryonic gestation. It felt like a cruel twist of fate.

I don’t have any other health issues, and I’m not on any medications, which makes this even more baffling and terrifying. I’ve been trying to understand why this is happening to me. I keep thinking, what if there’s something wrong that no one can figure out? I’ve been told that I need to undergo tests to find out what’s going on, and I’m just so worried. I want to know if it’s something serious. I feel like I’m in a fog of uncertainty, and I desperately want answers. I just hope that whatever tests they suggest will finally give me some clarity and, hopefully, a way forward.
options: A. Antiphospholipid antibody testing, pelvic ultrasound, and thrombophilia workup B. Parental karyotype, thrombophilia workup, and pelvic ultrasound C. Antiphospholipid antibody testing, hysterosalpingogram, and thrombophilia workup D. Parental karyotype, pelvic ultrasound, and thyroid testing E. Antiphospholipid antibody testing, thyroid testing, and parental karyotype F. Antiphospholipid antibody testing, hysterosalpingogram, and parental karyotype G. Thyroid testing, pelvic ultrasound, and thrombophilia workup H. Antiphospholipid antibody testing, pelvic ultrasound, and thyroid testing I. Hysterosalpingogram, pelvic ultrasound, and thrombophilia workup J. Antiphospholipid antibody testing, thyroid testing, thrombophilia workup, and hysterosalpingogram

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that washed over me when I first noticed the pain in my right flank. It started out dull, but soon radiated down to my groin, making it hard to focus on anything else. I’ve always been careful with my health, managing my hypertension with medication, but this pain was different. I even struggled with some constipation, which did get a bit better after I took a laxative, but I couldn’t shake the worry.

When I finally decided to go to the emergency room, I was a bundle of nerves. They took my temperature, and I could feel my heart racing as they checked my blood pressure and heart rate. I thought maybe it was just a passing issue, but then they examined me and found tenderness in my back. 

I was terrified when they mentioned my blood calcium levels were high, and I couldn’t help but think about what that could mean. They did a CT scan and found a calcium-based mass in my right ureter. I left the hospital with more questions than answers, feeling anxious about what could be causing all of this. What if it was something serious? What if it was related to my medication? I can’t help but worry about what comes next.
options: A. Functional adenoma B. Metastatic bone disease C. Hypervitaminosis D. Granulomatous disease E. Thiazide-induced hypercalcemia F. Tertiary hyperparathyroidism G. Adverse drug reaction H. Parathyroid hyperplasia I. PTH-related peptide J. Familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia

question:
I can’t shake off the feeling of dread that has settled over me this past week. It started with a persistent cough, and then I noticed blood-tinged sputum. I was so scared; I didn’t think it could get worse, but it did. I began having trouble breathing, which only heightened my panic. 

I finally made the decision to go to the emergency department. By the time I got there, I was running a fever of 102°F and felt chills coursing through me. My joints ached so much that I could hardly sit still. The staff took my vitals—my blood pressure was alarmingly high at 159/98, and my heart was racing. I felt a wave of anxiety wash over me as I realized something was seriously wrong. 

They did all sorts of tests, and though I was relieved that my oxygen saturation was okay, I couldn’t help but feel uneasy about what they might find. The doctors were talking about my cloudy urine and the fact that I had positive blood in it. It felt like everything was spiraling out of control. 

Now, I’m left wondering what the next step is. I just want to know what's happening to me. I can't help but worry about what lies ahead.
options: A. Prednisone B. Echocardiography to evaluate for endocarditis C. Pulmonary function tests D. Anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibody (ANCA) levels E. Azithromycin F. Sputum acid-fast bacilli (AFB) testing G. Bronchoscopy with biopsy H. Renal biopsy I. Empiric treatment with ceftriaxone and azithromycin J. Type 4 collagen antibody levels

question:
I can’t shake off the worry after what happened to me. Just the other day, I slipped on some ice and fell hard. The pain in my left groin was unbearable, and I really didn’t know what to think. I rushed to the hospital, and after some x-rays, the doctors confirmed my worst fear: I had a fracture in my left femoral neck. At 62, this kind of injury feels so daunting.

I’ve been living with type 1 diabetes since I was 14, and I also have vitiligo and primary hypothyroidism, which I thought I was managing well. But now, I can’t help but wonder if these conditions are catching up with me. During the physical exam, my heart rate was slightly elevated, and they noticed my left leg was externally rotated. 

What really worries me are the other findings they mentioned. My vitamin D levels were alarmingly low, and the scans showed significant bone density loss. I keep thinking about how fragile my health seems to be right now. I’m scared about what all this means for my future. I just want to understand what’s happening to my body and how to fix it, but I feel so overwhelmed by it all. What if this injury leads to something worse?
options: A. Autoimmune polyglandular syndrome B. Primary hyperparathyroidism C. Thyroid hormone-induced bone loss D. Celiac disease E. Idiopathic male osteoporosis F. Hypogonadal osteoporosis G. Type 1 diabetes-induced osteoporosis H. Vitamin D deficiency osteomalacia I. Age-related osteoporosis J. Secondary hyperparathyroidism

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping up on me lately. It started about two months ago when I began experiencing these bouts of diarrhea—thankfully, it’s non-bloody, but it’s so frequent and unpredictable. I’ve been on this raw food diet for six months to lose some weight, but now I’m questioning if that’s the right choice. 

To add to my stress, I’ve been dealing with anxiety, which I manage with fluvoxamine. And then there’s my osteopenia; I just can’t help but feel overwhelmed. I recently returned from Uganda three months ago, and I can’t shake the thought that something might have happened while I was there. 

When I went to the clinic, my vitals seemed stable, but the doctor found a new systolic ejection murmur during the exam. I couldn’t help but feel a chill run down my spine. My mother has lactose intolerance and was just diagnosed with osteoporosis, so I can’t help but worry about my own health. 

It’s all so much to process, and I’m left wondering what could be causing these symptoms. Could it be connected to something more serious? I just wish I could get some answers and find a way to feel better.
options: A. Decreased urinary 5-HIAA B. Decreased levels of chromogranin A C. Niacin deficiency D. Positive hydrogen breath test E. Elevated serum serotonin levels F. Folate deficiency G. Vitamin D deficiency H. Vitamin B12 malabsorption I. Thiamine deficiency J. Iron deficiency anemia

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of anxiety after my recent surgery for a lower extremity fracture. It’s been a whirlwind of emotions since the procedure. I keep thinking about when I’ll be able to regain my normal automobile braking ability. It’s crucial for my independence, and I just can’t help but worry. 

The doctor mentioned that recovery timelines can vary, but I’ve read different things online. Some say I might be back to normal in as little as six weeks post-op, while others suggest it could take up to three months. I just want to make the right choice about when it’s safe to drive again. 

Every day, I’m trying to assess my progress. I know I need to regain full range of motion in my ankle and knee, but how will I know when I’m ready? Will I be able to trust my body again? The thought of waiting even longer than eight weeks feels overwhelming. What if I push it too soon and end up causing more harm? I’m just so anxious about when I’ll feel safe behind the wheel again. It’s a constant worry that lingers in the back of my mind.
options: A. 6 weeks postoperatively regardless of weight bearing B. 3 months postoperatively regardless of weight bearing C. Once full range of motion of the ankle and knee exist D. 5 weeks after initiation of weight bearing E. 8 weeks from the date of injury F. 6 weeks after initiation of weight bearing G. 8 weeks after initiation of weight bearing H. 4 weeks after initiation of weight bearing I. 4 weeks postoperatively regardless of weight bearing J. 12 weeks after initiation of weight bearing

question:
I can't shake this feeling of worry that has settled in ever since I noticed my urine turning red over the last couple of days. It’s intermittent and honestly quite alarming. I haven’t had any flank pain, fever, or burning when I urinate, which is a small relief, but the sight of that red color is haunting me. I can't remember any recent trauma to explain this.

At 66, I’m already managing hypertension and atrial fibrillation, and I take lisinopril and warfarin, which makes me even more anxious. I’ve never been much of a drinker or a smoker, so I can’t help but wonder what’s going on with my body. I went to the doctor to find out what could be happening, and while the examination didn’t show anything abnormal, the fact that I have blood in my urine is just terrifying.

My doctor mentioned adjusting my warfarin dosage, but I can’t help but feel like there’s something more serious at play. I’m just trying to understand what the next steps are and why this is happening to me. What if it’s something really bad? I can’t get the thought out of my head. There’s so much uncertainty, and I just want answers.
options: A. Renal biopsy B. MRI of the pelvis C. CT urography D. Cystoscopy E. Antibiotic therapy for presumed UTI F. Ultrasound of the kidneys and bladder G. Repeat urinalysis in one week H. Observation and follow-up in two weeks I. Urine cytology J. Referral to a hematologist

question:
I can’t shake off this persistent low back pain that seems to nag at me throughout the day. It’s this dull ache, and honestly, it fluctuates so much that it’s hard to predict when it’ll hit the hardest. I can't even remember when it started; there wasn't a specific injury that I can recall, but I do have this history of ankle sprains from playing soccer when I was younger. 

I finally decided to see someone about it because the pain was getting worse. During the exam, the doctor pressed on my lower back, and it felt particularly tender there. I noticed that bending forward or backward made it even worse. When they did some tests, they pointed out that my right side seemed off—something about my right posterior superior iliac spine being more elevated and the sacral area feeling shallow. The asymmetry was concerning, especially when I moved into different positions. 

I can't help but worry about what this all means. The doctor mentioned a bunch of possible diagnoses, and I find myself anxiously trying to figure out what’s really going on. I just want to understand why this is happening and how I can make it stop.
options: A. Anterior sacral shear B. Left unilateral sacral flexion C. Left unilateral sacral extension D. Right unilateral sacral extension E. Right unilateral sacral flexion F. Right-on-left sacral torsion G. Left on left sacral torsion H. Bilateral sacral flexion I. Bilateral sacral extension J. Left-on-right sacral torsion

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that settled over me yesterday when I started experiencing this unbearable upper abdominal pain. It came on suddenly, and along with it, I felt nauseous and had this unsettling shortness of breath. My son rushed me to the emergency department, and I could see the concern in his eyes. Just three days ago, I had undergone a coronary stent placement after my heart attack, and it feels like everything is falling apart.

I’ve been managing my diabetes and trying to remember my medications, but with my Alzheimer’s, it’s becoming increasingly hard. I live alone, and even though I take my aspirin and other medications, I often forget doses. I’ve been having a couple of glasses of wine each day, which I know isn’t great, but it’s my way of coping.

When they examined me, I was alert and knew who I was, but I couldn’t keep track of the time. My heart rate felt slow, and my blood pressure was higher than usual. I’m just so worried about what this all means. I can’t help but think about what tests they might run to figure out what’s going on. I just want to feel better and not be a burden to my son. What if this pain means something serious?
options: A. Chest radiography B. Serum lipase measurement C. Serial measurement of serum troponin concentration D. Arterial blood gas analysis E. Echocardiography F. CT angiography of the abdomen G. Complete blood count with differential H. 12-lead electrocardiogram with right-sided leads I. Serum lactate measurement J. D-dimer testing

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of worry after my recent visit to the clinic. At 67, I’ve dealt with depression, type 2 diabetes, and insomnia for years, but things have taken a turn that really concerns me. I went in for a routine follow-up, but I was primarily worried about this persistent pain in both my knees. It started after I spent a whole day gardening last week, and while acetaminophen helps a bit in the mornings, I can’t ignore how it’s affecting my daily life.

But that’s not all. Just a week ago, I noticed something alarming—new-onset urinary incontinence. I find myself needing to rush to the bathroom frequently, and sometimes I just can’t fully empty my bladder. It’s so embarrassing, especially since it’s not linked to sneezing or laughing like I’ve heard can happen. I can’t help but feel anxious about it. I don’t have any burning or itching, so at least there’s that, but it still feels so unsettling.

To make matters worse, I started taking an over-the-counter sleep aid a few weeks ago and added echinacea to my routine a month back, hoping to boost my immunity. I can’t help but wonder if one of these new medications is causing this issue. My diabetes was under control, but now I’m just left feeling more anxious and confused about what’s happening to my body.
options: A. Echinacea B. None of the above - this is age-related incontinence C. The echinacea supplement D. A combination of empagliflozin and doxylamine E. Doxylamine F. A combination of metformin and empagliflozin G. Empagliflozin H. Dulaglutide I. Metformin J. Acetaminophen

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread after what happened today. I was installing a window when, out of nowhere, it fell on me. The pain in my left eye is unbearable, and everything looks so blurry. I can barely see out of the lower part of my left field; it’s like a dark curtain has dropped down. 

When I finally got to the Emergency Department, my heart was racing, and I felt so anxious. They took my vital signs, and I guess they were okay, but my focus was all on my eye. The doctors found multiple cuts on my face, arms, and legs, but honestly, I was more worried about my vision. They noticed lacerations on my eyelid and found some serious issues with my left eye—blood in the front chamber and what they called vitreous hemorrhage. 

My right eye is fine, but the left one? They couldn't even assess my vision properly. I just kept thinking, what if I lose my sight? I’m terrified of what all this means for my future. I heard them discussing the next steps for my care, but I can't help but feel overwhelmed and anxious about what’s going to happen next. I just want to see clearly again.
options: A. Administration of oral antibiotics and monitoring for intraocular pressure changes B. Examination of the left eye with fluorescein C. Placement of an ocular shield and outpatient ophthalmology follow-up D. Immediate CT scan of the orbits and systemic antibiotic administration E. Emergent surgical intervention without antibiotic administration F. Use of a slit lamp to evaluate for corneal abrasions prior to ophthalmology consultation G.
