Systemic administration of vancomycin and emergent ophthalmology consultation H. Placement of an ocular pad and emergent ophthalmology consultation I. Administration of IV dexamethasone and delayed ophthalmology consultation J. Administration of topical corticosteroids and emergent ophthalmology consultation

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry ever since we took our daughter to the doctor. She’s only 8 months old, and we adopted her from Latin America when she was just 2 months old. At first, everything seemed fine, but over the past three months, I noticed something alarming. Her weight has plummeted from the 50th percentile to the 5th percentile, even though her length and head circumference are still normal. It’s like she’s just withered away before my eyes.

The doctor mentioned that since coming to the U.S., she’s had five episodes of ear infections, and to make matters worse, she’s been dealing with recurrent diarrhea. When the doctor examined her, I could see the concern on their face. She looks so underweight, and her muscle tone is definitely not what it should be. I can’t help but feel like I’m failing her somehow.

Now, they’re suggesting various tests to figure out why she’s not thriving, and my mind is racing with all the possibilities. Is it a food allergy? Could it be something more serious? I’m terrified of what the results might show. All I want is for her to be healthy and happy, but I feel so helpless right now. I just hope we can get to the bottom of this soon.
options: A. Obtain sweat chloride test B. Evaluate for milk protein allergy C. Order celiac disease screening D. Order HIV testing E. Initiate an immunologic workup F. Check thyroid function tests G. Perform a stool examination for ova and parasites H. Screen for metabolic disorders I. Perform upper GI series with small bowel follow-through J. Ask the parent to maintain calorie counts

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that washed over me after my biking accident. It happened so fast—I fell right over the handlebars, landing hard on the uneven ground. I’ve had some health issues lately, like my high cholesterol and that recent diagnosis of deep vein thrombosis. I’m on apixaban, which makes me even more anxious about any injuries.

When I finally made it to the emergency department, I felt my heart racing. My pulse was 109, and I could tell something wasn't right. They checked my blood pressure, and it was low at 102/63. I remember feeling a wave of panic when they examined my abdomen. There was this large, painful mass on the right side, and it was so bruised. I could tell from the doctor's face that it wasn’t good—especially since the mass wouldn’t shift when I tensed my muscles. 

I just kept thinking, “What’s going to happen to me?” I felt so vulnerable, lying there with all these worries swirling in my head. They had to decide quickly what to do next, and I was terrified of what might come next, especially knowing I was on blood thinners. I just hope they can figure it out before it’s too late.
options: A. Call a consult for emergent angioembolization of the epigastric arteries B. Transfuse fresh frozen plasma C. Administer intravenous fluid bolus D. Discontinue apixaban immediately and monitor clinically E. Obtain CT abdomen and pelvis with intravenous contrast F. Administer packed red blood cells immediately G. Administer intravenous vitamin K H. Initiate broad-spectrum antibiotics for potential infection I. Follow serial complete blood counts J. Perform bedside ultrasound of the abdomen

question:
I can't believe what's been happening to me lately. Over the past four weeks, I've been struggling with erectile dysfunction, something I've never faced before. I’ve been with my partner for two years, and we’ve been seriously talking about marriage and even starting a family. But now, this issue is looming over me, and it feels so overwhelming.

I used to have no problems initiating or maintaining erections, and my desire is still there, so I can't help but worry about what could be causing this sudden change. The thought of not being able to perform has been weighing heavily on my mind, and it’s making everything feel so much more complicated, especially with the idea of marriage—it's intimidating enough as it is.

I've always considered myself healthy, with no medical conditions or regular medications, and my physical exams have come back normal. But despite that, I can't shake this feeling of anxiety. I’ve been thinking that maybe talking to someone, like a counselor, could help me figure out what's going on. I just want to restore my sexual function and feel like myself again. I’m genuinely concerned about what this means for my relationship and my future. What should I do next?
options: A. Provide reassurance only B. Initiate phosphodiesterase-5 inhibitor therapy immediately C. Screen for cardiovascular risk factors D. Detailed assessment of stress and relationship dynamics E. A full biochemistry profile including blood sugar levels F. Testosterone level assessment to rule out hypogonadism G. Referral for psychological counseling H. Doppler ultrasound of penile vasculature I. Educate about situational erectile disorder J. Measure thyroid function tests to exclude hypothyroidism

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that’s been building up over the past month. It all started after my breakup two months ago, and I suddenly found myself dealing with these awful palpitations. They hit me out of nowhere, whether I’m just sitting on the couch or trying to get through a workout. I thought maybe I was just stressed; after all, I’ve been pushing myself harder at the gym and even started taking some herbal weight-loss supplements. I’ve lost about 15 pounds, but now I’m not sure if it’s worth it.

Sleep has become a real struggle, too. I toss and turn for what feels like hours, only to wake up way too early, feeling restless. On top of everything, I’ve been smoking a pack of cigarettes daily for the last three years and drinking a couple of cups of coffee every day for as long as I can remember. 

When I finally went to the doctor, I was shocked to find out my pulse was racing at 110, and my blood pressure was way higher than usual. I felt so embarrassed when they pointed out my sweaty palms and shaky hands. It’s all so overwhelming, and I’m worried that there’s something seriously wrong with me. I just want to feel normal again. What if this is more than just anxiety? I can’t help but think about all the possibilities, and it terrifies me.
options: A. Pheochromocytoma B. Subacute thyroiditis C. Toxic multinodular goiter D. Generalized anxiety disorder E. Toxic adenoma F. Silent thyroiditis G. Caffeine toxicity H. Exogenous thyrotoxicosis I. Graves disease J. Thyroid storm

question:
I can't shake the feeling of despair that's been overwhelming me since yesterday. After working at my job for 20 years, I was suddenly let go, and now I feel completely lost. It's been six hours since I started crying, and I can’t even bring myself to get out of bed. My daughter is worried about me, and honestly, I’m worried too. I don’t know what to do with my life now; everything feels so uncertain.

I’ve been using my inhaler more often lately, especially since I’ve been dealing with this awful stress. I’m also on medication for my acne, which feels trivial compared to everything else. I used to smoke a lot, but I’ve been trying to cut back, only having two cigarettes a day now. 

Physically, I know I’m fine—my temperature is normal, and I can follow conversations, but inside, I feel like I’m spiraling. My heart races, and I can’t seem to calm myself down. I’ve been trying to keep it together, but the sadness is suffocating. I even know I don’t want to hurt myself, but the weight of everything is just too much right now. I’m scared about where this might lead and if I’ll be able to pull myself out of this dark place.
options: A. Normal stress reaction B. Acute stress disorder C. Bereavement D. Situational depression E. Substance-induced mood disorder F. Acute grief reaction G. Adjustment disorder H. Generalized anxiety disorder I. Major depressive disorder J. Dysthymic disorder

question:
I can hardly put into words how scared I felt when I brought my 9-day-old son to the clinic. He just wasn’t feeding well, and I noticed some alarming changes in his color. He was delivered full term via cesarean due to some concerning fetal heart tones, but we thought everything was fine after his stay in the nursery. Since we brought him home, he seemed so tired and took forever to breastfeed.

What really frightened me was when he turned blue while crying. His breathing was rapid, and sometimes he’d grunt, which made my heart race. I watched him closely during the examination, and it felt like my world was crumbling when the doctor noted his heart rate was high, and his oxygen levels were alarmingly low. He looked so fatigued and cyanotic, and those retractions were just heartbreaking to see.

They told me about the abnormal heart sounds and that his liver was swollen. I felt utterly helpless as they discussed the results of the chest X-ray and ECG, which indicated something serious. They started him on Prostaglandin E1 right away. I can’t shake the worry about what the next steps will be and what this all means for my little boy. I just want to do everything I can to help him.
options: A. Placement of a stent in the patent ductus arteriosus B. Balloon pulmonary valvuloplasty C. Surgical placement of a systemic-to-pulmonary artery shunt D. Transcatheter closure of a ventricular septal defect E. Balloon atrial septostomy F. Surgical repair of tetralogy of Fallot G. Initiation of sildenafil for pulmonary vasodilation H. Percutaneous atrial septostomy I. Administration of inhaled nitric oxide J. Initiation of diuretics for heart failure management

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that settled over me after my recent CT scan. It was just supposed to be a routine check-up following some minor trauma, but then I got the call. They found a 2 cm cystic mass in the presacral space. I mean, I’ve always been healthy, and there’s no significant family history of anything serious, but now I’m just spiraling with worry.

When I went in for the rectal examination, the doctor mentioned feeling a small posterior mass that could be easily palpated. I could see the concern in their eyes, and I couldn’t help but feel my heart race. They assured me the MRI showed it was just a cystic lesion with no signs of invasion, but I can’t stop thinking about what that really means. 

Now, I’m faced with the question of what to do next, and I’m overwhelmed. Should I have a colonoscopy with biopsy, or maybe a fine needle aspiration? I keep wondering if observation is enough, or if I should push for something more definitive like surgical excision. Each option just adds to my anxiety. I’m trying to stay calm, but all I can think about is what this could mean for my health. What if it’s more serious than they’re letting on? I just want to get this figured out.
options: A. Colonoscopy with biopsy B. MRI with contrast enhancement C. Endorectal ultrasound D. Fine needle aspiration biopsy E. Observation F. Flexible sigmoidoscopy G. CT-guided core biopsy H. Serial imaging every 3 months I. PET-CT scan J. Surgical excision

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread as I sit here, watching my 82-year-old father, who has been receiving hospice care at home. It's been so hard to see him decline, and now, with everything going on, I can’t help but worry about how much longer he has with us. 

His breathing has changed significantly; sometimes it feels like he’s struggling, and I think I noticed a sort of pattern—like he’s taking these deep breaths and then pausing for too long. The nurse mentioned something about Cheyne-Stokes breathing, and it has me on edge. I just want to understand what this means for him. 

I’ve also noticed he’s hardly passing any urine lately, and his fingers and toes are starting to look a bit bluish. I can’t help but feel scared. I keep thinking about the signs that might tell us he’s nearing the end. I’ve read about things like loss of the gag reflex and the “death rattle” that can happen when someone is close to passing, and it fills me with such anxiety. 

I wish I could just pause time and hold onto these moments with him a little longer. It’s so hard to face the reality that he might not have much time left, and I feel completely lost trying to navigate this painful journey.
options: A. Decreased urine output B. Cyanosis of nail beds C. Cheyne-Stokes breathing pattern D. Loss of gag reflex E. Death rattle breathing F. Terminal agitation G. Inability to open eyelids H. Drooping of the nasolabial fold I. Fixed pupils J. Respiration without mandibular movement

question:
I can’t shake the worry that’s been building over the past few days. My little boy, just two and a half years old, started with a mild cough and a runny nose about two weeks ago. I thought it was just a common cold, but then, three or four days ago, things took a turn for the worse. He developed a fever and his cough intensified, and now he seems so fatigued. He’s not playing like he used to, and he barely touches his food.

It’s terrifying to see him like this, especially since he hasn’t had any serious health issues before, and he doesn’t go to daycare. We made the choice not to vaccinate him, and I can’t help but wonder if that’s coming back to haunt us. I rushed him to the doctor, and my heart sank when they examined him. He looked so ill, with a rapid breathing rate and a high heart rate. They mentioned his oxygen levels were low and that he had a high fever.

Then, they found something on the chest X-ray—a mass in his chest that they said might be serious. They mentioned pneumonia and a biopsy, but I can’t get the thought of what could be happening out of my head. I keep worrying about what this all means for him and if he’s going to be okay. I just want my happy, healthy boy back.
options: A. This tumor has a low likelihood of metastasizing to the bone B. This tumor is associated with elevated catecholamine metabolites in the urine C. This tumor originates from the epithelial cells in the mediastinum D. This child might develop periorbital ecchymoses E. This tumor’s origin is primarily mesenchymal in nature F. This tumor is generally localized and does not have a high risk of spreading in distance G. The biopsy findings are consistent with a thymoma H. Most of the times the tumors of this kind are thoracic in location I. This tumor is most commonly associated with respiratory symptoms only J. The tumor is likely to arise from lymphoid tissue in the mediastinum

question:
I can't shake the fear that something serious happened to me. Just yesterday, my wife found me unconscious in our living room. I can't remember a thing, but I woke up confused and only able to recognize myself. It’s terrifying. I’ve never experienced anything like this before. 

My wife said I had been drinking regularly, but I hadn’t touched alcohol in the last 24 hours. I’ve struggled with hypertension, but I thought I was managing it. When I finally came to, I felt this awful diffuse headache and muscle pain all over, especially in my left arm, which was so weak it was like it wasn’t even mine. I was so fatigued, and my speech was slurred. 

When we got to the emergency department, I was scared out of my mind. They took my vitals, and my blood pressure was a little high. They even found a bruise on my shoulder that I don’t remember getting. I was terrified that something was seriously wrong with my brain—what if it was a stroke? 

The doctors did all sorts of tests, and thankfully, they said everything looked okay. But why did this happen to me? What caused me to lose consciousness like that? It’s haunting me, and I can’t help but worry that it could happen again.
options: A. Hypoglycemic episode B. Seizure C. Conversion disorder D. Complex migraine E. Todd's paralysis F. Syncope G. Hemiplegic migraine H. Alcohol withdrawal I. Transient ischemic attack J. Hypertensive emergency

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of anxiety that’s been creeping in ever since my ACL reconstruction a year ago. I had the surgery to fix my torn ligament, and they used a piece of my patellar tendon. At first, everything seemed fine, but now I’m really struggling with this persistent instability during certain activities. It’s so unsettling! 

When I was in surgery, the doctors told me everything went well, and they were pleased with how stable my knee was at the time. But now, I feel like something isn’t right, especially when I try to run straight or make quick cuts. I can’t help but worry that maybe they didn’t reconstruct my ACL properly or that something else has gone wrong. 

Every time I attempt to push myself—like during a game or even just jogging—I feel this unsettling wobbliness in my knee. I’ve tried to convince myself it’s just part of the healing process, but the fear keeps gnawing at me. What if the graft has elongated, or what if they missed something crucial during the surgery? I really want to get back to my normal activities, but this instability is making it feel impossible. I’m left wondering if I’m ever going to feel secure on my feet again.
options: A. Positive anterior drawer test and instability with straight-line running due to graft elongation B. Positive pivot shift test and instability with cutting activities due to failure to reconstruct the anterolateral bundle of the ACL C. Positive valgus stress test with instability during lateral movements due to MCL insufficiency D. Positive dial test with rotational instability due to posterolateral corner injury E. Negative pivot shift but positive posterior drawer due to concomitant PCL injury F. Positive lateral pivot shift with instability during pivoting due to failure to restore anatomic footprint G. Positive pivot shift test and instability with cutting activities due to failure to reconstruct the posterolateral bundle of the ACL H. Positive Lachman's test and instability with forward running activites due to failure to reconstruct the anteromedial bundle of the ACL I. Positive sag sign with instability during descending stairs due to graft impingement J. Positive Lachman test and instability during deceleration due to improper graft tensioning

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. About three months ago, I noticed a strange lesion developing on my right lower lip. At first, it didn’t hurt, so I tried to brush it off, thinking it might just be a minor irritation. But now, it’s grown to about 3 centimeters and looks really concerning. I work outside a lot as a farmer, and I know I’ve been exposed to the sun far too often over the years. I’ve also been chewing tobacco for a long time, which I worry could be playing a role in this.

When I finally mustered the courage to see a doctor, they examined my neck and said there’s no swelling in the lymph nodes, which is somewhat reassuring. But still, I can’t help but think about what this could mean. I’ve read that lip lesions can be serious, and I know that squamous cell carcinoma can be a risk, especially with my history. 

I keep wondering about the chances of it being something more serious. The thought of needing more tests or treatments is nerve-wracking. I just want to know what’s really going on and if I need to be worried about this lesion. What if it’s something I can’t just ignore? I’m feeling so anxious about it all.
options: A. Lip carcinomas are the 2nd most common cancer of the oral cavity, after tongue cancer. B. Squamous cell carcinomas that arise in the upper lip have a similar prognosis to those originating in the lower lip C. Squamous cell carcinomas of the lower lip have a better prognosis than those of the upper lip. D. Tobacco chewing is not a significant risk factor for lip squamous cell carcinoma. E. Squamous cell carcinomas compose approximately 50% of all lip malignancies. F. Lip squamous cell carcinomas are more common in the upper lip than the lower lip. G. Basal cell carcinomas are more commonly found in the lower lip than the upper lip. H. Sun exposure is a greater risk factor for basal cell carcinoma of the lip than squamous cell carcinoma. I. Lip squamous cell carcinomas rarely metastasize to cervical lymph nodes. J. There is a 25% risk of harboring occult cervical lymph nodal metastases in this patient.

question:
I've been feeling really uneasy lately. It all started a few weeks ago when I noticed I was having trouble swallowing. At first, I thought it was just a minor issue, but it quickly got worse. I can't believe I'm now struggling to swallow both solid foods and liquids. It’s been terrifying. 

I went to see a doctor, hoping for some answers. My temperature was slightly elevated at 100°F, and I felt this strange sense of urgency and anxiety. I had just returned from South America not long before this all began, which made me even more worried. What if it was something serious? 

During the examination, the doctor checked my throat, ears, and eyes, and everything seemed normal, which I guess was a bit of a relief. My blood pressure and heart rate were okay, but I couldn't shake the feeling that something was seriously wrong. 

I felt so lost as the doctor went through various options for what to do next. I couldn't help but think about what might be causing this problem. The uncertainty is overwhelming, and I just want to find a solution to this swallowing issue. What if it gets worse? I can’t help but worry about what might lie ahead.
options: A. CT scan of the chest B. Empiric proton pump inhibitor therapy C. Trial of dietary modification D. Upper gastrointestinal series E. Capsule endoscopy F. Esophageal pH monitoring G. Manometry H. Barium swallow I. Chest X-ray J. Endoscopy

question:
I can hardly believe what happened to me. It all started when I found myself in a terrifying situation, and before I knew it, I was on the ground, feeling the sharp pain of multiple stab wounds. I remember the paramedics arriving, but I was so disoriented. They said I lost a lot of blood, which explains why I felt so weak and confused.

When I got to the emergency department, everything became a blur. I could barely respond; my Glasgow Coma Scale score was at a frightening 3. They had to intubate me and start IVs. I felt like I was slipping away as they rushed to prepare for surgery. They told me they were following a massive transfusion protocol, yet I could barely comprehend it. 

I remember feeling cold, so cold, despite the room being warm. My blood pressure was alarmingly low, and my pulse was weak. They were trying everything to stabilize me, infusing blood and platelets, but nothing seemed to change. I could hear the doctors discussing my condition, and I felt a wave of fear wash over me. What was happening? Why weren’t they able to help me? 

I just wanted to be okay, but all I could feel was this overwhelming worry about what was going to happen next. I was terrified that I might not pull through.
options: A. Septic shock due to contamination of wounds B. Tension pneumothorax C. Acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) D. Hypovolemic shock due to inadequate resuscitation E. Myocardial contusion F. Cardiac tamponade G. Cervical spinal cord transection H. Hypothermia-induced vasoconstriction I. Neurogenic shock J. Occult hemorrhage

question:
I've been feeling pretty anxious lately. For the past six months, I've had this nagging neck pain that just won't go away, and occasionally, I even get dizzy. It's strange because I can't pinpoint any trauma that might have caused it. I spend most of my day in front of a laptop as a software engineer, which probably isn’t helping. 

I also have diabetes and high blood pressure, which I worry might complicate things. I don't smoke, but I do enjoy a few beers on the weekends. I recently went to see a doctor about my neck pain, and during the examination, they found that my neck has some restricted movement. It’s concerning, especially when I think about what could be wrong.

The doctor mentioned something about a treatment they want to do called HVLA, but before that, they talked about needing to run some diagnostic tests first. I felt a wave of concern wash over me as I sat there wondering what it all meant. What if this is something serious? I just want to get back to feeling normal again without this constant worry hanging over my head. Will these tests help? What if they find something more severe?
options: A. Extension and flexion cervical x-ray B. Lhermitte's sign test C. Vertebrobasilar insufficiency test D. Cervical distraction test E. Cervical compression test F. DeKleyn's test G. Wallenberg test H. Adson's test I. Spurling test J. Hoffman's test

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of unease as I recount the past few days. It all started when I developed a fever, which quickly escalated. I found myself coughing up phlegm and struggling to breathe. It’s been two days now, and I’m really scared. Just eight months ago, I had a serious bout of bacterial pneumonia, and the thought of going through that again is terrifying.

My medical history isn’t exactly reassuring either—I’ve had fevers with thick nasal discharge multiple times over the last couple of years, each episode lasting a week or more. Thankfully, I stay on top of my immunizations, and I don't smoke or drink, but the distress I felt during my examination was palpable. The doctor said my temperature was quite high, and I was really struggling to catch my breath.

They listened to my lungs and noted crackles in my right lung. I felt a wave of anxiety wash over me. I can’t help but worry about what this all means. I’ve heard of conditions that could arise from repeated respiratory infections, and it feels like I’m being pushed into a corner. I just want to know why this keeps happening and what I might be facing next.
options: A. Left heart failure B. Chronic granulomatous disease C. Immune thrombocytopenia D. Cerebellar ataxia E. Autoimmune hemolytic anemia F. Recurrent sinopulmonary infections G. Opportunistic fungal infections H. Pathological fractures I. Malignant transformation J. Bronchiectasis

question:
I can't shake the feeling of dread as I recount what happened during the marathon. At 27, I thought I was in great shape, but everything changed in an instant. I remember pushing through the race when suddenly, confusion washed over me. I could barely think straight. The next thing I knew, I was in the emergency department, feeling disoriented and scared.

My temperature was sky-high at 105°F, and my heart was racing at 167 beats per minute. I could see the concern in the faces of the medical staff as they rushed around me. I had a history of seizures, but I never expected to have one here, in front of all these people. It felt surreal when I suddenly experienced a tonic-clonic seizure that lasted what felt like forever, but I later learned it was just a minute. 

They started IV fluids right away, but the worry didn’t leave me. I overheard them talking about my urine showing red blood cells, which only added to my anxiety. I couldn’t help but wonder what was happening to me. I felt so helpless, and the uncertainty of the lab results looming over me made it even worse. What could be wrong? I just wanted answers, but all I felt was fear.
options: A. Hypoglycemia B. Elevated creatine kinase C. Hypocalcemia D. Hyperkalemia E. Hyperchloremia F. Hypomagnesemia G. Hypophosphatemia H. Hyponatremia I. Metabolic acidosis J. Elevated lactate

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that washed over me after my fall from the ladder. It was just a routine chore, and suddenly, I found myself on the ground, clutching my right shoulder in pain. I made my way to the emergency department, worried about what might be wrong. I’ve always been healthy, with no significant medical issues, so this was all very unsettling.

I remember the doctor examining me and noting the bruising and tenderness around my clavicle. The pain was sharp, and I felt terrified about what they might find. After a chest x-ray, my heart sank as I learned about the nondisplaced fracture in my collarbone. But then, they mentioned a pulmonary nodule in my left lung. A solid one, with well-defined borders. I had no idea what that meant, but I couldn’t help thinking about the worst-case scenarios.

All I could focus on was managing my pain and wearing the sling they gave me, but the thought of that nodule kept creeping back into my mind. What if it was something serious? I’m left with so many questions and a heavy weight of worry, especially as I wait for the next steps. Do I need more tests? Will I have to face surgery? I just want to understand what’s happening and hope for the best.
options: A. Immediate surgical resection B. Bronchoscopy C. Reassurance D. Follow-up CT scan in 3 months E. Sputum cytology F. Serial tumor marker measurements G. Bronchoscopy with biopsy H. PET scan I. Follow-up x-ray of the chest in 6–12 months J. CT-guided needle biopsy

question:
I recently went to my primary care physician for an initial evaluation, and I can’t shake the feeling of worry that’s been creeping in. Thankfully, I felt fine overall, but I’ve been undergoing treatment with a specialist for something I can’t even talk about yet. My medical history is pretty straightforward, so it’s alarming to think that something might be off now.

I’ve been drinking a couple of alcoholic drinks every night, which has me concerned. I’ve had just three sexual partners in my life and I use oral contraceptives, but I’ve never been pregnant. During my visit, I noticed the doctor seemed particularly focused on my weight and the swelling in my hands—I could see it in my fingers, which were bent unnaturally.

My vital signs were stable, but my liver enzymes were elevated, and that’s what really has me on edge. I can’t help but wonder if my drinking could be catching up with me or if it’s something more serious, like an autoimmune issue. I just feel this weight of uncertainty and fear about what it all means. What if it’s something really bad? I keep thinking about all the possibilities and I’m just hoping for some clarity soon.
options: A. Early cirrhosis B. Chronic inflammation due to rheumatoid arthritis C. Nonalcoholic fatty liver disease D. Alcohol use E. Obesity F. Hormonal contraceptive effect G. Autoimmune disease progression H. Undiagnosed hepatitis infection I. Genetic predisposition to elevated liver enzymes J. Medication side-effect

question:
I took my 12-month-old daughter to her well-child visit, but honestly, I couldn’t shake off this nagging worry. She’s such a bright little girl—she crawls, sits up, and even responds to us when we call her name. She waves "bye-bye" and says "mama" and "dada" with real meaning. But despite all that, she just can’t stand. I keep replaying our playtime in my head, and it feels like a punch in the gut each time I remember her struggling to pull herself up. 

She was born healthy, at 40 weeks, and has always been on track with her growth. There’s no family history of developmental issues, which adds to my confusion. During the appointment, the doctor examined her, and while she was playful and interactive, the fact that she couldn’t stand—either on her own or with help—left me feeling uneasy. 

I can’t help but wonder what this means for her future. Should I be worried about something more serious? The doctor talked about next steps, but I’m just overwhelmed and scared. Do I need to get her tested for something like cerebral palsy or a genetic issue? Or should I simply wait and see? I just want to make sure she’s okay, and the thought of her struggling with this breaks my heart.
options: A. Order a brain MRI to evaluate for cerebral palsy B. Perform a comprehensive genetic evaluation for muscular dystrophy C. Refer to an orthopedic specialist D. Reassure the parents and recheck at 18 months E. Initiate early intervention services without further assessment F. Refer for a hearing evaluation G. Begin physical therapy H. Assess for nutritional deficiencies, including vitamin D deficiency I. Refer to a pediatric neurologist for developmental delay J. Administer the Ages & Stages Questionnaire

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that settled over me when I took my 7-month-old son to the emergency department. Just two hours before, he had been fine, but suddenly, he started vomiting—non-bloody and non-bilious, but alarming nonetheless. His little belly became distended, and he was crying inconsolably, which is so unlike him. I felt a knot tightening in my stomach as I held him, watching his high-pitched wails. 

He’s usually a healthy baby, always up-to-date on his vaccinations and hitting all his developmental milestones. But when we got to the ER, things only got worse. His temperature was 38°C, and his heart rate was racing at 180. I could see he was struggling to breathe, and the nurse said his oxygen levels were low. They examined him, and I could tell he looked really ill. They found a tender, swollen mass in his groin, and my heart dropped. 

I kept thinking, what’s happening to my baby? I felt completely helpless as the doctors talked about tests and possible next steps. I just wanted someone to make him better. I couldn't understand why this was happening, and I was terrified. What if it was something serious? The uncertainty was unbearable.
options: A. Abdominal radiography for obstruction B. Intravenous fluids and analgesia C. Observation and reassessment in 6 hours D. Pediatric gastroenterology consultation E. Administration of broad-spectrum antibiotics F. Supplemental oxygen G. Manual reduction of the groin mass H. Outpatient ultrasonography I. Emergency surgical consultation J. Incision and drainage of the right groin mass

question:
So, there I was, playing in a college football game, and everything was going great until I took a hard hit. Right after, I started feeling this strange numbness and tingling in my arm. At first, I thought it was just a normal reaction, but when it didn’t go away after a few minutes, I started to worry. 

I remembered hearing that if you have these kinds of symptoms, especially if they get worse or don’t resolve, it could be serious. I had experienced this kind of thing before, but never this intensely. I started thinking about the potential consequences of ignoring it. What if it was something more serious? What if I had done real damage? 

I couldn’t shake the thought of whether I should get an MRI before returning to play. I heard stories of players who rushed back and ended up with long-term issues. There were so many factors to consider—like if my symptoms were unilateral or if I had any signs of weakness or even loss of consciousness. I just felt this overwhelming concern about my health and safety. Should I be worried about the potential for cervical spine instability? I just wanted to make the right decision, but the fear of the unknown was really getting to me.
options: A. Player has had unilateral symptoms on two prior occasions. B. Unilateral symptoms do not resolve within 15 minutes. C. Symptoms and physical exam findings are found in both upper extremities. D. Symptoms associated with loss of consciousness. E. Unilateral symptoms with normal cervical spine imaging. F. Persistent neck pain associated with arm weakness. G. History of prior cervical spine surgery. H. Arm symptoms accompanied by bowel or bladder dysfunction. I. Evidence of cervical spine instability on physical exam. J. Recurrent symptoms occurring with minimal contact.

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of worry since I took my 6-week-old son in for a weight check. He was born at 38 weeks and 3 days, and everything seemed fine; I remember the delivery being smooth, and we were so relieved to have a healthy baby. But now, I'm feeling anxious. 

During his first few weeks, he did have some mild abdominal distention, but the doctors assured me it was nothing serious. He even passed meconium after a contrast enema, and we were sent home thinking everything was okay. He seemed to be thriving, eating 90 mL of formula every three hours, and he was so vigorous and energetic. His stools looked normal, and he had plenty of wet diapers.

But then, I learned his weight had dropped from the 50th percentile to the 3rd percentile! I can’t help but feel like something is wrong. The doctor examined him and said he looked well, with clear lungs and a soft belly, but I can’t shake my fears. His newborn screening came back normal, but I’m left wondering what to do next. The options for managing this situation all sound daunting, and I just want to make sure he’s okay. I’m terrified of missing something important and not knowing how to help him.
options: A. Perform sweat testing B. Refer for suction biopsy C. Order abdominal ultrasound D. Obtain serum electrolytes and blood glucose E. Perform 72-hour fecal collection F. Schedule follow-up weight check in 1 week G. Increase formula concentration to 24 kcal/oz H. Obtain serum IgA and tissue transglutaminase antibodies I. Switch to elemental formula J. Switch to extensively hydrolyzed formula

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of worry ever since I took my son to the clinic. He’s just 6 years old, and for the past month, he’s been having such a hard time with his bowel movements. It used to be that he would go every day without any issues, but now it’s only twice a week. I can still hear him straining and crying out in pain during those moments, and I feel so helpless. 

What’s worse is that he’s noticed red streaks when he wipes, which really scares me. He doesn’t complain about any stomach pain, but the straining and discomfort he’s showing—it’s just heartbreaking. I know he’s a bit overweight, and I’ve tried to encourage him to play outside more, but ever since he started primary school three weeks ago, he’s been glued to his video games instead. 

He eats fruits and vegetables, and he loves his meats, but he confesses that he hardly drinks water during the day. I can’t help but think that maybe that’s a big part of the problem. I just wish I knew what to do to help him. I’m worried that this isn’t just a phase and that there’s something more serious going on. I just want him to be healthy and happy again.
options: A. Recently starting primary school B. Dietary fiber deficiency C. Lack of exercise D. Diabetes mellitus E. Inadequate fluid intake F. Anal fissure development G. Obesity H. Withholding behavior I. Pain J. Hypothyroidism

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming worry that something is seriously wrong with me. It all started about a month ago when I began experiencing these awful intermittent fevers and chills. I’d feel utterly drained, and then, out of nowhere, it would fade away only to come back days later. I’ve been feeling so fatigued that I can barely get out of bed. 

Just two months ago, I was on a safari in Africa, and I took chloroquine as a precaution, even continuing it for four weeks after returning. I thought I was being responsible, but now I’m not so sure. I went to the emergency department yesterday because my fever reached 102°F, and my heart was racing at 103 beats per minute. They examined me, and I could see the concern in their eyes when they noted my pale conjunctiva and that my spleen was enlarged. 

I can't help but think that maybe the chloroquine wasn’t enough, or perhaps I’ve contracted something resistant to it. The idea of being exposed to parasites again after returning home is terrifying. I keep replaying everything in my mind, wondering if I missed any signs or if there’s something I could have done differently. I just want answers and to feel healthy again.
options: A. Cross-reactivity between different strains of Plasmodium B. Unprotected intercourse with a new partner C. Incorrect dosing of chloroquine prophylaxis D. Release of dormant hypnozoites from hepatocytes E. Infection with parasites resistant to chloroquine F. Mixed infection with multiple Plasmodium species G. Inadequate duration of chemoprophylaxis H. Reactivation of latent merozoites in the bloodstream I. Mosquito bites after returning to the United States J. Inadequate absorption of chloroquine due to gastrointestinal illness

question:
I can’t shake this unsettling feeling about what’s happening with my neck. It all started three days ago after a weekend of sailing. I was doing a lot of repetitive movements and looking up a lot, and suddenly I was hit with this sharp, constant pain in my neck. It’s been relentless, and I’d rate it an 8 out of 10. I’m really worried because it feels so intense and doesn’t seem to be getting any better.

I’ve been trying to convince myself that it’s just a strain, but I can't help but think about my brother and his slipped disc. I can’t ignore the anxiety that creeps in whenever I feel the pain. Thankfully, I don’t have any numbness or tingling in my arms, but that thought lingers in the back of my mind.

When I went to see the doctor, my vital signs were all normal, which was a relief, but the examination revealed something concerning. There was a tender spot on the right side of my neck at C5 that was really pronounced when I flexed. I can’t stop worrying about what it all means. What if this is something serious? I just want to understand what’s happening and how to make it better.
options: A. At the anterior aspect of the C4 transverse process B. Medial to the spinous process of C3 C. At the posterior lateral mass of C4 D. Superolateral to the spinous process of C6 E. Lateral to the spinous process of C6 F. At the transverse process of C5 G. Posterolateral to the articular pillar of C5 H. Immediately inferior to the spinous process of C5 I. Inferolateral to the spinous process of C4 J. Directly over the spinous process of C5

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that’s been creeping over me for the past couple of days. It started with this confusion that I just couldn’t explain—I felt lost and disoriented. To make matters worse, I noticed I hadn't urinated at all, which terrified me. I didn’t want to admit it, but I knew something was really wrong.

My medical history isn’t exactly clean. I’ve battled chronic kidney disease for years, and I manage hypertension and type 2 diabetes. I’ve also been living with HIV and hepatitis C. It’s a lot to handle, and now I was feeling so weak. I could hardly keep my eyes open when I got to the emergency department. My heart was racing, and my breathing felt shallow. The medical staff noticed my swollen legs and muscle weakness, and I felt their concern, which only fueled my anxiety.

As they ran tests, I couldn’t help but think about my past—surviving leukemia as a child after a stem cell transplant. I’ve been through so much, and now, with the arrhythmia and metabolic issues they found, I started to fear the worst. In the back of my mind, I’d always hoped to donate my organs one day, but now I wondered if my health would even allow it. The thought of not being able to help others in that way was almost too much to bear. I just want to get through this.
options: A. No absolute contraindications B. History of leukemia C. Uncontrolled hypertension D. Cardiac arrhythmia E. Metabolic acidosis F. Active alcohol use G. HIV infection H. Hepatitis C infection I. Chronic kidney disease J. Age over 55 years

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping in since my last appointment. I’m only 30 weeks pregnant, a first-time mom, and I thought this would be such a joyful time. But during my routine checkup, I mentioned to my doctor that I’ve been feeling unusually fatigued and have this constant urge to urinate. I’ve always been healthy, and I take my prenatal vitamins and folate every day, so I didn’t expect anything to be wrong.

Then, during the examination, my doctor measured my fundal height, and it only came out to 25 centimeters. I couldn’t help but feel a knot in my stomach. They did an ultrasound, and when the results came back, I learned that there was a proportional reduction in the measurements of my baby’s head, trunk, and limbs. I felt my heart sink. 

With my family history of diabetes in my mom and coronary artery disease in my brother, I can’t help but feel anxious about what this could mean for my baby. I’m just trying to understand what might be causing all of this. The uncertainty is so overwhelming, and I can’t help but worry about my baby's health. What if something is really wrong?
options: A. Antiphospholipid syndrome B. Toxoplasmosis infection C. Fetal alcohol syndrome D. Cytomegalovirus infection E. Placental insufficiency F. Cigarette smoking G. Rubella infection H. Gestational diabetes I. Parvovirus B19 infection J. Maternal malnutrition

question:
I can hardly believe what happened to me after that camping party. Just a few hours after I got home, I suddenly started vomiting uncontrollably. It hit me out of nowhere; one moment I was enjoying the evening, and the next, I was in the bathroom, feeling absolutely awful. The worst part? I didn’t have any diarrhea, which made me feel even more unsettled. 

I’ve never experienced anything like this before. Other than my lactose intolerance and some diet-controlled hypertension, I’ve always considered myself pretty healthy. When I finally decided to go to urgent care, I was still feeling shaky and worried about what could be wrong with me. My temperature was slightly elevated, and my heart was racing at 110 beats per minute, which just added to my panic. 

The doctors examined me, and all they found were some signs of tachycardia and generalized discomfort in my abdomen. I couldn't shake the feeling that something was really wrong. They mentioned food items that could be associated with this kind of reaction, and all I could think about were what I ate at the party. Was it the fish, or maybe the pasta salad? I just want to know why this is happening to me. The uncertainty is really weighing on my mind.
options: A. Fish B. Pasta salad C. Raw oysters D. Egg salad E. Soft cheese F. Refried rice G. Fresh fruit salad H. Undercooked steak I. Grilled chicken J. Canned tuna

question:
I recently went in for my annual work-related physical, and I can’t shake off this feeling of worry that's been creeping in. For the past three months, I’ve been experiencing this uncomfortable chest pressure, especially when I’m stressed at work or when I’m out playing racquetball with a friend. It’s this alarming sensation that lasts up to an hour after I exert myself, and I found that taking a nitroglycerin tablet really helps resolve it—though I borrowed that from a coworker, which feels a bit troubling.

I don’t have any history of heart issues, diabetes, or high blood pressure, but I was told two years ago that my cholesterol levels were elevated. They advised me to stick to a low-fat and low-cholesterol diet, which I’ve been trying to follow as best I can. 

During my visit, the doctor checked my blood pressure—130 over 70—and my heart rate was 68 beats per minute, but everything else seemed fine. Still, I can’t help but wonder about the possibility of having significant coronary artery disease. What if this pressure is a sign of something more serious? I’m honestly feeling quite anxious about it all.

I can’t believe what just happened. I’m a 15-year-old girl, and I was brought to the emergency department after having this terrifying episode. It lasted about two minutes, but it felt like an eternity. I was just hanging out after a sleepover, feeling pretty tired, when suddenly my left arm and leg started jerking rhythmically. I couldn’t control them at all. I remember looking to the left, and then everything got fuzzy. I was so scared because I lost control and even wet myself. 

When it finally stopped, I felt confused and weak on my left side, but thankfully that went away after about 15 minutes. I’ve had no fever or recent illnesses, and I definitely haven’t hit my head or used any substances. I was so worried about what was happening to me. 

When the doctors checked me out, my vital signs were normal, and I managed to answer their questions okay, but I still felt anxious. They did some tests, but I don’t know what they found yet. I just can’t shake this feeling of fear that something is seriously wrong. I keep wondering if I need more tests or if I should be admitted for observation. What if this happens again? I just want to feel safe and understand what’s going on with my body.
options: A. Perform MRI of the brain to evaluate for structural abnormalities B. Arrange for electroencephalography in the outpatient setting C. Admit the patient for 24-hour video EEG monitoring D. Reassure the patient and discharge to home with instructions to follow up if there is a recurrence E. Initiate therapy with sodium valproate and refer to a neurologist F. Prescribe a short course of benzodiazepines to prevent recurrence G. Conduct toxicology screening to rule out substance use H. Obtain an urgent neurology consultation for inpatient evaluation I. Start prophylactic antiepileptic therapy immediately J. Perform CT of the brain followed by a lumbar puncture

question:
For the past month, I’ve been dealing with these headaches that just won’t go away. At first, they were only occasional, but over the last two weeks, they’ve gotten so much worse. The pain is mostly on the left side of my head, and it’s intense. I’ve tried over-the-counter pain relievers, but they only help a little. Along with the headaches, I’ve been feeling nauseous and have even thrown up a few times. Bright lights make it worse too. 

I don’t have any trouble seeing or had any seizures, but I can’t shake this feeling of dread. Ten years ago, I had surgery for a brain aneurysm, and now I can’t help but worry that something is wrong again. When I went to the doctor, my blood pressure was a bit high, and they checked my vital signs, but what really caught my attention was when they examined my eyes. They noticed that my pupils were different sizes and that I had some drooping on the left side of my face. 

To top it all off, I’ve been feeling weak in my right leg; it’s so frustrating. I thought I was doing okay, but now I’m scared that something serious is happening. Why is this happening to me? I can’t help but think I need more tests done to figure out what’s going on.
options: A. Cup-to-disc asymmetry between the eyes B. Right-sided weakness C. Nausea and vomiting D. Photophobia E. History of posterior communicating artery aneurysm F. Subtle left-sided ptosis G. Elevated BMI H. Mid-dilated left pupil I. Lack of focal neurologic deficits in the upper extremities J. Left eye findings

question:
I can hardly believe what just happened. I’m 66 years old, and for the past two hours, I've been dealing with this terrible headache on the right side of my temple. It’s so bad that it feels like my head is going to explode. To make matters worse, my right eye has been blurry, and I can’t shake this feeling of dread. 

Over the last few weeks, I've had these headaches before, but they always seemed to get worse when I was eating. I try to manage my chronic shoulder and hip pain with ibuprofen, but now I’m starting to worry that something more serious is going on. When I got to the emergency room, my temperature was a bit high, and I felt so anxious as they took my vital signs.

The doctor examined me and noted that my right temple was tender. They also tested my vision—my right eye is only at 20/60, while my left eye is fine. I can’t help but think about what this all means. I’ve heard about issues that can arise with headaches and vision problems, and I’m terrified of what might be wrong. 

What should I do next? I feel so overwhelmed and just want someone to tell me what’s happening.
options: A. Neurology consultation before treatment B. Acetaminophen and rest C. Increase ibuprofen dosage D. Methylprednisolone E. Anticoagulation with heparin F. MRI with contrast of the brain G. Non-contrast CT scan of the head H. Temporal artery biopsy before starting treatment I. Supplemental oxygen and sumatriptan J. Ophthalmology consultation before treatment

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry after my surgery. I’ve been diagnosed with ankylosing spondylitis, and I knew I had a hip flexion contracture, but I never expected to go through a total hip arthroplasty. The surgery went as planned, and the doctors said everything was uneventful, which was a relief. But now, I find myself constantly thinking about what could go wrong.

I’ve read that with my condition, I could be at an increased risk for various complications, and it’s honestly terrifying. I keep wondering if I’m at risk for something like a dislocation or even a fracture. The thought of having a prosthetic joint infection really haunts me too. I try to follow the post-op instructions to the letter, but I can’t help but feel this nagging anxiety about what might happen next.

Every little ache or pain makes me second-guess myself and worry that something is wrong. I just want to recover without complications, but it feels like I’m walking a tightrope. I’m trying to stay positive, but it’s hard when my mind races with all these possibilities. I really hope I can get through this without any major setbacks.
options: A. Superior hip dislocation B. Trochanteric bursitis C. Anterior hip dislocation D. Periprosthetic fracture E. Prosthetic joint infection F. Inferior hip subluxation G. Acetabular component loosening H. Heterotopic ossification I. Posterior hip dislocation J. Sciatic nerve palsy

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread as I sit here reflecting on my health. I’m 65 and have been struggling with type 2 diabetes for over 30 years, but lately, things have taken a turn for the worse. Despite my efforts, my blood sugar management has been poor, and I’ve developed some serious complications—retinopathy, nephropathy, and neuropathy. 

In the last three months, I’ve lost about 7 kg, which really worries me. I’ve been feeling full after just a few bites, and there's this nagging discomfort in my stomach. To make matters worse, I’ve been dealing with nausea and vomiting after meals, which only gets better when I don’t eat. My bowel movements seem normal, but I can’t help but feel that something is off. 

I’m on insulin glargine at night and insulin aspart before meals, but it doesn’t feel like enough anymore. When I went to see the doctor, they found some mild tenderness in my abdomen and noted my weight—87 kg with a BMI of 29. It’s all just so overwhelming. Now, I’m left wondering what the next step is and what’s really going on inside me. What do I need to do to get to the bottom of this?
options: A. Abdominal ultrasound B. Capsule endoscopy C. Gastric manometry D. Hydrogen breath test E. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy F. CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis G. Scintigraphic gastric-emptying study H. Fecal occult blood test I. Hydrogen breath test for small intestinal bacterial overgrowth J. Serum gastrin level measurement

question:
I can't shake this nagging feeling as I think back to the last couple of days. It all started with this intense pain in my lower abdomen, right above my bladder, and I couldn’t ignore how painful it was to urinate. I thought it was just an annoyance at first, but it quickly worsened. I’m 78, and I already have my share of health issues—hypertension and COPD—and the fact that I’m paralyzed below the waist from a previous injury only adds to my worries.

When I ended up in the emergency department, I was running a fever of 101.7°F, which felt alarming. My heart was racing and I felt so weak. The doctors examined me and confirmed the tenderness in my abdomen. It was scary to think that my chronic urinary catheter might be causing more problems. They took samples for blood and urine cultures, which added another layer of anxiety as I waited for answers.

Now, I’m just left worrying about what’s happening inside my body. I know the doctors have options, but I’m scared. Will they give me the right treatment? What if this infection gets worse? I just want to feel better and not be in pain anymore.
options: A. Prescribe nitrofurantoin for 5 days B. Initiate vancomycin therapy alone C. Initiate ceftriaxone therapy D. Place bilateral percutaneous nephrostomy tubes E. Obtain non-contrast CT of the abdomen and pelvis F. Perform a suprapubic bladder aspiration G. Replace the indwelling urinary catheter H. Await urine culture results I. Administer ciprofloxacin orally J. Initiate piperacillin-tazobactam therapy

question:
For the past month, I’ve been feeling incredibly fatigued and lightheaded, and it’s really starting to worry me. As a daycare teacher, I need to be alert for the kids, but it’s been a struggle. I manage my diabetes with metformin, but recently I've noticed my periods have become much heavier. On top of that, I’ve been urinating more frequently and have gained some weight around my abdomen, which is so concerning. 

I found out that my cousin has von Willebrand disease, which adds to my anxiety. When I went to see the doctor, they took my vital signs, and thankfully, they seemed okay: my temperature was normal, but I couldn’t shake the feeling that something is wrong. 

Now, I’m left with so many questions. I just want to understand what’s causing these symptoms. Do I need more tests? I’ve heard about iron studies and other tests, but I’m terrified of what they might find. I can’t help but feel overwhelmed. What if this is something serious? I just want to feel better and be the teacher the kids need. What’s the next step for me?
options: A. Iron studies and ferritin level B. von Willebrand factor activity test C. Hemoglobin A1C measurement D. Hysteroscopy E. Coagulation profile F. Endometrial biopsy G. CT scan of abdomen and pelvis H. Pelvic ultrasound I. Parvovirus B19 IgM and IgG J. Complete thyroid function panel

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping in since my last doctor’s visit. I’m only ten, but it seems like my blood pressure readings are all over the place. Initially, during a routine check-up, it was 136/86 mm Hg, which didn’t seem too bad. But then the school nurse measured it at 134/82 mm Hg, and I just felt this knot in my stomach.

Lately, I’ve been getting these intermittent headaches, and today it was pretty bad—like a 6 out of 10 on the pain scale. When they took my blood pressure again, it was even higher—142/90 mm Hg. I was so worried; I could feel my heart racing. The doctor said everything else looked fine physically, and the urinalysis came back normal, which was a small relief, but I couldn’t help but think, what’s going on with me?

I just want to know what the next steps are. Should I be doing something different? I keep wondering if I need more tests or if they’re going to put me on medication. I just hope it’s nothing serious, and I can get this under control soon. It’s just so unsettling to think about.
options: A. Measure plasma catecholamines, metanephrines, and plasma renin activity B. Measure the level of thyroid-stimulating hormone C. Order comprehensive metabolic panel D. Order ambulatory blood pressure monitoring E. Schedule renal ultrasound within 1 week F. Start oral amlodipine therapy G. Recommend lifestyle modifications and follow-up in 1 month H. Refer to the emergency department I. Obtain echocardiogram to assess for left ventricular hypertrophy J. Perform fundoscopic examination

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that’s been hanging over me for the last few months. It all began with this swelling in my legs that just wouldn’t go away. At first, I thought it might be nothing, but as the weeks went on, the swelling got worse, and I started having trouble breathing, especially when I exerted myself. I’ve also been feeling nauseous and have lost my appetite completely, which led to me losing about 6 kilograms—I just don’t have the energy to eat.

I have a history of ovarian cancer that I was treated for with paclitaxel, and I’ve had two pulmonary embolisms in the past year. I’ve smoked for years and drink a couple of glasses of wine daily, but I never imagined it would come to this. When I went to see the doctor, I could barely keep up with the physical exam. I felt so fatigued and weak, and with my pulse racing at 115 beats per minute, I was terrified something was seriously wrong.

I noticed the yellowing in my eyes and the bloating in my abdomen that seemed to come out of nowhere. The doctor mentioned things like fluid buildup and pitting edema in my legs. What could be causing all of this? I’m just so worried about what it all means for my health moving forward.
options: A. Obstruction of the hepatic veins B. Superior vena cava syndrome C. Peritoneal carcinomatosis D. Right ventricular failure E. Liver cirrhosis F. Portal vein thrombosis G. Liver metastases H. Hypoalbuminemia I. Constrictive pericarditis J. Nephrotic syndrome

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of dread that’s been building up over the past week. It all started about seven days ago when I noticed a strange weakness creeping into my arms and legs. At first, I tried to brush it off, but it only got worse, and now I can barely move them at all. On top of that, I’ve been experiencing this awful tingling sensation in my extremities. 

Then, just six hours ago, I lost control over my bladder completely. I’m terrified. I rushed to the emergency department, hoping for answers but feeling more lost than ever. I mentioned to the doctor that I had a mild respiratory infection about a month ago, but I don’t think that could be related, right? I have no significant medical history, and my family history isn’t anything alarming either.

I’ve had a couple of sexual partners, and I’m not always careful, but I don’t think that’s what’s causing this. I used to smoke, but I quit a year ago, and I only drink occasionally. The doctors did some tests, but I’m still waiting to hear back. They told me my vital signs were stable, but I can’t help but feel that something is seriously wrong. Why is my body betraying me like this? What is happening to me?
options: A. Elevated oligoclonal bands in cerebrospinal fluid B. Elevated creatine kinase levels C. Anti-ganglioside antibodies in serum D. Abnormal nerve root potentials on EMG E. Pleocytosis on cerebrospinal fluid analysis F. Positive titers on a rapid plasma reagin test G. Demyelinating lesions on brain MRI H. Positive anti-acetylcholine receptor antibodies I. Anterior nerve root enhancement on spinal MRI J. Decreased peripheral nerve conduction velocity on an electrophysiological examination

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread since I was taken to the emergency department. It all started ten days ago when I developed a fever that just wouldn’t go away. My pediatrician referred me because my condition seemed to worsen. I’ve been feeling increasingly fatigued, and to make matters worse, I’ve lost about eight pounds without even trying. It’s so hard to explain how weak and drained I feel.

For the past month, I've also had this persistent dry cough that doesn't respond to my inhaler, which normally helps with my asthma. My parents seem worried too; they keep asking me if I’m okay, but I don’t feel okay at all. When I arrived at the hospital, I was nervous and pale, and they took my vitals. My heart was racing, and I felt so vulnerable. They examined me and found some swelling in my abdomen and lymph nodes, which only added to my anxiety. 

I overheard them talking about my lab results and how they were concerning, but I didn’t understand everything. They mentioned something about needing to run more tests, and that thought terrifies me. What could be wrong with me? I just want to feel better and not be stuck in this endless cycle of worry and illness.
options: A. Mantoux test (PPD) B. Lymph node biopsy C. Chest x-ray D. Echocardiogram E. Peripheral blood smear F. Antinuclear antibodies (ANA) G. Bone marrow biopsy H. CT scan of chest, abdomen, and pelvis I. Epstein-Barr virus titers J. Flow cytometry

question:
I can’t believe what's happening to me. For the last three days, my stomach has been so distended, and I feel full after just a few bites. It’s like my body is betraying me. I’ve been throwing up undigested food multiple times, and today it got worse—I actually vomited this dark brown stuff, which really scared me. 

This pain in my upper abdomen has been unbearable; it comes and goes but always gets worse at night or hours after I eat. I’ve been trying to manage it with over-the-counter antacids, but they barely help. I keep thinking about my dad—he had colon cancer, and I can’t shake the feeling that something is seriously wrong with me too. 

I’ve been smoking for 15 years, and I drink a couple of beers every day, which isn’t exactly great for my health. When I went to the emergency department, they took my vitals and noted that I was a bit dehydrated. The doctors pressed on my abdomen and found tenderness in my left upper quadrant, which made me even more anxious. They heard a strange splash sound when they rocked my hips, and I felt like I was falling apart inside. 

I just can’t help but worry about what this could mean for my future. What if it’s something severe? I need answers, and I need them fast.
options: A. Vascular compression of the duodenum B. Gastric volvulus C. Gastric outlet obstruction due to a bezoar D. Walled-off pancreatic fluid collection E. Neoplastic growth F. Scarring and fibrosis G. Chronic pancreatitis leading to obstruction H. Abnormal gastric rotation I. Peptic ulcer disease with perforation J. Inflammation and edema

question:
I've been feeling extremely uneasy for the past week, and I finally decided to seek medical attention. It started with blood in my urine, but there was no pain, which was oddly comforting at first. However, I've also been feeling more fatigued and lethargic than usual, and I couldn't shake the worry when I realized I had lost about 20 pounds over the last six months without even trying. 

I’ve always enjoyed a couple of beers on the weekends, but I've never smoked, so I thought I was doing okay. But then there's my job—30 years at a plastic chemical plant. I can’t help but think about the possible risks from that place. My dad passed away from a heart attack at just 62, and a distant relative had pancreatic cancer, which adds to my anxiety.

When the doctor did some tests, they confirmed blood in my urine, and a cystoscopy revealed a mass in my bladder. The biopsy came back with the worst news possible—it was malignant. I feel so overwhelmed and scared. I can't help but wonder which of my past exposures might have led to this. I keep replaying everything in my mind, convinced that my work and family history might have played a part in this terrifying situation. What does all of this mean for my future?
options: A. Chronic urinary tract infections B. Vinyl chloride exposure C. Exposure to ionizing radiation D. Aromatic amine exposure E. *Schistosoma haematobium* infection F. Chronic alcohol consumption G. Benzene exposure H. Long-term NSAID use I. Family history of pancreatic cancer J. Occupational asbestos exposure

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been consuming me. About four weeks ago, I decided to start jogging regularly, hoping to get in better shape. But shortly after I began, I started experiencing this nagging pain in my left lower leg. It’s not just the pain; my range of motion is really limited, and it’s been driving me crazy.

I finally went to the clinic because the pain was becoming unbearable. They did some imaging at the emergency department, which thankfully didn’t show anything serious, but I still feel uneasy. During the physical exam, the doctor noted some mild swelling in my left ankle and foot. It hurt when they tested my movement, especially when trying to move my ankle up and out. I can’t help but worry that something more serious might be going on.

Every time I try to move my ankle, it feels restricted, and I can’t help but think about what might be causing all this. I’m left wondering if there’s something I’m missing, something that could explain this discomfort. It’s just so frustrating, and I can’t help but feel anxious about what the next steps might reveal. What if it’s something that won't just go away on its own?
options: A. Restricted eversion of the subtalar joint B. Tightness of the gastrocnemius muscle C. Restricted anterior glide of the talus D. Tightness of the tibialis anterior muscle E. Posterior fibular head F. Point tenderness of the deltoid ligament G. Lateral malleolus displacement H. Increased plantar flexion of the ankle I. Posterior talus J. Medial tibial torsion

question:
I can hardly wrap my head around what happened when my baby was born. He arrived at just 34 weeks, weighing only 5 pounds 8 ounces. I hadn’t received any prenatal care, which I now realize was a huge mistake. The moment he was delivered, everything felt surreal and terrifying. He was cyanotic, gasping for breath, and his little body was struggling to breathe regularly.

As I held him, I noticed his low-set ears and broad auricles—features that seemed so out of place. His nasal tip was flattened, and I could see that his jaw was smaller than it should be, with the lower part pushed back. It broke my heart to see that he had a clubfoot on his right side. I felt an overwhelming wave of worry wash over me. 

What could be causing all of this? I couldn't shake the thought that something was terribly wrong. All I could think was how much I wanted him to be okay. I kept wondering if my lack of prenatal care had a role in this, or if there was something else that had gone wrong during the pregnancy. The doctors were talking about possible underlying causes, but all I could focus on was the fear of what the future holds for my precious baby.
options: A. Posterior urethral valve B. Pierre Robin sequence C. Chromosomal deletion syndrome D. VACTERL association E. Pulmonary hypoplasia F. Fetal alcohol syndrome G. Neural tube defect H. Maternal diabetes I. Amniotic band syndrome J. Oligohydramnios sequence

question:
I can't believe what just happened. I was out playing basketball, just having a good time, when suddenly I felt this intense pain shoot through my right shoulder. It happened so fast—I think I must have landed awkwardly after going for a rebound. Now, my shoulder is stuck, and I can't lower my arm at all. It's stuck up at this weird angle, around 140 degrees, and I’m really worried. 

I rushed to the emergency room, and the pain is just unbearable. I keep thinking, what if it’s something serious? I’ve heard about dislocations, and I can’t shake the feeling that my humeral head might have dislocated. I just hope it’s not too complicated. The doctors are going to take some X-rays, but I can't help but think about what they might find. What if it’s an anterior dislocation? I’ve read that those can be pretty common, but the thought of being sidelined for a long time really worries me. I just want to get back to playing without pain. I’m trying to stay calm, but it’s hard when you don’t know what’s going to happen next.
options: A. Inferior B. Posterosuperior C. Anterior D. Medial E. Anteroinferior F. Posterior G. Posteroinferior H. Anterosuperior I. Lateral J. Superior

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of anxiety as I think about everything that’s been happening to me. At just 16, I’ve never had a period, which has been incredibly worrying. I remember my doctor mentioning that I had partial labial fusion and clitoromegaly when I was born, and it always made me feel different. My mom had abnormal chin hair growth while she was pregnant with me, and I can’t help but wonder if that affected me somehow.

Lately, I’ve been battling severe acne, and it’s frustrating. I’m on isotretinoin and oral contraceptives, but nothing seems to help. I’ve also had these scary moments where I’ve fractured bones easily—like my wrist after a little fall three years ago and a spinal compression fracture from lifting a box last year. It makes me feel fragile and worried about my health.

To top it off, I stand tall at the 97th percentile for height, but my weight is only at the 50th percentile, which feels off balance. My doctor did a pelvic ultrasound, and while they said my uterus looked normal, they found multiple ovarian cysts. I’ve been so overwhelmed and confused, especially since I didn’t want to go through a pelvic exam. I just want to understand what’s going on with my body and why I’m facing all these challenges.
options: A. P450 oxidoreductase deficiency B. Androgen insensitivity syndrome C. 17β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase deficiency D. 17α-hydroxylase deficiency E. Aromatase deficiency F. Polycystic ovary syndrome G. Congenital adrenal hyperplasia H. 3β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase deficiency I. Steroidogenic acute regulatory protein deficiency J. 5α-reductase deficiency

question:
I remember the moment when my baby was born; it was supposed to be such a joyful occasion. But just 15 hours later, I found myself in the emergency department, terrified and overwhelmed. My little boy, who weighed 6.9 pounds, was so feverish and irritable. I felt like I’d failed him somehow. 

I had delivered him at home, and everything seemed fine until I noticed some blood-tinged fluid just four hours before labor. That didn’t feel right, but I brushed it off as normal. I hadn’t seen a doctor since my first trimester, and I worried about whether I had done enough for him. 

Now, as I looked at him, he appeared so lethargic and ill. The doctors mentioned he had a high fever of 39.9°C and seemed to struggle to breathe. My heart sank when they told me his pulse was racing and his blood pressure was low. He looked jaundiced, and I felt completely helpless. 

I couldn’t shake off the memory of the painful, itching genital vesicles I had weeks ago. What if that was somehow linked to all this? I just wanted him to be okay, but the doctors said he might have an infection, and I couldn’t help but feel a rising panic as I thought about all the possible causes. I just wanted to hold him and make everything better.
options: A. Herpes simplex virus B. Candida albicans C. Escherichia coli D. Streptococcus agalactiae E. Neisseria gonorrhoeae F. Haemophilus influenzae G. Enterococcus faecalis H. Group A Streptococcus I. Staphylococcus aureus J. Listeria monocytogenes

question:
I can't shake off this feeling of dread ever since I went to the emergency room. It all started when I noticed my skin turning yellow, and my stomach felt like a balloon ready to burst. I’ve never had any medical issues before, and I don’t take any medications or supplements. I thought it would just be a passing thing, but when I saw the doctor, I could tell something was seriously wrong.

They took my vital signs, and although everything seemed relatively normal, I was still so anxious. The doctor examined me and pointed out the yellowing of my eyes; I couldn’t believe it. The tenderness in my right upper abdomen was concerning, and I felt a wave of panic wash over me. 

Then came the news that they found something about my liver. I heard “Hepatitis B” mentioned, and my heart sank. I didn’t understand what it all meant, but the thought of having a serious liver condition left me feeling utterly helpless. I kept wondering if I had somehow gotten this infection without knowing. 

Now I'm just waiting for answers, and I can't help but worry about what this all means for my future. What if this is something chronic? Or worse? I just want to understand what’s happening inside my body.
options: A. No hepatitis B vaccination or infection B. Hepatitis B immune tolerance phase C. Reactivated hepatitis B infection D. Occult hepatitis B infection E. Inactive hepatitis B carrier state F. Resolved hepatitis B infection G. Early convalescent phase of hepatitis B H. Acute hepatitis B infection I. Hepatitis B vaccine response J. Chronic hepatitis B infection

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry. It’s been such a whirlwind since my cesarean delivery five days ago. Everything seemed to go well; my baby was born without any complications. But then, on the fourth day, things took a turn. I started experiencing this awful abdominal pain and a fever that just wouldn’t go down. The doctors put me on IV antibiotics—clindamycin and gentamicin—thinking it might be postpartum endometritis. 

I thought I was getting better when my abdominal pain lessened, but the fever kept spiking. They added another antibiotic, ampicillin-sulbactam, but now I’m feeling this low back pain, and the fever still hasn’t gone away. I’m so anxious about what this means. I’ve been trying to stay positive, but I can’t help but feel something isn’t right.

The doctors have checked my incision, and everything looks clean, but I can’t shake this unease. My blood tests showed some elevated white blood cells, and I can’t help but wonder if there’s something lurking that they haven’t found yet. It’s terrifying not knowing what’s causing all of this. I just want to be healthy and take care of my baby, but I’m starting to feel like I’m stuck in this cycle of worry. What if this gets worse? What if they can’t figure it out?
options: A. Add vancomycin to current regimen B. CT scan of the pelvis C. Dilation and curettage D. Continue current antibiotic regimen for 48 hours E. Endocervical swab culture F. Add metronidazole to current regimen G. Switch to meropenem monotherapy H. Perform laparoscopic exploration I. Obtain pelvic MRI with contrast J. Obtain MRI of the pelvis

question:
I can’t shake the worry that’s been gnawing at me since my last visit to the doctor. It’s been six weeks since I was hospitalized for that pulmonary abscess in my left lung. The whole experience was terrifying—I still remember the fear when they told me I needed a transthoracic tube drainage. I never thought I’d be dealing with something like this, especially since I’ve never smoked or used any drugs.

Now, at my follow-up appointment, I learned about the residual scar tissue in my lung. The chest x-ray showed this peripheral opacification, and I can't help but feel anxious about what it means for my future. I find myself constantly thinking about the potential long-term complications. What if this scar turns into something worse? 

I've been reading about the types of lung cancers that can arise from scar tissue, and it just adds to my anxiety. I’m scared of the unknowns—what if I’m at risk for a serious malignancy? I can’t shake the thought that this could lead to a life-threatening condition. I just want to understand what’s happening to my body and what I should be prepared for. The uncertainty is overwhelming, and I can’t help but feel like I’m on shaky ground.
options: A. Small round blue cells B. Lymphocyte-derived cells C. Pleomorphic giant cells D. Alveolar macrophage-derived cells E. Bronchiolar epithelial cells F. Neuroendocrine cells G. Squamous tumor cells H. Undifferentiated basal cells I. Spindle-shaped mesenchymal cells J. Glandular tumor cells

question:
I can’t shake off this nagging feeling of worry after my recent visit to the doctor. I’ve been feeling off for a while now—just not like myself. They decided to run some tests, and while they told me my serum vitamin B12, thyroxine, and thyroid-stimulating hormone levels were normal, I couldn’t help but feel anxious.
