Then came the lumbar puncture. I was terrified at the thought of it. As they prepared, I kept wondering what they might find in the cerebrospinal fluid. I mean, what if something was seriously wrong? I’ve read about so many conditions that could show up in those results. Would they find increased neuron-specific enolase or maybe even the presence of alpha-synuclein aggregates? 

I couldn't help but think about the possibility of elevated tau protein levels or oligoclonal bands. What if the analysis revealed something that would change everything? The doctor mentioned elevated white blood cell counts could indicate infection, and that terrified me. I just want to feel normal again. I spent the whole time waiting for answers feeling like I was teetering on the edge of something I couldn’t understand. I just hope whatever they find isn’t too serious.
options: A. Increased neuron-specific enolase B. Presence of alpha-synuclein aggregates C. Presence of oligoclonal bands D. Elevated tau protein levels E. Elevated beta-amyloid levels F. Decreased glucose concentration G. Decreased β-amyloid protein concentration H. Increased α-synuclein protein concentration I. Increased 14-3-3 protein concentration J. Increased white blood cell count

question:
This morning started off so normally, but I woke up with a sharp pain in my neck that I just can’t shake off. It feels like I can’t turn my head to the left at all, and it’s really frightening. I don’t even know how this happened—there was no injury I can think of, but I did fall asleep on the couch last night. Maybe that’s it? 

I tried taking some acetaminophen and putting a warm compress on it, but nothing seems to help. The pain just won’t go away, and now I’m really worried. I’ve never had anything like this before, and I don’t take any medications regularly. My medical history is pretty unremarkable, so why is this happening to me? 

When I went to see a doctor, they examined my neck and mentioned some tenderness and tightness in the muscles there. I just felt so helpless as they talked about the vertebrae and how they were resisting movement. It’s all so confusing, and I can’t help but feel anxious about what it all means. What if it’s something serious? I just want to understand what’s going on and how to make this pain go away.
options: A. C4–C5 ERLSR B. C4–C6 FRRSR C. C4–C6 NSRRR D. C5–C6 ERRSR E. C4–C6 NSRRL with somatic dysfunction F. C4–C6 ERRSR with compensatory rotation G. C4–C6 ERRSR H. C4–C6 FSRRR I. C5–C6 FSRRL J. C4–C6 NSRRL

question:
I took my 15-month-old son in for his routine well-child check-up, and to be honest, I was feeling a bit uneasy. The pediatrician didn’t seem overly concerned, but my heart sank when I heard that he speaks less than his siblings did at his age. I mean, he can walk independently and even climbs furniture, which is great, but it worries me that his language skills seem so limited.

I know he can say “mama” and “dada,” but that’s about it. No jargoning or any of that playful gibberish I’ve seen other kids do. He points to what he wants and waves goodbye, showing affection towards me, which I’m grateful for, but I can’t shake this nagging feeling. He’s hitting the growth milestones, tracking at the 50th percentile, and the doctor said everything looked normal during the physical exam, including his hearing.

Still, I can’t help but wonder if I’m missing something. I feel like I should be doing more to support him, especially with communication. Should I schedule more screenings, or is it time to consider speech therapy? The options swirling in my head are overwhelming. I just want to make sure he gets the help he needs before it’s too late.
options: A. Schedule developmental screening in one month B. Refer to pediatric neurologist for consultation C. Initiate speech therapy without further evaluation D. Refer for genetic testing to rule out developmental disorders E. Refer the child for physical and occupational therapy F. Order brain MRI to evaluate for structural abnormalities G. Refer the child for early intervention services H. Start behavioral therapy focused on communication skills I. Recommend increased reading time with parents J. Reassure the parents and schedule a reassessment in 3 months

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of dread as I reflect on the past few months. Out of nowhere, I’ve gained 10 kilograms, and it’s been really unsettling. I didn’t change my eating habits or exercise routine, yet my clothes are tight, and I feel so uncomfortable in my own skin. My libido has dropped significantly, which has left me anxious about my health and relationships. To make matters worse, I’ve been struggling to sleep, tossing and turning every night.

I’ve noticed my skin has turned oily and even started breaking out, which is unusual for me. I’ve always been a bit of a smoker—about a pack a day for the last decade—but I didn’t think it would lead to anything like this. I feel lethargic and my energy is just gone. When I went to the doctor, they found my blood pressure was high at 150/90, and I’ve got some concerning symptoms like stretch marks and bruises that appear easily on my arms and abdomen. 

I can’t help but worry there’s something seriously wrong. The doctor mentioned my blood sugar was high, too. I keep thinking about what might be behind all of this—could it be something with my adrenal glands? I feel so lost and anxious about what the future holds.
options: A. Adrenal adenoma B. Bilateral adrenal hyperplasia C. Pituitary adenoma D. Pulmonary tumor E. Ectopic ACTH-producing tumor F. Paraneoplastic syndrome-induced adrenal hypertrophy G. Retroperitoneal mass H. Hypothalamic tumor I. Adrenal cortical carcinoma J. Adrenal hemorrhage

question:
I can't shake off this feeling of anxiety about what’s been happening to me during volleyball practice. I’m 19 and have always been active, but lately, I've been experiencing these scary episodes. Just 10 to 15 minutes into our 3-hour practices, I start to feel this tightness in my chest. It’s like I can’t catch my breath, and then I end up in these awful coughing fits. It feels so overwhelming, and I can’t help but worry about what’s going on with my body.

I’ve always had seasonal allergies, but they’ve never interfered with my sports before. Now, after practicing five days a week, I feel like I’m struggling just to keep up. I went to see a doctor, and they checked me out but said everything looked normal. That didn’t help ease my mind at all. 

I’m really concerned about what this means for my volleyball career. I’m scared that if I don’t get this figured out, I might have to stop playing, which I can’t imagine. I just want to be able to play without feeling like I’m gasping for air. I keep thinking about what I should do next. Should I get medication? Maybe something to help me breathe better before practices? I just want to feel normal again.
options: A. Prescribe a daily low-dose inhaled glucocorticoid and an as-needed inhaled short-acting beta2-agonist B. Prescribe an inhaled short-acting beta2-agonist, to be used 15 minutes before exercise C. Initiate subcutaneous immunotherapy for seasonal allergies D. Recommend discontinuation of exercise until symptoms resolve E. Prescribe a long-acting beta2-agonist as monotherapy for symptom control F. Recommend the use of an antihistamine before exercise to address seasonal allergies G. Prescribe a leukotriene receptor antagonist to be taken daily H. Prescribe daily oral corticosteroids to reduce inflammation I. Prescribe a combination of oral theophylline and inhaled corticosteroids J. Prescribe an antihistamine, to be used daily

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry after what I went through recently. It all started two days ago when I began experiencing this intense urgency to urinate, along with a stinging pain each time. I figured it was probably nothing, but then the mild pain in my lower abdomen started, and I just couldn’t ignore it anymore. I rushed to the emergency department, feeling anxious about what could be wrong.

I was relieved that I didn’t have a fever or any chills, but that didn’t ease my mind. My heart was racing a bit when they checked my vital signs. I felt so uncomfortable during the physical exam, especially when they pressed on my abdomen. They said there was some tenderness, but thankfully, no severe signs that would suggest something worse. 

I’ve been on a combined oral contraceptive and started taking methimazole two weeks ago for my Graves disease, and I couldn't help but worry about how that could be affecting me. I just want to know what's causing all this discomfort and what the next steps are. Will I have to take more tests? I’m just really anxious about what might be happening inside my body.
options: A. Complete blood count with differential B. Urinalysis with reflex to urine culture C. Serum creatinine measurement D. Discontinuation of methimazole E. CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis F. Blood cultures G. Pelvic examination H. Empiric nitrofurantoin I. Renal ultrasound J. Thyroid function tests

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry since I took my 5-year-old son to the clinic. It all started five days ago when I noticed his face was swollen. At first, I thought it might be something minor. But then I remembered that just two weeks before, he had a sore throat that seemed to clear up on its own. 

When we got to the clinic, I felt my heart race. His temperature was normal, but his pulse was elevated, and I was anxious to hear what the doctor might say. The examination revealed concerning signs: there was pitting edema all over his arms and legs, and around his eyes, too. His abdomen looked a bit distended, and I couldn’t help but feel panic rising in my chest.

The doctor mentioned various tests, and while I tried to stay calm, I couldn’t help but worry about what could be happening inside his body. The thought of him possibly needing a renal biopsy filled me with dread. I just kept thinking about how innocent he is and how this all seems so unfair. I feel lost and scared, hoping for answers while wrestling with the fear of what might lie ahead.
options: A. Tubular atrophy and interstitial fibrosis B. Mesangial cell proliferation C. Crescentic formation in Bowman's space D. Effacement of foot processes of podocytes on light microscopy E. Normal light microscopy findings F. Immune complex deposits in the subepithelial space G. Thickening of the glomerular basement membrane H. Deposits of IgG and C3 at the glomerular basement membrane on immunofluoresence I. Wire loop lesions in the glomerular capillaries J. Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of anxiety since my last mammogram. I'm 50, and when the results came back, they told me there was this developing asymmetry that they hadn’t seen before. It’s terrifying to think about what that could mean. They didn’t find anything on the ultrasound, which is somewhat reassuring, but it’s still so unsettling. 

Now, I’m left wondering what the next steps should be. I’ve been going back and forth in my mind about whether I should just wait and see what happens or if I should push for something more invasive, like a biopsy. I mean, I want to be proactive, but the thought of having a procedure done is daunting. 

The doctors mentioned options like additional mammographic views or maybe even an MRI, but I just can’t help but feel overwhelmed. It’s hard not to think about the worst-case scenarios. I keep telling myself to stay calm and that they’re just being cautious, but it’s so hard to not let my mind spiral. I just want to know what this asymmetry means and if it’s something serious or if I can just breathe a little easier. I really hope the next steps lead to some clarity.
options: A. Clinical correlation and observation B. Vacuum-assisted biopsy C. Spot compression mammographic views D. Six month follow up E. Stereotactic core biopsy F. Contrast-enhanced mammography G. Breast MRI H. Digital breast tomosynthesis I. Routine screening mammography J. Fine needle aspiration

question:
I can't shake this feeling of dread as I sit in the emergency department. For the past week, I’ve been struggling to catch my breath, especially when I try to do anything even slightly physical. It’s terrifying. I don’t have chest pain or feel lightheaded, but this persistent cough is alarming. It’s producing white sputum, and I can’t help but think something is seriously wrong.

I’ve dealt with hypertension and diabetes for years, but this feels different. I’ve smoked for a long time—over 50 years—and now I wonder if that’s finally catching up with me. I walked in here feeling anxious, and the nurse took my vitals; my temperature read 101°F, my blood pressure is high, and my heart is racing at 110 beats per minute. They strapped me to a non-rebreather mask, and I can barely breathe, my oxygen levels are so low.

Looking around, I can see the concern in the staff's faces as I struggle to inhale. I feel like I’m in distress, and every breath is a laborious task. The wheezing in my chest is unnerving, and I can feel my body’s weight pressing down on me, both physically and mentally. I just want to know what’s happening and how to fix this. What are they going to do next?
options: A. Alpha-1 blocker B. Beta-2 agonist C. Oxygen therapy alone D. Antibiotics E. Combined inhaled corticosteroid/long-acting beta agonist F. Muscarinic blocker G. Methylxanthine derivative H. Leukotriene receptor antagonist I. Alpha-2 blocker J. Phosphodiesterase-4 inhibitor

question:
I recently had my first visit to the clinic for a checkup, and I can’t shake off the feeling of unease. My parents were there with me, and they talked about my childhood, mentioning how I had to go through physical therapy for hypotonia and struggled with gross motor skills. It’s always been tough for me, especially in school, where I’ve been diagnosed with learning disabilities and have a hard time focusing.

As the doctor checked my vital signs, I felt a wave of anxiety wash over me. Everything seemed normal, but I couldn’t help but worry. I’m in the 85th percentile for height and 75th for weight, which sounds good, but then there’s the fact that I haven’t gotten my period yet. The doctor noted my breast development and pubic hair, which are supposedly at Tanner stage 3, but that doesn’t ease my mind. 

During the exam, the doctor pointed out my epicanthal folds and how my joints are hyperextensible. I couldn’t help but wonder what that meant for me. The doctor mentioned something about potential genetic disorders, and my heart raced. What if I have something serious? I just want to understand what’s going on with my body, but the uncertainty is overwhelming.
options: A. Triple X syndrome B. Turner syndrome C. Marfan syndrome D. Fragile X syndrome E. Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome F. Prader-Willi syndrome G. Klinefelter syndrome H. Noonan syndrome I. 22q11.2 deletion syndrome (DiGeorge syndrome) J. Williams syndrome

question:
I can't shake the feeling of dread that washed over me last night. I was jolted awake by this unbearable pain in my right toe—it felt like something was crushing it. It was alarming enough to rush to the emergency department. I’ve never experienced anything like it before, and the pain was so severe that I couldn’t even bear to touch it.

When I got there, the doctors examined my toe. It was swollen, red, and warm to the touch, and just moving it was impossible. I’ve been a long-distance truck driver for years, and I thought I was relatively healthy, but my history of smoking a pack a day and binge drinking on weekends has me worried. I’ve had an appendectomy when I was younger, but nothing else serious, so this felt out of the blue.

The doctors talked about the signs they were seeing, and I could sense their concern too. They mentioned something about crystals in the fluid they took from my joint, and I couldn’t help but feel terrified. What could this mean? I’ve always thought of myself as resilient, but now I’m facing questions about my health that make me anxious. I just want to understand what’s happening and why this pain hit me so suddenly.
options: A. Impaired uric acid metabolism due to genetic mutation B. Overproduction of uric acid due to enzyme deficiency C. Organic acids competing with urate for tubular secretion D. Secondary hyperuricemia due to hematologic malignancy E. High-purine diet F. Increased dietary fructose intake G. Alcohol-induced lactic acid accumulation H. Increased renal reabsorption of urate I. Decreased renal clearance of urate due to dehydration J. Chronic lead exposure impairing renal urate excretion

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping in for the past two months. My husband finally insisted I see a doctor because I’ve been so persistently sad. I’ve had trouble sleeping and oddly, I’ve found myself eating more than usual, which feels so unlike me. This isn’t the first time I've felt this way, though. I had similar episodes nine months ago and even two years back, each lasting about four months. 

I remember those times clearly; I would have bursts of energy, needing only about three hours of sleep, and I often forgot to eat altogether. It's been such a rollercoaster, especially since I just got a promotion at work five months ago as a stock market trader. I still manage to keep up my yoga classes with friends, but everything feels so heavy right now. 

When I was evaluated, I could tell my affect seemed blunted, but I was adamant—I don’t feel suicidal and I’ve never used drugs. I just feel trapped in this cycle. I can't help but worry about what this all means. What’s happening to me? I wish I could pinpoint what’s going on and find a way to feel like myself again.
options: A. Recurrent brief depressive disorder B. Persistent depressive disorder (dysthymia) C. Bipolar I disorder D. Bipolar II disorder E. Cyclothymic disorder F. Bipolar disorder with rapid cycling G. Seasonal affective disorder H. Adjustment disorder with depressed mood I. Borderline personality disorder J. Major depressive disorder with atypical features

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of worry that’s been creeping in since my last doctor’s visit. At 15, I thought I’d be further along with puberty by now, but it seems like I’m stuck. I remember starting to develop body odor and getting pubic and underarm hair when I was 11, but since then, it’s like nothing has happened. I haven’t experienced any morning erections, my voice hasn’t changed, and thankfully, I haven’t had any acne. 

I’ve always been a bit different, especially with my speech delay as a kid, but overall, I thought I was healthy. At the appointment, the doctor measured me—I'm 175 cm tall and weigh 65 kg, which seemed okay, right? But then they examined me and found that my testicles were only 5 mL in size and noted some mild gynecomastia. The doctor seemed concerned, especially when talking about my hormone levels, which are way lower than normal.

Now, I’m left wondering what comes next. They mentioned various tests, and I can’t help but feel anxious about what they might find. Am I going to be okay? Will I ever catch up to my peers? I just want answers, but the uncertainty is really weighing on me.
options: A. Testicular ultrasound B. Gonadotropin-releasing hormone stimulation testing C. Bone density assessment D. Anti-Müllerian hormone level testing E. Serum prolactin level measurement F. Karyotype testing G. Androgen receptor mutation analysis H. MRI of the pituitary gland I. Semen analysis J. Thyroid function testing

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry as I reflect on my daughter’s recent check-up. She’s only six, and while she’s generally a happy and healthy child, I’ve been increasingly concerned about her weight. She’s such a picky eater, always opting for chicken nuggets and French fries, which I fear isn’t the best for her. 

During the visit, I noticed the mild acne on her cheeks and forehead, and I couldn't help but think it might be related to her reluctance to bathe. It’s hard to believe she’s already in kindergarten, and thankfully, her teacher says she interacts well with her classmates, which eases my mind a bit.

What really caught me off guard was the examination. Her height and weight are above the 95th percentile, which sounds alarming. The doctor mentioned some physical signs—like the breast tissue and the hair growth that seemed a bit early for her age. They also talked about her bone age being more advanced than her actual age. I felt a wave of anxiety wash over me as I heard the doctor mention hormone levels that were definitely outside the normal range.

Now, I’m left wondering what the next steps are. I’m so worried about what this all means for her future. What if something is seriously wrong? I just want to make sure she’s okay.
options: A. Karyotype analysis B. Thyroid function tests C. Dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate levels D. Bone marrow biopsy E. Serum testosterone levels F. 17-hydroxyprogesterone levels G. Head computed tomography (CT) H. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the brain I. Pelvic ultrasound J. Serum insulin-like growth factor-1 (IGF-1) levels

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry. My 10-year-old son has been complaining about back pain for the past week, and I just can’t figure out what’s wrong. He hasn’t had any falls or accidents that I know of, but he did start carrying a much larger backpack for school. Maybe that’s it? 

When we went to the pediatrician, I could see the concern in her eyes as she examined him. She noted some tenderness along his back, especially around the area where his spine meets his shoulder blades. I could see he was tense and uncomfortable. It seemed like the muscles were tight, and she mentioned that one side of his back felt different from the other. It’s terrifying to think something might be wrong.

She also pointed out that even when he bent forward or backward, the unevenness in his back didn’t change at all. Thankfully, she said there were no neurological issues and that his muscle strength was fine. But still, I can't help but feel anxious about what this could mean. What’s going on with his back? I just want to make sure he’s okay, and I can’t help but feel like I should’ve noticed something sooner. Every little detail makes me worry more. What if this is serious?
options: A. T1-T3 neutral, sidebent right, rotated left B. T1-T3 extended, sidebent left, rotated right C. C6-T1 neutral, sidebent left, rotated right D. C6-T3 neutral, sidebent left, rotated right E. T1-T3 flexed, sidebent left, rotated right F. T1-T3 neutral, sidebent left, rotated right G. T1-T5 neutral, sidebent left, rotated right H. T2-T4 neutral, sidebent left, rotated right I. T3-T6 neutral, sidebent right, rotated left J. T1-T3 flexed, sidebent right, rotated left

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of unease. At 72, I’ve always tried to stay active, but for the past eight months, I’ve been experiencing this alarming chest pressure and pain in my left arm whenever I exert myself. It’s only during significant physical activities, and thankfully, it goes away quickly when I rest, but it’s still terrifying. I’ve got a history of hypertension and high cholesterol, so I’ve been on medications like pravastatin, amlodipine, and aspirin. 

Just the other day, I went in for a check-up, and they did a physical exam. Everything seemed normal—no fluid buildup or heart murmurs, which was a relief, but still, I felt uneasy. They ran an ECG, and it looked fine, but during the exercise test, I was so anxious. I managed to last 11 minutes, but they found some concerning signs in the imaging, indicating a reversible issue with blood flow in my heart. 

Now, I’m left wondering what comes next. They mentioned starting some new medications, but I can’t help but worry about whether I need more tests. Should I undergo a stress echocardiogram or something more invasive? The uncertainty is weighing heavy on me, and I can’t shake this feeling that something isn’t right.
options: A. Stress echocardiography B. Exercise stress echocardiography C. Cardiac MRI with stress perfusion D. Myocardial viability study E. Pharmacological nuclear stress test F. Dobutamine stress test G. 24-hour Holter monitoring H. Coronary CT angiography I. No additional investigation J. Cardiac catheterization with coronary angiography

question:
I can’t shake the feeling of dread that washed over me when my roommates brought me to the emergency room. It all started a few days ago when finals hit, and the stress started to pile up. I had been feeling increasingly withdrawn, but that night was different. I remember sitting at my computer, feeling this intense irritation bubble up inside me. I yelled at my screen before I actually broke it in a fit of frustration. 

Then I went to the gym for hours, trying to work off the anxiety, but it didn’t help. At some point, everything spiraled out of control. I felt so agitated and my heart was racing like I couldn’t calm down. When I got to the hospital, it was like I was in a fog. I was sweating profusely, my speech was rapid, and I couldn’t focus. I felt trapped in my own mind, acting aggressively without really understanding why.

They ended up treating me with some medications and put me in soft restraints. I could see the worry in my friends' faces, and it made me feel even more anxious. After what felt like forever, I finally started to calm down, but I couldn’t help but wonder what was happening to me. I’m still trying to piece together those chaotic hours, and I’m scared about what this all means for my health.
options: A. Methamphetamine intoxication B. Serotonin syndrome C. Alcohol withdrawal delirium D. Phencyclidine intoxication E. Acute mania with psychosis F. Cocaine intoxication G. Lisdexamfetamine intoxication H. Anticholinergic toxicity I. Hyperthyroidism-induced psychosis J. Bath salts (synthetic cathinone) intoxication

question:
I can’t shake off this feeling of dread as I sit in the clinic with my 4-month-old daughter. She’s been so lethargic lately, and it’s terrifying to see her struggle to thrive. I remember the joy of her birth; she came into this world after a smooth pregnancy, delivered at 39 weeks. But now, my heart sinks as I think about her weight and height being below the 10th percentile. 

The doctor examined her, and I noticed their concerned expression as they looked at her. They mentioned her pallor and some unusual features—like her flattened nasal bridge and the way her thumbs only have three phalanges. I can’t help but feel a wave of panic. 

When they took her vital signs, I felt a chill run down my spine. Her pulse was racing at 150 beats a minute, and I couldn’t understand why everything seemed so off. The doctor is talking about lab results, mentioning things like a low hemoglobin level and elevated erythropoietin. I just keep thinking, what’s wrong with my baby? 

I can’t help but feel lost and worried about what this all means for her future. I just want to understand what’s happening and hope that they find something that can help her.
options: A. Folate metabolism B. DNA repair mechanisms C. Heme Synthesis D. Ribosome Synthesis E. Iron transport F. Mitochondrial function G. Pyrimidine synthesis H. Globin chain synthesis I. Erythropoietin receptor function J. Erythrocyte cytoskeleton

question:
I can’t shake the worry I felt when my 2-year-old son started showing alarming symptoms. It all began with him vomiting and having bloody diarrhea. He seemed so irritable, and then, to my horror, he became lethargic. It was terrifying to see him like that, especially since he hadn’t been drinking enough fluids. I remembered his medical history—he was born premature at just 33 weeks, weighing only 1900 grams. I never thought that his early arrival would come back to haunt us like this.

When we rushed him to the emergency department, I was overwhelmed with panic. The doctors examined him and noted his crying, the pronounced distention in his abdomen, and how tender it was when they touched it. I couldn’t help but think about the hepatitis B vaccine that we had deferred at birth, wondering if that decision had contributed to his current state.

As I sat there watching him struggle, the gravity of the situation hit me. The doctors were discussing necrotizing enterocolitis, and I remembered hearing that it’s more common in premature infants like him. I felt a wave of guilt wash over me, worrying about whether I could have done something differently. All I could do was hope he would be okay and that we would get answers soon.
options: A. This condition is caused by a congenital malformation of the gastrointestinal tract B. Necrotizing enterocolitis is more common in breastfed infants C. Infants born at term are at the highest risk for this condition D. This is a condition that happens in premature children and the more premature the child the earlier after birth it happens E. In term infants this generally happens within the first week of life F. 50% of premature children or those born 1500 g or less are effected G. This condition is unrelated to the child’s gestational age or birth weight H. This condition is typically self-limiting and resolves without medical intervention I. The risk of this condition decreases with formula feeding J. The condition is primarily due to a genetic predisposition rather than environmental factors

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry after my recent check-up. I’m 61, and I thought I was doing okay with my health, managing my atrial fibrillation, hypertension, and high cholesterol with my medications—rivaroxaban, lisinopril, and simvastatin. But then I got this routine blood test back, and it showed that my platelet count was alarmingly low. The technician even mentioned something about platelet clumping in the blood smear; that sounds serious, right?

I’ve been using quinine for my leg cramps, but I never imagined it could lead to something like this. I don’t have any history of high-risk behaviors, like unprotected sex or drug use, and my family doesn’t have any bleeding disorders. When I went for my physical, everything seemed normal—my vital signs were stable, and there were no signs of bruising or swelling. But this low platelet count has me feeling anxious. 

I can’t help but think about what could be causing it. The doctor mentioned a few possibilities, but I’m left feeling uneasy and confused. What does this mean for my health? Will I need more tests or treatments? I just want to know what’s happening to my body and how I can fix it.
options: A. Immune thrombocytopenic purpura B. Pseudothrombocytopenia C. Hypersplenism causing platelet sequestration D. Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia E. Quinine-induced immune thrombocytopenia F. Bone marrow suppression due to medication toxicity G. Immune thrombocytopenia H. Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura I. Drug-induced thrombocytopenia from rivaroxaban J. Disseminated intravascular coagulation

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of dread as I sit in the waiting room, gripping my stomach, which feels like it’s in knots. The pain is unbearable, and I can’t even bear the thought of anyone touching my abdomen. I’ve had issues before, especially with my history of peptic ulcers and my struggles with alcohol, but this feels different—much worse. 

I can’t help but worry that something serious is happening. The thought of spontaneous bacterial peritonitis keeps creeping into my mind, and I’m terrified of what might be found. I remember the doctor trying to examine me, but I just couldn’t let them press on my belly; it hurt too much. 

I’ve heard about some signs that might indicate a serious problem, like if I had absent bowel sounds or if they could feel something unusual in my abdomen. What if they find something like Cullen's sign or any other alarming symptoms? I just want to know what’s going on, but the fear of what they might say is almost paralyzing. I can’t focus on anything but this pain and the anxiety of waiting for answers. Will I be okay?
options: A. Pain that improves with movement B. Gentle pressure at the costovertebral angle elicits pain C. McBurney's point tenderness D. Absent bowel sounds E. Shifting dullness on percussion F. Murphy's sign positive G. Guaiac positive stool H. Cullen's sign present I. Rebound tenderness on light palpation J. Forced cough elicits abdominal pain

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that’s been creeping in over the past three months. It all started with this nagging discomfort in my left leg. At first, I thought it was nothing, just some cramping in my calf after I walked a couple of blocks. But it hasn’t gone away; in fact, it’s been getting worse. I have to stop and rest before it eases up, which is really starting to concern me.

I’m 65 and have type II diabetes and hypertension, which already puts me at risk for various health issues. My mother had a pulmonary embolism when she was just 55, and I can’t help but think about that. I quit smoking five years ago, but now I’m left feeling anxious about what could be happening in my body. 

When I visited the clinic, they checked my vital signs, and everything seemed stable, but I noticed the blood pressure in my left ankle was unusually high. Both of my legs looked normal, no swelling or discoloration, but the cramping is really alarming me. I keep wondering what’s next—what tests do I need? I just want to understand what’s going on and make sure I'm not ignoring something serious. The uncertainty is really weighing on me.
options: A. Segmental pressure measurements B. Doppler ultrasound C. Digital subtraction angiography D. Pulse volume recording E. Toe-brachial index F. Transcutaneous oxygen pressure measurement G. MR arteriography H. CT angiogram I. Exercise ankle-brachial index J. Venous plethysmography

question:
I can’t shake off this worry that’s been creeping in over the last month. It all started with some tingling in my right hand, which I initially brushed off as nothing too serious. But then, the tingling turned into numbness, and soon I was dealing with this constant, nagging pain in my shoulder. I’m a carpenter, so I figured it might be work-related, but now I’m really starting to panic. 

The pain has gotten worse, and it’s at a 6 out of 10 even when I’m resting. But the moment I try to move my arm or hand, it shoots up. I can barely grip anything with my right hand anymore; it feels so weak. 

When I went to the clinic, I felt so vulnerable explaining all of this. The doctor seemed concerned too, especially when they examined me and found that my grip strength was significantly reduced. They mentioned something about my shoulder and neck muscles being tense, and I just felt this knot of anxiety in my stomach. 

I’ve never experienced anything like this before, and I can’t help but worry about what it all means. What’s causing this? Is it going to get worse? I just want to get back to my normal self, but right now, I feel so lost and uneasy.
options: A. Spurling test B. Adson test C. Tinel's sign D. Military brace test E. Costoclavicular test F. Upper limb tension test G. Phalen's test H. Wright test I. Allen test J. Phalen test

question:
I can’t shake off this nagging worry about my health. A month ago, I fell while shoveling snow and hurt my lower back. I thought it would get better, but it hasn’t. I went back to the clinic for a follow-up, and while I did receive some osteopathic manipulative treatment, my pain has only slightly improved. It’s so frustrating!

During the exam, the doctor mentioned that my L5 vertebra is rotated to the right, which sounds serious. They said it becomes more aligned when I bend forward, but honestly, that didn’t reassure me much. To make matters worse, I found out that the right sacral sulcus is deep, while the left side is lower. The rest of the exam seemed fine, but I can’t help but feel like something is still off.

Now, I’m left wondering which additional test might confirm what’s happening with my sacrum. I keep thinking about all the options they talked about, and it’s hard not to feel anxious. What if it’s something worse? I just want to feel normal again, but this uncertainty is really weighing on me. I keep replaying the visit in my head, hoping for any hint that things will improve soon.
options: A. Negative sphinx test B. Positive Gaenslen's test on the left C. Positive Patrick's test bilaterally D. Positive Stork test on the right E. Positive straight leg raise on the right F. Positive sacral spring test G. Positive standing flexion test on the right H. Positive FABER test on the right I. Positive ASIS compression test on the right J. Positive seated flexion test on the left

question:
I can't shake off this nagging worry that something is seriously wrong with me. For the past six months, I’ve been battling a cough that just won’t go away. It feels like every time I exert myself—even just walking up the stairs—I'm gasping for air. Sometimes, the cough brings up clear sputum and there’s this wheezing that’s really unsettling. 

I thought it was asthma, so I’ve been following the treatment plan. I’ve tried inhaled steroids, a leukotriene blocker, and bronchodilators. I even took multiple rounds of antibiotics, thinking maybe it was an infection, but nothing has helped. I’m relieved I haven’t lost weight or had night sweats, and I haven’t traveled recently or smoked, so I keep wondering—what could it be? 

When I went to the doctor, they did some tests. I felt a bit of relief when they said my heart rate and oxygen levels were stable, but the wheezing on one side of my chest is troubling. The chest scans didn’t show anything alarming, but I can’t help but feel anxious. What’s causing this persistent cough and breathlessness? I keep thinking about what test could finally give us some answers, but I’m scared of what those answers might be.
options: A. Sputum culture and cytology B. Serum immunoglobulin E (IgE) level C. Bronchoscopy D. Esophageal pH monitoring E. Thoracentesis F. Flexible laryngoscopy G. Methacholine challenge test H. High-resolution CT of the thorax I. Allergy skin testing J. Cardiac stress testing

question:
I can hardly believe what’s happening to me. At 72, I thought I had a good grip on my health, but now I’m in the hospital with acute alcohol-induced pancreatitis. They placed a central venous catheter and a urinary catheter when I was admitted, and honestly, it felt overwhelming. My history isn’t exactly the best—alcohol use disorder, depression, and I had my aortic and mitral valves replaced. I’ve been taking bupropion, citalopram, and warfarin, but things took a turn for the worse on the fifth day of my stay.

I started running a fever and was harder to wake up than usual. It scared me to feel so out of it! I tried to explain to the nurses that I didn’t have a cough, nor was I short of breath or in pain anywhere. Yet, something felt very wrong. They did some blood tests, and I overheard them mention leukocytosis. My urinalysis didn’t show anything alarming, and my chest X-ray looked fine, but I just couldn’t shake this feeling of dread. 

Then, they told me my blood cultures grew coagulase-negative *Staphylococcus*. What does that even mean? I can’t help but worry about where this infection is coming from. They’re talking about more tests, and I just want to make sure I’m going to be okay. It’s all so terrifying.
options: A. Stool *C. difficile* toxin assays B. CT of the chest C. Catheter tip culture for microbial analysis D. Echocardiography to evaluate for endocarditis E. Procalcitonin levels to confirm bacteremia F. Gram staining of the blood culture isolates G. CT of the abdomen and pelvis to rule out intra-abdominal infection H. Urine culture I. No further testing is needed J. Repeat blood cultures

question:
I can't shake this feeling of worry since my recent MRI scan. At 56, I never expected to find out I have a 9-mm pituitary adenoma, discovered while they were checking for the persistent left-sided migraines that have been plaguing me. The doctors reassured me that the lesion is confined to the sella, without any alarming signs of extension or involvement with the pituitary stalk, but I can’t help but feel anxious about what this all means for my health.

I’ve been keeping track of my symptoms, or lack thereof, but I still feel unsettled. Thankfully, I haven’t experienced any visual disturbances or signs of hypercortisolism, which I read can be serious. Since going through menopause at 51, I haven’t had any hot flashes or other hormonal symptoms either, but the elevated prolactin levels—107 ng/mL—have me on edge. I just don’t understand why they’re so high when everything else seems normal.

My mind races with questions about what should happen next. Should I be worried? Are there treatments I should start right away? The doctors mentioned monitoring my prolactin levels and possibly starting medication, but the uncertainty is overwhelming. I just want to know what’s next and if I should be doing anything differently to manage this situation.
options: A. Reassure the patient that no immediate treatment is indicated; consider another MRI in 1 to 2 years B. Repeat prolactin levels after a dopamine agonist withdrawal period C. Initiate high-dose cabergoline therapy to normalize prolactin levels D. Begin bromocriptine 2.5 mg daily; remeasure the prolactin level in 1 month E. Perform visual field testing to assess for optic chiasm compression F. Begin cabergoline 0.25 mg twice weekly; remeasure the prolactin level in 3 months G. Refer the patient for radiation therapy to reduce adenoma size H. Initiate hormone replacement therapy to normalize estradiol levels I. Measure serum cortisol and ACTH levels to rule out subclinical Cushing syndrome J. Perform transsphenoidal surgery to remove the pituitary adenoma

question:
I can’t shake off this unease that’s been building over the last week. It all started six days ago when I began experiencing this relentless abdominal pain. It’s been unbearable, and I’ve noticed my stools turning black, which really freaked me out. I used to drink around 11 beers a day, but I had to stop five days ago because of the pain. 

I have a history of peptic ulcer disease, but I haven't been taking the omeprazole I was prescribed. I really thought I could manage it on my own, but now I’m not so sure. When I finally went to the emergency department, I was terrified. They checked my temperature and vital signs, and thankfully, they were mostly normal. Still, the mild tenderness in my abdomen is nagging at me. 

I didn’t expect them to find black stool during the digital rectal exam. It’s such a scary thought. They mentioned my hemoglobin levels and some liver enzyme numbers, but honestly, I was too worried to fully understand what that all meant. They’re considering next steps, and I can’t help but feel anxious about what’s going to happen next. I just want to feel better and not have to deal with this fear any longer. What if it’s something really serious?
options: A. Start IV fluids and monitor for variceal bleeding B. Start oral pentoxifylline C. Calculate MELD score D. Start IV lorazepam E. Perform upper endoscopy immediately F. Administer IV vitamin K G. Start IV octreotide H. Administer oral N-acetylcysteine I. Start oral prednisolone J. Transfer to a liver transplant center

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of worry that has been creeping in over the last couple of weeks. About ten days ago, I started experiencing these nagging headaches at the back of my head, right where it meets my neck. The dizziness comes and goes, and it’s really unsettling. 

I can’t help but think that it might be related to that incident two weeks ago when I accidentally hit my forehead on a car door frame. At first, I thought it was just a minor bump, but now I’m not so sure. I’ve been taking over-the-counter pain relievers, and while they help a bit, the headaches keep coming back. I’ve noticed that I don’t feel nauseous, and I haven’t lost consciousness, but something feels off.

When I went to see the doctor, I was nervous. They checked my cranial nerves and said everything seemed intact, but I could tell they were concerned during the examination. I overheard them discussing something about sphenobasilar synchondrosis, which sounded complicated. It left me feeling even more anxious, as I just want to understand what’s happening and how to feel better. I really hope this isn’t anything serious.
options: A. Left torsion B. Flexion dysfunction C. Lateral strain to the left D. Inferior vertical strain E. Lateral strain to the right F. Compressive dysfunction G. Extension dysfunction H. Cranial sidebending rotation I. Superior vertical strain J. Right torsion

question:
I've been feeling increasingly worried about my health lately. For the past few months, I've been dealing with this relentless headache that just won't go away, no matter how much acetaminophen I take. I really thought it was just stress or something minor, but it’s just gotten worse. I’m 59 years old, and I have a history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, and chronic kidney disease, which makes me feel even more anxious.

When I finally went to see the doctor, my blood pressure was 132/88, which didn’t seem too bad to me. My heart rate was steady, and I felt okay on the surface—my temperature was normal, and my oxygen levels were good. But then the doctor mentioned something about my vision. I didn’t even realize it until they tested me and found I have bitemporal hemianopsia. That really scared me. 

They checked my heart and lungs, which seemed fine, but I could feel the dread creeping in as they noted the slight swelling in my legs. Everything else in the exam was normal, but all this has been weighing on my mind. I can't shake the feeling that something serious might be going on. I’m just left wondering what the next steps will be and what imaging they might need to do to figure this out. It’s hard to stay calm when there are so many unknowns.
options: A. Digital subtraction angiography B. CT with iodinated contrast C. MRI with gadolinium D. CT without iodinated contrast E. MRI without gadolinium F. SPECT imaging G. Cerebral angiography H. PET-CT scan I. MR venography without contrast J. CT angiography

question:
I can't shake the feeling of worry that has settled in since the day I brought my newborn daughter home from the hospital. She's just four days old, and for the past two days, I've noticed a strange pink discharge. I remember the excitement of her arrival after a smooth delivery at 39 weeks, but now I’m overwhelmed with concern. She seemed to be feeding and voiding normally, which I tried to reassure myself with, but this discharge has me on edge.

I had chlamydia during my first trimester, but I thought that was all behind us after the treatment. My boyfriend has been a huge help with childcare since her biological father is absent, but I still feel so alone in this. When the pediatrician examined her, everything seemed fine—her temperature was normal, and her heart and lungs sounded good. But then the doctor mentioned the discharge, and my heart sank.

I can't help but worry about what this could mean. I mean, is it something serious? Should I be considering social services or a referral to a specialist? I just want to make sure my baby is healthy and safe, and the thought of anything being wrong is unbearable. I feel like I need guidance, but I’m terrified of what the next steps might bring.
options: A. Social services consultation B. Vaginal culture and sensitivity testing C. Referral to pediatric gynecology D. Urgent pelvic ultrasound E. Reassurance F. Warm water irrigation of the vagina G. Maternal hormone level testing H. Report to child protective services I. Sexual abuse evaluation J. Daily external cleaning with antiseptic solution

question:
I can't shake this overwhelming sense of worry that’s been creeping in on me. At 65, I’ve battled a host of health issues—chronic smoking, type 2 diabetes, obesity, COPD, and hypertension. Recently, I went in for a preoperative evaluation because I'm scheduled to repair a 5.5 cm abdominal aortic aneurysm, and I can't help but feel anxious about it all.

I tried to reassure myself when the doctor asked about any symptoms, and I was relieved to say I wasn’t experiencing chest pain or shortness of breath. Still, my limited mobility due to severe knee osteoarthritis weighs heavily on my mind. I can only manage to walk a block before needing to stop, and I rely on a wheelchair for most of my movements.

The doctor checked my vitals, and while my blood pressure was decent and my heart rate seemed okay, I couldn’t shake the feeling that something was off. They mentioned my kidneys might be struggling, and my heart showed signs of a chronic issue. Now, I’m left wondering what additional tests I might need to go through to assess my risks further. It’s all a lot to process, and I can’t help but feel a knot of fear in my stomach about what lies ahead. What if the next tests reveal more than I’m ready to handle?
options: A. Nuclear stress test with thallium imaging B. Exercise treadmill stress test C. Cardiopulmonary exercise testing D. Cardiac CT with coronary calcium scoring E. Resting transthoracic echocardiography F. Regadenoson stress test with myocardial perfusion study G. Dobutamine stress echocardiography H. Dobutamine stress cardiac MRI I. Coronary angiography with fractional flow reserve J. Transesophageal echocardiography

question:
I can hardly shake off the worry that’s been gnawing at me since my dad was brought to the clinic. He’s 72, and it breaks my heart to see him struggling with his dementia. Just last week, I took him to his primary care doctor for a thorough evaluation, and thankfully, the tests came back normal. But something feels so off. He’s been more agitated lately, and it’s like he can’t express any pain or discomfort, which makes it even more frustrating and scary for both of us.

During the examination, the doctor mentioned something that really stuck with me. They noted the greater wings of the sphenoid were higher than the occiput, which is concerning. I can’t help but feel anxious about what that means for him. I keep wondering if there's something more serious going on, like cranial strain or nerve issues. I wish I could understand it all better, but the medical terms are overwhelming. 

I just want to make sure he’s okay, and I can’t shake this feeling that we might be missing something important. Each day feels like a struggle, and I’m worried about what the future holds for us.
options: A. Dysfunction of the tentorium cerebelli due to cranial base strain B. Torsional strain pattern with left sphenoid rotation C. Superior deviation of the occiput at the sphenobasilar synchondrosis D. Caudad deviation of the sphenoid at the sphenobasilar synchondrosis E. Presence of a physiologic craniosacral strain pattern F. Restricted craniosacral rhythmic impulse (CRI) G. Favoring of the extension phase in craniosacral motion H. Compression of the sphenobasilar synchondrosis I. Exaggeration of the flexion phase in craniosacral motion J. Vagal nerve entrapment at the occipitoatlantal joint

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. Just two days ago, I started noticing a headache that wouldn’t go away, but I brushed it off. Then things took a turn for the worse. I felt this numbness and tingling in my left arm that seemed to spread like wildfire. Suddenly, it was affecting my face and even my leg. 

Before I knew it, I was in the emergency department, feeling clumsy and having a hard time walking. I kept veering to the left, and I couldn't understand what was happening to me. My mind was racing with worry—what could be wrong? I don’t have any history of medical issues, and I’ve never used recreational drugs, so why was my body betraying me? 

The doctors examined me, and I tried to stay calm, but they found weakness in my left side and noticed my left hand drifting. The sensory tests were alarming too; I could barely feel anything on my left side. It felt surreal. I kept thinking, “What does all of this mean?” 

I just want answers. I need to know what’s happening to me. The uncertainty is overwhelming, and I can’t help but worry about what could be going on in my brain. The thought of something serious is haunting me.
options: A. Viral meningitis B. Intracranial tumor C. Subdural hematoma D. Migraine with aura E. Brain abscess F. Acute stroke G. Transient ischemic attack H. Conversion disorder I. Cerebral venous thrombosis J. Viral encephalitis

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of dread. It all started three days ago when I woke up with this excruciating pain in my right arm. I must have slept on it wrong because I can’t move it at all. I’ve always been healthy, but now I feel utterly drained. Between working all those night shifts and taking care of my daughter during the day, I’m just exhausted. It’s like I can’t catch a break.

I never thought I’d be in the emergency department, but here I am, with my wife by my side, trying to convince me to get checked out. I feel so helpless and completely reliant on her now, especially since she’s had to pick up extra work to help us make ends meet. I keep hoping this will pass, but the pain is just too much.

When the doctors examined me, I felt so embarrassed. They said my muscle strength in my right arm was almost non-existent, but I still could feel them touching it, even if I didn’t want to. I couldn’t help but think: what’s happening to me? Why can’t I just shake this off? I’m terrified of what this could mean for my family and my job. I just want to be okay again.
options: A. Munchausen syndrome B. Radiculopathy C. Neuropraxia D. Malingering E. Anxiety disorder F. Factitious disorder G. Psychogenic paresis H. Functional neurological symptom disorder I. Somatic symptom disorder J. Conversion disorder

question:
I've been feeling so exhausted lately, and it's not just the usual tiredness. For the past six months, my fatigue has been getting worse, and I've started experiencing shortness of breath and palpitations whenever I try to do anything physical. It's really frightening. To make matters worse, I've noticed red blood in my stools three times in the last four months. Thankfully, my bowel habits haven't changed, and I haven't lost any weight, but still, the blood is alarming.

I have a medical history of type 2 diabetes and end-stage renal disease, and I remember having a colonoscopy a year ago where they found and removed three hyperplastic polyps. My mom passed away from colon cancer at just 69, which weighs heavily on my mind. I drink a couple of beers daily, but I don’t smoke, so I thought I was okay.

When I went to see the doctor, they said my vital signs were stable, but my conjunctivae looked pale, which got me worried. The abdominal examination was unremarkable, but the thought of what might be causing this bleeding is haunting me. With my family history and my symptoms, I can't help but think the worst. What could be going on with me? I’m just so scared of what it could mean.
options: A. Inflammation in an outpouching of the colonic wall B. Hemorrhoidal bleeding due to portal hypertension C. Angiodysplasia in the gastrointestinal tract D. Iron-deficiency anemia due to occult gastrointestinal malignancy E. Chronic use of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs leading to gastrointestinal bleeding F. Bleeding secondary to alcohol-induced thrombocytopenia G. Ischemic colitis causing mucosal ulceration H. Erosion of a colonic polyp leading to chronic blood loss I. Malignant transformation of colonic mucosal cells J. Arteriovenous malformation in the colonic wall

question:
I can’t shake this overwhelming sense of worry about what’s been happening to me lately. Just a week ago, I started experiencing this awful shortness of breath whenever I exerted myself, and it’s only gotten worse. I feel constantly fatigued, and there are times when I feel lightheaded, which is really alarming. To add to it all, my legs have been swelling up, and I can’t help but think something is seriously wrong.

Last week, I had a low-grade fever and felt achy and just unwell in general, but I didn’t think much of it at the time. Now, I’m sitting in this walk-in clinic, and the nurse took my vital signs. My blood pressure was shockingly low at 94 over 58, and my heart was racing at 125 beats per minute. I could hear crackles in my lungs when the doctor listened, and she mentioned something about my heart having an unusual rhythm. 

I’m really scared. They referred me to the hospital for further tests, and I can’t help but worry about what they might find. What if this is something serious? I just want to understand what’s happening to me and if I’m going to be okay.
options: A. Prolonged QT interval leading to arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy B. Viral-mediated myocardial inflammation C. Autoimmune-mediated destruction of cardiomyocytes D. Increased deposition of amyloid fibrils in the myocardium E. Cardiomyocyte hypertrophy F. IgA anti-endomysial antibodies G. Eosinophilic infiltration H. Disruption of the dystrophin-glycoprotein complex I. Abnormal sarcomere protein function J. Chronic vasospasm-induced ischemic myopathy

question:
I'm really worried about what’s happening to me. It all started five days after my mitral-valve replacement surgery. I thought I was on the mend, but then, out of nowhere, I felt this severe pain in the middle of my left foot last night. It was so sudden and intense; I can’t shake the feeling that something is really wrong.

I've been having some mild volume overload issues, and they had to give me furosemide, but I didn’t expect this foot pain. I’ve never had joint pain or any recent injuries, so I’m really confused. Now, I can see that my foot is swollen and red, and it hurts just to touch it—even a little squeeze sends sharp pain shooting through me. I can't bear weight on it at all without feeling like I’m going to scream.

To make matters worse, I’ve developed a fever. My temperature hit 38.2°C, and I just feel so unwell. My heart rate is okay, but I can’t help but feel anxious. I’m scared about what this could mean—whether it’s something serious like an infection or worse. I keep thinking about the possible diagnoses the doctors might consider, and it fills me with dread. What if it’s something really bad? I just want to know what’s going on and if I’m going to be okay.
options: A. Ischemic necrosis of the foot B. Deep vein thrombosis C. Plantar fasciitis D. Acute osteomyelitis E. Septic arthritis F. Cellulitis G. Stress fracture H. Pseudogout I. Cholesterol embolism J. Gout

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. I’m just a 19-year-old student-athlete, and until recently, I thought I was perfectly healthy. But now, my blood pressure readings have been alarming. Today, it was an unsettling 182/100 mm Hg. Last week, it was 162/95 mm Hg, and even six months ago, it was 185/90 mm Hg. I can’t believe these numbers! 

I’ve never had any medical issues before and don’t take any medications. It’s terrifying to think that something could be wrong with me. I went to get checked out, and while the doctors said my physical exam looked normal—no signs of anything wrong except for the high blood pressure—it doesn’t ease my worries. They did a pregnancy test, and thankfully that came back negative, but what if it’s something worse? 

I keep thinking about the possible diagnoses they mentioned. Could it be something like coarctation of the aorta or renal artery issues? I’ve read about so many possibilities and I’m scared. I just want to understand what’s happening to my body. Why is this happening to me? I feel like I’m constantly on edge, waiting for answers.
options: A. White coat hypertension B. Thyroid storm C. Renal artery fibromuscular dysplasia D. Coarctation of the aorta E. Primary hyperaldosteronism F. Pheochromocytoma G. Essential hypertension H. Cushing's syndrome I. Renovascular atherosclerosis J. Performance-enhancing drug use

question:
I can’t shake off the panic I felt when I was brought to the emergency department just a couple of hours ago. It all started suddenly with this severe stabbing pain in my back, right between my shoulder blades. It felt like a knife, and I rated it a 9 out of 10. I was so overwhelmed that I even vomited once. 

I’ve had hypertension and type 2 diabetes for years, but this was different—I was drenched in sweat and completely disoriented. I couldn’t even tell where I was or what was happening to me. My heart was racing at 110 beats per minute, and my blood pressure shot up to 210 over 130. I knew something was wrong. 

The doctors were focused and seemed concerned as well, noting my elevated creatinine levels, which made me anxious given my history of diabetic nephropathy. And to top it all off, they mentioned that a urine toxicology test came back positive for opiates and cocaine, which I couldn’t understand. I felt trapped in my own body, confused and scared. 

They were discussing next steps, and I could tell they were considering some serious tests and interventions. I just hope they figure this out quickly because I can’t bear the thought of what might be happening inside me.
options: A. Magnetic resonance angiography B. Transesophageal echocardiography C. Cardiac catheterization D. Serial troponin measurements E. Transthoracic echocardiography F. Immediate beta-blocker administration G. Aortography H. Emergency thoracotomy I. D-dimer testing and V/Q scan J. Contrast-enhanced CT angiography

question:
I can’t shake this feeling of dread. Just a few hours ago, I was lifting a heavy object when I suddenly felt a sharp pain in my right groin that radiated down to my scrotum. It was like nothing I’ve ever experienced before—intense and overwhelming. I noticed swelling, which I’ve had for years, but it never hurt like this. It just kept getting worse, and now I’m feeling nauseous on top of everything.

When I arrived at the emergency department, I was so anxious. They took my blood pressure, and I could see it was high at 150/90. My heart was racing, and I felt so uncomfortable. The doctor examined my abdomen, which was distended, and they found the swelling on my right side was tender and red. I couldn’t help but worry about what this could mean.

I’ve always been pretty healthy, aside from my smoking habit, but now I’m terrified. The thought of something serious happening is weighing heavily on me. I overheard the medical staff discussing what tests might be needed, and I can’t help but feel overwhelmed. I just want answers and hope it’s nothing too severe. What if this is something really serious? I wish I could shake this worry off, but it’s just so hard.
options: A. Ultrasonography B. Exploratory laparoscopy C. No further tests are needed D. Scrotal transillumination E. Doppler ultrasound of the scrotum F. Testicular biopsy G. Complete blood count (CBC) H. MRI of the scrotum I. CT scan J. Abdominal X-ray

question:
I can hardly believe what’s happening to me. I’ve been feeling so unsteady on my feet lately, like I might just fall over at any moment. It’s really alarming. Just the other day, I had trouble buttoning my shirt, which is something that should be so simple. 

When I got to the emergency department, I was terrified. The doctors did some tests, and during the exam, they noticed something strange with my fingers. When they extended and moved them, my little finger just kind of popped out on its own. That was shocking enough, but then they tried snapping the end of my middle finger, and suddenly all my other fingers just curled in. 

It’s hard to explain, but it feels like my body isn’t listening to me. I’ve been diagnosed with a COL1A1 genetic mutation, and now I can’t shake this awful feeling that something is really wrong. I keep worrying about what could be causing all of this. The doctors mentioned a list of possible issues, but I’m just left feeling more anxious with every thought. What if it’s something serious? I’m scared about what this all means for my future.
options: A. Arnold-Chiari malformation B. Spinal cord tethering C. Thoracic outlet syndrome D. Cervical spondylotic myelopathy E. Syringomyelia F. Basilar invagination G. Atlantoaxial instability H. C6 cervical disc foraminal herniation I. Multiple sclerosis J. Carpal tunnel syndrome
